police warned wednesday that jail sentences may await opportunists who made off with more than $700,000 after an armored car accidentally dumped a crateful of cash in the street, sparking a mad scramble for the loot
three to five people who were driving or walking by when the truck dropped a reported $771,000 in an industrial area tuesday scooped up clear plastic bags full of cash and sped off. only $40,100 was recovered, police said
we've only had one honest man so far,'' said lt. barry johnson. a tv repairman picked up two bags containing $20,050 each and took them straight to the nearby offices of loomis armored inc
late wednesday, a woman identified only as a 30-year-old postal worker turned gave police two clear plastic bags containing a total of $28,000
she said she picked up the money and then got kind of scared, so she decided to turn it in,'' said sgt. william herndon
investigators were tracing license plate numbers and vehicle descriptions reported by witnesses and trying to compile a list of the lost bills' serial numbers
if they turn it in, the company is considering a reward,'' said johnson. ``the alternative is we trace them down and they go to jail. it's their choice.''
the opportunistic motorists or pedestrians could face felony charges of grand theft if they took $500 or more, police said
a spokesman for oakland-based loomis declined to comment on the accident, which occurred at 3:40 p.m. on a busy thoroughfare in the potrero district, adjacent to the low-income hunter's point neighborhood that has been plagued by rock-throwing and violence against city buses this year
the armored truck, filled with more than $1.7 million collected from 20 banks in the san francisco bay area, was headed for loomis' offices from downtown
johnson said the driver claimed the rear door had been locked, but the dolly containing a crate of bills slammed against it and somehow forced it open
the driver, whose name was not disclosed, did not learn of the mishap until a honking motorist pointed it out 2{ blocks away
before the driver could return, a crowd gathered around the fallen bags. some people put the money back into the crate and others hung onto it, including one man who tossed numerous bags into his pickup truck and drove off despite the urgings of bystanders
it was a free-for-all,'' police officer harry soulette, who was at the scene, told the san francisco examiner. ``people were throwing bags of bills into their cars and taking off. it was wild.''
police declined to be specific wednesday about the amount involved, saying only that it was more than $500,000. the examiner reported that $771,000 in $10, $20 and $50 bills fell out of the truck while close to $1 million remained inside
the money is ``potentially traceable,'' johnson said
police said the driver was not a suspect
we're looking at every possibility, but there doesn't appear to have been any collusion at this point,'' johnson said
repairman luis lopez who had spent the day working on tv monitors at loomis' offices, told police he tried to recover more money for the company but was was told by the loot-grabbers to mind his own business
the 29-year-old lopez, who lives in daly city, does not have a listed telephone number and could not be reached for comment wednesday
soulette was impressed with his honesty
he was one of a few people who tried to do what was right,'' the officer said. ``while everyone else was busy grabbing what they could get, he was thinking of getting the money back to its rightful owner.'' contempt</head>
a judicial conduct board said it will seek a contempt citation against a former judge for refusing to answer questions wednesday at a hearing on misconduct charges against a former state supreme court justice
jane wheel, a former chittenden county assistant judge, cited her fifth amendment right against self-incrimination in refusing to answer questions during the judicial conduct board hearing on former justice william hill
hill was one of three supreme court members charged with misconduct in january 1987. one of the three died; the case against the third was dropped
hill, who has since retired from the high court, is accused of improperly using his judicial clout to assist wheel, 55
wheel's refusal to answer questions prompted the hearing panel to direct its lawyer to petition the supreme court to find wheel in contempt. she could face jail
i don't think we're risking contempt,'' said wheel's lawyer richard davis. ``if asserting one's right to refuse to testify under the fifth amendment presents a risk in this country then we better start with a new system.''
wheel was found guilty in state court last month on charges of lying under oath during an inquiry into allegations she submitted false pay vouchers. the case is under appeal
the board had ruled that wheel may invoke the fifth amendment on questions relating directly to the criminal charges. but panel chairman harvey otterman said that protection does not extend to questions that are merely embarrassing
wheel gave her name, address and length of service but balked when prosecutor william donahue asked about her relationship with hill
prosecutors allege hill allowed his friendship with wheel to interfere with his judicial duties. assistant judges are commonly lay people; they handle civil cases. hill was a teacher before she was elected
hill has said his relationship with wheel was a proper professional one. but margaret maskell, a courthouse employee, testified tuesday that she once found wheel with her arms around hill's neck in his chambers
the hearing panel is composed of three of seven members of the judicial conduct board; the three hearing the case will make recommendations to the full board. canceled talks. picks up 6th graf: three days ...</note>
president daniel ortega canceled truce talks with rebels tuesday after the insurgents said they would not attend a planned meeting in southern nicaragua
ortega accused both president reagan and the rebels, known as contras, of sabotaging the talks
this signifies the killing of the possibility of a meeting,'' he said on voice of nicaragua radio, but suggested new talks no later than the third week in march
contra leader adolfo calero said earlier tuesday the u.s.-supported rebels would not attend the meeting scheduled by the leftist sandinistas
the sandinista government spoke with the nicaraguan resistance at the last minute (monday), informing us that they were ready for the meeting in sapoa,'' calero said in a telephone interview from miami. ``we are not willing to take part in a unilateral meeting mounted by the sandinistas.''
ortega said reagan ``made a virulent speech against nicaragua yesterday. he said `no' to the meeting
so if there is anyone responsible for the meeting not being held tomorrow and for the the blood that continues being shed ... it is the president of the united states.''
reagan said in washington monday that congressional opponents of further aid to the contras lacked the courage to fight communism and the defeat of the rebels would be a ``grave strategic defeat for the united states.''
three days of talks had been scheduled at sapoa, 90 miles south of managua on the border with costa rica
they would have been the first talks held on nicaraguan territory and without a mediator. roman catholic cardinal miguel obando y bravo mediated previous talks
a contra statement issued in miami said the rebels wanted preliminary discussions in san jose, costa rica
we accept to go to sapoa but we are asking a previous meeting to clear up the details,'' said aristides sanchez, one of five contra directors. ``we have to discuss dates, an agenda, security. it must all be established beforehand, since there is no longer a mediator.''
he said it would be impossible for contra negotiators to get together in time to reach sapoa by wednesday
ortega publicly called for the talks last week and said obando y bravo no longer would be needed because negotiators would meet face-to-face
the contras insisted on the presence of obando y bravo, a frequent critic of the government who leads the catholic church in nicaragua, as ``witness, moderator, and guarantor of the talks.''
on monday, ortega asked the cardinal and joao baena soares, secretary-general of the organization of american states, to witness the talks
baena soares arrived in managua on tuesday, and ortega announced cancellation of the talks after meeting with him
contra spokesmen also insisted ortega's government agree to discuss political points outlined by obando y bravo during the last round feb. 18 in guatemala
his plan would require the sandinistas to grant amnesty to political prisoners, restore full press freedom, reopen talks with internal political opposition parties and review the military draft law
sandinista and opposition sources said obando y bravo's proposals caused his ouster as mediator
the sandinistas have refused to discuss internal political issues with the contras. they say the only purpose of talks is to work out a cease-fire in accordance with the regional peace plan signed aug. 7 by the five central american presidents. tax-exempt status</head>
a federal judge has cleared the way for the internal revenue service to revoke ptl's tax exemption, which could affect income for the fort mill television ministry
u.s. district judge karen henderson on monday overturned a preliminary injunction against the irs that bankruptcy judge rufus reynolds issued in december
this puts the ball back in our court,'' irs spokesman les witmer of atlanta said tuesday. the irs may revoke ptl's tax exemption soon, he said
the irs informed ptl trustee david clark in december that it would revoke the exemption, retroactive to may 31, 1981. but clark got the injunction, and reynolds ordered the irs not to revoke before may 1, 1988
the order of the bankruptcy court enjoining revocation of ptl's tax exempt status was issued outside its jurisdiction and is therefore reversed,'' henderson ruled
clark and ptl attorney bradford leggett of winston-salem, n.c., could not be reached for comment tuesday
the irs granted ptl its tax exemption in 1973
although the irs can't collect back taxes while ptl is protected by chapter 11 bankruptcy laws, the impending revocation may affect ptl contributors. the irs calculates the back taxes at between $62 million and $82 million, while ptl's current leaders calculate the amount owed at about $5 million
the ministry is engaged in a march telethon to raise $4 million
henderson ruled that revoking the tax exempt status would cause taxes to be assessed only against taxpayers who contribute to ptl _ contributors who are not debtors in bankruptcy
the irs said that ptl's former leader, jim bakker, his wife, tammy, and top aides received excessive compensation that was not consistent with the ministry's tax-exempt status. the irs said the couple received $11 million during their last seven years with the ministry
bakker resigned a year ago, admitting he had had a tryst with a church secretary
the sheriff's office ended its witch hunt, dropping efforts to obtain a list of library patrons who check out books on the occult
assistant district attorney dexter ryland said tuesday he had advised the library against releasing the list, and the sheriff's office withdrew its subpoena for the information
the rapides parish sheriff's office wanted the list to get information on serious followers of satanic cults because such beliefs often are connected with narcotics trafficking, said chief deputy tommy hollingsworth
library director stephen rogge said about 20 of the 150,000 books at the library deal with the occult
most of it is pretty silly stuff actually, but they are entertaining and people are curious,'' rogge said
i've read some myself,'' he said. ``but i haven't sacrificed any animals.''
a 70-year-old kept a shotgun under his pillow because of repeated break-ins, but the latest burglar got the weapon without waking the man and shot the sleeper's cousin with it, authorities said
wally newton woke up when he heard the blast and simpson brown yelling after being shot in the leg early monday
brown, 70, and newton share a home in mead valley, an unincorporated area about 65 miles southeast of los angeles
brown told deputies he was sleeping when he saw a shadow pass his bedroom
he called out, thinking it was newton, but got no answer, said riverside county sheriff's sgt. john horton. brown got up, and found the burglar holding newton's shotgun, according to horton
he (brown) grabbed the barrel,'' horton said. the gun went off. brown yelled. newton woke up
brown was hospitalized in good condition. the burglar escaped with the gun, horton said
police took a bite out of crime by tracking down a robbery suspect through dentures left behind after he allegedly tried to bite his victim
he denies it, but we've got the teeth, and he doesn't,'' sgt. ray hudson said
joseph bennett, 62, was charged with strong-arm robbery, hudson said
bennett's dentures fell out saturday when he tried to bite bobbie mccloud, 76, police said
he was choking me, and then he tried to bite me on the arm, but it was just gums,'' ms. mccloud said monday
although her eyesight and hearing are failing, ms. mccloud said she had no trouble identifying bennett as the robber
when police brought bennett back to her house, ms. mccloud said, they had him try on the teeth left at her house
they fit right in his mouth,'' she said
a south african diplomat has apologized for a traffic accident in which his car struck an anti-apartheid protester and a police officer
vice consul duke kent brown, charged with simple assault in monday's accident and released on his own recognizance, was ordered to appear in court in april
brown said he had not expected protesters to block his exit after he took part in a talk show at wjoy-wqcr
in an interview tuesday with the radio stations, he said he did not see police officer todd shepard, who suffered bruises on his leg
i was very surprised to hear that a policeman had been injured and i did apologize to him when i saw him,'' brown said
brown said he was glad to hear that protester laurie larson of richmond, who suffered minor bruises, was not badly injured
hearing-impaired theatergoers are calling for a boycott of a stage production of ``children of a lesser god'' because only actors who can hear were cast, says an interpreter for the deaf
a hearing person who pretends to be deaf is not going to look right, and it's not going to be presented properly,'' kellie perkins, who also has a hearing problem, said tuesday
director mark bacus disagreed, and said he tried unsuccessfully to cast hearing-impaired actors for the piasaw players' amateur production
the play, about the relationship between a deaf woman and a man who can hear, won tony awards in 1980. marlee matlin, who is deaf, won an oscar for her portrayal of the woman in the 1986 film version
the drama was written specifically for deaf people, to show their concerns to society, said ms. perkins, an interpreter at impact inc., a center that helps the handicapped in this southern illinois community
what bothers me is that a hearing person cannot understand what a deaf person feels,'' she said
the lead actress will be unable to learn all the required sign language by showtime, ms. perkins said
bacus said the actors will learn enough signing to handle their parts well
all theater has to exaggerate to provide illusion,'' he said. ``if i do a show that has a french character, must i find somebody that knows all french and the french culture?
i don't want to fight. i'd rather carry on with the play,'' bacus said
he said he tried to cast deaf or hearing-impaired actors, but auditions last month, announced in the local newspaper and through the theater group, drew just one hearing-impaired player
rita campbell of alton, who is deaf, was unsuited for the lead, bacus said
ms. campbell, speaking through ms. perkins, said she'd received up to 100 telephone calls from people with hearing problems urging her to stop the play
suppose someone pretended to be like you,'' she said. ``and you saw it and said, `that's not how i act.' you'd be insulted.when you use hearing people to portray deaf people, it makes us look awkward and dumb.''
ms. perkins said ms. campbell would meet this week with groups of deaf and hearing-impaired people to make plans for a boycott if there are no casting changes
it's sad and it's ridiculous,'' said bacus, who received a few letters protesting the casting
the play is going to go on,'' he said. ``it must. if i decide to fold, then what's next? what other theater group will knuckle under to special interest groups?''
national park service officials are pursuing a plan to buy and remove a 370-foot-high observation tower that has overlooked the civil war battlefield here for 15 years
my opinion is that the tower dominates the skyline at gettysburg and it's totally out of keeping with what we're trying to accomplish here in preserving the battlefield,'' john earnst, gettysburg national military park superintendent, said tuesday
the preliminary proposal is part of a study ordered by congress to determine permanent boundaries for the park, site of the 1863 union victory and president abraham lincoln's legendary address
the proposal, outlined at a meeting monday night, has yet to be reviewed by park service officials in washington and would require congressional approval, earnst said
the steel tower, built in 1973 on private land separating parts of the park, was the focus of controversy over preserving the park area's historical integrity
when the tower was built, then-gov. milton shapp brought an unsuccessful lawsuit against attorney thomas ottenstein of bethesda, md., who came up with the idea for the tower and is a co-owner
ottenstein, reached in delray beach, fla., said he could not comment about monday's meeting because he was unaware of it. the tower's manager, gertrude paris, also declined to comment
i didn't know a thing until i read the paper,'' she said
congress ordered the study last year while passing legislation to allow a group's donation of 30 acres to the park
the study has identified about 1,800 acres that should be added to the 3,874-acre park, said planner jonathan doherty of the park service's regional office in philadelphia
vice president george bush humbled bob dole with a republican primary win in the kansas senator's backyard, while tennessee sen. albert gore triumphed convincingly in oklahoma's democratic contest tuesday
with 2,272 of 2,439 precincts or 93 percent reporting, bush edged dole from with 69,813 votes or 37 percent to dole's 66,147 votes or 35 percent. pat robertson was next with 40,039 votes or 21 percent and new york rep. jack kemp was a distant fourth with 10,170 votes or 5 percent
in the democratic race, with 2,317 of 2,439 precincts or 95 percent reporting, gore had 154,217 votes or 41 percent, gephardt had 78,834 votes or 21 percent and dukakis had 62,958 votes or 17 percent
jesse jackson was next with 48,556 votes or 13 percent; former colorado sen. gary hart had 13,897 votes or 4 percent; and illinois sen. paul simon had 6,460 votes or 2 percent
the democrats were competing for 46 delegates; the republicans for 36
a poll broadcast by two television stations last week showed gephardt, gore and dukakis each getting 18 percent of the democratic vote. but 27 percent of those surveyed between feb. 26 and march 1 were still undecided
dole crisscrossed the state in the closing days and stepped up his advertising campaign in an effort to overtake bush, the perceived front-runner who was endorsed by gov. henry bellmon and most prominent state political leaders
ads for dole touted his positions on agriculture and reducing the federal deficit. dole was supported by u.s. sen. don nickles
matt seward, bush campaign director in oklahoma, said oklahoma was ``a special prize'' since it was listed by dole operatives as one of the states dole was counting on to win
if he can't win in oklahoma, where can he win?'' seward asked. 03-09 0821</first> alexander re-elected in arkansas and updating returns, picks up after dash, ``roemer</note>
mississippi democrats picked a young congressman as their candidate to replace john c. stennis in the u.s. senate, while democratic sens. paul sarbanes of maryland and lloyd bentsen of texas easily overcame little-known primary opponents tuesday
as the first state primaries coincided with super tuesday, rep. wayne dowdy defeated secretary of state dick molpus for the democratic senate nomination in mississippi. he is expected to face a hard fight from rep. trent lott, the house minority whip who was unopposed in the republican primary
with 90 percent of the vote counted, dowdy had 167,640 votes or 54 percent to molpus' 133,547 votes or 43 percent. a third candidate, pipefitter gilbert fountain, had 11,454 or 4 percent
molpus saluted the winner as ``a decent and likable man. he has conveyed those characteristics to the people of this state and we pay him tribute.''
texas republicans will need a runoff to choose bentsen's opponent, while republican jim mccrery advanced to a runoff against democratic state sen. foster campbell to fill the u.s. house seat being vacated by governor-elect buddy roemer
sarbanes easily won renomination for a third term and will face thomas blair, a millionaire political newcomer who beat eight other candidates for the republican nomination. with 78 percent of the vote counted, blair had 54,408 votes or 47 percent while none of his eight opponents had more than 13 percent
in arkansas, rep. william alexander swamped political consultant darrell glascock in the democratic primary, and won re-election because there is no republican opposition. with 56 percent of the vote counted, alexander had 54,079 or 66 percent to glascock's 27,570 or 34 percent
rep. jamie whitten, seeking his 25th term, and rep. mike espy, mississippi's first black congressman since reconstruction, were overwhelming winners in democratic primaries. there were tight, crowded races in both parties for the nominations to succeed dowdy and lott.
in a rematch of the 1982 primary, bentsen defeated professor joe sullivan of san antonio by better than 5-1. with 48 percent of the vote counted, bentsen had 587,121 votes or 84 percent to 114,946 or 16 percent for sullivan
houston millionaire wes gilbreath and u.s. rep. beau boulter of amarillo were headed for a runoff for the gop nomination to oppose bentsen
with 39 percent of the vote counted, gilbreath had 101,292 or 35 percent and boulter had 96,212 or 33 percent. former state rep. milton fox of austin had 53,481 or 18 percent and businessman ned snead of georgetown had 41,564 or 14 percent
with returns 91 percent complete in louisiana's 4th district, mccrery had 30,859 or 30 percent while campbell nailed down the other spot in the april 16 runoff with 21,278 or 21 percent
stan tiner, the former editor of the shreveport journal who had roemer's support, was third with 15,600 or 15 percent, followed by june phillips, the only black in the race, with 13,479 or 13 percent and state rep. claude ``buddy'' leach with 12,254 or 12 percent
roemer will resign on monday to become governor
roemer said he would vote for tiner, and even gave his campaign a check, but insisted he had not formally endorsed anyone
dowdy, 44, stressed his seven years experience as a member of congress, while the 38-year-old molpus pointed to his record as director of federal-state programs under former gov. william winter and as secretary of state since 1984
mississippi is one of the states where the gop hopes to reduce or even reverse the democrats' 54-46 advantage in the senate. eighteen of the 33 seats at stake this year are held by democrats
stennis, 86, retiring after 41 years in the senate, did not choose sides in the democratic primary
bentsen, who is seeking a fourth term has said he is prepared to spend $10 million in november, and didn't care who the republican nominee was
gilbreath was the big spender in the texas gop race, investing about $500,000 of his own money
in addition to the mississippi race, republican hopes in the senate this year were spurred by the retirement of democratic sen. william proxmire of wisconsin and sen. lawton chiles of florida
however, the gop is losing sens. paul trible of virginia, daniel evans of washington and robert t. stafford of vermont
in new jersey, republican businessmen pete dawkins _ a west point football star, rhodes scholar, decorated combat veteran and former army general _ is challenging sen. frank lautenberg, d-n.j., who is seeking a second term
in new york, republicans had hoped to mount a strong challenge to incumbent sen. daniel patrick moynihan, but were disappointed when high-profile federal prosecutor rudolph giuliani ruled himself out. orders</head>
a taiwanese gangster accused of fatally shooting a chinese-american journalist was acting on orders from the head of taiwan's intelligence agency, a prosecutor charged tuesday
in his opening statements, assistant district attorney bob bishop told the jury that taiwanese adm. wang hsi-ling hired tung kuei-sen to assassinate henry liu, whose writings were highly critical of the taiwanese government
liu's wife, helen, also testified before the jury in san mateo county superior court. tung, an acknowledged member of the taiwanese crime syndicate known as the bamboo gang and one of two alleged triggermen in the slaying, entered a plea of innocent last june
tung, 35, is serving a 20-year prison sentence for herion smuggling
the 52-year-old liu was gunned down at his daly city home on oct. 15, 1984. he was a columnist for chinese-language newspapers in san francisco and had just published an unflattering biography of taiwan president chiang chung-kuo when he was slain
bishop said that liu was making it known that he was about to publish memoirs of a former high-ranking taiwanese official, something that hsi-ling feared would be embarrassing and damaging to president chiang. chiang died in january
wang, the admiral, wanted liu killed before the memoirs were published, bishop said. wang hired bamboo gang leader chen chi-li, who surrounded himself with a group of men, including defendant tung, to help carry out the assassination plot, the prosecutor said
the memoirs contained nothing that would shock u.s. citizens, bishop said. but in taiwan, anything dealing with the personal lives of the president or his father, chiang kai-shek, were considered treasonous, he said
mrs. liu testified tuesday afternoon, tearfully describing her husband's murder
she said that the day before the slaying, she noticed two people on bicycles surveying their neighborhood. however, their faces were covered with hooded sweatshirts and she did not think anything of it until following day, when she noticed they had returned on the bikes
less than an hour later, she said she sent her husband down into the garage to load boxes into their car and heard a loud noise. she went downstairs and found her husband dying on the garage floor
she also said that before her husband's slaying, the taiwan government had started sending over former friends of her husband's to try and persuade him to quit his critical writings
the suspects in the slaying fled and eventually resurfaced in taiwan, believing they had acted on the orders of the taiwanese government, bishop said. the suspects thought they were immune from prosecution, he said
however, the slaying had strained u.s.-taiwan relations, and the united states began putting so much pressure on chiang's regime that ``something had to be done,'' bishop said
chen and another bamboo gang member were convicted of the murder in taiwan in 1985 and given life sentences, and three top taiwanese intelligence officers were also separately convicted by a military court in the alleged murder plot
but tung fled taiwan and eventually became the only one of liu's suspected killers to be brought to trial in the united states. race</head> succeed roemer in congress; no pickup.</note>
jesse jackson repeated his 1984 democratic primary victory here tuesday, staving off sen. albert gore jr.'s bid for an upset, while george bush swamped the gop field
in a special election, a republican former aide to democratic gov.-elect buddy roemer led the 10-candidate field to succeed roemer in congress, but was forced into an april 16 runoff with a state senator
in the democratic race, with 2,903 of 3,272 precincts or 89 percent reporting, jackson had 194,118 or 34 percent; tennessee's gore had 168,500 votes or 30 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 83,117 votes or 15 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 61,375 votes or 11 percent
in republican voting, bush left sen. bob dole battling for second place with pat robertson. with 2,857 of 3,272 precincts or 87 percent reporting, bush had 76,155 votes or 58 percent; robertson had 24,052 votes or 18 percent; dole had 23,354 votes or 18 percent; new york rep. jack kemp had 6,665 votes or 5 percent
the democrats were deciding 63 convention delegates; the republicans 41
in the closing days of the democratic presidential primary, roemer endorsed gore, who said he felt his campaign was gaining steam in the state, but the same claim was made by kitty dukakis, the wife of the massachusetts governor
backers of former television evangelist robertson claimed their work was responsible for most of the 19,000 voters who switched their registrations from democratic to republican. the rev. billy mccormack, robertson's state campaign director, predicted the former tv evangelist would carry louisiana
in the 4th congressional district, roemer's former congressional aide jim mccrery, the sole republican in the race, was forced into a runoff with state sen. foster campbell to succeed roemer in the u.s. house
with 91 percent of the vote in, mccrery had 30,859 votes, or 30 percent, to 21,278 or 21 percent for campbell; former shreveport newsman stan tiner was third with 15,600 votes, or 15 percent. june phillips, the only black in the race, gather 13,479 votes, or 13 percent and state rep. claude ``buddy'' leach, who held the seat for one term until he was defeated by roemer in 1980, had 12,254 votes, or 12 percent
roemer resigns on monday to become governor. couldn't sue</head>
the u.s. government contributed 40 percent to settlements for two challenger astronauts who worked for the government even though federal law protects the government against claims like theirs
a key legal reason: the government was concerned that morton thiokol would end up passing claims against it along to the federal government. thiokol made the defective rockets that were blamed for the challenger explosion, but government officials had also spurned warnings by thiokol engineers that a launch on jan. 28, 1986, might be unsafe because of cold temperatures at cape canaveral
relatives of all seven astronauts were free to sue morton thiokol for damages, but only the families of the two non-government employees _ high school teacher christa mcauliffe and hughes aircraft employee gregory jarvis _ were allowed to sue the federal government
documents released by the government this week to settle a lawsuit filed under the freedom of information act by the associated press and six other news organizations show that the government and morton thiokol paid $7,735,000 in cash and annuities to settle with the four spouses and six children of dick scobee, ellison onizuka, jarvis and mcauliffe
scobee was a civilian astronaut with the national aeronautics and space administration. onizuka was an air force lieutenant colonel
the government has refused to contribute to settlements reached by morton thiokol with the survivors of civilian nasa astronauts ronald mcnair and judith resnik
and last month, government lawyers opposing a lawsuit filed by the family of the other military officer aboard, navy cmdr. michael smith, got the government dropped as a defendant because he was a military officer
the government documents showed that morton thiokol paid 60 percent and the government 40 percent of the settlement with the four families
in a letter to the news organizations that sued, justice department lawyer joanne s. marchetta stipulated that the ``single percentage split ... is applicable to all four settlements in the aggregate.''
the government did not require morton thiokol to bear a larger share of the settlement with the scobee and onizuka relatives, even though those families could sue only the company
in a brief filed in the foi case, the government suggested why it contributed at all to the scobee and onizuka settlements
it was entirely possible under the facts presented by the challenger accident that the government would be brought in as a third party to any claims by the families brought against government contractors like mti,'' the brief said
that reference was to the objections by morton thiokol engineers to launching the shuttle in extreme cold _ objections that were withdrawn under government pressure
ronald krist, a houston lawyer who represented the mcnairs, jarvis' father and resnik's mother, noted that a 1983 supreme court decision allows a contractor who pays damages to a federal employee's survivors to try to recover part of those damages from the government if federal employees shared the blame. so far, however, morton thiokol has made no move to do this
that law is on the books and that would give the government the theoretical incentive to settle'' with the families of government workers, krist said
thus, by entering into joint settlements with thiokol and the families, the government extinguished the potential third-party claim of thiokol against the government in these four cases and avoided trials that would have replayed the painful government errors that led to the fateful decision to launch in cold weather
michael j. sniffen has covered the challenger disaster and its aftermath for the associated press
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis parlayed a strong statewide organization into a decisive victory in idaho's democratic presidential caucuses on tuesday
with 34 of 45 precincts or 76 percent reporting, dukakis had 727 votes or 43 percent; uncommitted received 470 votes or 28 percent; jesse jackson had 269 votes or 16 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 107 votes or 6 percent; illinois sen. paul simon had 65 votes or 4 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 41 votes or 2 percent
state party chairman mel morgan and gov. cecil andrus led a campaign to have as many of tuesday's caucus participants as possible remain uncommitted. idaho has only 18 delegates at stake
this thing is looking more and more like a brokered convention,'' morgan said, ``so we might as well get some power while we can.''
the internal revenue service is preparing to report that americans are cheating less on their federal tax returns even though the government is still losing as much as $90 billion a year to scofflaws
that figure for the 1987 ``tax gap'' doesn't even include untold billions that are lost because illegal income is never reported to the irs
nevertheless, says irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs, ``the amount of the tax gap has diminished since the last time we did a study.'' that was in 1983, when the irs estimated an $81.5-billion tax gap that would rise to more than $100 billion by 1987
gibbs, defending the irs's proposed budget before a house appropriations subcommittee on tuesday, said the new tax-gap study could be released within a week. the new figure will be between $80 billion and $90 billion, he said
he attributed the decline in cheating to several actions by congress and the irs to force better compliance with the tax laws, including enhanced ability to match virtually every tax return with supporting income statements filed by employers, banks and other payers. gibbs also suggested the massive tax revision enacted in 1986 contributed to better compliance
in other developments:
_gibbs said the irs is temporarily suspending efforts to collect back taxes from many students whose colleges paid them stipends for research or teaching assignments in 1984, 1985 or 1986. the colleges reported those stipends to the irs as income but many students failed to report them on their tax returns
we've put the word out (to irs offices) to hold up on any'' such cases until the agency can develop a uniform policy on how to treat stipends paid in those years, he said. the 1986 tax revision cleared up any ambiguity for subsequent years; all stipends are taxable
some irs field offices are following a 1975 irs ruling that set guidelines for taxing some stipends; others follow different court interpretations
several colleges have reported numerous graduate students receiving tax-due notices from the irs because of their stipends. the washington post cited one unofficial estimate that up to 17,000 students might be involved and that several have already filed suit in tax court to contest the assessments
gibbs said the irs has no campaign to crack down on these students, but blamed their problems on the fact their tax returns did not square with their w-2 earnings statements. he said he hopes the agency can have a clear-cut policy within a month
_more than one-third of taxpayers have filed their 1987 returns, and, despite the sweeping nature of the 1986 tax overhaul, the irs is finding only about 2{ percent more errors this year than last, gibbs said. ``i'm delighted,'' he said
_the irs issued a reminder that a new tax on certain vaccines is now in effect. although it is imposed on producers, it is likely to be passed on to patients. the tax, which was enacted last december, will finance compensation for patients who die or are injured because of vaccinations
the tax is $4.56 for a dose of dpt (diphtheria, whopping cough and tetanus) vaccine; 6 cents for diphtheria and tetanus; $4.44 for measles, mumps and rubella, and 28 cents for polio
the last irs study of the tax gap, published in 1983, estimated that individuals and corporations dodged $81.5 billion in taxes on legal income in 1981 by understating income and overstating deductions
the agency estimated that another $9 billion in taxes was lost on three types of illegal income: drugs, prostitution and gambling. the new report will not even attempt to estimate the tax loss from illegal income that is never reported
since the last tax gap study was published, irs researchers have found evidence that taxpayers may be cheating less. in may 1986, the agency released a preliminary report indicating that a 20-year trend of declining compliance with the tax laws might have been reversed
that study estimated that voluntary compliance rose to 91.8 percent in 1982, from 91.0 percent in 1979. compliance had declined steadily from 94.3 percent in 1965
an episode of nbc's new series ``day by day'' placed second to perennial favorite ``the cosby show'' and helped the network climb back to the top of the ratings after abc's two weeks as no. 1
nbc won the ratings for the week that ended sunday with an average prime-time a.c. nielsen co. rating of 16.3. cbs had a 15.0 rating and abc, whose 16 days of winter olympics coverage catapulted it to the top the previous two weeks, fell back to third, with a 12.8
for the season, nbc continues in the lead with a 16.3 overall rating to abc's 14.1 and cbs's 13.6
a rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with televisions
the episode of ``day by day'' that ranked second was shown at 8:30 p.m. thursday, after no. 1-rated ``the cosby show.''
day by day,'' a comedy about a young couple operating a home daycare center, also was shown by nbc on sunday night after ``family ties'' and on monday night after ``alf.''
the sunday night show placed 20th in the nielsen ratings and the monday night show 14th. the show's regular slot will be sunday night, where it received its lowest rating
the three-hour grammy awards show on cbs, which featured a rare television performance by michael jackson, finished eighth
the cosby show'' on nbc was rated no. 1 for the week with a 31.4 rating
nbc's ``cheers'' was no. 3 with a 25.9, followed by nbc's ``night court'' with a 24.5
abc's ``growing pains'' was no. 5 with a 24.5 rating, and its ``who's the boss?'' was next with a 22.0
cbs' ``the golden girls'' held seventh place with a 21.5 rating, followed by a tie between the grammys and cbs' ``60 minutes,'' at 21.0
no. 10 was nbc's ``alf,'' with a 20.5 rating
in the news category, ``the cbs evening news'' was no. 1, with an 11.3 rating. abc's ``world news tonight'' had a 11.2 rating, and the ``nbc nightly news'' 9.6
