panama's military regime could find itself subject to ``a whole panoply'' of economic sanctions by the end of this week, including the withholding of $6.5 million this month for use of the panama canal, u.s. officials say
final decisions on the sanctions are expected at an inter-agency meeting scheduled thursday, said the officials, who insisted on anonymity. a formal announcement is likely either thursday or friday, they added
the economic punishment is intended to aggravate an already acute cash shortage in that country and pressure military strongman manuel antonio noriega out of office
the officials spoke late tuesday, the same day that the house foreign affairs committee urged president reagan to consider economic sanctions against panama's military regime
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said in response to the house committee vote that the administration would not take such action lightly
the threat's still out there,'' fitzwater said. ``the situation is changing rapidly and we're still monitoring it. but we don't want to act precipitously.''
the administration has called for noriega's ouster since he was indicted on federal drug trafficking charges in florida last month and for a return to civilian rule under president eric arturo delvalle
another sanction being considered is the withdrawal of panamanian participation in a system of trade preferences accorded to most third world countries, the officials said. this would make panamanian products more expensive in u.s. markets
another possibility, they said, is panama's exclusion from the caribbean basin initiative under which some panamanian products can be exported to the united states without duties
also being considered is suspension of alaskan oil shipments through a trans-panamanian pipeline, from which oil is delivered to u.s. markets on the east coast
on march 15, the united states is due to pay the $6.5 million monthly installment to the panama canal commission on the $75 million to $80 million paid out each year under the canal treaties
the sanctions are not something that we want to do, but something that we feel would be responsive and would be helpful, but it's not an action we take lightly,'' fitzwater said
delvalle has been in hiding for more than a week after attempting to fire noriega and being, in turn, dismissed by him
in statement issued at both the white house and state department on tuesday, the administration said it recognizes delvalle ``as he who now exercises the office of president.''
the statement welcomed declarations by delvalle and panamanian opposition parties on monday that called for the establishment of a ``government of national reconciliation.''
this is a blueprint for progress for democracy in panama,'' the u.s. statement said. ``we support their goal of restoring democratic government and civilian constitutional order. once this goal has been achieved, we will work cooperatively with the government of panama toward the recovery of panama's financial and economic health.''
fitzwater said the decision on possible sanctions depends upon ``a very complicated set of criteria.''
among them, he said, are the status of the noriega government and the impact that sanctions might have on u.s. interests in panama. he mentioned the canal and u.s. investments
in its unanimous vote, the foreign affairs committee endorsed reagan's course of action against the military regime as well as urging him to consider sanctions
the resolution will be voted on by the house this week. it reaffirms congressional support for the full implementation of the panama canal treaties, which require the united states to hand the canal over to panama at the end of the century
the senate foreign relations committee has adopted a resolution calling for a total trade embargo against panama, but several members of the house panel said they thought that approach was premature
in the networks' race to call super tuesday contests, nbc news incorrectly predicted that jesse jackson would win the north carolina democratic primary, then switched its pick to sen. albert gore jr. about an hour later
nbc declared jackson the winner shortly after the state's polls closed at 7:30 p.m. est, said spokeswoman mary lou o'callaghan. ``we made a mistake,'' she said. ``we retracted the projection and shortly afterward, we called gore.''
gore won with 35 percent, to jackson's 33 percent
o'callaghan said the projections are based on totals from the news election service, sample precincts and exit polling. ``we used the same criteria we use in making all our calls, and this one was just wrong,'' she said
mary fishbyrne, a 101-year-old politicial activist who hasn't missed voting since women were given that right, fumed because she couldn't vote for the man of her choice
why can't i vote for bush?'' a snippish voice said from behind the voting machine curtain on super tuesday
because you're registered as a democrat, miss mary,'' precinct commissioner betty shelton said apologetically. ``crossover voting isn't allowed in presidential primaries.''
i'm just miserable,'' came back the curtained voice. ``i'll vote for bush in november.''
she's kind of independent,'' shelton explained
if anything, mary fishbyrne is independent, brought up that way by her father on a south dakota farm before that state was admitted to the union
he raised us that way,'' she said. ``he had six daughters and was mad because we couldn't vote. he named my youngest sister after susan b. anthony _ you know she gave us the vote.''
miss fishbyrne's first vote came in 1921 near the virginia farm her father purchased when she was 12
i remember i didn't vote for hoover. he was the worst. he told us to mix our corn meal with flour to make it last. i never did know what he wanted to last the longest _ the corn meal or the flour. i'd rather have just a little of both.''
her favorite president was franklin roosevelt. ``he must have been, he had the most terms.''
miss fishbyrne, who was born aug. 18, 1886, was a seamstress and tailor for most of her adult life. since reaching age 65, she has been living with various relatives throughout the united states
she moved to shreveport in 1961 to live with a niece and they mostly vote republican, she said
we voted for reagan. i think bush will be pretty good.''
she said she can't understand why people don't get out and vote
i was 35 before i was allowed to vote and i know what it's like when you can't. it's a privilege some people don't appreciate.''
she never married because her fiance died shortly after her father was killed in a fall from a wagon
dad was so proud when my sisters and i went to vote. i'm the only one left. i'll vote as long as i have legs to walk.''
well, you've never missed an election here and we're going to have another one in april before the november election,'' shelton told her favorite voter
i'll be here,'' miss mary promised
lofti mansouri, head of the canadian opera in toronto, has been offered the job of general director of the san francisco opera
mansouri has been a leading candidate for the position since terence a. mcewen announced on feb. 9 that he would retire
they have offered it and i am considering it very seriously,'' mansouri said tuesday in a telephone interview from toronto. he said he would make a decision by friday
the san francisco opera association's board of directors on tuesday accepted the recomendation of a subcommittee and authorized that the job be offered to mansouri
mansouri, 58, a native of iran, has directed 31 productions for the san francisco opera on a visiting basis since 1963
wall street investor jitters eased enough to allow the closely watched dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks to rise to its highest level since the october market crash
the dow on tuesday finished up 24.70, to 2,081.07, the best post-crash close since 2,071.62 on feb. 29
analysts said the rally partly reflected a desire by managers of institutional investment funds to put unused money to work before they present their portfolios when the first quarter ends in three weeks
we're coming into show-and-tell time, the window-dressing period,'' said lawrence wachtel, an analyst at prudential bache securities inc. ``these guys can't sit there with piles of cash in a boiling market and not get called down by the people who pay them to manage money.''
takeover speculation and increased demand for high-yield and blue chip stocks also powered the rally
two stocks advanced for every one that fell on the new york stock exchange, where volume totaled 237.68 million shares, compared with 152.98 million in the previous session. victory</head> totals first 3 grafs; percentages unchanged.</note>
vice president george bush rocked bob dole's presidential hopes with a narrow primary victory in the gop senator's back yard, steamrolling to a super tuesday sweep
and democratic rep. richard gephardt, an overwhelming winner in his home state's first presidential primary, found it was his only victory of the night
in republican voting, with 3,851 of 3,954 precincts or 97 percent reporting, bush had 169,427 votes or 42 percent; kansas' dole had 164,646 votes or 41 percent; pat robertson had 44,379 votes or 11 percent; new york rep. jack kemp had 14,178 votes or 4 percent
in the democratic race, with 3,900 of 3,954 precincts or 99 percent reporting, gephardt had 290,289 votes or 60 percent; jesse jackson had 83,749 votes or 17 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 59,132 votes or 12 percent; illinois sen. paul simon had 20,095 votes or 4 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 14,284 votes or 3 percent
this has been absolutely wild,'' bush's missouri campaign director, randy enwright, said of the gop race. ``no matter what, we don't lose here.''
enwright and missouri bush supporter bill macon said dole needed to win big in missouri rather than just edge bush slightly in his neighbor state
sure, if it's close, that's good, but i really wanted to break dole's political back here,'' macon said
dole accused bush of trying to deliver a ``knockout punch'' in missouri by canceling stops in other states while bush said dole probably thought he ``could dust me off'' in missouri since it was next to dole's homestate of kansas
lee atwater, bush's national campaign manager, said dole would be in trouble if he lost missouri
bob dole has repeatedly said missouri is his most important state. he's been here more than anyone else and spent more money. he's practically campaigned as a favorite son candidate. he's sure going to be rocking and reeling if he loses here,'' atwater said
while bush and dole fought for the lion's share of the 47 gop delegates at stake, gephardt, a congressman from the st. louis area, overwhelmed the 11 other democrats listed on the ballot, competing for 77 convention delegates
it's been a one-man show from the beginning,'' said missouri democratic party chairman betty hearnes. ``we just haven't seen anybody else.'' whites</head>
an overwhelming black vote carried jesse jackson to victory over tennessee sen. albert gore in georgia's democratic presidential primary, while vice president george bush crushed kansas sen. bob dole
with 2,461 of 2,571 precincts or 96 percent reporting early today, jackson had 235,088 votes or 39 percent; gore had 194,824 votes or 33 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 93,442 votes or 16 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 40,658 votes or 7 percent, and former colorado sen. gary hart had 15,384 votes or 3 percent
in the republican race, with 2,398 of 2,571 precincts or 93 percent reporting, bush had 188,512 votes or 53 percent; dole had 81,647 votes or 23 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 57,901 votes or 16 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 21,662 votes or 6 percent
gore had won the backing of sen. sam nunn, gov. joe frank harris and state house speaker tom murphy
but jackson scored big in georgia's 5th congressional district, composed largely of atlanta, where he beat both gore and dukakis by better than 8-to-1
according to abc news exit polls, jackson won 95 percent of georgia's black democratic vote, and added 10 percent of the state's white democratic votes. he even picked up 117 votes in forsyth county, the virtually all-white site of racial violence and civil rights marches in 1987
atlanta mayor andrew young, like jackson a veteran of the civil rights movement, said the strong showings by jackson and gore ``are probably good for the south. both jesse and al gore represent where the south is.''
the republicans had 48 delegates up for grabs. the democrats offered 77 delegates to their convention in atlanta in july
robertson, who watched the returns in atlanta, vowed that he is still a contender
this is not the end,'' he told supporters. ``this is just the beginning. we're going to new orleans. ... i'm in all the way. i'm in to see a republican conservative congress in 1990, and we're in for the presidential race in 1992.''
attorney general edwin meese iii is rejecting a request by 11 democrats on the house judiciary committee that he temporarily step down until pending federal investigations into his conduct have been completed
this is an old idea, a politically partisan idea and a thoroughly bad idea,'' meese's chief spokesman, terry eastland, said tuesday after being informed of the request. ``no one should be urged to step down from a government position simply because that person is under investigation.''
the democrats said in their letter, ``we strongly believe that your increasing inability to spend time on the day-to-day demands of your job, the deteriorating morale at the department of justice, and the continuing cloud over your office are undermining your ability to act effectively as the nation's chief law enforcement officer.''
meese has been under criminal investigation by independent counsel james mckay since last may 11. mckay has been examining meese's involvement with scandal-plagued wedtech corp., and with a $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline project. mckay also has been examining the attorney general's involvement with the regional bell telephone companies at a time when he owned $14,000 in phone stock
in addition, independent counsel lawrence walsh, investigating the iran-contra affair, has called meese before a grand jury numerous times
eastland said meese ``has every intention of serving to the end of this term.''
he has spent some time with his lawyers on the investigation, but there has been no serious subtraction of his time or effort from leadership of the department of justice,'' eastland said
the letter said the pending investigations ``detract from the time required to properly administer the department of justice.''
the pervasive perception that you have allowed personal considerations to encroach on your constitutional responsibilities threatens to breed contempt for your office, your administration and the rule of law itself,'' the lawmakers said
the letter was signed by reps. dan glickman, kan.; edward feighan, ohio; howard berman, calif.; barney frank, mass.; bruce morrison, conn.; lawrence smith, fla.; harley staggers jr., w. va.; john conyers, mich.; george crockett jr., mich.; mike synar, okla.; and patricia schroeder, colo
thousands of mourners attended the funerals of three israelis killed in a palestinian terrorist attack, many sobbing uncontrollably as relatives threw themselves on the coffins of their beloved
such killings ... only strengthen our lust for and link to this land, to this country,'' prime minister yitzhak shamir told the 5,000 israelis who attended the services tuesday
services were held for the three residents of this southern negev desert town who were killed monday, when three palestinian guerrillas hijacked a commuter bus. nine israelis were wounded
anti-terrorist police stormed the bus three hours after the hijacking and 15 minutes after the guerrilla leader shot to death victor ran, 39, a widower and father of three children
the guerrillas, from yasser arafat's mainstream fatah branch of the palestine liberation organization, were killed during the 30-second rescue operation
two israelis, rina shiratzky, 31, a mother of two, and miriam ben yair, 46, mother of four, were fatally wounded in the rescue
the guerrillas were demanding freedom for hundreds of palestinians held in israeli jails on rioting charges
we have to hold responsible all the countries in the region, the arab states from where the murderers came and where you read and hear today in the media praises for this murder,'' shamir said
the war of the jewish people for their land, the land of israel, is not over .... despite our tremendous longing for peace, there are still people _ if they might be called human beings _ who are after our blood,'' he said
family members of the dead threw themselves on the coffins, screaming in grief and clutching the lids. many in the crowd sobbed as they gazed at the coffins, which had been placed on a sunlit podium
maj. gen yitzhak mordechai, chief of the army's central command who headed the rescue operation, also spoke at the funerals
we promise today near their coffins not to rest in continuing the holy enterprise of mantaining security along the borders of israel and within the country,'' mordechai said
the murderers have found their death yesterday. some day we will reach those who sent them.'' memorial</head>
a measure that would let a memorial to the black veterans of the revolutionary war be built in the most-traveled tourist area of washington has won subcommittee approval, but the house has just four weeks to act
a vote by the house interior and insular affairs subcommittee on national parks and public lands followed pleas tuesday by historians, black activists and the reagan administration
the patriots memorial is not a war memorial; it is not an ethnic memorial,'' said maurice a. barboza, a virginia lawyer who has been the driving force behind the project. ``as a memorial to the struggle for freedom, it will stand as a universal symbol to define for generations to come our american nationality, which is based on principles rather than on pigmentation.''
the subcommittee also approved, without discussion, locating a planned korean war memorial in the city's prime tourist area
last year, president reagan signed into law a measure pushed by barboza that authorizes a black patriots memorial in washington
but barboza, formerly of plainville, conn., and rep. nancy l. johnson, r-conn., whom he enlisted to carry on the fight in congress, want the memorial in a prominent place, a move that requires another layer of administrative and legislative approvals
last november, interior secretary donald p. hodel declared that barboza's proposal had ``pre-eminent historical and lasting significance to the nation.'' that finding is needed to place a memorial in the city's monument-filled area i, which includes the mall, the ellipse, lafayette park and west potomac park
the senate has approved the siting resolution, but the house only has until april 7 to take action. without congressional approval, the memorial cannot be placed in area i
robert k. wright, an army historian, said most history books ignored the role of the estimated 5,000 blacks who served in the continental army
even if the area i legislation is accepted, proponents still would have to go back to the interior department, commission of fine arts and the national capital planning commission to get specific siting and design approval
barboza, who quit his job as a lobbyist for the american bar association to work on the memorial project full time, envisions a ``modest'' memorial nestled in constitution gardens, a grassy area near both the lincoln memorial and washington monument
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,605.39 points, up 139.66 points, on the tokyo stock exchange wednesday
the nation's firefighters are incensed by a federal law that could require them to obtain commercial licenses if they want to continue to drive their equipment
the commercial vehicle safety act of 1986, which is being phased in starting this year, will require commercial licenses of anyone who operates a vehicle that weighs 26,000 pounds or more, carries 15 or more people or transports hazardous materials
but associations representing many of the nation's 225,000 paid and 900,000 volunteer firefighters say the law was meant to foster safety in the commercial trucking business, not impose costly new rules on their members
tim butters, a spokesman for the international association of fire chiefs, said tuesday, ``the burden on the fire service is going to be very significant when this law goes through because of the road test that they're going to have to go through, the (written) examination, and i think there's going to be a lot of cost factors.''
stanley hamilton of the federal highway administration said the licensing regulations won't be ready until july 15, and they will be phased in through 1992. the law also will affect farmers who drive heavy equipment, and hamilton said his agency has been inundated with protest mail from farm communities
under the law, the secretary of transportation may issue waivers ``with respect to class of persons or class of vehicles,'' but hamilton said requests for exemptions would not be considered until the regulations are written
rep. sherwood boehlert, r-n.y., wrote to transportation secretary james burnley last week to ask that firefighters be exempted from the commercial license requirement
let's solve the problem with truckers, not create new ones for firefighters,'' boehlert said tuesday. ``volunteer fire companies are people who are farmers, lawyers, they work in the factory and they volunteer their time and services to the fire department. now this regulation, if it's enforced, would require these people to spend about $400 to get a commercial license ... when there's no evidence whatsoever that firefighters are creating any safety problems on our nation's highways.''
federal legislation introduced last week in the house by rep. jim slattery, d-kan., and the senate by sen. david karnes, r-neb., would exempt the drivers of fire trucks and farm vehicles that are driven less than 15,000 miles a year
francis a. mcgarry, new york state fire administrator, estimated that it would cost $58 million to commercially license 95,000 of the state's 165,000 firefighters
he put test fees at $350, a physical exam at about $150, ``and that's without even including the time a volunteer has to take off from work to go and do this.'' 
a 40-year-old bomb exploded and killed a boy and two other people in central henan province when the boy tried to open it, thinking the explosives inside had medicinal value, the official china daily said today
it said wei shuangxi, a farmer living near sanmenxia city, found the bomb while digging for medicinal herbs last year
on feb. 19, a boy playing at wei's home tried to chop the end off the bomb, thinking the explosives inside could cure diseases, and the bomb went off, killing the boy, wei and one other person, the newspaper said
the report gave no details of the bomb. forty years ago, the communist red army and the nationalists were waging a civil war that ended in 1949 with the communist forces gaining control of the mainland
jesse jackson, buoyed by a big turnout in the heavily black delta, sailed to a decisive victory in mississippi's presidential primary, while vice president george bush blew away other gop challengers like a gulf hurricane
voters on tuesday also set up a november matchup of two popular congressmen for the seat of retiring sen. john c. stennis
with 2,268 of 2,340 precincts or 97 percent reporting, jackson had 162,431 or 45 percent and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 120,708 or 33 percent. massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 31,188 or 9 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 19,811 votes or 5 percent; and former colorado sen. gary hart had 12,748 votes or 4 percent
in the republican race, with 2,249 of 2,340 precincts or 96 percent reporting, bush had 103,094 votes or 66 percent to kansas sen. bob dole's 26,287 or 17 percent. former tv evangelist pat robertson had 21,017 or 13 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 5,782 or 4 percent
based on those returns, jackson would get 23 delegates to 16 for gore and one for dukakis. bush would secure 27 gop delegates, with two each for dole and robertson
we knew we were going to do well ... but we didn't think we'd do this well overall, or in mississippi,'' said eric kimbrough, executive director of the state's bush campaign. ``we believe this is a resounding victory for us.''
u.s. rep. wayne dowdy, a democrat who jumped in the u.s. senate race the day after stennis, 86, retired in october, defeated secretary of state dick molpus, 38, by a comfortable margin. stennis is retiring after 41 years in the senate
polls rate a contest between liberal dowdy and conservative republican trent lott a toss-up
it will take a united democratic party to beat him,'' dowdy said. ``it can be won, and things are ripe for the democrats to win in november. mississippi should have at least one democrat in the u.s. senate.''
early polls had shown dowdy, 44, trailing molpus, who recently won re-election to a new four-year statehouse term. the two tussled over dowdy's voting record, which molpus said was among the five poorest based on attendance in the house
i think that hurt me a little, and it hurt him a little, too, but going into the final days we felt very confident,'' dowdy said. ``we said we would get about 55 percent, and that's the way it turned out.''
in lightly contested democratic primaries, 24-term rep. jamie whitten and mike espy, the state's first black congressman since reconstruction, were overwhelming winners
runoffs appeared certain in both parties for the 4th and 5th district seats given up by dowdy and lott, respectively. they will be held march 29
five self-proclaimed lesbians were arrested for chaining themselves to buckingham palace's gates to protest the government's plan to stop giving public funds to homosexual groups
police cut the women free from the gates after a half-hour and took them into custody
the demonstrators said their action tuesday coincided with the 70th anniversary of suffragettes doing the same in the campaign to win votes for women. twelve female supporters, some in victorian clothing, paraded on the sidewalk
the demonstration was against a government bill that would make local councils stop funding homosexual groups or promoting homosexuality as a legitimate lifestyle
we chose the palace because the bill will have to gain royal assent next month before it becomes law,'' said one of the women, who refused to give her name
vice president george bush's lopsided victory in kentucky's gop primary surprised even his staunchest supporters, while tennessee sen. albert gore jr. also won big in his neighbor state
bush captured 71,912 votes, or 59 percent of the gop total tuesday, according to unofficial returns with 3,235 of 3,237 precincts, or 99 percent, reporting. the vote apparently won 27 of the 38 delegates up for grabs
i think bush is unstoppable after this. i think he clinched the presidency today,'' said u.s. rep. harold rogers, bush's state campaign chairman, who said he had predicted bush would win 48 percent of the vote
kansas sen. robert dole finished second with 27,844 votes, 23 percent of the total. he apparently won 11 delegates
no other republican crossed the 15 percent threshold to win any delegates
with 3,241 of 3,243 democratic precincts reporting, gore received 150,286 votes, or 46 percent. because of the way delegates are apportioned, though, he apparently won 37 of the 55 available democratic delegates, or 67 percent
al gore is right for kentucky; he's right for america. we're just now starting the momentum in this campaign,'' said gov. wallace wilkinson, gore's leading supporter in the state
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis ran second in kentucky with 59,457 votes, or 18 percent, and was slated for 12 delegates
only the jesse jackson among other democrats was able to make the threshold and win delegates. jackson received 49,655 votes, or 15 percent, to earn six delegates
among other republicans, former tv evangelist pat robertson received 13,538 votes, or 11 percent. no other republican broke 2 percent
missouri congressman richard gephardt received 29,048 votes, or 9 percent. no other democrat received more than 4 percent
jesse jackson built his triumphs in the south's super tuesday primaries by piling a 10 percent share of the white vote on top of a near sweep of black votes
it was jackson's finest hour in two runs for the presidency and he said it gave him ``a sense of joy ... and a sense of victory.''
we're now in a dead-heat contest running for the nomination of our party,'' he told abc news from houston tuesday night. ``it shows that america is getting stronger and better, but also that in the south, my message began to break through: stop drugs, save jobs and invest in our children.''
jackson demonstrated anew what he had shown earlier in such states as iowa, maine and vermont, where only a tiny share of the population is black: he is now able to attract a significant share of white votes
he has also benefited from changes in the party delegate selection rules he complained so bitterly about in 1984, when he won 18 percent of the popular vote but wound up with only 12 percent of the delegates
and this time out, jackson didn't have to share the black vote with walter mondale
blacks made up nearly 25 percent of the electorate in the south, and exit polls by abc news indicated jackson got 95 percent or more of their votes
abc polls said jackson had about 10 percent of the white vote in the south, while the cbs news-new york times poll said he had 8 percent. nbc figures ranged from 4 percent in tennessee to 15 percent in virginia and 19 percent in massachusetts
at a virtually all-black precinct in mobile county, ala., jackson got 1,837 votes to second-place albert gore jr.'s 31. in macon county, about 90 percent black, jackson led with 2,540 to gore's 43
overall, according to abc's polls, jackson got 6 percent of the white alabama vote and 96 percent of the black vote. by comparison, four years earlier, jackson got 1 percent of the white vote and 55 percent of the black vote in alabama
likewise, in florida, where jackson managed 1 percent of the white vote and 58 percent of the black vote in 1984, he pulled in 7 percent of the white vote and 82 percent of the black vote tuesday, said abc. its exit polls had a 5-point margin of error in either direction
frank dexter brown, associate director of communications for the joint center for political studies, a black-oriented think tank based in washington, said tuesday jackson has been defying expectations all along this year with his showings in new england, minnesota and iowa
jackson got 28 percent of the vote in maine compared to 1 percent four years earlier. he also got 28 percent in vermont, 20 percent in a second-place finish in minnesota, 11 percent in the iowa caucuses and 8 percent in new hampshire
most national polls have given jackson 4 percent to 5 percent of the white vote
a survey last august by the joint center for political studies found 80 percent of blacks and 10 percent of whites supported jackson
blacks comprise about 11 percent of all americans of voting age
since delegates are awarded by congressional district, not statewide, it is still possible for a candidate to wind up with a smaller share of delegates in some states than his popular vote
but jackson stood to profit from the lower threshold of votes needed in each congressional district to gain delegates. it was 20 percent in 1984; now it is 15 percent
voters polled by abc gave jackson high marks for his ability to handle foreign affairs, protect the poor and elderly and hold down unemployment
among those who voted in democratic primaries, 29 percent said they definitely would not vote for jackson for president; 45 percent nixed republican pat robertson; 37 percent ruled out george bush and 36 percent said no to democrat gary hart. his three main democratic rivals, michael dukakis, gore and richard gephardt, were ruled out by 12 percent to 14 percent. 10th graf pvs, ``it isn't. should stand for ams</note>
vice president george bush declared tuesday, ``i'm going to be the next president of the united states,'' as he overwhelmed sen. bob dole in lopsided republican voting. dole sought to deflect the shock while the presidential aspirations of jack kemp and pat robertson were dealt shattering blows
robertson kept bush from a super tuesday shutout, winning the washington caucuses
but it was a small loss for bush, who was triumphant in the 16 remaining states that held gop primaries tuesday
bush was leading for 571 of the 712 delegates up for grabs
this is a unique political happening,'' an elated bush told cheering campaign workers in houston. ``it exceeded my fondest expectations.''
a more subdued dole told his supporters in chicago: ``tomorrow we will be on the road to recovery.''
dole, shutout in the south, turned his sights north, to the illinois primary next tuesday, where he hoped to stage a comeback. ``i want to congratulate the vice president ... he'll probably sleep better tonight than i will,'' he said. ``we'll take turns.''
dole's campaign chairman, william brock, acknowledged that the campaign had suffered a serious defeat. ``the psychological hit is very heavy,'' he said
tuesday's voting appeared to put the other two gop candidates, kemp and robertson, well out of contention for the party nomination
robertson continued to show strength in state caucuses with his win in washington. he vowed to fight on
it isn't too bad for an amateur, but it's not near what i expected,'' robertson said. he suggested he might win the illinois primary and asserted, ``i do have resources left. we have the largest donor base of any candidate and i can carry all the way to new orleans.''
robertson offered his congratulations to bush and said, ``he ran a superb campaign.''
bush won decisive victories all over, capturing more than 50 percent of the vote in many states, including delegate-rich florida and texas
the vice president also scored big wins in tennessee, kentucky, georgia, alabama, virginia, mississippi, louisiana, arkansas, north carolina, maryland, massachusetts and rhode island. in oklahoma and missouri, the margin was much closer, but bush hung on to win.
dole had pinned his southern hopes on north carolina, the home state of his wife, elizabeth
at stake tuesday were 712 delegates to the republican national convention. virginia was alone among the 17 gop contests holding a ``beauty contest'' that awards no delegates. it takes 1,139 votes for the nomination
bush led for 571, giving him 698 when combined with the delegates he won in earlier contests. dole led for 100, a total of 165. robertson was getting 10 for a total 18. kemp led for 4 for a total 39
bush's national campaign chairman, lee atwater, predicted that bush would pick up more than 600 delegates _ a gain that would give him a near-unassailable lead toward winning the gop presidential nomination
i would certainly hate to be in sen. dole's shoes after tonight and especially if he loses in illinois,'' atwater said
the dole campaign had sought to keep bush from picking up more than 500 delegates
dole hoped to wage a come-from-behind effort in midwestern and western states. he said earlier in springfield, ill., ``if we take a little bath today, i am going to start my road to recovery in illinois just like i did 40 years ago.''
he was referring to his recuperation in an illinois hospital from wounds suffered during world war ii
kemp and robertson were far outdistanced by bush and dole. kemp trailed robertson in most southern states, and was expected to drop out by week's end. for robertson, the voting throughout the south was a replay of his third place finish in saturday's south carolina primary, when he could muster no more than about 20 percent of the vote
bush voted in houston, and then told reporters, ``if we exceed our expectations or live up to them, i think we'll be in good shape.''
it's going to be a little tougher as we go along, but i've been in tough fights before,'' dole acknowledged at a morning news conference in kansas city, mo
he then traveled to illinois and immediately challenged bush to a series of debates _ ``one-on-one, without moderator'' _ in that state, which holds its primary next tuesday
if bob dole was so serious about debating, he would have shown up for the (feb. 19) dallas morning news debate,'' bush spokesman pete teeley said. ``we have a strategy which has been highly successful and we plan to pursue it, and that doesn't include having one-on-one debates with bob dole.''
the senate minority leader, a 1980 presidential contender and gop vice presidential candidate in 1976, was reportedly spending $500,000 on television advertising in illinois
a defeat there could all but end dole's presidential efforts and a strong showing for the kanasan was by no means assured. bush is backed by illinois gov. james thompson and 93 of the state's 102 republican county chairmen
kemp, dead last in the south carolina primary last weekend, had not been expected to see that flagging effort revived in tuesday's voting. aides said the new york lawmaker and former pro-football star would reassess his race later in the week. he was expected to pull out
robertson's chances as a serious contender seemed likely to be all but ended if his losses in super tuesday states were as decisive as his third-place finish in south carolina, where he won only 19 percent of the vote
robertson's candidacy came to life with his strong second-place finish the iowa caucuses on feb. 8. but in the primaries that followed, his strength ebbed
riot police fired birdshot and tear gas to disperse demonstrators who blocked streets with hundreds of trash fires to protest the country's military rule and its tottering economy
the demonstrations tuesday were the largest since president eric arturo delvalle was deposed feb. 26, just hours after he tried to fire gen. manuel antonio noriega
noriega, chief of panama's 15,000-member defense forces, is considered the real power behind the country's civilian government
reporters saw at least eight protesters captured, beaten with rubber truncheons and fists and driven away in military vehicles
a photographer for the mexico city newspaper excelsior was slightly injured by birdshot fired by police
the national civic crusade, which has organized demonstrations calling for noriega's ouster since last june, said at least 23 people were detained. by late tuesday, all but two had been released
it was another black day for panama,'' said aurelio barria, president of the panama chamber of commerce, industry and agriculture. ``when the people of panama go into the streets, they get repressed,'' he told reporters tuesday night
we are in the hands of armed terrorists,'' barria added, referring to the noriega regime
barria is a director of the crusade, a broad coalition of business, professional, labor, student and political organizations opposed to noriega
small groups of protesters erected barricades across hundreds of streets in the central and eastern parts of the city tuesday afternoon, snarling traffic and forcing many businesses to shut down early
riot police were out in force, but they could not keep up with the hundreds of demonstrators, many of whom stepped out of their homes and shops to hurl plastic bags of garbage into the streets then quickly ran back inside
other protesters, mostly roving bands of youths, set fire to piles of debris and built barricades of burning tires, dry palm fronds, wooden signs, boulders and anything else they could lug into the streets
some tried to throw rocks at police but could not reach their targets. when police appeared, groups ran a few blocks then set up another barricade
the stench of burning garbage and the acrid smell of tear gas wafted over large parts of the city as the demonstrations, and the government's attempts to halt them, continued into the evening
smouldering rubbish still littered the streets of this tropical capital late tuesday night, but demonstrators had dispersed
the protests came on the seventh day of a bank shutdown that has crippled commerce. most businesses were not accepting checks or credit cards, only cash
depositors began a run on panamanian-owned and -operated banks the day delvalle was dismissed
the 12 locally owned banks closed march 1 during a nationwide general strike called by noriega's opponents. the banks opened briefly but the government ordered them shut again last thursday because of a lack of cash
in miami, a u.s. district judge froze panamanian assets in banks there after a suit was filed tuesday to prevent noriega's government from withdrawing official monies. a similar order was issued last week in new york city and another suit was filed tuesday in boston
the united states continues to recognize delvalle as panama's president. it has been calling for noriega's removal since his indictment in florida in february on federal drug trafficking charges
delvalle has been in hiding in panama since noriega orchestrated his ouster by the legislative assembly
jorge abadia, panama's foreign minister, on tuesday accused the united states of conducting ``the prelude of an armed invasion'' by staging military exercises along the panama canal
but the u.s. southern command said the exercises, involving nearly 700 soldiers from u.s. military installations in panama and u.s. national guard troops from florida and puerto rico, were scheduled a year ago. the command said the exercises, which began last weekend, are ``routine training.''
dennis mcauliffe, administrator of the panama canal commission, said on tuesday that the waterway was operating normally despite the strain that the tension between the united states and panama has created for canal workers
support from key democratic figures pushed tennessee sen. albert gore jr. past jesse jackson in north carolina's presidential primary, while victorious vice president george bush stressed his ties to president reagan
gore's victory tuesday showed voters ``trusted him on defense, believed he was committed to jobs and economic growth, and they trusted him to be fiscally responsible,'' said former gov. jim hunt, who with sen. terry sanford endorsed gore in january
with 2,373 of 2,387 precincts or 99 percent reporting, gore had 234,595 votes or 35 percent; jackson had 222,494 votes or 33 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 136,459 votes or 20 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 37,854 votes or 6 percent, and former colorado sen. gary hart had 16,506 votes or 2 percent
in the republican race, with 2,374 of 2,387 precincts or 99 percent reporting: bush had 123,781 votes or 45 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 109,678 votes or 40 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 26,583 votes or 10 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 11,348 votes or 4 percent
gore was expected to take 34 of the state's 82 democratic delegates, with jackson getting 31 and dukakis 17. bush was expected to take 29 of the state's 54 delegates and dole 25
bush held off a late surge by dole, who targeted north carolina in his effort to avoid a southern shutout. during an all-day swing across the state saturday, bush said he was worried because polls had indicated the contest was neck-and-neck
the popularity of dole's wife, former transportation secretary elizabeth dole, in her native state helped but not enough, observers said. ``you have to remember that mrs. dole is not on the ticket,'' said joan shaffer, co-chairman of bush's wake county organization
a republican candidate has to carry the south,'' said jack hawke, the state gop chairman. ``what george bush has shown is that he is strong in the south. ... people are associating him with the president.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and vice president george bush built vigorous campaigns on already strong personal ties to score resounding victories in rhode island's presidential primaries
our mission has been accomplished,'' said gov. edward d. diprete, who repaid bush's campaign journeys to the state with strong backing. ``there is really a bush blastout tonight all over the country.''
bush, a new england native, swept his chief rival, kansas sen. bob dole, in 16 states around the country in the super tuesday primaries
in the democratic race, with 100 percent of 320 precincts reporting, dukakis amassed 34,159 votes or 70 percent, making his victory even bigger than that of another bay stater, sen. edward kennedy, in the 1980 primary
jesse jackson was a distant second with 7,369 votes or 15 percent, followed by missouri rep. richard gephardt with 2,013 votes or 4 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. with 1,932 votes or 4 percent; illinois sen. paul simon with 1,392 votes or 3 percent and gary hart with 738 votes or 2 percent
among republicans, with 319 of 320 precincts or 99 percent reporting, bush won 10,403 votes or 65 percent, trailed by dole with 3,637 votes or 23 percent; pat robertson with 921 votes or 6 percent and rep. jack kemp, 783 votes or 5 percent
based on those results, bush would likely capture 15 gop delegates and dole would win six, while dukakis would gain 19 democratic delegates and jackson three
dukakis, as the governor of a neighboring state, was a familiar face to rhode islanders long before he began running for president. he campaigned here several times and quickly picked up support from most of rhode island's democratic hierarchy
providence mayor joseph r. paolino jr., state chairman of the dukakis campaign, said the governor's win was even more impressive than kennedy's victory over president carter in the 1980 democratic primary
kennedy ``had about 65 to 67 percent of the vote in a two-man race,'' paolino said. ``this is a five-man race.''
jackson supporters broke out champagne to celebrate their candidate's strong showing in a state that is only 2 percent black
amnesty international today accused philippines forces under president corazon aquino's government of unlawfully killing left-wing foes and people suspected of supporting that nation's 19-year communist insurgency
the london-based human rights organization called on the aquino government to end the killings by military and paramilitary forces, saying the slayings represented the philippines' most serious human rights problem since mid-1987
there was no immediate response from the aquino government
last month the president accused the communists of using charges of human rights abuses as a smokescreen to discredit the military and draw attention away from rebel actions
in manila today, task force-detainees _ a private, social activist group supported by the roman catholic church _ said the number of illegal arrests in the philippines had increased since the february 1986 collapse of president ferdinand marcos' authoritarian regime
spokesman noel salazar said his group's investigations showed that 7,444 people were illegally detained or arrested in 1987, and of that number 602 were tortured. he said that in 1985, the last full year of the marcos administration, 5,967 people were illegally detained
mrs. aquino promised to restore human rights when she succeeded marcos on feb. 25, 1986, after a military-civilian uprising drove marcos into exile
the amnesty report said most victims were singled out because they either belonged to legal, left-wing organizations or were suspected of backing the new people's army, the armed wing of the communist party of the philippines
it said their killers belonged to the regular military and police forces, paramilitary civil defense forces and community-based vigilante groups acting with government support
the aquino government has sanctioned formation of more than 200 civilian anti-communist vigilante groups, some of which have forged alliances with armed religious fanatics, or tadtads. many of the vigilante groups have been armed by the military. church and human rights organizations have accused the vigilantes of murder, intimidation and other abuses
amnesty said it did not know of one military or police officer who was convicted and sentenced for such political killings or for any other serious human rights offense since mrs. aquino assumed office
it praised the aquino government for ``some very real progress'' in human rights, particularly in restoring legal safeguards and in greatly reducing the use of torture. but it called on the government to reaffirm publicly its commitment to protect human rights
many killings reported to amnesty followed acts of violence by communist rebels in which civilians and military personnel were killed, the report said
it argued that crimes by opposition groups ``can never be used to justify unlawful retaliatory killings by agents of the government'' supposed to uphold the law
amnesty cited scores of cases of filipino men, women and children shot to death since mid-1987
among the cases cited were:
_17 villagers, including six children, killed by soldiers in february 1987 in apparent reprisal after troops were ambushed in lupao, nueva ecija province
_a 29-year-old peasant activist, his wife and two small children, hacked to death after masked members of a civil defense unit were seen entering their home in magpet, north cotobato, in may 1987
_a 28-year-old farm worker, mutilated and beheaded in front of a neighbor by members of a vigilante group in kabankalan in southern negros occidental in june 1987
the report said the aquino government responded swiftly to many highly publicized killings by setting up task forces to conduct official inquiries. it said many less well-known cases were handled by the commission on human rights or its predecessor
but amnesty said official investigations of such killings rarely led to prosecutions for reasons that included fear on the part of witnesses, lack of cooperation from the military and apparent lack of impartiality by military courts, which have jurisdiction over cases involving soldiers and police
amnesty expressed concern about occasional reports of torture and about the fate of campaigners for left-wing political parties who disappeared after allegedly being abducted by military personnel following may 1986 congressional elections
the super tuesday primaries produced a blizzard of numbers. here are some figures from exit polls conducted by abc news in a dozen southern states that help provide a snapshot of who voted how:
_ white voters were narrowly split between michael dukakis and albert gore jr., 34 percent to 33 percent. but jesse jackson's 10 percent share of the white vote helped him roll to victory in several deep south states
_ black voters favored jackson by margins of 95 percent or higher
_ hispanics gave 42 percent of their votes to dukakis, 23 percent to jackson
_ protestants favored gore over jackson, 31 percent to 27 percent
_ catholics went with dukakis by 45 percent to jackson's 16 percent
_ jewish voters picked dukakis by 78 percent to gore's 11 percent. jackson had three percent of the jewish vote, as did richard gephardt
_ born-again christians picked jackson by 40 percent to gore's 29 percent. but among only white born-again christians, gore got 46 percent to dukakis's 22 percent and jackson's eight percent. jackson got 96 percent of the black born-again vote. evangelicals sided with dukakis, 27 percent, over gore, 22 percent, and jackson, 21 percent
_ about a third of democratic primary voters in the south had pulled the lever for ronald reagan in 1984. they favored gore (35 percent) over dukakis (25 percent), gephardt (15 percent) and jackson (12 percent)
_ pat robertson was the candidate with the highest negatives among democratic voters. forty-five percent said they definitely would not vote for him. thirty-seven percent expressed the same sentiment about george bush, 36 percent about gary hart and 29 percent about jackson
_ eighty-two percent of democratic voters said the next president should change the course set by reagan; among them, 33 percent were for jackson, 29 percent dukakis and 22 percent gore. among the 18 percent who want the next president to follow reagan's course, 38 percent were for gore, 21 percent for dukakis and 16 percent for jackson
_ dukakis commanded 75 percent of the greek-american vote, and 70 percent of the italian-americans
_ forty-seven percent of farmers went for dukakis; so did 39 percent of the feminists
_ five percent of the voters were from union households. thirty-seven percent of them went for jackson, 31 percent for dukakis and 22 percent for gore
_ nearly a quarter said the national economy was the overriding issue, and they went with dukakis by 35 percent to 24 percent for jackson and 20 percent for gore
_ the youngest voters and those in their 50s were george bush's biggest supporters. those age 18-24 favored bush over dole by 73 percent to 11 percent, while those in their 50s picked him by 65 percent to 14 percent
_ dole's worst showing was among high school graduates and dropouts, where he trailed bush by 60-17; his best was among those with more than four years of college, where he narrowed the gap to 50-33
_ among protestants, bush beat dole 58-21, with robertson claiming 17 percent and kemp 3 percent. among catholics, bush trounced dole, 72-21, with kemp getting 6 percent
_ among born-again christians, bush beat robertson, 46-33, with dole third at 14 percent and kemp at 5 percent. among white born-agains, bush was the choice, 44-34, over robertson. among evangelicals, bush was the choice by 48-28 over dole, with robertson third at 18 percent and kemp last at 5 percent
_ among the five percent of republican voters who owned up to voting for walter mondale in 1984, dole was the choice by 33-30 over bush, with robertson at 17 percent and kemp at 13 percent
_ among reagan voters, bush walloped dole, 62-19, with robertson getting 14 percent and kemp 4 percent
_ robertson got eight percent of the votes of those who called themselves liberals or moderates, but 16 percent of the conservatives. his conservative votes came at dole's expense
_ robertson was near the top of the republican voters' list of candidates they definitely would not vote for. forty-two percent mentioned hart; 41 percent said robertson and jackson; 23 percent simon and 21 percent dukakis
_ seventy-nine percent wanted to stay the reagan course; they favored bush 64-17 over dole, with 13 percent for robertson and 5 percent for dole. among the 21 percent who want a change, bush led dole 47-38, with 10 percent for robertson and 3 percent for kemp
_ republican voters from union households picked dole with 56 percent over bush and robertson, both 22 percent
_ among those who considered the candidates' stands on abortion crucial, robertson tied bush with 40 percent
_ eighty percent of jews went for bush, 20 percent for dole
the abc exit polls had a standard margin of error of five points in either direction. abc interviewed voters as they exited 690 precincts around the super tuesday states. it questioned at least 1,000 voters in each republican primary state and 700 in the democratic primaries
many of these results were based on an extended questionnaire given to voters at 50 precincts across the south
pat robertson, supported by troops of energetic fundamentalists, marched to his sole super tuesday victory by pushing past kansas sen. bob dole and vice president george bush in washington state's republican caucuses
with 3,683 of 6,594 precincts reporting, the former tv evangelist picked up 4,659 votes or 38 percent. dole had 3,245 or 27 percent, and bush came in third _ his only loss of the night _ with 2,958 or 24 percent
new york rep. jack kemp was a weak fourth with 906 or 7 percent
we'll take it!'' robertson's state organizer, bruce hawkins, cried as the results rolled in
to claim their share of the state's 41 gop delegates, the candidates will have to fare as well in this spring's county or legislative district caucuses, which precede the july 15 state convention where delegates will be allocated
state republican chairwoman jennifer dunn said the proportions set caucus night traditionally hold up throughout the delegate selection process
in early results for the democrats, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, endorsed by gov. booth gardner, had 45 percent and jesse jackson 32 percent. tennessee sen. albert gore jr. received the votes of 7 percent of those democrats represented in the party's sample of statewide precinct voting. ten percent were undecided
at stake were 73 democratic delegates. however, final democratic results were not expected for a week
as many as 220,000 registered voters, or 10 percent of those eligible, were expected to take part in caucuses that represented the first step toward electing the west's second largest bloc of national convention delegates
super tuesday rocked the presidential aspirations of bob dole and richard gephardt, who just a month ago were basking in their first-place victories in the iowa caucuses
it also appeared to claim at least one immediate casualty, republican jack kemp, whose expected withdrawal from the race could come as early as today. the future of democrat gary hart's campaign also seemed dim
republican dole and democrat gephardt vowed to press on. but both were clearly shaken by poor showings in the largest-ever round of primary contests
i never told you it was going to be easy,'' gephardt said after winning only his home state of missouri
i don't give up very easily,'' said dole, who came away from super tuesday with no wins and few delegates
republican pat robertson and democrat paul simon also said they would stay in the race, at least for now, despite disappointing showings in their respective primary races on tuesday
robertson _ who consistently beat only kemp throughout the native south that he claimed as his base of support _ said he ``didn't frankly have the concentration i should have had in key states.'' he didn't come close in any of the 16 gop primaries, but did win washington's caucuses
but the former television evangelist, who three weeks ago told a new hampshire audience ``i assure you that i am going to be the next president,'' said his super tuesday showing ``isn't too bad for an amateur.''
he said, ``i do have resources left. we have the largest donor base of any candidate and i can carry all the way to new orleans'' to the republican convention this summer
democrat simon was expected to hold on, at least until the primary next week in his home state of illinois. he largely stayed away from super tuesday races and declared the outcome a ``gridlock'' with ``no clear winner.''
no candidate is going to win on the first ballot at the (democratic) convention,'' simon suggested. ``it's going to be a brokered convention.''
hart was on the ballot but out of the presidential picture in all primary states. he failed to get more than single-digit percentages anywhere
but hart, who declared ``let the people decide'' when he re-entered the race last december, made no public comment on his future plans
he had said last week that ``so long as i can be treated seriously, i will continue.'' hart listened to the returns on television at his home outside of denver
dole, who was crushed by bush in a sweep across the south that netted the vice president close to 700 new delegates, hoped to make a comeback effort in the midwestern and western primaries that follow _ beginning with next tuesday's contest in illinois
tomorrow we will be on the road to recovery,'' dole told a group of supporters in chicago
i want to congratulate the vice president. ... he'll probably sleep better tonight than i will,'' dole added. ``we'll take turns.''
a dole defeat in illinois could give bush a nearly unassailable lead and could all but end dole's chances for the gop presidential nomination
gephardt also sought to look beyond the losses
now we go on, to illinois, to michigan ... '' he said. gephardt claimed, ``i'm far from chucking it in because this is a long race.''
kemp spent the evening with his family in suburban washington rather than with supporters
the 52-year old former pro quarterback, who had earlier sought to portray himself as a ``consensus conservative'' who could carry on the reagan revolution, had failed to see his candidacy take off
his withdrawal from the race appeared inevitable after his fourth-place finish in south carolina last weekend
out of cash, kemp decided to make one last stand in the super tuesday contests. but in only a single primary, massachusetts, did he finish any better than fourth. there he edged out robertson for third place
the dollar rose slightly in tokyo on wednesday, while stock prices gained substantially following an overnight advance on wall street
the dollar closed at 128.08 yen, up 0.28 yen from tuesday's close. it opened at 127.80 yen and ranged between 127.73 yen and 128.27 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the 225-share nikkei stock average, which lost 150.85 points tuesday, gained back 139.66 points, or 0.55 percent, closing at 25,605.39. trading was relatively heavy at 1.3 billion shares
michio katsumata of nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage house, said tokyo stock prices were supported by tuesday's rally on the new york stock exchange and by stabilization of the foreign exchange market
investors also appeared to be buying shares deemed to be at bargain prices after the tokyo market's decline on tuesday, dealers said
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis used a strong local organization to smash democratic rivals in maryland's presidential primary, while vice president george bush won without even campaigning in person
we were well organized today. we were the only candidate really to have extensive poll coverage,'' said baltimore county executive dennis rasmussen, one of the organization democrats involved in the dukakis campaign
with 1,459 of 1,574 precincts or 93 percent reporting today, dukakis had 193,258 votes or 43 percent; jesse jackson had 140,025 votes or 31 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 40,061 votes or 9 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 34,170 votes or 8 percent, and illinois sen. paul simon had 13,628 votes or 3 percent
in the republican race, with 1,548 of 1,574 precincts or 98 percent reporting, bush had 103,899 votes or 53 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 62,721 votes or 32 percent; pat robertson had 12,328 votes or 6 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 11,579 votes or 6 percent
dukakis was expected to take 27 delegates and jackson 20. bush grabbed the state's 41 republican delegates
also on the ballot, incumbent democratic sen. paul sarbanes easily won nomination for a third term. he will be opposed in the general election by millionaire businessman thomas blair, a newcomer to politics
bush carried all eight congressional districts even though he didn't campaign personally in maryland. dole spent less than one day in the state
dukakis benefitted from strong democratic organizational support, especially in the populous suburbs around baltimore and washington, d.c
u.s. rep. kweisi mfume, jackson's state chairman, said dukakis ``ran a good campaign, had a good organization, had a good message, and people latched onto it.''
but he said he felt good about jackson's showing, which was boosted by strong support in the state's two predominantly black congressional districts
the campaign strategy was really to hold onto what we had in 1984 and to slightly increase it, and so we've done better than that,'' mfume said. ``jesse jackson and dukakis both were organized in maryland. they spent time here, and the voters responded accordingly.'' defeat</head>
republican presidential candidate bob dole, reeling from super tuesday losses, says he is ``on the road to recovery'' in illinois and that the industrial midwest will revive his struggling campaign
this is going to be bob dole's recovery state,'' the kansas senator told a crowd of cheering supporters tuesday night
it's going to be the turnaround state. it's going to get us back on the winning track.''
after dole's losses in tuesday's primaries and caucuses, the march 15 illinois primary is a make-or-break event for the senator's candidacy, his aides concede
we've got to make it happen in illinois,'' said thomas d. rath, a senior strategist in the campaign
although polls indicate that vice president george bush leads dole in illinois, rath said, the campaign hopes to surge ahead by focusing on what has become a dominant theme _ dole's leadership in the senate and contrasting that to bush's record
if you're looking for somebody who understands the issues, somebody who deals with the issues every day and somebody who has made a difference, you can pretty well judge a candidate by what they've done in the past,'' dole told supporters in oak brook, a chicago suburb where he watched the super tuesday results on television
the dole campaign is counting on strong support in downstate farming areas and in republican counties near the illinois-missouri border. in addition, the campaign is targeting white-collar suburban areas around chicago
william brock, dole's campaign chairman, acknowledged that tuesday's losses dealt a serious blow to the dole campaign
the psychological hit is very heavy,'' said brock
brock attributed bush's victories to president reagan's popularity in the south, and expressed frustration that the dole campaign had not been able to make gains by attacking bush and focusing the campaign on issues such as the deficit and drug use in america
you do the best you can. we did not have time to develop the one-on-one message that we did in the earlier states,'' brock said. ``now we've got a little more time. we'll see if we can do a better job.''
on arriving in illinois on tuesday, dole immediately took aim at bush when he spoke at a rally at the state capitol in springfield, challenging the vice president to a series of debates
later tuesday, when it became clear he had suffered a big defeat, dole rallied his supporters by recalling that he had come to chicago 40 years ago for treatment by a surgeon for crippling wounds suffered in world war ii
i've been coming to illinois for a long, long time,'' dole said. ``i don't give up very easily. we're going to be on the road to recovery in the state of illinois.''
the owner of the albany knickerbocker news, an afternoon daily with declining circulation, announced plans to combine it with the larger morning times union as a single all-day newspaper
the knickerbocker news will be discontinued on april 16, executives of capital newspapers, which operates both papers, said tuesday. the company is a division of the hearst newspapers group
william clemens, general manager of capital newspapers, said demand for the knickerbocker news was slumping and demand for the times union growing in an area that has five daily newspapers
we see our resources devoted in two different directions. we think the best way is to concentrate our resources in one paper,'' he said
clemens said company officials are still working on plans to combine the workforces of the newspapers, and don't know yet how many employees may be affected
the company declined to release current figures on its circulation and number of employees
audit bureau of circulations figures cited in editor and publisher international yearbook show that the daily paid circulation of the knickerbocker news was 30,699 on sept. 29, 1986, compared with 89,049 for the times union
two years earlier, the abc reported audited circulations of about 35,000 for the knickerbocker news and 87,000 for the times union
company officials said there will be personnel reductions, but said they hope to minimize layoffs by depending on attrition and voluntary measures
by day, st. agnes boys catholic high school is where nearly 300 teen-agers are educated. hours later, it's a nocturnal haven for hundreds of homeless in an unusual time-share concept
many of the boys at st. agnes, run by the marist brothers, come from some of the city's tougher areas _ harlem, hell's kitchen, the lower east side
they gulp down their lunches in the school cafeteria, taking advantage of the time allotted afterward to play a quick game of basketball in the gym
worn knapsacks stuffed with books and paper are thrown on the floor, the mandatory ties are tucked inside the dress shirts, and the boys are shooting free-throws and trampling the lines painted on the floor the day before
_
a half-day later, noon has turned to midnight and the gym is still occupied. the boys are gone; replaced by 350 of the city's estimated 60,000 homeless
st. agnes is transformed into the grand central drop-in center
folding chairs that had been neatly stacked against the wall in the day are spread out across the floor. homeless men are sleeping, stretching over two or three chairs. the only noise comes from snoring. a guard is posted outside the door
in contrast to the neatly dressed boys here earlier, many of the men are unkempt, unshaven and unwashed. a few appear to be in poor health, either physically or mentally
downstairs, in the cafeteria, men and a few women are sitting at tables talking
they will all be out by 5:30 a.m. two hours and a cleaning crew later, school will start
_
to hear school officials and the students tell it, no one would ever know they had overnight company
brother thomas schady and brother thomas potenza, principal and vice-principal, respectively, say there are no remnants of the shelter program once school begins. and, they say, the cafeteria, gym and the showers _ all used by night guests _ are clean by morning
the nighttime inhabitants stand in line outside the school, then go through a security checkpoint that includes a metal detector. any items that can be construed as weapons _ icepicks, hammers, knives, scissors _ are dropped off in a box near the door
the guests can eat, courtesy of the salvation army, and can shower and sleep on the folding chairs. there is access to social workers and medical care. there are no beds
the drop-in center idea is the city's alternative to the usual shelters. william j. grinker, commissioner of the city's human resources administration, has said that for a variety of reasons, some of the homeless don't use the established shelters
the grand central drop-in center, along with others that will follow, will provide an option between shelters on the one hand and bus depots and train stations on the other, grinker said
at the center, one man who declined to give his name said he was grateful to be inside, away from ``the weather.''
and 22-year-old stephanie frazier said she was relieved to be away from her usual haunt _ grand central station _ where she has had to beg for food
you don't have to beg nobody,'' she said. ``they just walk past. they don't give you nothin.'''
the 2-month-old program is welcomed by students
i think it's kind of cool that the school is helping other people,'' said 17-year-old carlos pinto
similarly, 16-year-old charles huller jr. said: ``we're doing something good for the homeless. it's part of our duty.''
and, as schady pointed out, it is easy to talk to students in a classroom about reaching out to others _ ``but it's rare to get the opportunity to experience it.''
the international civil aviation organization, a united nations body that oversees the safety and efficiency of world airlines, chose a new secretary-general in a close election, one of its officials said
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said sivinder singh sidhu, former head of india's civil aviation administration, defeated frenchman yves lambert, who had held the post for 12 years and was seeking his fifth three-year term. the election was held tuesday
two other candidates were bidding to head the organization, which has 157 members. sidhu was elected by the organization's 33-member council after three rounds of balloting in a closed vote
the official said most western members of the council supported lambert on the first ballot, while latin american nations backed brazil's adyr da silva and third world members backed sidhu
jesse jackson squeaked out a democratic primary win over tennessee sen. albert gore in the cradle of the confederacy early wednesday, while vice president george bush drubbed kansas sen. bob dole in alabama's republican race
jackson rallied a phalanx of black voters behind him to defeat gore, a white son of the neighboring state. with 3,448 of 4,304 precincts or 80 percent reporting, jackson had 157,887 votes or 44 percent to gore's 133,153 votes or 37 percent
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis was next with 27,846 votes or 8 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 25,825 votes or 7 percent; former colorado sen. gary hart tallied 6,586 votes or 2 percent and illinois sen. paul simon had 2,644 votes or 1 percent
in the republican contest, with 3,366 of 4,304 precincts or 78 percent reporting, bush amassed 123,285 votes or 64 percent; dole had 31,279 votes or 16 percent; pat robertson had 27,192 votes or 14 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp had 9,458 votes or 5 percent
for the democrats, 56 delegates were at stake, while republicans picked 38 delegates
jackson banked on a strong turnout of black voters, but gore hoped his appeal as a southern neighbor and his endorsement by sen. howell heflin would lift him into the no. 1 spot, despite early predictions that jackson would win
jackson made the largest investment of his campaign in tv ads in the birmingham area in hopes of nailing down a victory
bush had the endorsement of alabama republican party chairman emory folmar. but republican gov. guy hunt remained publicly neutral, and other party officials joined up with dole and kemp, saying they wanted a tougher, more conservative candidate
robertson, drawing strength from religious fundamentalists, was given a chance of capturing the no. 2 spot
jackson ran fourth in alabama in the 1984 primary when walter mondale drew blacks from his camp. but this time black voters avoided any major split
gore billed himself as the conservative democrat _ but in 1984 more than 75 percent of the votes went to the liberal democrats mondale, jackson and gary hart
the days prior to the election were marked by a new series of skirmishes over the democrats' rule against crossover voting, a rule that ended up bloodying the party in 1986 and leading to the election of a republican governor for the first time this century
democratic party chairman john baker said voters who cast ballots in the republican primary tuesday could not come back and vote in democratic primaries in june when nominees for hundreds of local, state and congressional posts are chosen. critics said alabama has no practical way to enforce the rule
a decision by three mushers to take a mandatory 24-hour layover early in the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race paid off as they sailed into the lead on a trail packed smooth by other mushers
joe redington, who helped organize the first iditarod 16 years ago but has never won it, found himself in an unfamiliar place tuesday _ the lead
the wasilla resident, trailed closely by herbie nayokpuk of shishmaref and joe garnie of teller, left tuesday morning from the rohn roadhouse checkpoint, 271 miles into the race
the three took their layovers sunday in skwentna, just 150 miles from the start in anchorage. the race leaders passed them, only to get bogged down in new snow. they took their mandatory layovers at rohn and watched helplessly as redington, nayokpuk and garnie raced through. they had to wait until tuesday afternoon to leave
i kind of have this feeling in the back of my mind that we're going to see two eskimos _ garnie and nayokpuk _ blazing across this state,'' said jerry austin of st. michael, one of the mushers taking his layover at rohn
joe runyan of nenana was the first musher to leave rohn, and at 4:39 p.m. tuesday became the first musher to arrive at nikolai, the next checkpoint 93 miles down the trail. but he had not yet taken his 24-hour layover, and so will have to sit in nikolai for a day while the caravan of mushers passes
redington left rohn at 7:20 a.m. tuesday. nayokpuk followed two minutes later, and garnie left at 9 a.m
by tuesday evening, 49 of the 52 teams racing had reached the rohn roadhouse
u.s. mushers from outside alaska, and their positions at last report: frank teasley of jackson, wyo., 23rd; dan maceachen of snowmass village, colo., 25th; terry adkins of mikado, mich., 26th; john patten of grand marais, minn., 27th; stan ferguson of philadelphia, 35th; and robin jacobson of minnetonka, minn., 40th
jesse jackson repeated his 1984 louisiana democratic primary triumph, his only victory four years ago, and won four more southern states on super tuesday as vice president george bush overwhelmed gop rivals
jackson won in georgia, mississippi, virginia and alabama, fighting off a strong challenge here by tennessee sen. albert gore, whose state campaign leader said jackson should be disappointed by his showing in louisiana and worried about gore's challenge
we feel that a turnaround has come, and again looking further down the road we feel that sen. gore can pull the democratic party back together,'' said bud courson, gore's state campaign coordinator
with 3,180 of 3,272 precincts, or 97 percent, reporting, jackson had 214,426 votes, or 34 percent; gore had 177,279, or 29 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 95,309, or 15 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt tallied 66,357, or 11 percent
with reports in from 3,166 of the 3,272 precincts, or 97 percent, bush had 85,837 votes, or 59 percent; kansas sen. bob dole tallied 25,710, or 18 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 25,601, or 18 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp had 7,614, or 5 percent
the results apparently translate into 31 delegates for jackson, 23 for gore and seven for dukakis and two for gephardt. on the republican side, bush nabbed 34 delegates with seven uncommitted
greg beuerman, dole's louisiana campaign boss, said he was not surprised by the vote and the pendulum would shift to dole in the midwest primaries. ``the south is to george bush what the midwest has been to bob dole,'' he said
in the 4th congressional district race to replace democratic gov.-elect buddy roemer in the u.s. house, roemer's former aide jim mccrery, a republican, and democratic state sen. foster campbell claimed spots in an april 16 runoff
mccrery, the sole republican in the race, led the 10-candidate field. roemer voiced support for former shreveport journal editor stan tiner during the campaign
however, tiner ran third as mccrery and campbell, a state senator since 1976, claimed runoff spots. mccrery tallied 31 percent of the vote to 19 percent for campbell
tennessee sen. albert gore jr., three weeks from his 40th birthday, received an early gift of victory from adoring constituents in the democratic presidential primary, while vice president george bush handily defeated gop rivals
in 1960, we replaced the oldest president then to serve with the youngest to be elected,'' gore said on tuesday night, comparing himself with the late john f. kennedy. ``today, history is going to repeat itself.''
with 2,369 of 2,391 precincts or 99 percent reporting, gore had 410,202 or 72 percent. jesse jackson had 117,152 or 21 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 18,982 or 3 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 8,503 or 2 percent
among republicans, with 2,298 of 2,391 precincts or 96 percent reporting, bush had 141,743 or 60 percent and dole had 51,239 or 22 percent. former tv evangelist pat robertson had 29,326 or 12 percent and new york rep. jack kemp had 11,490 or 5 percent
that should give bush 28 of the 45 delegates, with 11 for dole, one to robertson and five uncommitted
gore would take 56 of his party's delegates with 14 for jackson
this is a fight for the future of the democratic party,'' gore told 1,000 supporters crowded into a hotel ballroom on tuesday night. ``it's a fight for whether we are going to have a viable democratic party and win in november.''
gore, who staked his hopes on a campaign concentrated in the 14 southern states that conducted super tuesday primaries, plans to fly to chicago today to begin his campaign for the illinois primary next tuesday. the michigan primary is march 26, five days before gore's birthday
jackson supporters said they had expected a better showing in the volunteer state
we were hoping we'd do a little better,'' said state rep. roscoe dixon, d-memphis. ``the rain in the west tennessee area kept our turnout down, but we feel good about it.''
u.s. rep. james quillen, a tennessee republican and a leader of bush's tennessee campaign, said bush's victory didn't surprise him
the victory ``demonstrates that the people realize that he is fully dedicated and qualified to be next president of the united states,'' quillen said
voter turnout across tennessee was light to moderate, election officials said
president daniel ortega accused the white house of being behind the contras' pullout from cease-fire talks that had been set for today, saying the rebels and their sponsors ``fear negotiations.''
he said president reagan should be held responsible for continued bloodshed caused by the contras, whom he branded as u.s. ``mercenaries,'' and called for rescheduling the talks, which were to have been the first in nicaragua and without a mediator
ortega's comments came after the contras on tuesday pulled out of the talks that were to be held at a post bordering costa rica. the rebels said preliminary meetings should first work out details
this shows again the lack of political will of the united states government and the counterrevolutionary leaders, as their instrument, to end the war of aggression and terrorist acts against the nicaraguan people and accept a peaceful solution to the conflict,'' ortega said, reading from a prepared statement
he suggested the talks be held during the third week of march and have an open agenda. his leftist sandinista government had made preparations for the talks to be held at sapoa, 90 miles south of managua
the secretary-general of the organization of american states, joao baena soares, arrived in nicaragua tuesday, a day after ortega invited him to a witness the talks
the rebels, supplied and trained by the united states, said monday that they would not accept the talks without cardinal miguel obando y bravo serving as ``witness, moderator and guarantor of the talks.''
ortega responded by calling on the nicaraguan roman catholic prelate, who has often criticized the sandinistas, along with baena soares, to attend the talks but only as a witness
in a communique, the contras said details of the talks needed to be worked out. it also appeared the rebels would press for more involvement in the meetings by the cardinal, whom ortega removed as mediator last week
ortega said obando y bravo's efforts no longer were needed because the talks would be face to face. but sandinista and opposition sources said the cardinal was removed for trying to take the initiative with a proposal of his own at the last contra-sandinista meeting to end the 6{-year-old civil war
in a speech tuesday night at the revolution plaza in honor of international women's day, ortega said his government was ready to resume talks ``without conditions.''
he added, however, ``it is clear we will not discuss the revolution. we will not discuss the right of the nicaraguan people and the legitimate government of nicaragua to arm itself. this we won't negotiate.''
the sandinistas, who came to power in a 1979 revolution that ousted dictator anastasio somoza, maintain the talks should deal only with the mechanics of the contras' disarmament and amnesty
ortega cemented that position last week when he named his brother, gen. humberto ortega, the defense minister, to head the government delegation to the talks
the rebels named adolfo calero, the top political leader of the nicaraguan resistance, the contra umbrella organization, to lead their side
obando y bravo on feb. 18 called on the sandinistas to grant total amnesty, restore full press freedoms, reopen talks with the internal political opposition and revise the military draft law. he also called for a 30-day truce to allow the contras to move into enclaves to later lay down their arms
the contras accepted obando y bravo's proposal. the sandinistas hesitated and the cardinal broke off talks, saying the two sides were at an impasse
in his speech tuesday night, ortega said reagan was responsible for the suspension of cease-fire talks
reagan and his mercenaries have not accepted our proposal to talk tomorrow,'' he said. ``they fear negotiations.'' course</head>
the practice of flooding city council members with free passes to municipal golf courses has driven the city's portion of the profits slicing into the rough
a move to end the practice was opposed this week by only two of the 16 council members present and has landed in the same place
we have funny rules,'' said councilman robb pitts
two years ago, the city leased its four courses to american golfing co. for $80,000 a year. the lease gives each of the 19 council members 10 passes good for unlimited play
but the price of each ``free'' round is deducted from the lease fee, and instead of the $80,000 the city might have received this year, it will take in only about $14,000 based on projected free use through may 1
the lease fee increases to $120,000 next year
with a city budget of some $250 million, that's a not a lot of money, but for months council members passed it around like a grenade with the pin pulled
we lease the golf courses out not only to improve the courses but to make a profit. i don't think we ought to erode that profit by giving free passes to people who are able to pay,'' councilwoman myrtle davis said before the vote
councilman dozier smith defended the passes, saying they allowed elderly constituents on fixed incomes to play
councilman hosea williams, who voted to retain the passes and abstained on a companion proposal to abolish them, said he favored perquisites such as the passes, claiming council members are not well paid
most council members, including williams, who owns a chemical company, have substantial income outside their $18,400-a-year council salaries and say they don't use the passes themselves
most of them apparently give them to their constituents. the people who get them the most are those that can afford to pay,'' said pitts, who led the drive to eliminate the passes
you would be surprised at the names of the people i have heard mentioned who have them. it is more of a prestige thing than a need, to say you have one. it got out of hand.''
he cited park and recreation department figures projecting a city loss of more than $670,000 during the first 10 years of the lease based on current free uses
he said he is dropping the fight and knows of nobody eager to pick it up. ``the results would be the same,'' he said
this week's attempt to eliminate the passes was killed through abstentions, which, under council rules, have the effect of a ``no'' vote. more than half of the members present must vote ``yes'' on an issue to pass it. while only two of the 16 members present voted against abolishing the passes, nine abstained. update with vote total for top three democrats. inserts one graf after numbers 19th graf pvs bgng: he added ... to update with nevada, hawaii and american samoa. new delegate totals</note>
michael dukakis circled dixie and claimed a national candidacy on super tuesday, while albert gore jr. looked ahead to a ``long, hard-fought contest'' after passing his do-or-die southern test. jesse jackson hailed his ``new southern message'' that produced victories in a fractured democratic field
super tuesday's loser was richard gephardt, who won his home state of missouri but fared badly elsewhere. he failed to meet the 15 percent threshold required to win delegates in many states
with a splintered outcome, three of the democratic candidates could _ and did _ argue they did well on the busiest day of presidential primaries in history
for jackson it was victories in five states and an impressive improvement over his campaign four years ago. for dukakis it was a display of support outside his native new england and claim to a national candidacy. and for gore it was the right to claim wide support across the south and a spot among the contenders for the nomination
gore immediately took aim at dukakis as his chief rival and compared him to walter mondale and the democrats' 1984 debacle
i think mike dukakis is going to represent for many voters the same old formula that led to the loss of 49 out of 50 states twice in the last five elections,'' gore said
he said the race ``is going to be a long, hard-fought contest. it's also going to be a long, hard-fought contest in the fall. we need to select the candidate with the best chance of winning.''
dukakis, the massachusetts governor, countered: ``remember, this was a place where the guy from massachusetts wasn't supposed to do well at all.''
if we can come out of super tuesday with the largest cumulative total of delegates, i think we're going to be on our way,'' dukakis said
jackson won alabama, georgia, mississippi, louisiana and virginia; gore won arkansas, north carolina, oklahoma, kentucky and his home state of tennessee
jackson, the black civil rights leader, savored his alabama showing and recalled the violent struggle for equality in selma, ala. 23 years ago
the same state that wouldn't let us walk across the bridge _ we won that state today,'' jackson said
dukakis won in his home state of massachusetts as well as in neighboring rhode island, in maryland, idaho caucuses and in the two mega-states of florida and texas
this has been a great night for us,'' said dukakis. ``to be able to take texas and florida, the two big ones, and to do well across the board demonstrates that this is a national candidacy, a national campaign.''
demonstrating the mixed verdict, jackson, gore and dukakis each collected roughly the same number of votes: 2.4 million votes
jackson's big win in virginia with nearly half of the vote and strong showing elsewhere assured he would fare better than his 1984 campaign, when he won only louisiana
i've won southern states today, either number one or number two, with a new southern message,'' jackson said
and that message is fundamentally, we the people must stop drugs from threatening our national security and our streets, we must fight to end economic violence. that message is getting through
we've gone from a narrow mainstream to a broad-based river,'' jackson said
he added: ``we're the underdog with the biggest bite.''
gore led in the nevada caucuses, while jackson led dukakis in early returns from hawaii's caucuses. american samoa gave one delegate to dukakis, one to gephardt and one to the ranks of the uncommitted
all were vying for a share of the 1,307 democratic presidential nominating delegates at stake in 20 states
in the crucial delegate battle, dukakis won 372 delegates out of super tuesday. gore won 316, jackson won 353 and gephardt won 94
gore said he would be among the three candidates going to the convention _ suggesting gephardt wouldn't be able to
i think that three of us are going to go all the way to the convention,'' gore said. ``it will be a choice between the politics of the past and the politics of the future.''
gephardt, who was caught in a withering crossfire of negative television advertisements by gore and dukakis, offered congratulations to all three. he blamed his failure on a lack of money and vowed to go on to the next round of primaries
i'm far from chucking it in because this is a long race,'' gephardt said. ``when we've been able to get my message across, as i did in iowa and new hampshire and south dakota ... we do well.''
democratic party elder statesman robert strauss said the news of super tuesday was grim for gephardt, 
he said jackson, dukakis and gore ``are going north now, and we'll see how it comes out. ... i expect one of those three fellows will probably be the nominee.''
i think dick gephardt's in trouble,'' strauss said. ``certainly dukakis and gore each have a great deal to be happy about tonight.''
gephardt criticized the super tuesday process with 20 states voting on a single day _ an arrangement that left his money-strapped campaign hard pressed to keep up
i think maybe it was a disservice to the voters to put 20 states on one day,'' he said
jackson, a black man born and educated in the south, relied on his wide support among that region's large black population and figured to be among the delegate leaders in the super tuesday voting
exit polling said jackson won nearly all the black vote and 10 percent of the white vote
two other candidates, sen. paul simon of illinois and gary hart, the former senator from colorado, weren't factors
simon, looking forward to the illinois primary, said the outcome was delegate ``gridlock.''
it's going to be a brokered convention,'' he ssaid
opposition leaders today accused the government of arresting and harassing poll workers who refused to work during last week's violence-marred parliamentary elections
sheik hasina and khaleda zia, the two opposition leaders who led the boycott of the march 3 balloting, said ``many'' people had been arrested, but neither woman gave any numbers
if they are not released, the people will set them free,'' mrs. zia said in a statement published by dhaka newspapers today
ms. hasina, in a separate statement carried by the press, said president hussain muhammad ershad's government had once again displayed its ``autocratic nature.''
on tuesday, newspapers in the capital said five people had been arrested in the southern town of barisal and 19 teachers in dhaka had gone into hiding to avoid arrest
school teachers and government employees normally staff polling places during elections, but many who were slated for duty last week did not show up, apparently out of fear for their safety
at least 13 people were killed and more than 300 injured in election day clashes between supporters of rival parties. on feb. 10, more than 100 people were killed during non-partisan elections for local councils
hasina's awami league and mrs. zia's bangladesh nationalist party led a score of other political parties in boycotting the parliamentary election. that left the field clear for ershad's jatiya party, which faced only token opposition
according to incomplete returns, the jatiya party has won 238 of parliament's 300 seats. small parties and independents took 41 seats
voting was postponed until saturday in 20 constituencies because of violence. in another constituency, voting was delayed indefinitely after a candidate was killed in pre-election violence
hasina, daughter of president mujibur rahman who was assassinated in 1975, and mrs. zia, widow of president ziaur rahman who was assassinated in 1981, have led a 4-month-old campaign to topple ershad
ershad, a former army general, seized power in a 1982 coup and subsequently won a presidential election the opposition says was rigged
meanwhile, the state-operated news agency bangladesh sangbad sangstha said the government had ``initiated action'' against those responsible for preventing a prominent opposition official from leaving the country
the news agency did not say what this action was
former foreign minister kamal hossain, a member of the awami league's presidium, was taken off an airplane tuesday when he tried to leave for sydney, australia
it was never the intention of the government to stop his going abroad,'' the news agency said
with their sights set on the white house, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and vice president george bush stalked and bagged a prize apiece in florida, one of the biggest catches in the presidential primaries
you can't win with smoke and mirrors,'' mike abrams, a political strategist for dukakis in florida, said on tuesday. ``you need people. we knew the organization had to be here. from the way we put together our phone banks to our wooing of constituent leaders, it was relentless.''
with 4,143 of 4,459 precincts or 93 percent reporting, dukakis had 466,831 votes or 40 percent; jesse jackson had 238,142 or 20 percent. missouri rep. richard gephardt had 171,131 or 15 percent, followed closely by tennessee sen. albert gore jr. with 152,120 or 13 percent
in the gop race, with 4,143 of 4,459 precincts or 93 percent reporting, bush had 497,993 votes or 63 percent; dole had 162,057 or 20 percent; former tv evangelist pat robertson had 86,656 or 11 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp had 36,810 votes or 5 percent
bush took advantage of president reagan's popularity, a gubernatorial endorsement and family ties in florida to trounce dole and claim the lion's share of 82 gop delegates
i'm pretty confident now that he will win the nomination,'' said bush's son jeb, florida's secretary of commerce. ``he got knocked down in iowa, changed strategy a little bit and came back.''
dukakis, who organized here early, visited frequently and courted the retirees and condo dwellers who have fled from colder regions, built an impressive late lead based on polls in the state that boasted the second-biggest prize of super tuesday after texas: 136 democratic delegates
when we first came down here we were told not to expend much effort, this was a media state,'' said steve rosenfeld, dukakis state campaign manager. ``tonight we proved that (to be) obsolete wisdom. we won with people, we won with organization and we won with the best candidate.''
robertson looked for support in conservative north florida and played heavily to cubans with his assertions about missiles in cuba. dole, who keeps a winter home in bal harbour, admitted he was out-organized by bush
among democrats, the state was seen by some as a litmus test of national appeal, with liberal democrats in south florida, traditional southern democrats in north florida, arch-conservative cubans in miami and midwestern retirees on the southwest gulf coast
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis captured the top delegate state in the super tuesday presidential primaries, while vice president george bush shut out republican rivals to grab all 111 texas gop delegates
it has exceeded my fondest expectations,'' bush told several hundred supporters crowding a ballroom at at houston hotel soon after polls closed on super tuesday
with 6,079 of 6,933 precincts or 88 percent reporting, dukakis had 497,592 votes or 33 percent; jesse jackson had 364,242 votes or 24 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 313,026 votes or 20 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 212,972 votes or 14 percent; former colorado sen. gary hart had 77,184 votes or 5 percent, and illinois sen. paul simon had 29,038 votes or 2 percent
in the republican race, with 4,687 of 5,616 precincts or 83 percent reporting, bush had 542,206 votes or 65 percent; pat robertson had 125,164 votes or 15 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 115,119 votes or 14 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 40,468 votes or 5 percent
dukakis was expected to get 45 of the state's 183 delegates up for grabs, jackson 40, gore 23 and gephart 10. fourteen other democratic seats go to party officials
meanwhile, democratic u.s. sen. lloyd bentsen easily won renomination in his bid for a fourth term. top republican challengers beau boulter, who gave up his congressional seat for the senate race, and wes gilbreath, a houston investor making his first race for a political office, will meet in a runoff. the winner squares off against bentsen in november
dukakis, in a televised interview tuesday from chicago, said, ``i feel very good about the south. i feel good about tonight, obviously.''
bush, who built an oil business in texas, rents a motel in houston so he can vote in the state. he led in polls throughout the campaign
at the victory party tuesday night, tom loeffler, the former texas congressman who is co-chairman of bush's texas campaign, gave the vice president a t-shirt emblazoned with ``bush in '88 _ texas victory _ super tuesday,'' while the crowd cheered and waved u.s. flags
it's a wonderful evening, i'll tell you,'' bush said
vice president george bush won by a little and gained nearly all the state's gop delegates, while tennessee sen. albert gore won big in a 12-candidate field and settled for half of the democratic prize
bush beat kansas sen. bob dole by 2 percent, but won in five of the six congressional districts, apparently gaining 33 of 36 delegates available, while dole won three delegates and pat robertson finished third and got none
if dole can't win in oklahoma, where can he win?'' said matt seward, bush's campaign director in oklahoma. he said oklahoma was one of three states dole had targeted to win in the 20-state super tuesday elections
gore captured 41 percent of the vote among 12 candidates, almost twice that of his nearest rival, missouri rep. richard gephardt, but claimed only 23 of the state's 46 delegates up for grabs
gephardt, the early frontrunner in oklahoma, finished second in five districts and claimed 13 delegates. dukakis got seven delegates and jackson received three
in republican voting with 2,422 of 2,439 precincts reporting, or 99 percent, bush had 77,938 votes, or 37 percent; dole had 72,683 or 35 percent. robertson had 44,197, or 21 percent and new york congressman jack kemp had 11,018, or 5 percent
with 2,434 of 2,439 precincts reporting, or 99 percent of democratic returns, gore had 162,187 votes, or 41 percent; gephardt had 82,267, or 21 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 66,150, or 17 percent, and jackson had 52,460, or 13 percent
bush supporters were hoping today that tuesday's victory in dole's backyard will prove decisive in derailing the vice president's main opponent in the republican presidential sweepstakes
supporters of gore said the senator's surprisingly strong victory in the sooner state will help the southerner stake a claim as the ``mainstream'' candidate who can return the white house to the democratic fold in november
super tuesday has proven that al gore is the candidate for mainstream democrats,'' said state sen. stratton taylor, co-chairman of the gore drive in oklahoma.   - here is the current breakdown of the outcomes of primaries and caucuses held on march 8. for each candidate, the number of states the candidate has won or is leading in is given
