two native sons, gov. michael dukakis and vice president george bush, scored convincing wins in the massachusetts primary. jesse jackson in the democratic race and sen. bob dole in the gop contest finished far behind
the win at home and victories in florida and texas gave dukakis the three biggest super tuesday prizes. the bush victory in massachusetts, where he was born, was part of a super tuesday landslide
with 1,925 of 2,140 precincts, or 90 percent, reporting, dukakis led with 367,637 votes, or 59 percent, followed by jackson with 117,408 votes, or 19 percent
with 1,924 of the 2,140 precincts, or 90 percent, reporting, bush had 127,918 votes, or 59 percent. dole had 57,426 or 26 percent
dukakis, the popular governor of this liberal state, was a prohibitive favorite in the democratic primary, where 98 delegates were at stake, the party's third-biggest prize of the day. it appeared dukakis would get 79 of the delegates and jackson the remaining 19
this augurs very well for the future,'' said dukakis in a television interview from chicago
but he denied the super tuesday results would secure the democratic nomination for him
dukakis had not campaigned in massachusetts until last week, when he took to the streets of cambridge for about an hour of stumping. none of his rivals bothered to spend time or money here
in the republican primary, 52 delegates were at stake, the fourth-biggest batch on super tuesday
bush established a wide early lead in the tiny massachusetts republican party and held off dole, who did not campaign here. bush won the 1980 gop primary here, defeating ronald reagan
well behind bush and dole were rep. jack kemp, who had 15,134 votes, or 7 percent, and pat robertson, who received 9,963 votes, or 5 percent
analyzing bush's victory, gordon nelson, state co-chair for kemp's campaign, said the vice president convinced voters he was president reagan's logical successor: ``george bush won because he is reagan ii.''
in third place among the democrats was missouri rep. richard gephardt with 63,865 votes, or 10 percent, followed by tennessee sen. albert gore jr. with 28,135 votes, or 4 percent, and illinois sen. paul simon with 22,692 votes, or 4 percent
gary hart, who won the 1984 massachusetts democratic primary, trailed the field of active candidates with 9,955 votes, or 2 percent
emigres from soviet armenia are flocking to southern california, and local officials are scrambling to meet their needs
since october, about 2,000 soviet armenians have arrived in the los angeles area, and 8,000 to 10,000 more are expected by the end of the year, along with as many as 3,000 armenians from iran, according to the state department
the whole city's not ready for this,'' said arick gevorkian of the glendale office of the armenian national committee
right now, we're organizing with the school district, with the churches, trying to facilitate these newcomers,'' gevorkian said. ``but we are racing against time and we are not very ready.''
the influx began when soviet leader mikhail gorbachev launched his campaign of ``glasnost,'' or openness, and officials were instructed to approve exit visas for armenians wanting to join relatives in america
officials say the influx is not related to recent turmoil in soviet armenia and neighboring azerbaijan
`going to hollywood, going to hollywood.' you hear it all the time on the streets of yerevan,'' armenia's capital, said harry diramarian, a local armenian leader
southern california's armenian-american population numbers in the tens of thousands. prominent armenian-americans include gov. george deukmejian and the late author william saroyan of fresno
worried officials said absorbing the newcomers probably will be hampered by the nearly 50 percent cutback in federal refugee assistance funding since 1984
however, with the increasing numbers of emigres entering public schools and applying for public assistance, welfare offices in hollywood and glendale have added nearly a dozen armenian-speaking employees
glendale schools hired five additional armenian-speaking teachers or aides to complement the eight already on staff. more are planned
officials said it's essential to provide such services early on or risk the refugees becoming permanently dependent on the government
every public and private agency is understaffed, and it means that the armenians are confronting delays in getting their most basic services,'' said bruce whipple, director of the local office of the international rescue committee, a private agency that assists refugees during their first 30 days of resettlement
right now, we have no job training or esl (english as a second language) slots to put armenian refugees in,'' said joan pinchuk, los angeles county's coordinator for refugee affairs
last year, 3,250 soviet armenians emigrated to the united states, more than 13 times the number who came in 1986
armenian community leaders said these numbers reflect only a fraction of the potential emigres who would like to move to southern california
terry rusch of the state department's bureau for immigrant programs said the relaxation of emigration restrictions has been extended to soviet jews, but not to the same degree as for armenians
some armenian-americans are dismayed by the influx, arguing that a mass exodus from the soviet union weakens the only homeland the armenians know, as well as their claim to armenian lands in turkey
every armenian who leaves armenia not only diminishes our collective power there, but is also risking the eventual loss of his or her national heritage and identity,'' said harut sassounian, editor of the california courier, an armenian-american weekly published in glendale
unlike soviet jews, soviet armenians are not emigrating to their homeland. instead, they are leaving it.''
when the space shuttles begin flying again, they will have a new emergency landing site at an abandoned strategic air command base near ben guerir, morrocco
the national aeronautics and space administration tuesday announced construction of the new site has begun at the base, 40 miles north of marrakech. it will be the fourth emergency landing site
the former sac base has a 14,000 foot runway, but its surface must be rejuvenated to make it usable by shuttles that for some reason they fail to reach the speeds necessary to get into orbit
nasa announced earlier in the week that another airport site in northwest africa, in the tiny country of the gambia, will be upgraded to accommodate shuttles. the space agency intends to continue using runways at zaragoza air base and moron air base in spain
foundations for shuttle approach and landing aids are being laid at the new sites and other equipment, including 10 personnel vehicles, will be shipped
a group of jewish advisers to president reagan says the 30 senators who wrote a letter supporting the administration's position that it is time for israel to exchange land for peace is acting too quickly and meddling in israeli internal affairs
the group, known as the national jewish coalition, said the senators ``operated in haste'' and were ``inserting themselves into the internal politics of israel.''
the coalition, formed after the 1984 election to advise reagan on jewish matters, issued its statement after a meeting in the oval office with reagan. however, richard fox, the chairman of the organization, said the president did not discuss the peace process or the violence in the israeli-occupied territories
he said the meeting with reagan lasted only 12 or 13 minutes and the president's comments were ``really more of a ceremonial statement. there was no forum for discussion of the issue.''
on monday, the white house had said it welcomed the senators' statement, in which they criticized israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir and his likud party, suggesting they may be blocking efforts to reach a peace settlement in the middle east
the eligibility for legalization of hundreds of illegal aliens may rest on a federal court's interpretation of four words in the u.s. immigration and naturalization service rules for implementation of the government's amnesty program
a class action suit was filed tuesday in u.s. district court on behalf of five illegal aliens to block ins rules defining which illegal aliens were ``known to the government'' and are eligible for amnesty
ins rules under the immigration reform and control act of 1986 provide amnesty to aliens who lived illegally in the united states before jan. 1, 1982 as well as to agricultural workers who can prove they lived in this country for at least 90 days in the year ended may 1, 1986
a problem has arisen over individuals who arrived legally _ with a visa _ but who remained in the country illegally after the jan. 1, 1982 cutoff date, according to debbi sanders of the washington lawyers committee for civil rights, one of the attorneys for the plantiffs
in cases like these, the statute grants amnesty to those whose illegal status was ``known to the government'' and advocates for illegal aliens have sought to use social security and internal revenue service forms to prove that aliens in this category were known
the ins, however, maintains that ``known to the government'' meant known to the ins, sanders said, noting that this difference of interpretation disqualified hundreds of illegals
a week of talks between u.s. and japanese officials over participation by u.s. firms in billions of dollars worth of japanese building projects has ended in failure
and, a u.s. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, tuesday said that president reagan under the law could retaliate against japan for what are considered unfair trade practices
that is one of the options,'' the official said, adding that the reagan administration will decide probably by the end of next week what its next step will be
the official said the u.s. side had exhausted its capacity to resolve the issues and was not ready to go on talking, given the differences between the two sides
the official said the u.s. delegation to the talks also had wanted the arrangements on participation by u.s. construction firms written into a formal agreement, while the japanese did not want to be bound and sought only a joint statement that unspecified arrangements were satisfactory
the dollar rose slightly in tokyo today, while stock prices gained substantially following an overnight advance on wall street
the dollar closed at 128.08 yen, up 0.28 yen from tuesday's close. it opened at 127.80 yen and ranged between 127.73 yen and 128.27 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the 225-share nikkei stock average, which lost 150.85 points tuesday, gained back 139.66 points, or 0.55 percent, closing at 25,605.39
share prices in new york rose yesterday, and the foreign exchange market has stabilized,'' said michio katsumata of nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage house
today's heavy volume of 1.3 billion shares was concentrated in steel and heavy industry stocks, which made strong advances, said richard bixon, a trader at vickers da costa
the market had been apprehensive about the outcome of presidential primary elections in the united states on tuesday, bixon said
the main worry there ... was always going to be (democratic candidate richard) gephardt, because he was widely interpreted as a protectionist,'' he said. gephardt fared poorly in the elections
trading was slow on the foreign exchange market as dealers waited out the final days of the japanese fiscal year, which ends march 31, said shigeki kawano, a dealer at mitsubishi bank
dealers also were awaiting the release of key economic indicators. japan's february trade data are to be released thursday, and figures for u.s. january trade are scheduled for release next week in washington
it's still a very sleepy market,'' kawano said
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis coasted to victory in idaho's democratic presidential caucuses, but jesse jackson surprised party leaders with a strong showing
with all 45 precincts reporting early today, dukakis had 1,516 votes or 38 percent; jackson had 882 votes or 22 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 333 votes or 8 percent; illinois sen. paul simon had 280 votes or 7 percent, and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 44 votes or 1 percent
dukakis captured 8 of idaho's 18 delegates, with jackson winning four. six delegates will go to the national convention uncommitted
michael dukakis is foreseen as the frontrunner _ a winner,'' said former governor john evans, who headed the dukakis campaign. ``he is perceived as the candidate of the people.''
the turnout was higher than the number of democrats who attended the 1984 caucuses. ``the real message tonight is that we are getting a lot of people out,'' said gov. cecil andrus, who says he will go to the convention uncommitted
jackson's strong finish, in a state with a minority population of less than 5 percent, surprised most campaign leaders
i didn't recognize where his strength was coming from,'' evans said. ``but he (jackson) is doing better than four years ago. obviously he has matured, but it still surprises me.''
the republican presidential primary will be held may 24
tennessee sen. albert gore jr., a fresh face in the democratic crowd, waltzed to victory in arkansas while another neighbor, missouri rep. richard gephardt, was battered into defeat by his rivals, the state's governor said
i was a little surprised by how far gephardt fell,'' gov. bill clinton said after gore scored a decisive win over massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in the super tuesday democratic primary, leaving gephardt a distant fourth
that's really the story of this election. what happened was dukakis and gore were attacking gephardt. gore and gephardt were attacking dukakis. nobody was attacking gore on television. he got off with a free ride in this fight.''
gephardt, an early front-runner in the 1988 campaign with his iowa win, suffered a similar fate elsewhere on super tuesday, winning only his home state of missouri. gore, who stayed out of the national spotlight by focusing on the south, triumphed in five of the day's 20 state primaries
on the republican side, vice president george bush trounced sen. bob dole on his way to a 16-state sweep of his kansas rival
rep. bill alexander had little trouble defeating political consultant darrell glascock for the democratic nomination for the 1st congressional district of eastern arkansas. there was no republican candidate in this heavily democratic state
with 2,541 of 2,762 precincts or 92 percent reporting, gore tallied 178,502 votes or 37 percent to dukakis' 93,543, or 19 percent, and jesse jackson's 85,064, or 17 percent. gephardt trailed with 57,783 votes, or 12 percent
far behind were gary hart with 18,520 votes or 4 percent and paul simon with 8,981 votes or 2 percent
democratic candidates must attract at least 15 percent to share in the 38 delegates up for grabs. gore will likely get 19 delegates, dukakis 10 and jackson nine
with 3,366 of 4,304 precincts or 78 percent reporting, bush tallied 123,285 votes or 64 percent to dole's 31,279 or 16 percent. former tv evangelist pat robertson had 27,192 or 14 percent and new york rep. jack kemp was far back with 9,458 or 5 percent
republican candidates must get at least 3 percent of the vote to qualify for delegates. with half the precincts reporting, bush garnered 14 delegates to dole's seven, robertson's five and kemp's one
gov. bill clinton, who all but endorsed dukakis, said gore benefited from the undecided voters
dukakis and jackson should be very pleased,'' the democratic governor said. ``gore should be relieved. he did better than he was expected to do for the last couple of weeks, (although) probably not quite as well as he hoped he'd do when he started.''
port-au-prince, haiti (ap) _ the government has warned the media it will not tolerate ``cynical insinuations,'' ``false accusations'' and ``public insults,'' presumably in reaction to news reports of high-level corruption
the communique issued tuesday night did not mention specific cases
however, local newspapers and radio stations have relayed u.s. media reports of charges of drug trafficking made against col. jean-claude paul, the target of a u.s. federal grand jury probe
the haitian military said the charges were unfounded
also, the protestant station radio lumiere recently broadcast an interview in which opposition leader sylvio claude accused president leslie manigat of accepting bribes from philadelphia authorities for allowing toxic ash from that city to be dumped in haiti
claude presented no proof to substantiate his charges
the information ministry has noticed a tendency of the haitian media to not control its language when releasing news or interviews,'' says the communique signed by information minister roger savain and broadcast by radio stations
there is also a tendency to emit erroneous information under the pretext of citing the foreign news media as a source,'' it says
though the constitution guarantees the freedom of speech ... its authors also made clear what were the limits beyond which freedom of speech becomes an abuse,'' the statement continues. ``cynical insinuations, false or libelous accusations and serious public insults are intolerable cases of abuse of the freedom of speech
the ministry of information ... invites the haitian and foreign press to respect in the strictest manner the constitution and law.''
the constitution says a journalist cannot be censored, but has the ``duty to verify the authenticity and accuracy of his information.''
during anti-government strikes and demonstrations in july and august, radio stations were firebombed and riddled with bullets. at least four haitian reporters were shot and wounded by soldiers during the period, and soldiers shot at foreign reporters in at least 10 cases
on the eve of the the aborted nov. 29 national elections, in which gunmen and soldiers killed 34 people at polling stations, witnesses saw uniformed soldiers blow up the transmittor tower of the catholic church's radio soleil
gunmen shot and killed at point blank range a dominican photographer, carlos grullon, during the election day violence
no gunman or soldier has been brought to trial for the shootings
paul's unit, the widely feared dessalines barracks, is responsible for virtually all army repression and killings of demonstrators last year. soldiers from the 700-man batallion were also seen in the streets during the aborted nov. 29 elections
manigat was elected president jan. 17 in balloting boycotted by the opposition and marred by widespread irregularities
albert gore jr.'s do-or-die southern strategy succeeded at the expense of democratic rival richard gephardt, while republican george bush's association with the reagan administration carried him to his super tuesday sweep, pollsters say
michael dukakis maintained his democratic front-runner status on the strength of victories in texas and florida, but jesse jackson bolstered his nearly monolithic black support with additional backing from whites, the analysts said
gore's campaign did what it had to do in the south. the tennessee senator, who eschewed early contests in iowa and new hampshire in favor of the 14 southern and border states up for grabs tuesday, won five of them
it worked. he cleaned up in the south,'' said warren mitofsky, chief pollster for cbs news. ``but he's got to prove it in the next couple of weeks in illinois and wisconsin. he's got to show support beyond the south.''
gore did well mainly at the expense of gephardt, the missouri congressman, who won only his home state. gore and dukakis had accused gephardt of waffling on the issues, and exit polls indicated the charges stuck
gore won among conservative democrats, with 35 percent, abc news exit polls said. he also found help in his tennessee roots: of the 52 percent of southern voters born in the south, gore was backed by nearly a third, while dukakis got 20 percent
if gore's going to be the only conservative who goes on, then he's got a shot,'' said sheldon gawiser, poll analyst for nbc news. ``the real question is, can he take his show on the road? the jury is out on that.''
one problem for gore is the relative dearth of conservative democratic primary voters outside the south. abc said conservatives made up 27 percent of the southern democrats, considerably more than is likely elsewhere
but jackson demonstrated an ability to drain liberal and moderate votes from dukakis, possibly leaving gore an opening to siphon off a plurality in some states, gawiser said
if jackson continues to cut up the liberal vote with dukakis,'' he said, ``gore can score.''
jackson won about 95 percent of the black vote in the south, but also improved his showing among white voters compared with his support in the 1984 campaign. abc said he won 8 percent of white votes in the region; the cbs news-new york times poll put it at 9 percent
nbc, which gave state-by-state results, said jackson's white support ranged from 4 percent in tennessee to 15 percent in virginia and 19 percent in massachusetts, dukakis' home state
dukakis stitched together support from older voters, hispanics, jews and moderates for his southern victories. in florida, 47 percent of democratic voters were 60 and over and 52 percent of them backed dukakis, the cbs-times poll said
the massachusetts governor also did well with older voters across the south. he split the moderates with jackson, and jackson won more liberal democrats, but abc said dukakis won 78 percent of the jewish vote across the region, compared with 3 percent for jackson
nbc said dukakis was backed by 52 percent of hispanic voters in texas, who made up 18 percent of the democratic turnout. dukakis speaks fluent spanish and had courted the hispanic vote
moreover, dukakis had the best image among the democratic candidates, showing a 60 percent favorable rating compared with 31 percent unfavorable, the cbs-times poll said
he's demonstrated appeal across the country. he's a very strong candidate and he's got to be the leading contender at the moment,'' gawiser said
the hardest hit of the democrats was gephardt, whose get-tough-on-trade message failed to strike a chord. only 12 percent of southern democrats rated the issue as important, the cbs-times poll said, and even those went mainly for gore, 35 percent to gephardt's 21 percent
on the republican side, bush benefited from his credentials in the reagan administration. in some states as many as 80 percent of the republican voters approved of president reagan, and 60 percent of them backed bush, the cbs-times poll said
bush also maintained favor among conservative republicans and among the one-third of gop voters who rated experience as important; nearly 80 percent of them went for the vice president, polls said
dole fared better with independents who voted republican, a relatively small group in the conservative-dominated south, mitofsky said
the rev. pat robertson failed to break out of his core support of evangelical christians, and rep. jack kemp of new york fared poorly in all categories, polls said
with the depth of his support, ``it's going to be very, very, very difficult for bush to be defeated at this stage of the game,'' gawiser said. ``unless he makes some horrendous mistake, he's not going to lose.''
results of the state exit polls had error margins of about 5 percentage points either way; the cbs-times poll results for the region as a whole had a smaller margin of sampling error, about 2 percentage points. pickup.</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis held a narrow lead over jesse jackson in hawaii's democratic presidential caucuses tuesday
with 152 of 284 precincts or 54 percent reporting, dukakis had 1,152 votes or 48 percent; jackson had 1,045 votes or 43 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 55 votes or 2 percent, and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 26 votes or 1 percent
about 30,000 democrats were eligible to participate, but fewer than 5,000 were expected to attend the precinct meetings. and most of the 2,000 new members signed up by jackson's campaign were expected to show up
gov. john waihee, who earlier had urged that the state's delegation remain uncommitted, endorsed dukakis last week, as did sens. daniel inouye and spark matsunaga
twenty delegates were at stake in the caucus voting
jackson was the only candidate to visit hawaii
vice president george bush stung bob dole with a narrow victory in the missouri gop presidential primary, crushing the kansas senator's last hope to win a key super tuesday state
democratic rep. richard gephardt easily won his home state with 57 percent of the vote, but it was his only victory of the night. his closest rival, jesse jackson, took 21 percent of the vote
the bush victory in dole's back yard went down to the wire, with bush pulling ahead only when final returns were reported from st. louis county, a republican stronghold
being in missouri, right next to kansas, i can't tell you how sweet this victory is,'' said bush campaigner sissy chamberlain. ``i'm not being vindictive, but we wanted to win it for the vice president and we were able to squeak it out.''
with 3,878 of 3,954 precincts, or 98 percent, reporting, bush had 167,991 votes, or 42 percent, and dole had 163,394 or 41 percent; pat robertson had 44,334, or 11 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 14,125, or 4 percent
in the democratic race, with 3,919 of 3,954 precincts, or 99 percent, reporting, gephardt had 307,877 votes or 58 percent and jackson had 106,619 votes or 20 percent. massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 61,645 votes or 12 percent, illinois sen. paul simon had 21,622 votes or 4 percent; and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 14,686 votes or 3 percent
the news election service said bush received 22 delegates, dole received 18 and seven were uncommitted, but state gop officials predicted a final tabulation would show bush with 20 delegates, dole with 18 and nine uncommitted
nes said the discrepancy resulted from not being able to reprogram its election tabulation computer to accommodate a change in the complicated district delegate assignment formula
neither kemp or robertson qualified for any of missouri's 47 gop delegates at stake
the nes results showed gephardt with 62 delegates, jackson with 14 and dukakis with one
suddenly, maneuver and momentum, strategic ploys and comeback vows count for little in the campaign for the republican presidential nomination. it is a contest of plain numbers now, and they add up to vice president george bush
it isn't over, but it isn't open, and won't be unless a weakened, shrinking field finds a way to stop bush
after his super tuesday primary election sweep, on the biggest election day of a political lifetime, bush needs little more than one-third of the republican national convention delegates yet to be chosen in order to gain a nominating majority
to prevent it, sen. bob dole would have to score a succession of shutouts and capture more than three-quarters of the delegates left to be won. dole says he will storm back in the illinois primary next week. but even if dole does win there, bush surely will add significantly to his delegate count
and just now, the shutout belongs to bush: 16 victories, only two of them even close, and both of those on the borders of dole's kansas home
among democrats, sen. albert gore jr. has proven himself a strong regional candidate in the south, and now must prove that's not what he is. gore wagered his campaign on a southern strategy that defied conventional campaign guideposts, and made it work
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis won big, too, at home and away. jesse jackson was a winner as well
the democrats' big three divided 15 states evenly among them. dukakis won his home state, and captured two of the biggest prizes in the south, texas and florida. that translated into more than 350 delegates for dukakis, with jackson and gore close behind
rep. richard gephardt managed to win only in his missouri home, losing in regional competition he once thought was structured to his advantage
gore bypassed the iowa and new hampshire contests after early forays showed his chances there were negligible. while gephardt and dukakis were splitting those contests, gore concentrated his time and, more important, his money on his southern base
it worked, and he won front-rank status for the next set of contests. now he must compete in the industrial north, beginning next week in illinois. that will be a difficult test
the political terrain there is promising for the liberal dukakis. jackson's black vote is solid and his base is chicago. illinois sen. paul simon returns to the campaign, at least for a week, as a favorite son. and while gephardt is battered, he isn't finished
gore boasts of his caucus showings in some states outside the south as evidence that he's more than a regional figure. but he says realistically that he must prove himself in places like illinois, michigan and ohio
add new york and pennsylvania to that lineup, and the schedule seems made to order for dukakis
while the massachusetts governor is the democrat to beat, bush's gop rivals will have to become political magicians to find a way to stop him
bush's triumph came exactly one month after the iowa caucuses in which he ran an embarrassing third, behind dole and pat robertson, the former television evangelist. bush then won the new hampshire primary, and said that reports of his death had been greatly exaggerated
dole and robertson were left to try to fend off the obituaries this time. rep. jack kemp wasn't even trying that. kemp, who once saw the south as a prime target for his conservative campaign, ran far behind the field, effectively ending his quest
as state after state went to bush, dole, in chicago, pronounced the illinois primary next tuesday ``more and more important.''
this is going to be bob dole's recovery state,'' he said, ``it's going to be the turnaround state.''
if it isn't, illinois could be the farewell state
robertson, whose evangelical supporters are dedicated and formidable in caucus states, salvaged one victory tuesday, in the washington state caucuses. ``coming out of illinois, it's very possible that it will be a two-man race _ bush and robertson,'' said robertson
by way of evidence, he said only that he has the financing to go all the way to the republican convention next summer
after losing states in bunches, dole, robertson and democrat gephardt agreed on one thing: they're glad to be going back to competition in which one state votes at a time
i think maybe it was a disservice to the voters to put 20 states on one day,'' said gephardt, after winning only one of them
editor's note: walter r. mears, veteran political reporter for the associated press, is now executive editor
democrat jesse jackson hammered the opposition in virginia's first presidential primary, while vice president george bush swept to another easy victory in his 16-state clean-up
jackson's campaign leaders had expected a sterling performance tuesday from their candidate, who carried the state's presidential caucuses in 1984
we laid the groundwork,'' said mary cox, jackson's virginia coordinator. ``our goal was to expand at least 10 to 12 percent beyond our natural black base, and we've successfully done that.''
with 1,967 of 1,986 precincts or 99 percent reporting, jackson had 161,704 votes or 45 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 81,139 or 23 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis 78,141 or 22 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt 16,082 or 4 percent
in the republican race, with 2,298 of 2,391 precincts or 96 percent reporting, bush had 141,743 votes or 60 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 51,239 or 22 percent, and virginia native pat robertson had 29,326 or 12 percent. new york rep. jack kemp had 11,490 or 5 percent
jackson, relying on strong support in hampton roads and the richmond area, overcame gore's numbers in southwestern virginia and dukakis' power base in virginia's washington, d.c., suburbs
with 75 of the state democratic party's 85 national convention delegates riding on the outcome, jackson appeared to have won 37 delegates to 22 for gore and 16 for dukakis
no gop delegates were at stake; the 50 national convention delegates are allocated through local caucuses and mass meetings
boyd marcus, state coordinator for the bush campaign, said he would have been pleased with a mid-40 percent showing. the 2-to-1 win over dole ``has been the most surprising thing,'' he said
robertson, a former tv evangelist, placed third even in his home city of virginia beach, a showing his supporters had anticipated
anne kincaid, robertson's virginia coordinator, said the former evangelist ``expected to run third because we hadn't done anything to broaden his base of support. ... pat's going to stay in this thing right through the convention.'' killed</head>
