_canada: montreal 28 cloudy; toronto 37 cloudy
the u.s. dollar steadied against european currencies and the japanese yen today after falling sharply against a surging british pound. gold was unchanged to slightly lower
in london, the british pound was quoted at $1.8340, compared with $1.8415 tuesday, and eased down from a high of 3.09 west german marks to 3.065
we think the pound will stabilize around these levels,'' said a trader with a frankfurt bank. ``its rise was too sharp and too fast.''
the pound has gained a massive 10 cents this week, powered by high british interest rates. although the bank of england has intervened to stem the rise, it was strengthened further by prime minister margaret thatcher ruling out a cut in interest rates
in tokyo the dollar rose 0.28 yen to a closing 128.08. later, in london, it was quoted at 128.23 yen
a dealer in rome speculated that vice president george bush's triumph in the super tuesday primaries may also have calmed markets, because he is perceived here as an anti-protectionist
the dollar, trading in a narrow range, was little changed from late tuesday. some rates:
_1.6718 west german marks, up from 1.6668
_1.3810 swiss francs, up from 1.3790
_5.6590 french francs, down from 5.6625
_1.8774 dutch guilders, down from 1.8780
_1.233.00 italian lire, down from 1,234.00
_1.2545 canadian dollar, up from 1.2524
gold opened in london at a bid price of $435.80 a troy ounce, compared with late tuesday's $438.10. at mid-morning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $436.10
in zurich, the bid price was $435.80, down from $436.50 late tuesday
earlier, in hong kong, gold rose one cent to close at a bid $438.01
silver was quoted in london today at a bid price of $6.28 a troy ounce, down from tuesday's $6.36
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis rode an endorsement by hawaii's top elected democrats to a narrow victory over jesse jackson in a presidential preference poll at the state's democratic party caucuses
with all but about a dozen of 283 precincts reporting, dukakis had 2,026 votes, while jackson had 1,470. none of the other candidates or the choice of ``uncommitted'' had enough votes to qualify for any of the state's 20 pledged delegates to the democratic national convention
party officials were analyzing the results today to determine the allocation of the pledged delegates, but it appeared dukakis would get 12 delegates and jackson 8
in endorsing dukakis, gov. john waihee was joined by sens. daniel inouye and spark matsunaga, rep. daniel akaka, lt. gov. benjamin cayetano, and the mayors of hawaii and kauai islands
waihee said he was not surprised by jackson's strong showing and said it was ``healthy for the democratic party.''
jackson supporters signed up about 2,000 new party members prior to the caucuses
the jackson campaign claimed victory with their strong showing against the endorsement of the democratic establishment
jackson's showing in hawaii puts an end to the belief that jesse jackson is not electable, and to the belief that jackson can win only in states with large black populations,'' said richard port, manager of the jackson campaign in hawaii
the votes of other candidates were richard gephardt, 83; paul simon, 46; albert gore, 41; gary hart, 83; and ``uncommitted,'' 183
only 36 democrats took part presidential preference caucuses in this south pacific territory, dividing their support between massachusetts governor michael dukakis and missouri rep. richard gephardt
the democrats rejected a call by party leaders in american samoa to endorse an uncommitted slate of delegates to the democratic national convention
american samoa was the smallest player in super tuesday, with three delegates available and about 300 democrats eligible to take part in the meetings
national committeeman glenn jones said 36 democrats attended the caucuses. he said few voters turned out probably because the territory has no electoral votes in the presidential election
of the 36 votes cast, 14 went for dukakis, eight for gephardt, and two for jesse jackson. the remaining 12 were uncommitted
that means that dukakis and gephardt will have one delegate each, and the third member of the american samoa delegation will be uncommitted
jones said that of all the candidates, only jackson's campaign had contacted party officials for convention support
we would rather wait to see where the trend is going ... who doesn't make the cut,'' said party chairman utu r.m. sinagege
at least $1.7 million fell into the street from an armored truck, and when a crowd gathered up the cash at least three people made off with $500,000, police said
two unidentified men and a woman disappeared tuesday afternoon with cash-stuffed money bags scattered from a crate that fell out of the moving loomis armored inc. truck in the city's mission district
(they) decided they were going to take advantage of what happened, threw the bags into their cars and left,'' said police officer harry soulette
soulette said he was flagged down by the loomis truck driver, who was unaware of the loss until a motorist honked his horn and told him the door of the truck was ajar, soulette said
two blocks back, a crowd gathered around the crate, which postal worker daniel higginbotham moved to the sidewalk. some people helped him gather the bags, recovering about $1.2 million, police said. some didn't
there was a gentleman from the post office grabbing bags of money out of people's hands and putting them back in the (crate),'' soulette said. ``at least three people looked at him and told him what he could do with his suggestion.'' others may have taken a few bags and fled on foot, police said. it's not a case of finders keepers, soulette said. if caught, the money-grubbers face grand theft charges. ``that's a felony. my advice to them is to turn it in,'' soulette said
witnesses gave detailed descriptions of the two men and the woman, who each took several bags, and their cars, soulette said
one man picked up two sacks and returned them immediately to the company, police said. louis a. lopez, of daly city, drove straight to loomis to hand over two bags containing $40,100 in cash, soulette said
neither lopez nor higginbotham could be reached for comment tuesday night
the money had come from different banks and businesses. the truck was on the way back to loomis and was several blocks away when the door, which may not have been closed securely, sprang open, soulette said
republican presidential candidate george bush was the clear-cut winner on super tuesday, capturing the largest delegate prize, while michael dukakis led a three-way democratic race in the primaries and caucuses
dukakis led among the democrats with 386 delegates for a total of 455.5, but jesse jackson and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. were hot on the heels of the massachusetts governor
jackson picked up 366 delegates for a total of 393.55 while gore collected 326 delegates for a total of 347.8
the close finish among the three democrats fueled the theory of sen. paul simon's campaign that super tuesday would produce a ``gridlock'' of delegates, making it unlikely that any candidate would gain a majority of the delegates after the last round of primaries in june
bush, who amassed 578 delegates with wins in 16 primaries, has 62 percent of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the gop nomination _ a total of 705. kansas sen. bob dole was a distant second, collecting 98 delegates for a total of 163
former television evangelist pat robertson won 9 delegates for a total of 17 and new york rep. jack kemp added four delegates to his previous total of 35. thirty-five delegates remain uncommitted
simon, who bypassed the super tuesday contests to concentrate on the primary in his home state of illinois, slated for next week, gained no delegates and stands at his previous total of 35.5
rep. richard gephardt apparently failed to get his message across in the southern and border states, capturing just 93 delegates, including 61 of 77 in his home state of missouri. gephardt emerged from super tuesday with a total of 143 delegates
former colorado sen. gary hart had no delegates, and 259.65 are uncommitted
in minnesota, the state democratic party released results from its feb. 23 precinct caucuses, which had been kept under seal until super tuesday at the demand of the national party. the results were so incomplete, however, that a national figure could not be calculated for 78 of minnesota's delegates
going into super tuesday, bush held 127 gop delegates and dukakis had 69.5 democratic delegates
dole began the day with 65 delegates, robertson had eight and 12 republican delegates chosen before tuesday were uncommitted
gephardt had 50 democratic delegates before tuesday's balloting, jackson had 27.55, gore had 21.8, and 254.65 were uncommitted. in addition to delegates picked through primaries or caucuses, those totals included democratic ``super delegates,'' the party leaders, governors and others who will automatically hold seats as delegates to the national convention
under democratic party rules, some of the ``super delegates'' cast fractional votes
in all, 4,162 delegates are to attend the democratic national convention in atlanta in july and 2,277 delegates will attend the republican national convention in new orleans in august. winning the democratic presidential nomination will require support from at least 2,082 delegates
britain demanded today that the panamanian ambassador waive his diplomatic immunity and face police questioning about a raid he authorized to seize control of his country's london consulate
the foreign office said it expected an answer from ambassador guillermo vega by the end of the day, and warned that expulsion ``remains an option.''
vega was summoned to the foreign office twice tuesday to explain monday night's seizure, an extension of the struggle for control of panama's government
representatives of vega, accompanied by hired security guards, crashed a land rover through the glass doors of the consulate on fleet street and occupied the offices
vega supports panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega, who engineered the ouster of president eric delvalle feb. 26. consul eduardo arango, whose offices were seized, is loyal to delvalle
the foreign office said it asked vega and embassy counselor jorge e. constantino to waive their diplomatic immunity so that police can question them about the incident
we haven't given him a deadline as such. we made it clear that we want to hear (a reply) today,'' said a spokesman who, under british civil service rules, cannot be identified
under international law, accredited diplomats are immune from police action but can be expelled if the host government believes them guilty of misconduct
seven britons were arrested and charged with public order offenses for alleged roles in the consulate raid
the times quoted foreign office minister timothy eggar as saying: ``what is at issue here is whether any panamanian embassy official has taken the law into his own hands. the british government will not tolerate any such action.''
prime minister margaret thatcher told parliament tuesday: ``differences of opinion should not be fought out on london streets.''
vega has said the raid had his authority, and that the consulate was ``full of outsiders to the panamanian government.''
control of the panamanian embassy in washington is also in dispute
delvalle was ousted hours after he ordered noriega to step down. the general was indicted in florida last month on federal drug trafficking charges
the reagan administration says it still considers delvalle panama's chief of state. the thatcher government has not stated a position on the matter
the christian democratic politician died in the tuebingen university hospital of heart failure, the ard television network said on its 1 p.m. newscast
kiesinger served as west germany's third chancellor, from 1966 to 1969
he grouped together the christian democrats and their bavarian counterparts with the leftist-leaning social democrats (spd) to form what is called the ``grand coalition.'' willy brandt served as the coalition's foreign minister, before taking over as chancellor. integrity</head>
the engineer who tried to prevent the launch of the space shuttle challenger before its fatal 1986 launch has been honored as nation's the most courageous and most ethical engineer
allan j. mcdonald, a vice president of morton thiokol corp., received an honorary award tuesday from design news magazine, said steve thompson, the publisher of the magazine
al mcdonald was the one guy who tried to stop it,'' said thompson, who presented the magazine's awards at a banquet in chicago
he had the courage to stand up to the whole world and say `look, you can't do this' _ that's why he's special.''
a presidential commission has blamed the challenger disaster on a flaw in a booster rocket built by morton thiokol. seven astronauts died in the explosion
during a speech after receiving the award, mcdonald, 50, said he hopes the challenger disaster does not leave the nation's space program paralyzed
my biggest concern is that we've lost the nerve to ever fly anything again,'' mcdonald said. ``we think we have to have complete safety. i don't think we will ever have that.''
mcdonald said the space shuttle will be ready for its next scheduled launch in august
one thing worse than failure is not to try,'' he said
also honored tuesday was elbert rutan, who designed the voyager, the first aircraft to fly around the world without refueling. rutan was voted best engineer by the magazine's 750,000 readers, thompson said
a preliminary autopsy on the body of 300-pound female impersonator divine, star of the cult film classic ``pink flamingos,'' failed to pinpoint a cause of death, coroner's officials said
the 42-year-old actor, whose real name was harris glenn milstead, was found dead in his bed monday at the hollywood regency plaza hotel
the los angeles county coroner's office has ordered a microscopic examination of tissue samples, but preliminary tests taken tuesday showed no signs of trauma or any other factor that would have contributed to the actor's death, coroner's spokesman steve stewart said
drugs and alcohol are unlikely to have caused the death of milstead, his manager said. publicist john west of pmk said the actor apparently died of asphyxiation
john waters, director of ``hairspray'' and ``pink flamingos'' who grew up with milstead in baltimore, read a tribute to his friend tuesday afternoon at a downtown baltimore hotel
not only did i respect him as the best actor i've ever worked with, i knew him personally as a kind and gentle man,'' waters said, his voice catching. ``a huge portion of the success of my film is owed him. ... divine is as irreplaceable to me as a member of my own family. i'll miss him incredibly.''
manager bernard jay said milstead had a long-term weight problem, but except for that was found to be in excellent health during a medical checkup last friday
he was not on drugs at all, and he never drank alcohol,'' jay said. ``i suppose it all comes down to his weight. he was constantly trying to diet, but as soon as he'd take the pounds off, they'd come right back on again.''
milstead was in town to appear in an episode of ``married ... with children,'' a fox television network series
he had been pleased over critical praise for his role in ``hairspray'' as edna turnblad, the fat mother of a fat teen-age girl
he'd call me in the middle of the night to read me some newspaper interview and say, ``isn't it wonderful! they called me divine, the 300-pound actor, not divine, the 300-pound transvestite,'' jay said
a native of lutherville, md., milstead's came to fame as the bizarre star of ``pink flamingos,'' ``lust in the dust,'' ``polyester'' and ``female trouble.''
milstead played one full non-transvestite role in his career, that of a sydney greenstreet-type character in the 1985 film ``trouble in mind.''
besides film roles, milstead also used the divine persona in a nightclub act
waters said that the last time he had spoken to divine was two days ago, and he had last seen him at the premiere of ``hairspray'' in new york city
in their last conversations, waters said, ``he was just so happy. he said `can you believe we came this far?'''
here, at a glance, are results from the super tuesday primaries and caucuses:
jesse jackson had expected to win comfortably on the strength of a sizable black vote, but instead narrowly defeated tennessee sen. albert gore jr., who was endorsed by sen. howell heflin. vice president george bush swamped kansas sen. bob dole just as expected
democrats in the south pacific territory, smallest of super tuesday's players, chose one national convention delegate for massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, one for missouri rep. richard gephardt, and one uncommitted. only 36 people voted at party caucuses
gore won with 36 percent, dukakis had 19 percent and jackson had 17 percent. gov. bill clinton said gore benefited from undecided voters, and the big surprise was the fourth place, 12 percent showing of gephardt. bush won with nearly half the vote
rep. bill alexander won re-election to an 11th term, defeating political consultant darrell glascock by 2-1 in the democratic primary. alexander is unopposed in the general election
dukakis found a warm reception from transplanted northerners and pulled in 39 percent of the vote to jackson's 20 percent. bush took advantage of president reagan's popularity, gov. bob martinez' endorsement and family ties (his son jeb is secretary of commerce) to trounce dole nearly 3-1
jackson won by piling up margins of better than 8-1 over gore and dukakis in the 5th congressional district, composed largely of the city of atlanta. the heavy black vote outweighed gore's endorsements by sen. sam nunn and gov. joe frank harris. bush beat dole better than 2-1
endorsements by the state's top democrats were credited with helping dukakis defeat jackson at hawaii's democratic party caucuses by nearly a 3-2 margin. gov. john waihee, who backed dukakis, said he wasn't surprised by jackson's strong showing and called it ``healthy for the democratic party.''
dukakis captured 8 of 18 uncommitted delegates, with jackson winning 4 and 6 going to the state convention uncommitted. gov. cecil andrus, who says he will go to the convention uncommitted, said the turning point in the dukakis campaign was a last-minute visit to boise last weekend. jackson's strong showing was a surprise because the state has a minority population of less than 5 percent
gore won his neighboring state with help from gov. wallace wilkinson, gaining 46 percent of the vote to dukakis' 18 percent. bush's 59 percent vote was termed ``astounding'' by his state campaign chairman, rep. harold ``hal'' rogers, who had predicted a 48 percent victory
jackson edged gore 34 percent to 29 percent despite gore's endorsement by democratic gov.-elect buddy roemer. bush breezed to victory with 59 percent, leaving dole and roberston each with 18 percent
in the 4th congressional district race to replace roemer, his former congressional aide jim mccrery, a republican, and democratic state sen. foster campbell claimed spots in an april 16 runoff
jackson finished second to dukakis, 31 percent to 43 percent, with a strong showing in the two predominantly black congressional districts. bush carried all eight districts even though he didn't campaign personally in maryland, while dole did spend some time in the state. bush led 53 percent to 32 percent
democratic sen. paul sarbanes easily won nomination for a third term and will be opposed by millionaire businessman thomas blair, a newcomer to politics
dukakis' home state gave him 59 percent of the vote. jackson was second with 19 percent. the win at home and victories in florida and texas gave dukakis the three biggest super tuesday prizes. bush, who was born in massachusetts, got 59 percent of the vote to dole's 26 percent. gordon nelson, state co-chairman for new york rep. jack kemp's campaign, said bush convinced voters he was reagan's logical successor: ``george bush won because he is reagan ii.''
bush and jackson rang up big victories, with jackson helped by turnout in the heavily black delta that enabled him to defeat gore
in a democratic primary for the seat of retiring sen. john stennis, voters chose rep. wayne dowdy to oppose gop rep. trent lott in november
bush won a narrow victory in dole's backyard, getting 42 percent of the vote to dole's 41 percent. bush pulled ahead with returns from st. louis county. gephardt easily won his home state with 58 percent of the vote, but it was his only victory tuesday. jackson was second with 21 percent
gore won in a tally at nevada's democratic caucuses, with dukakis second and jackson a surprisingly strong third. in balloting for county convention delegates, gore, who got support from sen. harry reid and other top state democrats, had 33 percent to dukakis' 26 and jackson's 22. party chairman beecher avants said jackson's strong showing ``was a real surprise.''
dole lost his wife's home state as bush emphasized his ties to president reagan. bush had 45 percent to dole's 40 percent of the gop vote. endorsements from such key democrats as sen. terry sanford and former gov. jim hunt helped gore squeeze past jackson 35 percent to 33 percent
gore got 41 percent of the vote, almost double his nearest competitor, gephardt. gore's victory margin was a surprise because a recent poll showed him in a tie with gephardt and dukakis. but he visited the state several times and spent more on advertising than any other democrat. as expected, the gop contest was close, with bush capturing 37 percent of the vote and dole 35 percent
bush and dukakis continued their new england sweeps, with the vice president winning 65 percent of the gop vote and the governor from neighboring massachusetts getting nearly 70 percent of the democratic vote. bush had built up good will through previous campaign journeys on behalf of gov. edward d. diprete and rep. claudine schneider
gore's home state gave him about 74 percent of the vote, leaving jackson, with 19 percent, a distant second. bush trounced dole nearly 3-1
dukakis won the top delegate state with 33 percent of the vote. bush, who built an oil business in texas, crushed all his rivals, receiving 65 percent of the vote. robertson got 15 percent and dole 14 percent
democratic u.s. sen. lloyd bentsen easily won renomination for a fourth term. rep. beau boulter and wes gilbreath, a houston investor, advance to gop runoff for u.s. senate. the winner faces bentsen in november
jackson received 45 percent of the vote, with gore far behind at 23 percent and dukakis with 22 percent. jackson got strong support in hampton roads and the richmond area, overcoming gore's numbers in southwestern virginia and dukakis' power base in suburbs near washington, d.c. boyd marcus, bush's state coordinator, said he would have been pleased with a mid-40 percent showing. the 2-to-1 win over dole (60 percent to 22 percent) ``has been the most surprising thing,'' he said.virginia native robertson had 12 percent
robertson's 38 percent of the vote gave him his only victory of super tuesday. dole had 27 percent, and bush was third, his only loss of the night, with 24 percent. to claim their share of the state's 41 gop delegates, the candidates will have to fare as well in this spring's county or legislative district caucuses, which precede the july 15 state convention where delegates will be allocated. dukakis, endorsed by gov. booth gardner, led democrats with 45 percent, followed by jackson with 32 percent. the democrats' tally won't be completed for a week
the man who found what police believe to be a valuable stolen painting by french impressionist claude monet stolen says the artwork appears to be damaged
you could see places where it was rolled up very tightly and maybe flattened. it had lines running down it from that, and some of the oil paint was peeled off in places,'' said charles polley, postmaster at legrand who found the painting tuesday morning in a mail drop-off box
local police, the fbi and the international police agency interpol have been searching for the oil painting since it was cut out of its frame at the fisher community center on march 19, 1987
the painting, ``fishing boats in front of the cliffs at etretat,'' was insured for $175,000 by st. paul fire and marine insurance co. the canvas was painted by monet around 1891
the painting was rolled up and bound by two rubber bands when polley found it mixed in with other pieces of mail. he said it was dropped sometime after 3 p.m. monday and before 7:30 a.m. tuesday when he opened the mailbox
i thought it was trash at first _ but it sure wasn't trash,'' polley said. ``it had the look of canvas, and i looked at the edges and knew exactly what it was.''
when the painting was cut out of its frame, which was rigged to an alarm system in the police department, the thief didn't make a clean cut along the bottom of the frame, leaving a jagged tear in the painting
i called just about everyone but interpol,'' said polley. ``you never know what a day will bring.''
lt. darrell templeton said at a news conference that he unrolled part of the left edge of the painting _ the side that shows the cliffs _ and to him it appears the painting is the original
he said the fbi will be contacted, and examiners hired by the insurance company will have to determine for certain that the painting is the stolen monet
templeton said it was a frustrating investigation involving countless telephone calls and false leads. but he said articles about the theft probably kept it from being sold on the black market, ``because it was an odd way of getting it back.''
templeton said police have no suspects other than a white male, about 6-foot-2 or 6-3 and weighing about 250 pounds, who was seen cutting the painting out of its frame
rex ryden, in charge of the fisher foundation, wasn't sure yet how the insurance company will react, since the insurance was paid
he said the painting will have to be inspected for damage and whether it can be restored
it will be a drawn-out procedure,'' ryden said
guerrillas derailed a passenger train with a mine and then attacked it, killing at least 11 people and wounding 29, the national news agency reported today
the news agency, aim, said attack occurred tuesday after the train crossed into mozambique from south africa. it said many of the passengers were mozambican miners returning from jobs in south africa
rebels of the mozambique national resistance killed 23 people and wounded 71 in an attack on a train in the same area last dec. 31, according to mozambican officials
the rebels have been waging a hit-and-run insurgency against the marxist government since 1977. maputo claims the rebels are backed by south africa, a charge both the rebels and south africa deny
ewes imported from britain, new zealand and australia for breeding are being sheepish about sex, veterinary officials said
local rams are not interested either, apparently because they like their mates petite and find the foreigners too big. the coy ewes may be disoriented by the tropical weather, because they are used to four seasons
agriculture minister sanusi junid has suggested keeping the animals in the dark, an idea the veterinary services department is taking seriously, director-general ahmad mustaffa babjee said at a conference today
the imported sheep should be put in a dark room at a certain time of the year for some time. when they come out into the light they may think it is another season and get into the mood to mate,'' sanusi said in a speech to the commonwealth veterinary officers conference
about 20,000 sheep are imported annually for breeding as part of a government plan to have 1 million head of sheep in malaysia by the year 1990
italian soldiers will have to brave the weather without umbrellas, defense minister valerio zanone has decided
zanone, a liberal, said equipment issued to italian soldiers provides adequate protection in the average climatic conditions of this mediterranean country
the radical party had suggested that italy follow the u.s. military's decision to authorize use of umbrellas
a white supremacist accused of plotting to overthrow the government said he would plead guilty after a judge refused to suppress a statement the man gave to authorities
bruce pierce had sought dismissal of the statement he gave to fbi agents after he was arrested in georgia in 1985. when u.s. district judge morris arnold refused, pierce rose in the courtroom
i'm going to plead guilty, if that's the court's decision,'' pierce said tuesday
arnold told him to discuss the matter with his attorney, bennett nolan, and after a conference with pierce and other defendants, nolan said that pierce would make a final decision this week on whether to plead guilty
pierce and nine other white supremacists are charged with sedition. five defendants are accused of conspiring to kill a federal judge and an fbi agent, and two are accused of interstate transportation of stolen money
pierce is serving sentences totaling 250 years in prison _ 100 years for racketeering and 150 years for violating the civil rights of outspoken jewish radio talk show host alan berg, who was machine gunned to death in denver
wayne manis, an fbi agent, had been scheduled to testify tuesday that pierce confessed several crimes to him while pierce was in federal custody in atlanta
pierce had argued that his statement was not made voluntarily and should be suppressed. he said agents threatened to have his wife arrested and put his three children in foster homes if he refused to make the statement
arnold said he decided the statement was made voluntarily
silent screen actress lois wilson, who appeared in more than 100 early films including the 1923 western epic ``the covered wagon,'' has died of pneumonia. she was 93
the actress, who sought fame in hollywood after winning a 1915 statewide beauty contest in alabama, died at the riverside hospital for skilled care here on march 3, a nursing supervisor confirmed today
miss wilson was buried monday at forest lawn memorial-park in glendale, calif., after a memorial service at the church of the good shepherd in beverly hills, calif
after her arrival in hollywood, miss wilson landed a small part in ``the dumb girl of portici,'' which starred legendary ballerina anna pavlova. she went on to act in more than 100 silent and sound films over the next 33 years
her best-known roles included molly wingate in ``the covered wagon'' and daisy buchanan in the 1926 version of ``the great gatsby,'' for which she won the photoplay magazine best performance award
miss wilson acted opposite such leading men as rudolph valentino and john gilbert
after retiring from motion pictures in 1941 _ except for a bit part in the 1949 comedy ``the girl from jones beach,'' starring ronald reagan _ miss wilson turned to the broadway stage, and eventually television
among the network soap operas in which she played featured character roles were ``the guiding light'' and ``the edge of night.''
although she never married, miss wilson, a 5-foot-5 brunette, was once described as cultivating a screen image of the ``soft, marrying kind of woman.''
selected in 1924 by paramount to represent the motion-picture industry at the british empire exposition, miss wilson was termed ``a typical example of the american girl in character, culture and beauty.''
on leaving television, miss wilson returned to the los angeles suburb of north hollywood, where she shared a home with a sister. she later moved near a niece in reno. 3rd graf pvs, he was</note>
tennessee sen. albert gore, who vaulted into the front rank of the democratic pack with a strong super tuesday showing, said today that ``people were responding to my message,'' not his southern background
we won in the west also, and sooner or later it's going to stop being a surprise,'' gore said on abc-tv's ``good morning america.''
i am not a southern candidate,'' gore said tuesday night in nashville, tenn. ``i'm a national candidate who's a southern and proud of it.''
i'm excited about this victory. i thought it would happen exactly this way ... people were responding to my message,'' gore said today
i think it essentially is a three-person race,'' gore said. ``democrats are looking at who can best carry our party's standard into the fall election
he was leaving today for chicago before heading for south carolina, where he hoped to pick up delegates at that state's democratic caucuses on saturday
gore established himself as a solid contender by winning five states in his native south: tennessee, kentucky, arkansas, north carolina and oklahoma
even as the votes were being counted in tuesday's races, gore was looking ahead to the next round of contests, in the industrial states of the north
