bob wieland, the legless vietnam veteran who co-stars in the nbc-tv series ``sonny spoon,'' started the los angeles marathon a day early and ended it two days late, exhausted but proud
wieland, 41, covered the 26.2-mile course in about 74{ hours without using a wheelchair. he bettered his 1987 marathon time by an impressive 18 hours, using his powerful arms to push himself along on his padded hands
he crossed the finish line tuesday morning to cheers from about 100 well-wishers and reporters. ``outside of vietnam, this has been the most intense 72 hours i ever spent in my entire life,'' he said as he neared the finish
wieland was the first to start the la marathon on saturday, a day earlier than most of the 17,040 runners, and was the last to finish. pickup.</note>
former chancellor kurt georg kiesinger, who overcame the taint of a nazi past to head west germany for three years in the 1960s, died today at age 83
kiesinger had been a member of the nazi party from 1933 to 1945 and worked in the foreign ministry's radio propaganda section during world war ii. he was never charged with war crimes or atrocities
the christian democratic politician died in the tuebingen university hospital of heart failure, his office in bonn said in a statement released to the news media
in 1966, kiesinger succeeded fellow christian democrat chancellor ludwig erhard, whose mini-coalition with the small free democrats had broken up
kiesinger, serving as west germany's third chancellor, was a symbol of reconciliation to many germans. he grouped the conservative christian democrats and their bavarian counterparts with the leftist-leaning social democrats to forge what was called the ``grand coalition.''
it was the first german government in a generation to include the social democrats, whose willy brandt served as the coalition's foreign minister before taking over as chancellor in 1969
kiesinger, a roman catholic, was born april 6, 1904 in ebingen, baden-wuerttemburg. tall and silver-haired, he spoke with a vibrant voice tinged with the dialect of his native swabia
as a 29-year-old lawyer, kiesinger joined the nazi party in 1933, the year adolf hitler came to power. he said he became disillusioned with the party a year later because of the bloody purge of storm trooper leader ernst roehm and his associates
during world war ii, kiesinger worked in the radio propaganda section of the nazi foreign ministry, acting as department head for some of his term there
after the war, he spent 16 months in an american internment camp. a german court fined him 50 marks, then $12.50, for being a party member. the fine was remitted when the court ruled later that he had risked his life to get a student out of a nazi prison
kiesinger's nazi past brought him much unfavorable publicity when he became a candidate for chancellor, and the issue cropped up again during his term. he always denied any wrongdoing and declared:
i have clean hands. i know what i did and what i did not do.''
he forged stronger ties with the communist states of eastern europe, breaking with past policy. he opened diplomatic relations with romania and yugoslavia, but his overtures suffered a setback when the soviets invaded czechoslovakia in 1968
his government remained a resolute ally of the united states, but he feuded with president johnson in 1967, when he complained that he had not been adequately consulted on a u.s.-soviet nuclear weapons treaty
he also let johnson know that bonn no longer could afford to buy enough u.s. arms to offset the cost of stationing u.s. troops in germany. as a result, the united states withdrew 35,000 troops in 1967
his administration had inherited a recession, but the coalition suceeded in revitalizing the economy. toward the end of his kiesinger's tenure, however, the booming economy wrought high inflation that was a key to cracking the coalition he helped forge
attackers hurling hand grenades and firing automatic rifles assaulted a police station in soweto and injured nine black officers, police headquarters said today
the assailants fled in a vehicle after policemen returned fire with shotguns, according to police. no arrested were reported
the attack occurred tuesday night as municipal policemen were changing shifts at the mapetla police station in soweto, johannesburg's main black township
police said the attackers threw three hand grenades at the officers and fired soviet-made ak-47 rifles. only one of the wounded officers was seriously hurt, police said
black policemen have been frequent targets of attacks by anti-apartheid militants who view them as government collaborators
authorities have blamed many previous attacks on the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement
union writers refused to continue working on next month's academy awards ceremony script and cbs-tv shelved two new shows as a strike by the writers guild of america put a crunch on hollywood
the academy awards ceremony, scheduled for worldwide broadcast by abc-tv on april 11, will air without the aid of the striking wga, spokeswoman cheryl rhoden said tuesday night
the union's western unit board voted unanimously tuesday night to reject a request for a waiver from the producers of the academy of motion picture arts and sciences show. a waiver would have allowed union work despite the strike
ms. rhoden said the guild's eastern unit didn't vote because the show is produced in los angeles and would only involve members of the western unit
scriptwriter mel shavelson, former wga president, and jack rose were hired by the academy to write the program
if there is no waiver, i won't do the show,'' shavelson said before the vote. he added that the writing is far from complete. ``most of the work is done when the cast shows up at rehearsal. it's rewriting, really.''
cbs-tv announced tuesday that two new shows scheduled to debut later this month have been shelved indefinitely
the dictator,'' a comedy starring christopher lloyd, was in its third week of production in new york but didn't have enough scripts completed to warrant going ahead with next week's premiere, the network said
no scripts had been completed for the other show, ``the smothers brothers comedy hour,'' which was to debut march 23
cbs said ``my sister sam,'' which had been removed from the network's schedule earlier this year, would return in place of ``the dictator.'' the network said it would fill ``the smothers brothers comedy hour'' slot with special programming
on tuesday, leonard farrell of the federal mediation and conciliation service brought together negotiators for the scriptwriters and producers to review differences
both sides outlined differences and issues, but no bargaining was conducted, said herb steinberg, a spokesman for the alliance of motion picture and television producers. sticking points were writers' demands for increased fees and creative rights
in the early evening, the meeting was recessed until 11 a.m. thursday
this strike is going to be over someday,'' farrell told reporters. ``and it might just as well be over now. that's what we usually tell (the opposing sides).''
the strike began monday with a massive picket line in front of 20th century fox studios. it followed the writers' rejection sunday of the producers' final contract offer
talk shows and soap operas would be the first to feel the effects of the strike, probably turning to reruns, the union said. producers said other shows had stockpiled scripts
the wga strike is the fourth since a 17-week walkout in 1973. the longest, in 1981, lasted three months. quote; picks up 4th graf bgng, `bybee contended</note>
a government attorney contends that although the united states committed ``great wrongs'' to the thousands of japanese-americans detained in prison camps during world war ii, the victims shouldn't be allowed to sue now for damages
the statute of limitations clearly began to run in the 1940s,'' justice department attorney jay bybee told the u.s. circuit court of appeals for the federal circuit during arguments tuesday on a $24 billion lawsuit filed in 1983 on behalf of 120,000 japanese-americans
bybee told the three-judge panel of giles rich, phillip baldwin and helen nies, ``there is no dispute that there were great wrongs done to japanese-americans.... but even when mistakes are made, people must file timely claims for redress.''
bybee contended that the six-year statute of limitations on suits against the government expired decades ago
but plaintiffs' attorney benjamin zelenko argued that the statute of limitations did not come into play until the early 1980s because of ``deliberate concealment and misrepresentation by the government of critical information regarding its claim of `military necessity''' for the internment
president franklin d. roosevelt authorized the internment of japanese-americans and japanese citizens living in california and parts of oregon, washington and arizona in the wake of the 1941 japanese attack on pearl harbor, when he was advised by military leaders that people of japanese descent could not be trusted
the only time the supreme court has ruled on the internment itself was in 1944, when it found the action was a constitutionally acceptable military necessity. government documents discovered later indicate no such military necessity existed
the concealment didn't end, zelenko argued, until the 1980s, when a congressionally appointed commission found that there was no military necessity for the internment. the policy was ``driven by race prejudice, war hysteria and lack of political leadership,'' he said
this is the second time a federal appeals court has heard the case. in 1986, the u.s. circuit court of appeals for the district of columbia ruled that the government must defend itself at trial against the suit. that ruling overturned a 1984 decision by district court judge louis f. oberdorfer, who had ruled that the statute of limitations had expired
but last june, the supreme court ruled that the statute of limitations issue should have been decided by a different court _ the u.s. circuit court of appeals for the federal circuit
the lead plaintiff in the case is william hohri, a computer programmer living in chicago. hohri, a san francisco native who lived in southern california when the war began, said tuesday he was interned at manzanar camp east of the sierra nevada shortly after his 15th birthday. he left for the midwest 2{ years later and never returned to california
an inmate at the federal correctional institute who arranged a helicopter escape with an undercover fbi agent was seized just as he was trying to make his getaway, officials said
prison officers grabbed william m. carroll, 28, on tuesday after he used a red apron he was wearing to signal a helicopter pilot hovering over the facility, said ray hooker, executive assistant to warden john gluch
but it didn't land, and the guy tried to blend into the prison population,'' said kenneth walton, head of the fbi's michigan office
he thought he had it made, and then the guards started coming out of the woodwork. they arrested him and now he's in segregation.''
carroll, a georgia native, was serving a 15-year sentence on a 1986 conviction for aiding and abetting in the counterfeiting of $20 bills, hooker said. he had been scheduled for parole in october 1992
carroll allegedly offered $1.25 million in counterfeit money for the escape, and $1 million if the pilot would kill a federal witness, walton said
authorities at the prison 45 miles southwest of detroit learned of the escape plan through an internal investigation, hooker said. they referred the matter to the fbi, which planted an undercover agent who acted as carroll's contact and also supplied the helicopter and pilot, hooker said
a mathematical puzzle that has fascinated scientists and researchers for hundreds of years may now be solved, a professor at west germany's max-planck institute said today
the puzzle has been how to prove fermat's last theorem, developed by french mathematician pierre de fermat, who lived from 1601 to 1665
the theorem states: x to the nth power, plus y to the nth power, equals z to the nth power, where x, y, and z are nonzero integers, has no solutions for n when n is an integer _ or whole number _ greater than the number two
fermat, who was also a magistrate, developed his expertise in mathematics as a hobby, and was one of the founders of modern number theory and probability
many important developments in number theory have resulted from unsuccessful attempts to prove fermat's last theorem,'' professor don zagier said in a telephone interview
now, japanese mathematician yoichi miyaoka, who also works at the max-planck institute for mathematics in bonn, may have finally proven fermat's last theorem, zagier said
this whole thing is of course in the preliminary stages, but miyaoka, who gave a presentation on his solution 10 days ago, believes he has proven the theory and it is certainly serious and very exciting,'' zagier said
zagier, an american working as a researcher at the max-planck institute, is also a professor at the university of maryland
he said he jotted down notes at miyaoka's presentation and sent them to several experts, including gerd faltings at princeton and mathemeticians barry mazur and christophe soule' in paris
of course the notes alone are not sufficient, and miyaoka has been preparing and checking his manuscript on the solution for the past week, and that will also be sent to the experts to check,'' said zagier
zagier said he hoped some results from the experts would be forthcoming ``within 10 days, but it could also take several months.''
asked if miyaoka was available to discuss his solution of proving fermat's last theorem, zagier said the japanese was ``too busy rechecking his work, because there is always a chance of an error, and he wants to be sure the manuscript is accurate before it goes out.''
i've been more or less answering the telephone for him since word of this leaked out,'' zagier said. corrects number captured to eight, sted 10. adds byline. picks up 6th graf pvs, `military and ...' ^by robert h. reid</note>
eight communist rebels, including a former regional commander, were captured and two were killed in separate raids and clashes across the country, the military said today
also today, opposition sen. juan ponce enrile, a former defense minister, claimed the 19-year communist insurgency was strengthening because the nation's 160,000-member armed forces was increasingly disorganized and poorly supplied
the military said troops killed the leader of the rebel propaganda unit in nueva ecjia province in a clash tuesday north of manila. government forces, which suffered no casualties, also captured four rebels, the report said
brig. gen. domingo rio said nemesio demafiles, former commander of the communist new people's army on negros island, was captured tuesday afternoon in a private home near the local headquarters of the philippine constabulary in bacolod, 300 miles south of manila
three others were arrested in the same raid, the military said, adding that it came a day after demafiles' bodyguard was arrested near bacolod
in a separate incident tuesday, troops killed a rebel officer near the mindanao city of butuan, the military said
military and rebel sources said demafiles was replaced last year as the negros commander of the new people's army, the armed wing of the communist party of the philippines
in a report to constabulary headquarters in manila, rio said police found a .45-caliber pistol and a map of the constabulary office in bacolod during the raid in which demafiles was arrested. the report said demafiles was apparently planning an attack on the paramilitary police bacolod headquarters
negros has been a stronghold of the new people's army
in manila, enrile told the american chamber of commerce that disorganization in the armed forces and a lack of supplies are hampering the anti-insurgency drive
he said the new people's army had grown in size to between 25,000 and 30,000 fighters and that they controlled more territory than at any time during the rebellion
michael dukakis, proclaiming himself ``halfway to winning'' the democratic presidential nomination, said today he was looking forward to the prospect of facing george bush in the fall election
but dukakis, who won in the big super tuesday states of texas and florida and generally split the day's spoils with jesse jackson and albert gore, said he's not assuming the democratic contest is over
i said when this started this is a marathon and we're going to have to take it contest by contest,'' dukakis said on cbs-tv
interviewed on nbc-tv, he said, ``i'd say i'm about halfway to winning the nomination.''
he said he expects to gain enough delegates in the final round of primaries, in california and new jersey, to secure the nomination before the democratic convention
looking past that, he said that ``it looks like the republican nominee is going to be george bush. i'm looking forward to that.''
dukakis, here to campaign for next week's illinois primary, said, ``it's really a great day'' following his showing tuesday
to be a son of massachusetts and to go into florida and texas and beat some candidates who obviously have some very strong ties with the south is just a terrific thing, as well as to do well in maryland ... and out in the pacific northwest.''
asked whether he intended to use negative ads similar to those he has aimed at rival richard gebhardt, dukakis said, ``if people insist on using this negative stuff, then i've learned, unfortunately from painful experience, that you have to respond.''
kicking off his illinois primary campaign, dukakis was playing up his greek immigrant heritage. the chicago area is among the most ethnically diverse in the nation, with its heavy population of first- and second-generation eastern europeans
many of your families, like my parents, came to this land in search of opportunity,'' dukakis told cheering supporters on tuesday. ``they didn't have much money in their pockets; they couldn't speak the language, but they believed in the american dream. ... it was their broad shoulders and strong arms and keen minds that built the mightiest industrial machine in the world.''
despite the cash drain of super tuesday with its emphasis on television advertising, the dukakis campaign remains financially well off
campaign finance chief robert farmer said dukakis was raising half a million dollars a week. coming out of super tuesday, he said, dukakis had $2 million in the bank and another $1 million on the way in federal matching funds
an undergraduate's bill at yale university will rise 6.1 percent to $18,060 for the 1988-89 school year, the prestigious private university said
the percentage rise was the same as last year's, said yale president benno c. schmidt jr. said tuesday. it cost $17,020 to attend yale this school year
the increase was approved over the weekend by the yale corporation, the school's board of trustees. tuition will increase 6.9 percent to $12,960, an increase of 6.9 percent, and room and board will go up to $5,100, an increase of 4 percent
announced increases at other ivy league schools range from 6.2 percent at princeton to 6.7 percent at cornell, said yale spokesman walter littell. the cost of attending most ivy league schools will be in the range of $17,000 to $18,300, according to figures supplied by littell
a bogus fund-raising ring that claimed to aid the families of police officers killed in the line of duty instead pocketed millions of dollars from donors, authorities have charged
three former police detectives for the brooklyn district attorney's office were among 11 people arrested following raids monday at 15 sites in new york city and on long island, manhattan district attorney robert morgenthau said
the ring raised $600,000 a year since setting up the fraudulent charity 10 years ago, morgenthau said tuesday. the ring operated under two names: the police conference of new york inc. and the new york state district attorney police benevolent association
the groups are not registered with the state as charities. the authorities said the groups kept all but about $4,000 a year, which was spent on insurance they sold to police officers on long island
the operation was run by joseph tarantola, 48, of tannersville, pa., who was a detective in the brooklyn district attorney's office until he was fired in 1976 because of questionable fund-raising activities, morgenthau said
also arrested were two of his associates who held the same post: neil lombardo, 44, of brooklyn, a detective from 1970 to 1983; and clark simmons, 66, of brooklyn, a detective from 1969 to 1977
the district attorney said tarantola's group, in business for several years, used solicitors operating out of ``boiler rooms'' to call and pressure potential contributors, most of them businessmen
the solicitors would call and claim connections to legitimate police groups. they would refer to news accounts of officers wounded or killed on duty and appeal to the donor's sympathy or sense of civic duty to get money
if the solicitor got a donation, he would send the giver a souvenir imprinted with an official-looking badge and slogan. souvenirs included decals, baseball caps, lapel pins shaped like badges and large metal shields designed to be affixed to a car bumper. a donor's gift determined which souvenir he got
they would tell the contributor that having this decal on your window is like having the chief in your backseat,'' the district attorney said
the solicitor received a percentage of donations, morgenthau said
the investigation into the ring began in july 1985 after people complained they were being harassed, morgenthau said
authorities raided 15 suspected boiler room sites monday in manhattan, the bronx, brooklyn and queens, and on long island in hempstead and massapequa
tarantola and nine others arrested were charged with first-degree scheming to defraud, punishable by up to four years in prison. an 11th person was arrested on a weapons possession charge for allegedly having an unlicensed pistol. carolina, fresh quotes, picking up 2nd graf pvs, ``this wasn't; subs 17th graf, to underscore</note>
richard gephardt headed for campaign stops in south carolina today after a super tuesday disaster he blamed on lack of money and a withering crossfire from rivals michael dukakis and albert gore jr
with 20 states and a million dollars, we just could not get our message ... in front of the voters,'' gephardt said in an interview broadcast today on abc-tv
i really think i'm the only one who has talked about the issues people really care about,'' gephardt said. ``i just couldn't get it across in enough southern states.''
gephardt said he's not finished ``if i can get back into the race in the states coming up.'' to make the point, he was flying to south carolina today, campaigning for that state's caucuses on saturday
tuesday night, gephardt told supporters, ``i never told you it was going to be easy.''
this wasn't the best of days,'' gephardt told a subdued group of backers after winning only on his home turf of missouri and finishing a dismal third or fourth in most of the 19 other states up for grabs tuesday
gephardt's loss was gore's gain, as the tennessee senator decisively won their battle for the mantle of moderate alternative to dukakis and jesse jackson. gephardt acknowledged that he was unable to counter a spate of negative ads aimed at him by both gore and dukakis
we had a situation where we had about $6 million or $7 million spent against us by those two candidates, against about $1 million we were able to spend,'' he said as the voters' verdict became apparent
later, addressing supporters at his st. louis headquarters, he spoke bravely of future victories rather than analyzing his super tuesday losses
he insisted there are still ``great days ahead'' for his campaign, which had jumped out of the starting gates with a win in the iowa caucuses but began slipping in successive contests
aides, however, conceded that gephardt's fourth-place overall showing would put a pinch on fund raising just when the campaign needs money the most
we're not penniless,'' said campaign consultant bob shrum. ``it won't be as easy to raise money, but we'll raise money. it's not a good thing to have happen to you.''
they pointed to michigan's caucuses later this month as the next ``clean shot'' of the campaign, downplaying the impact of next week's illinois primary
but as his spoke of targeting resources in selected tests, gephardt told his backers in the city he represents in congress that he will campaign everywhere and stay in the race until the democratic convention this summer
we're going to carry our cause to every one of those days in every one of those states,'' gephardt said. ``we didn't shrink when we were behind in iowa and we're not going to shrink now.''
gephardt said he simply didn't have the money to respond to the advertising blitz by dukakis and gore
our message got across in iowa, got across in new hampshire, got across in south dakota,'' gephardt said. ``but in 14 short days we were not able to get it across in the 20 states of the south the way we wanted.''
deputy campaign manager joe trippi said gephardt's financial shape isn't all that bad, because he has debts of only $75,000 and has $250,000 on hand. in addition, trippi said, the campaign anticipates raising $500,000 within two weeks despite the anticipated financial pinch stemming from tuesday's showing
gephardt aides spent most of the day tuesday saying the campaign will focus on the march 26 michigan voting, in effect conceding the large illinois showdown to home-state favorites sen. paul simon and jesse jackson
our intention is to compete in south carolina, campaign in illinois but really focus on michigan,'' trippi said
to underscore that point, gephardt made south carolina his first post-super tuesday appearance
he then was heading for michigan before traveling to illinois for two days of stumping. gephardt is scheduled to take a couple of days off the campaign trail next weekend, just two days before the big illinois primary, and trippi said that was to allow the candidate to prepare for michigan
this is a long campaign,'' gephardt said. ``those who prevail are those who don't lose their heart.''
radical priest jasbir singh rode was installed as the leader of 25 million sikhs today and vowed to win the fight to create a homeland for his people
rode was named by a sikh committee as chief priest of the akal takht, or the eternal throne within the golden temple, the holiest sikh shrine and the seat of sikhism's spiritual authority
the post, although religious, wields great political influence
rode was released from jail saturday in what apparently was a move by the federal government to involve militant sikhs in finding a solution to the violence in punjab state
militant sikhs have been waging a five-year war for a separate homeland in punjab, claiming that they are discriminated against by the predominant hindu community. sikhs form 2 percent of india's 800 million people but are in a majority in punjab state
rode said at his installation ceremony that he had not reached an understanding with the government prior to his release from jail. he had been held since 1985 for alleged sedition, but he never was brought to trial
we will try to reach a solution with the government which will not amount to a surrender,'' rode said. ``but we will struggle till we get our rights.''
he called for unity among political factions in the sikh community. during the ceremony, young men armed with soviet-made ak-47 rifles stood guard
more than 400 people have been killed in punjab this year in attacks blamed on sikhs. most of the victims have been hindus or moderate sikhs. more than 1,000 people died last year in attacks blamed on the extremists. revised delegate figures, picking up 11th graf pvs, gephardt's money</note>
northerner michael dukakis declared today he had a ``national victory'' with wins in texas, florida, maryland and the west but southerners jesse jackson and albert gore jr. celebrated their own strong super tuesday showings in the democratic primaries
rep. richard gephardt, the iowa winner, took only his home state of missouri and faced a fight to keep his campaign from fading into oblivion
this was a good national victory and i feel terrific this morning,'' dukakis said on abc-tv. ``i think that demonstrates who can win in november.'' the massachusetts governor won the day's three biggest prizes: florida, texas and his home state. he also won in rhode island, maryland, idaho and hawaii
dukakis scored well among elements of ``the new south,'' collecting heavy support from jewish voters in florida, hispanics in texas and catholics across the region, according to abc news surveys of voters as they left the polls
the democrat with the best-financed and probably best-organized campaign, dukakis emerged in a strong position for the next round of primaries in midwestern and northern industrial states
poised to challenge him were tennessean gore and south carolina native jackson, who divided the day's spoils with the front-runner. dukakis picked up 386 new delegates toward the party's july nominating convention, jackson collected 366 and gore 326
gore, who was seen as fighting gephardt for the more conservative southern democratic vote, suggested that rivalry was now behind him. ``it's a three-man race, no question about it,'' he said on nbc-tv
he immediately took aim at dukakis, calling him a representative of ``the politics of the past'' who lacks the appeal to moderate voters that democrats need to win back the white house in november
jackson declined to attack his democratic rivals. ``i'm concerned we run a campaign that will serve my party well,'' he said, contending intra-party bickering had cost democrats the white house in the past
gore racked up victories in kentucky, oklahoma, north carolina and arkansas, as well as his home state of tennessee, while jackson won in virginia, georgia, mississippi, louisiana and alabama
the day's big loser among democrats was gephardt, who won only in his home state of missouri and added just 93 delegates to his total
gephardt's money-starved campaign was unable to afford the expensive media buys necessary to blanket the 20 states which had democratic contests on tuesday. he said he was outspent seven-to-one by gore and dukakis and couldn't get his message across
it certainly wasn't the best of days,'' gephardt said in st. louis. he vowed to press on, despite comments like those from the party's senior statesman robert strauss, who said the contest had narrowed to dukakis, jackson and gore
i expect one of those three fellows will probably be the nominee,'' strauss said
jackson demonstrated that he had expanded his political base somewhat beyond what he established in his 1984 candidacy, doubling the proportion of white southern votes he won to 10 percent. he got virtually all of the black vote. in virginia, he piled up a surprising 2-1 margin over gore, his nearest competitor
jackson, who has campaigned hard on themes like economic justice and combating the drug crisis, told supporters: ``our message is winning. we have the poorest campaign, the richest message.''
gore, who sat out most of the early primary and caucus battles to concentrate his resources on his home turf, made the strong showing he needed. it remained to be seen, however, whether he could maintain that strength beyond the south
the day had been designed by southern democrats from the start to bring to the forefront a candidate like gore, whose strong views on defense and foreign policy have appeal in the south
one of those behind the ``super tuesday'' southern strategy, former virginia gov. charles robb, called the day a success. ``i think the emergence of al gore is the most important development on the democratic side,'' said robb
the message today is that we're still a part of the mainstream of the nation,'' said atlanta mayor andrew young. ``super tuesday probably won't decide anything, but it will take everybody one step further along the way. our job is to let the folks in illinois, pennsylvania (which have upcoming primaries) ... sort this all out for us, and give us a nominee we can get behind.''
bill britt, who gained fame as the ``hermit of chestnut hill'' before dying alone in the woods, will be cremated and his ashes scattered next to his favorite tree, his daughter said
i think my father would have wanted to return to the elements,'' ingrid boughner said tuesday. ``i know he would want to be returned to his favorite tree. i can almost hear him saying `yes.'''
britt, who resisted efforts to move him to a shelter, should have been more carefully monitored although he was unlike most homeless people, say city officials who knew him
britt, 52, died of hypothermia two weeks before his body was discovered monday by ms. boughner and her brother in a makeshift wigwam in brookline, the suffolk county medical examiner's office said tuesday
homeless people, people like britt who say they want to be alone, should be protected in this weather,'' said dr. stanton kessler, a senior pathologist in the medical examiner's office. ``he had no food in him. he had no sleeping bag. this type of thing should be prevented.''
ms. boughner said she decided on cremation after talking to her father's longtime friend william baird, the birth control activist, who told her the two had once discussed cremation
officials of the metropolitan district commission, on whose land britt lived, said they did not object to ms. boughner's decision
britt died in the woods in the chestnut hill reservoir, near the affluent community of the same name where he was born and grew up. he had lived in the woods since 1969 and did not attract much attention until 1985, when officials began trying to move him out of the woods and into public or subsidized housing
britt's continual resistance to efforts to help him gained media attention and led to his nickname ``the hermit of chestnut hill.'' at one point, actor mickey rooney said he planned to buy the rights to his story. in may, britt appeared on ``late night with david letterman.''
boston chief housing court justice e. george daher, who tried to arrange housing and medical aid for britt despite his lack of cooperation, said tuesday he was shocked and saddened by the news of britt's death
he represents in a microcosm what happens to the homeless, the unfortunates, the eccentrics in this cold society,'' said daher. ``someone should have checked in on him, rather than have him die a lonely tragic death like this.''
a one-time insurance agent who also worked in procter &amp; gamble's marketing division in new york city 30 years ago, britt once had been married with a family
both public officials and friends said he was a paradox; a loner who loved to chat with boston college students who went to class just yards from his shelter; an eccentric who said he wanted to be left alone but who regularly pitched stories about himself to the media
mary callahan, 27, was one of the first to write about britt as a reporter on a weekly newspaper
it seems so sad to me,'' said callahan, who now works for boston college. ``he was a singular person, a very interesting man. he looked very old but he was so articulate. he talked about writing poetry, about writing books. it's strange that he decided to live there.''
