jesse jackson said today that super tuesday proved ``the jackson message is winning'' and proclaimed the primary season is erasing democratic establishment doubts about the viability of his campaign
he said if his cash-poor campaign had spent as much money as the well-heeled forces of michael dukakis, ``it would have been a different situation'' in the results
he acknowledged that the endorsements of white democratic politicans, many of them elected with support of the black voters jackson has helped register in recent years, went to dukakis and rivals albert gore jr. and richard gephardt
`it would be fair to say that many of them had reasonable doubts about the success of our campaign,'' jackson said. ``in these elections we are removing those doubts ... our coalition represents the future of the democratic party.''
he said the white politicians will have to make choices, not only about who can win, but which candidate ``can help them.''
he also spoke about party unity and said the candidates should not ``self destruct'' their chances in november by attacking each other during the primary season
jackson's rivals thus far have refrained from criticizing him, but his campaign manager says the jackson forces are prepared for the possibility he will come under attack now that he has collected a sizeable number of delegates
jackson was heading today to cicero, ill, where voters go to the polls next tuesday. he was visiting the site of a general electric plant that is closing down, to show solidarity with workers who are losing their jobs
our campaign is winning,'' jackson told jubilant supporters tuesday night. ``our message is winning. we have the poorest campaign, the richest message.''
jackson won big in virginia and also won in the deep south states of georgia, louisiana, mississippi and alabama
he also came in second in the home states of his three main rivals, massachusetts, tennessee and missouri, home of rep. richard gephardt
`we're right where we wanted to be, and now it's on to north carolina and illinois,'' said campaign manager gerald austin. ``tonight jesse jackson became a valid candidate for president, with an organization and with a message, and he just happens to be black.''
an exit poll by abc news indicated that jackson won 10 percent of the white vote in the super tuesday contests, which included 14 southern and border states
jackson has vigorously courted sectors of the white population in his campaign, principally the economically hard-pressed, the unemployed, students, gays and lesbians
on tuesday night, jackson recalled the selma, ala., civil rights march 23 years ago that was violently turned back at the bridge into town by state troopers
the same state that wouldn't let us walk across the bridge _ we won that state today,'' jackson said. ``america has won.''
jackson was joined at the celebration by his wife and mother and other family members, and several political figures, including district of columbia mayor marion barry and rep. mickey leland, jackson's campaign chairman in texas. his longtime supporter, rock disc jockey casey kasem, was the master of ceremonies
jackson, who spent just $100,000 on super tuesday television ads, contrasted his low-budget campaign to the multimillion-dollar tv budgets of his opponents
he criticized the negative ads aired by his rivals as `party bloodletting.'' that is ``a way to lose and we want to win,'' he said
i'm not running against gore or dukakis or gephardt on super tuesday. i'm runing against george bush in the super bowl in november,'' he said
austin said jackson's success means he will now come under increasing scrutiny by the media and attacks from other candidates
we are prepared for the slings and arrows of outrageous fortune that will come our way,'' he said
he said he anticipates the campaign will benefit from greater fund-raising which has been on an upswing since the feb. 8 iowa caucuses. the campaign raised $600,000 in february, a one-month record for jackson, he said
decisions will have to be made on buying more media time than in the past, especially in large states such as new york and california, he said
this month, jackson took out $400,000 in loans to keep his campaign afloat for super tuesday. washington</head>
a formal complaint has been filed against an illinois appellate judge for saying south side residents who failed to vote for the late mayor harold washington ``ought to be hung.''
the complaint tuesday to the illinois courts commission cited comments made by appellate judge r. eugene pincham in a speech at an operation push gathering on jan. 31, 1987
pincham mentioned the hanging of several slaves and white collaborators during a 1741 slave rebellion in new york, then said, ``any man south of madison street who casts a vote in the feb. 24th election who doesn't cast a vote for harold washington ought to be hung as those were hung in new york.''
the speech before the civil rights group was broadcast over three chicago-area radio stations. washington won the election but died nov. 25, only a few months into his second term
former u.s. attorney dan webb filed the complaint on behalf of the illinois judicial inquiry board, contending that the judge's comments violated portions of the illinois code of judicial conduct
the code prohibits judges from participating in political campaigns or activities unless they are candidates for office or judicial retention
pincham said his comments were protected by the first amendment. to punish him would violate his constitutional rights, he said, adding that he would continue with his own court challenge to the complaint
pincham had attempted to avoid action by the judicial inquiry board by filing a lawsuit on first amendment grounds in u.s. district court, but that suit was dismissed last week. pincham said he would appeal that ruling
the illinois courts commission will set hearings on the board's complaint. picking up 2nd graf pvs, robertson said.</note>
george bush's powerful super tuesday punch packed such a wallop it knocked jack kemp and pat robertson flat and left bob dole scrambling in illinois today to regain his footing in the industrial midwest
dole was out campaigning today in the western chicago suburb of hinsdale, where he visited a commuter train station and gulped coffee and a pastry before television cameras at a restaurant counter across the street
it will be up to illinois now to turn it around,'' dole told one supporter
robertson said today that bush ``just ran a fabulous race.'' he also said, in an interview on abc-tv: ``i was running against the ghost of ronald reagan, not against george bush.''
while robertson vowed to stay in the race, kemp was meeting with his advisers to determine the future of his campaign. a spokeswoman said that kemp, who got no better than 7 percent of the vote in any of tuesday's primaries, would have a news conference thursday
an exhilarated bush said tuesday night that the voters' message was clear: ``i'm going to be the next president of the united states.''
the vice president was victorious in 16 of 17 gop contests tuesday, most of them in the south. he won a shutout in the primaries, though robertson did win washington state's caucuses
this is a unique political happening,'' bush told cheering supporters in houston as his lopsided victory became apparent. ``it exceeded my fondest expectations.''
while dole hadn't expected to dominate super tuesday, he'd hoped for a better showing than the distant runner-up status to which he was relegated
he began focusing on next week's illinois primary even before tuesday's results were final, telling a crowd of supporters in chicago: ``illinois is getting more and more important as the evening wears on.''
this is going to be bob dole's recovery state,'' he said. ``it's going to be the turnaround state.''
robertson, who earlier had predicted he'd emerge from super tuesday as the gop front-runner, insisted his third-place showing still was respectable
it isn't too bad for an amateur but it isn't near what i expected,'' said the former television evangelist
kemp kept out of public view as super tuesday voters designated him their last choice. aides said he'd be reassessing his candidacy
super tuesday's balloting represented a dramatic comeback for bush, who just a month earlier had been reeling from a third-place finish behind dole and robertson in iowa
damaged but not destroyed, bush managed to hang on to a slimmed-down lead in new hampshire a week later, and his self-portrait as loyal sidekick to ronald reagan was well-received in the south
bush claimed most of the 712 delegates at stake tuesday, adding them to the 126 he'd amassed in earlier contests. that put him well on the way to the 1,139 needed to land the gop nomination
his super tuesday victories reached across the nation, including delegate-rich florida and texas. he also triumphed in tennessee, kentucky, georgia, alabama, virginia, mississippi, louisiana, arkansas, north carolina, maryland, massachusetts, rhode island, oklahoma and missouri
robertson conceded he'd been damaged by some unusual comments he'd made on the campaign trail, such as his insistence there are soviet missiles in cuba, claims his christian broadcasting network at one point knew the whereabouts of american hostages in lebanon and his assertions that disclosure of the jimmy swaggart sex scandal had been timed to hurt his candidacy
i spoke too much and i should have kept my mouth shut but i was misinterpreted,'' he said
but he shrugged off any suggestion that the damage was irreparable or that he would join forces with dole in a stop-bush offensive, saying ``it looks like the one that may come out of illinois is going to be pat robertson rather than bob dole.''
i, right now, am going to be the rallying point for those who don't want george bush as the nominee of the party.''
dole, meanwhile, was challenging bush to a series of debates ``all over illinois, one on one, no moderator, no notes, stand up and have it out.''
lee atwater, bush's campaign manager, didn't welcome the invitation
there just doesn't seem to be any point in following the other guy's campaign schedule,'' he said
bush, however, was ready to fight dole for illinois' 82 delegates. while dole thus far has dominated contests in the midwest and has a strong organization in illinois, bush is supported by illinois gov. james thompson and 93 of the state's 102 gop county chairmen
the vice president planned to fly to chicago thursday. quote from bonior on possible federal funding cuts.</note>
gallaudet university students threatened to withdraw from the school for the deaf as a protest over the appointment of a hearing woman as president entered its fourth day today
gallaudet board of trustees chairwoman jane bassett spilman said the decision to hire elisabeth ann zinser will stand, and scheduled a press conference today for herself and the new president
at a campus rally tuesday night, student leaders said that up to two-thirds of the school's 2,200 undergraduate and graduate students might withdraw thursday if zinser is not replaced with a deaf president
psychology professor neil reynolds, who chairs two faculty groups, said they will meet today to discuss the controversy over zinser's selection, and could vote to suspend classes
there has been in the past week an escalation of overt support from faculty members for a deaf president,'' said reynolds, who chairs the school's 21-member faculty senate and a group that includes the entire faculty. ``this is definitely a change.''
when school officials announced sunday that zinser, an administrator at the university of north carolina at greensboro, had prevailed over two deaf finalists, students staged protest marches to the capitol, forced closure of the school monday, and boycotted classses tuesday
rep. david e. bonior, d-mich., a member of gallaudet's board of trustees, said congress might consider scaling back funding for the school if the conflict over zinser's appointment is not resolved
i'm concerned it has the potential to hurt the funding of the university, especially when you have leaders from both sides going out of their way to express themselves on this,'' bonior said
bonior, the chief deputy majority whip in the house, said he has been meeting privately with university officials, and intends to ask zinser ``whether she is indeed interested in coming into an environment that is as hostile as it is.''
gallaudet, founded in 1864 by an act of congress, is the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf. last year, federal funding accounted for $62.2 million of gallaudet's $76 million operating budget
spilman said the selection of zinser, a vice chancellor for academic affairs at greensboro, ``was a vote cast in the best interests of the university.''
zinser, who prevailed by a 10-4 margin over two deaf finalists, ``was selected for one and only one reason _ she was the best person qualified,'' spilman said
the students claim that by picking zinser, who doesn't know sign language, the board of trustees has shown it has no understanding of the importance deaf students place on having a deaf leader. including zinser, none of the school's seven presidents has been deaf
the alumni sympathize with and support the students,'' gerald burstein, president of the school's alumni organization, said at a campus rally tuesday. ``we _ unlike hearing members on the board _ know fully what it is like to be deaf.''
i'm behind the students 100 percent,'' said prof. herbert maples, chairman of gallaudet's math department, who is deaf. ``something has to be done about this situation.''
thirty percent of gallaudet's faculty and 22 percent of the school's 1,300-member support staff is deaf, according to university publicist barbara dennis
the national association of the deaf is planning to have state representatives from the 20,000-member organization meet in washington friday to discuss ways to help the protesting students, said fred weiner, a washington spokesman for the group
students vowed to continue their protest until they achieve their goal
we will not give up until we have a deaf president,'' said jerry covell, a leader of the student protest. ``we will just keep trying.''
students also want spilman replaced, and a plan to make deaf persons a majority on the board of trustees. the 20-member board now has four deaf members
president reagan was urged today to award the medal of freedom posthumously to three american journalists killed by soviet troops while covering the eight-year afghanistan war
rep. jim courter, r-n.j., introduced a resolution in the house urging reagan to give the nation's highest civilian award to relatives of charles e. thornton, a medical reporter for the arizona republic in phoenix, and independent filmmakers lee shapiro of north bergen, n.j., and jim lindelof of sacramento, calif
thornton was killed in an ambush by soviet troops on sept. 19, 1985, while preparing a story on volunteer doctors in afghanistan. shapiro and lindelof, a paramedic serving as soundman for a documentary being filmed by shapiro, were killed oct. 9, 1987, when they were strafed by soviet helicopter gunships and shot by soviet soldiers who confiscated their cameras and film. their bodies have never been returned from afghanistan
the journalists' only `crime' was in bringing a trace of glasnost to the most brutal war of the decade,'' courter told a news conference. ``unable to completely conquer the afghan resistance, the soviets have committed themselves to a policy of tracking down and murdering western journalists in an attempt to prevent the rest of the world from learning of the afghans' valiant struggle for freedom.''
courter's resolution is cosponsored by reps. bob stump, r-ariz., and robert t. matsui, d-calif. the same appeal to reagan will be introduced in the senate next week by dennis deconcini, d-ariz., and pete wilson, r-calif
the resolution urges reagan to award the medal of freedom posthumously to the three journalists at a white house ceremony on march 21, the afghan new year which the president designated last year as ``afghanistan day.''
the great courage displayed by these american heroes in facing the dangers of war and a lethal soviet threat against them as correspondents should not go unrecognized,'' matsui said
linda shapiro, the filmmaker's widow, said her husband was ``sought out and deliberately gunned down for telling the truth'' about the war. she urged continued u.s. support for the afghan rebels, and promised to finish her husband's documentary
bill lindelof, a reporter for the sacramento bee, said his brother originally went to afghanistan to provide medical treatment for afghan war refugees
he did so much and unselfishly, and this (award) would be sort of something in his memory,'' lindelof said. ``it would say that jim did all he could, and it was appreciated.''
experts from non-opec oil producing nations met today to debate moves aimed at halting plunging oil prices, said a spokesman at the mexican embassy, which served as host of the gathering
the meeting was called by egypt but was held in london because it was a more convenient location than cairo
apart from egypt, the other invited participants were the soviet union, china, angola, malaysia, brunei, oman, mexico and colombia
britain, which rejects group pricing policies for its north sea oil, was not invited. norway, another european producer, declined to attend
the meeting is at expert level with no ministers involved,'' said a mexican spokesman, who declined to be identified. ``they just want to talk about the situation in the market, although obviously they are not in any position to take a decision.''
on tuesday, oil minister abdel-hady kandil of egypt said the meeting was not against the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries, ``but is an attempt by non-opec producers to help save the world oil market from further deterioration.''
there was speculation that opec may call an emergency meeting about the oil price drop, due partly to increased output by non-opec producers and a mild winter in japan and europe
