israel's divided government today refused to endorse a u.s. plan designed to end more than three months of violence in the israeli-occupied lands. troops killed one arab and wounded 10 others in clashes
palestinians staged a general strike in observance of another ``martyrs' day'' to honor the arabs killed since the anti-occupation unrest began dec. 8
the death brought the confirmed death toll from the rioting to 85 since dec. 8. u.n. figures now put the number killed at 90, including five arabs who died from tear gas inhalation. however, there was no independent confirmation that the five arabs included in the u.n. count died as a result of the riots
israeli troops shot and killed a palestinian in the west bank village of silwad, 10 miles northeast of ramallah, the army said
officials at ramallah hospital said mohammed ochman sarris, 22, died of a gunshot wound to the back. they said another palestinian from silwad was admitted with a gunshot wound to the thigh
in clashes in nablus in the west bank, officials at al ittihad hospital said seven palestinians from the nearby faraa refugee camp were hospitalized with gunshot wounds to the legs, hands and side
another palestinian from the village of masha, 15 miles west of nablus, was treated for a gunshot wound to the left leg, the officials said
officials at rafidiyeh hospital in nablus said a palestinian from jenin, 20 miles to the north, was shot in the shoulder
prime minister yitzhak shamir successfully defeated attempts by the left-of-center labor party to force a vote in the 10-member inner cabinet on a peace plan offered by u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz
foreign minister shimon peres, who has accepted the shultz plan, attacked shamir's refusal in a speech in parliament
we might miss this historic opportunity, and we won't have an answer, not for our generation and not for those to coe, as to why we became afraid of peace,'' said peres, leader of the labor party. ``why did we reject the outstretched hand because of imaginary fears?'
in clashes near qalqilya in the west bank, israeli armored personnel carriers fired pebbles at demonstrators with a newly developed riot-control device, israel radio said. the gravel-firing gun was used for this first time this week, it said
the ``martyrs' day'' strike closed shops throughout the west bank and the occupied gaza strip and kept most of the 110,000 arabs who work in israel away from their jobs, an army spokesman and the palestine press service said
army spokesmen said the only exception to the general strike was the tulkarem area near the israeli town of kfar saba, where some workers ignored the boycott
in the west bank town of halhoul, an empty israeli-owned bus used to carry arab workers to their jobs was burned in front of the municipal building, the palestine press service said
it said arabs demonstrated at a dozen locations in gaza strip refugee camps and towns and shouted palestine liberation organization slogans, raised palestinian flags and threw stones
about 1.5 million palestinians live in the west bank and gaza strip, which israel captured in the 1967 middle east war
ezer weizman, a labor minister-without-portfolio, said ``the government is split 50-50'' over the u.s. peace plan
shultz, who brought the peace initiative to the arab and israeli leaders last week, had asked shamir to bring israel's response to washington for talks with president reagan on march 14. labor leaders had hoped to commit shamir to accept before he left
shamir's spokesman, yossi ahimeir, said the prime minister ``opposed most of the ideas'' in the u.s. plan and sought to talk the americans into making changes
shamir, leader of the right-wing likud bloc, objects to shultz's call for an international conference by may 1. he also opposes a proposal that talks on the final status of the occupied lands begin in december, even if agreement had not been reached on palestinian self-rule
ahimeir said that for the first time, shamir will suggest an agreement with jordan on a step-by-step plan for implementing self-rule quickly in a limited area of the west bank or gaza
the idea is to make autonomy work in a limited area such as nablus or hebron and then enlarge it until it is in force in all of the territories,'' ahimeir said
a soviet official acknowledged today that his country had supplied missiles to iraq, but he said their range was too short to strike iranian cities
the statement by foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov was believed to be the first time the soviet union acknowledged shipping missiles to iraq, iran's enemy in a 7{-year-old war
the soviets have been iraq's chief arms supplier
western military analysts say iraq has been using scud-b missiles, fitted with strap-on boosters for added power, in recent attacks on the iranian capital, tehran. the city is 290 miles from the iran-iraq border
iran also uses scud-bs in its attacks on iraqi cities
the missiles have a range of 190 miles
on sunday, iranian media reports blamed the soviet union for the missile attacks on iran, prompting an angry mob in tehran to try to storm the soviet embassy
gerasimov, asked about the iranian charges at a government news briefing, said soviet missiles had been shipped to iraq under an agreement between the two countries
the soviet union previously delivered a limited shipment of short-range missiles,'' he said. ``we never gave our permission to modify those missiles to increase their range, and modernization was not foreseen by that agreement.''
gerasimov said the agreement ``ruled out'' modernizing the missiles
this is the basis on which we're insisting that we have nothing to do with the `war of the cities,''' he said
iraq claims the missiles are iraqi-made
another soviet foreign ministry official, vsevolod l. oleandrov, was asked at the briefing if he believes the iraqi claims. after a long pause he said, ``it's difficult for us to say.'' 4th graf pvs, simon, his</note>
illinois sen. paul simon said today his presidential hopes are riding on a home-state primary victory next week, and he said he still can get the democratic nomination despite sitting out super tuesday
i'm going to finish first in illinois,'' said simon. ``if i don't i'm going to have to re-evaluate,'' he said in an interview on cable news network
simon said the strong showings of rivals michael dukakis, jesse jackson and albert gore jr. on tuesday showed that the democrats won't have a candidate picked before their convention in july
nobody's going to have that first-ballot nomination, and then groups are going to start leaving one candidate or another, going to someone who is going to be generally acceptable,'' he said. ``i think i fit that. but, i also have to win in wisconsin or ohio or pennsylvania or new york.''
there is no question that if i can do it in illinois, we're going to pick up some states after illinois,'' he said
simon, his campaign strapped for cash, sat out the 20-state super tuesday campaign in favor of concentrating on his home-state primary next week, as part of what he calls a midwest industrial strategy
the simon campaign has missed one payroll and is in danger of missing a second, said spokeswoman pam huey. simon also said tuesday the campaign was paying cash for expenses and hoped to avoid borrowing any more money, but had enough federal matching funds to cover its existing debt
february fund-raisers generated about $932,000 and federal matching funds totaled $364,000, said simon spokesman terry michael. the campaign owes about $145,000 but is in ``pretty solid condition as a result of not going into debt'' for super tuesday, michael said
we have a really small payroll, and we didn't make the big tv buys others did for march 8,'' he said
but simon doesn't plan to spend for television advertising in illinois either, again looking to future races
it would be foolish for us to make a big tv buy when we don't even know what the other candidates are going to do,'' michael said
we need a lift from illinois. with that help we can raise additional money so we can be more competitive in the states after illinois,'' he added
simon is eyeing his fellow illinois candidate _ jackson, who makes his home in chicago
some jackson supporters have called on simon to get out of the race before illinois, contending the democratic senator will only siphon votes from jackson with no hope of victory himself
i've heard more people say jesse should get out of the race because he's hurting me, but i'm not calling for him to drop out,'' simon countered
simon has pitched himself in recent days as the consensus candidate, the man most likely to get the nomination in atlanta if no clear favorite emerges from the primaries
any candidate winning enough of the remaining delegates to secure a clear first ballot victory is becoming a mathematical and political improbability,'' he said
right now, with no mr. inevitable in the race, it's going to be a situation where the one who gets hottest at the end wil be in the best possible position to negotiate a first ballot victory,'' michael said
so really, you just have to hang in there and hope to get hot at the end.''
surgeon general c. everett koop said today that claims about the spread of aids among heterosexuals by researchers dr. william masters and virginia johnson are unproven and irresponsible
koop, interviewed from london on abc-tv's ``good morning america'', said the sex experts have no scientific evidence to back claims that aids among heterosexuals is ``rampant,'' that the disease can be spread by casual non-sexual contact or that the nation's blood supply is unsafe
in as much as some very wild claims were made, we have to be very careful,'' koop said
the government's top medical officer was reacting to widely publicized findings from a new masters and johnson book, co-authored by dr. robert kolodny, ``crisis: heterosexual behavior in the age of aids.'' excerpts from the book appeared in this week's newsweek magazine
koop noted that masters and johnson did not submit their findings to scientific review or have them published in a recognized medical journal
i think it is irresponsible. it is scare tactics,'' koop said
the couple has published several books based on surveys of americans' sexual activities and attitudes. the new book calls for widespread mandatory testing for acquired immune deficiency syndrome infections, and estimates there are 3 million or more aids carriers in the united states. the government estimates up to 1.5 million
koop acknowledged that there is an explosion of aids among heterosexuals in africa but said ``the united states is not like africa... that's not going to happen here.''
he said heterosexuals have accounted for only 4 percent of aids cases in the united states and this is expected to increase to 5 percent by 1991
scientists say the disease is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from infected pregnant women to their offspring. the chief victims have been homosexual men and intravenous drug abusers
koop said if there were any truth to the suggestion that aids is spread through other means, the government would be warning against it. ``we have never gotten ahead of our scientific base, and that's something the american people can rely on,'' he said
he said that among more than 50,000 aids cases so far in the united states, ``not one single one was proven to be transmitted by casual non-sexual contact.''
aids is very hard to catch,'' said koop. with soviets admitting sending short-range missiles to iraq.</note>
iran and iraq bombarded each others' capitals with missiles today for the 10th day. iran said 35 people were killed in tehran and iraq reported baghdad residents died when a missile wrecked homes and stores
each side in the 7{-year-old war vowed to continue its missile, air and artillery assaults on population centers until the other halts the attacks
iran's official islamic republic news agency, monitored in nicosia, said the revolutionary guards corps fired two missiles into baghdad, one at 10 a.m. and the second five minutes later
baghdad's official iraqi news agency, also monitored in nicosia, said only one missile exploded in the city of 5 million. it said the missile demolished houses and stores, ``killing or wounding numbers of civilians.''
the iraqi army retaliated by firing an al hussein missile, named after the shiite moslem saint, into tehran at 11:24 a.m., the agency said
iran said it hit a residential district, killing 35 people, wounding 120, knocking down buildings and burying people under the rubble. among the survivors was an 80-year-old woman dragged from the debris by rescue workers, it said
iran claims to have fired 29 missiles into baghdad, the northern city of mosul and the southern town of al-amarah since the missile exchange began feb. 29. the iraqis have acknowledged 24 hits
iraq has reported firing 46 missiles into tehran, the holy city of qom, 100 miles south of the iranian capital, and the central city of isfahan during the same period
iraqi communiques said iranian artillery pounded the southern port of basra and al-amarah during the night, killing ``many civilians.''
the iraqi news agency said the iranian shells rained down on densely populated residential areas in basra. it said that among the dead were four children buried under the rubble of their home after it took a direct hit
the agency said the shelling spread to qurnah, 30 miles north of basra, and zubair, south of basra
gulf-based salvage executives said today that an iraqi warplane fired a missile at a cypriot oil tanker carrying iranian oil in the persian gulf on tuesday. the shipping executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 101,977-ton felicity sustained minor damage
baghdad's government-run al thawra daily said in an editorial that iraq will go on ``hitting new iranian targets every day to shatter the lies of the charlatans in tehran'' until iran accepts the u.n. security council's july 20 cease-fire resolution
iraq has said it will comply with the resolution, but iran demands that iraq must be branded the aggressor before it will agree to a cease-fire
the commander of the iranian revolutionary guards' air wing, mohsen refan, said that if iraq continues its ``atrocities in the war of the cities, we will increase our missile attacks on baghdad manyfold and attack other iraqi cities with our missiles.''
he said iraq has suffered more than iran recently because ``our missiles have four times the destructive force'' of iraq's weapons and are more accurate
the iranians charge that the soviet union, iraq's main arms supplier, provided baghdad with the long-range missiles capable of hitting tehran
soviet foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov acknowledged today that the soviets supplied iraq with missiles, but he said their range was too short to hit iranian cities and that the soviets never gave iraq permission to modify the missiles to extend their range
both iran and iraq have soviet-built scud-bs, which have a range of 190 miles. baghdad, only 80 miles from the border, is within easy range of the iranian batteries
to hit tehran, 290 miles from the frontier, the iraqis need longer range weapons. analysts say the iraqis attach booster rockets to the scuds to give them the range to hit tehran
