pat robertson said today he'll keep fighting for the republican presidential nomination because ``you never know what will happen between now and august,'' but a pile of third-place finishes on super tuesday was enough to start him talking about 1990 and beyond
the mantle of ronald reagan has passed to george bush,'' robertson said at a news conference today. ``none of us could have dreamed that he could be so strong.''
it isn't over yet,'' the former television evangelist added. ``still half of the delegates are to be selected.''
in separate comments, on abc-tv, ``i was running against the ghost of ronald reagan. in the south the love of ronald reagan is so deep with these people, and george bush is totally identified with him.''
robertson, who said earlier his showing wasn't ``too bad for an amateur,'' said, ``i'm in it for the long haul, for this time, for 1990, the congressional races, and who knows what will happen in 1992.''
politics are so erratic in america,'' robertson said. ``you never know what will happen between now and august.''
robertson conceded vice president george bush ``beat the daylights out of us'' in tuesday's voting, but he assured several hundred cheering supporters in an atlanta hotel ballroom tuesday night: ``this is not the end. this is just the beginning
we're going to new orleans. i'm going to be the conservative champion for everyone who wants to rally around the conservative cause in this nation,'' he said
i'm in all the way. i'm in to see a republican conservative congress in 1990 and we're in for the presidential race in 1992.''
robertson said his campaign has brought thousands of conservatives into the republican party ``for the long haul.''
they're in the process and american politics won't be the same in this century,'' he promised
in this campaign, robertson said, his supporters have worked the caucuses and dominated the delegate selection process in many states. when the republican national convention convenes in new orleans this summer, there will be many more robertson supporters than the numbers might suggest, he said
for one vote the georgia delegation is bound (to bush). beyond that, the georgia delegation will be a pat robertson delegation. the same is true in oklahoma, north carolina, the state of washington, most likely, and many other states _ hawaii, alaska and nevada,'' he said
although he gained only a handful of delegates in tuesday's voting, robertson told reporters he had greatly improved ``on my early ratings 10 months ago when i was laughed at with 3 percent.''
robertson called the performance ``not too bad for an amateur, but it's not nearly what i expected.''
the former television evangelist said he may have spread his campaign too thin by running in all the super tuesday states
i didn't have the concentration i should have had in ky states. i tried to play (to) everyone in the south,'' he said. ``we just didn't have the resources to compete with george bush.''
robertson admitted his campaign was hurt by controversy over several statements he had made _ trying to tie the bush campaign to the timing of revelations about the sex scandal involving evangelist jimmy swaggart; saying his christian broadcasting network reporters had known where some hostages were being held in the middle east, and proclaiming that the soviet union has missiles in cuba
i spoke too much and i should have kept my mouth shut,'' he said
but he blamed the news media for much of the controversy. ``i was misinterpreted,'' he said
the worldwide aids epidemic is causing an upsurge in tuberculosis in many countries, including the united states, a researcher from the world health organization said today
dr. gary slutkin told the first international conference on the global impact of aids that tuberculosis rates are going up in areas worst hit by acquired immune deficiency syndrome
about 1,100 specialists from 20 countries are attending the conference at london's barbican center
slutkin said the reason appears to be that aids suppresses immunity to tuberculosis, a lung infection
aids attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a variety of infections and cancers
slutkin, an epidemiologist, said the number of tb cases in the united states increased between 1985 and 1986 for the first time since records have been kept on the disease
he said the number of tb cases went up from 22,201 in 1985 to 22,768 in 1986
the largest increases in tb in the united states occurred in new york city, where the rate jumped by about 50 percent between 1981 and 1986, slutkin said. he said there also have been increases in tb rates in 25 states and in washington, d.c
he said that in africa, where aids is prevalent, 20 percent to 50 percent of tb patients tested positively for the aids virus. that's three to 20 times higher than the rest of the population
slutkin told reporterst the scale of the expected increases in tb due to aids, slutkin said, ``i think we should certainly expect to see increases in the number of cases of tuberculosis in the next five years. in fact, it's almost certainly already occurring in many countries.''
other speakers at the conference today discussed the economic and social impact of the aids epidemic, which has spread to 133 countries
anne scitovsky, the chief health economist for the palo alto medical foundation in california, estimated that the direct cost of treating aids patients in the united states will probably increase by eight-fold to $8.5 billion by 1991
indirect costs from lost wages and future earnings could soar to $55.6 billion by 1991, she said
aids is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
a woman armed with a toy gun failed in an attempt to rob a doughnut shop, but bit the baker who subdued her, police said
police arrived at the winchell's donut house tuesday to find the ``exhausted'' 59-year-old baker, jay anderson, holding a 36-year-old woman down on the floor, the police report said
the woman entered the shop at about 4 a.m. and bought a chocolate doughnut. when the baker opened the cash register, the woman pulled a gun from under her jacket and said ``give me all of it or i'll kill you,'' the report said
anderson stood back and told her to take the money herself. while the woman had her hands in the till, he grabbed her and pulled her across the counter. the gun, which anderson believed to be real, came out of the woman's hand and broke apart
after wrestling with the woman for what ``seemed like forever,'' the baker said he got to the phone and called police. meanwhile, the woman was kicking and punching him continuously, and also ``took a bite out of his arm,'' the report said
anderson was treated at a nearby hospital and released. police said the woman would be charged with aggravated robbery, but refused to release her name immediately
white house chief of staff howard baker today denied that the united states is planning an invasion of panama, saying american troops there are merely holding regularly scheduled training exercises
panama is the site of national guard training exercises and has been for years,'' baker said. ``and as i understand it, the rhode island national guard is now holding regularly scheduled exercises in panama
and certainly if the united states was going to invade panama, it wouldn't be with the rhode island national guard. so it simply is not so. it has no connection at all,'' baker said, talking with reporters at the white house after seeing president reagan off on a trip to indiana
jorge abadia, panama's foreign minister, on tuesday accused the united states of conducting ``the prelude of an armed invasion'' by staging military exercises along the panama canal
the u.s. southern command said the exercises were scheduled a year ago and were ``routine training.'' comments, picking up in 3rd graf pvs, just hours</note>
republican george bush took a breather today after the landslide super tuesday victories that he said made it virtually sure he'll be the next president
bush was relaxing in private today but planned to rejoin the campaign thursday in illinois, which has its primary next tuesday
in washington, meanwhile, white house chief of staff howard baker said today ``it would take a major event'' to prevent bush from winning the republican nomination. he said there is no sign president reagan is about to endorse anyone
bush, the winner in 16 of 17 states with gop contests, said: ``this is a unique political happening. it exceeded my fondest expectations.''
just hours after the vice president's top aides said he would not accede to sen. bob dole's demand for one-on-one debates in illinois, bush appeared before a crowd of supporters to declare ``a national victory.''
bush was getting a respite from the campaign wars today as he and his wife, barbara, remained in seclusion at their houstonian hotel condominium while aides held strategy sessions for next tuesday's illinois primary
bush's election performance on tuesday was stunning. after winning the south carolina primary on saturday, he captured delegate-rich florida and texas, and scored other victories throughout the south. he pushed his delegate total toward 700, close to two-thirds the number needed for nomination in new orleans next august
this will probably be the single most smashing win anyone's ever had from the standpoint of delegates in one day,'' exulted campaign manager lee atwater. ``a guiness book of records day.''
bob dole is on the canvas now,'' said bush's deputy campaign manager, richard bond. ``i don't think he's knocked out, though.''
top bush aides said they saw no benefit in the vice president meeting dole in the kind of lincoln-douglas face-to-face debates the kansas senator demanded on tuesday
atwater called dole's maneuver ``an eleventh-hour ploy'' and bush spokesman pete teeley said: ``we're not going to allow him to dictate how we run our campaign strategy in illinois.''
bush will fly to chicago tomorrow to kick off five days of intensive campaigning. ``we look very strong there,'' teeley said
but on tuesday night, it was bush's turn to bask in the glory of his finest political hour in more than 20 years in public life
after watching returns for about two hours with members of his family and political associates gathered in a 21st floor penthouse hotel suite, bush entered a ballroom to the cheers of supporters
as i said yesterday, whoever wins super tuesday convincingly is going to be the next president, and i'll repeat it. i'm going to be the next president of the united states,'' he declared
it's a national victory, not a victory so much for me personally as for the themes we've been discussing.''
bush said he would continue to hammer away at his basic themes of balancing the budget without raising taxes, ``make progress toward peace through strength ... and reducing the threat of war.''
this is a big, a major political victory,'' he said. ``my message is going to continue to be one of hope. america's best days, i am convinced, lie ahead.''
here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout the nation
march 2
albany (ore.) democrat-herald on the united states and panama:
the united states finds itself powerless to do anything about yet another irritant in central america
the irritant is manuel (antonio) noriega, the national guard general and dictator in panama. ..
the u.s. government is pussyfooting around partly because it used to rely on noriega for occasional help and partly because it doesn't know what to do. ..
many latin americans regard the united states as an imperialistic power, but in fact we can't seem to get rid of a tinpot dictator who gets rich by funneling narcotics to shiftless american youth. some imperialism!
march 7
lubbock (texas) avalanche-journal on the united states and nicaragua:
the muddled u.s. policy in central america became even more so over the weekend as experts pondered the house defeat of ``humanitarian'' aid for the nicaraguan contras
as a result, not only is the fate of the nicaraguan rebels fighting to overturn the marxist sandinista regime in jeopardy, but u.s. policy in the region remains one of vacillation and weakness _ the result of unbelievable on-again, off-again meddling by congress
with no immediate aid in the pipeline, the fate of the contras is now in limbo
the white house, congress, the media and the american people can be faulted for not coming to grips with the issue of what to do about soviet expansion into this hemisphere
the problem is the same as it has been all along _ fear of becoming involved in another guerrilla-type war and guilt for not being able to deal with third world problems which have no easy solutions
great nations do not let themselves become enmeshed in such fuzzy thinking
march 4
the tennessean, nashville, tenn., on barry goldwater on evan mecham:
one thing you have to say for barry goldwater, former arizona senator: he expresses his opinions forcefully and pulls no punches
another thing you have to say for him: he can admit a mistake
goldwater now says he was mistaken to support the election in 1986 of (arizona) gov. evan mecham, who is undergoing an impeachment trial and faces a recall election in may
the arch-conservative goldwater said mecham should go back to the job he had before becoming governor _ selling cars. but he acknowledges that mecham may not listen to reason
he is a very obstinate man,'' goldwater said of mecham. ``i used to drive mules and he's a lot like a mule.''
goldwater not only expresses opinions forcefully, he tells the truth
mecham, indeed, resembles a stubborn mule. but with goldwater's help, perhaps the state of arizona won't have to put up with the errant and arrogant governor too much longer
march 4
the press, atlantic city, n.j., on the war against drugs:
just say no.''
that's what the reagans have been saying to people who use drugs. it's not that simple. for thousands of addicts, going straight is difficult; many need help, but as a result of budget cuts, the help is often nowhere to be found
it should be easy, though, for the president to cut off all foreign aid and impose severe sanctions against those countries doing little, if anything, to stop the flow of drugs into this country
the penalties can range from a loss of foreign aid to a 50 percent tax on imports
according to congressional reports, wholesale corruption in mexico has made that country ``the portal through which flows one-third of all the marijuana, heroin and cocaine on america's streets and schoolyards.''
yet the administration declined to decertify mexico and other nations, citing national security problems. ..
that means the administration places a higher priority on how anti-moscow a nation is than it does on how anti-drug it is
march 3
morning sentinel, waterville, maine, on the shultz peace mission:
secretary of state george shultz accomplished two things on (his) peace mission to syria and jordan. he spent some of the taxpayers' money. and he spent some of the taxpayers' money. ..
the truth is that the palestinians, though they are falling to israeli gunfire at the rate of two or three a day in occupied towns, see no reason to give up their position at this time. ..
what the recent skirmishes ... have done is publicize the plight of the palestinian refugees, a situation that had existed for so long that even terrorist acts failed to make it big news. ..
what the u.s. proposal would do is move the bitter dispute of palestinians and israel to the bargaining table. such a move would defuse the explosive situation in the occupied territories, and end the battle that has been costly in terms of palestinian lives but a boon politically
if the united states or any other party is going to bring peace to this troubled land, it will take more than vague promises of negotiation. without the ingredients for a real compromise, peace envoys might as well just stay home
march 3
carlsbad (n.m.) current-argus on george shultz:
the man is aging gracefully, just like his boss. unlike ronald reagan, though, secretary of state george p. shultz skips around the globe on a monthly basis, handling missions of import with savvy and vitality
nearing the end of a lengthy and distinguished career in governmental service, shultz has not only survived in an administration that has had constant turnover, he has thrived. he has emerged as the true superstar of the reagan years
a gentleman in the most complimentary sense, shultz possesses an iron will and discipline. he has hung tough with an impeccable dignity through some trying circumstances, ranging from lebanon to ollie north
though he has been off the mark on occasion, he has never wavered from what he believes. a man of intense patriotic devotion, shultz has been the man that has kept things together for reagan
unlike his whirling dervish predecessor, al haig, shultz exudes a calm that has made the difference in various situations. he's everybody's favorite uncle george
march 7
los angeles daily news on alcoholism firings:
last wednesday, u.s. district judge elizabeth kovachevich ruled in tampa, fla., that the national marine fisheries service's firing of an alcoholic who missed 14 months of work in a three-year period constituted unlawful discrimination because the employee was legally crippled by alcohol
kovachevich's ruling was based on a law that requires federal agencies to ``make reasonable accommodations'' for handicapped workers, including alcoholics and drug addicts
that law seems part of a trend, one that the u.s. supreme court will fortunately have an opportunity to stop this summer when it rules on another case. that case involves two veterans who claim that alcoholism prevented them from taking full advantage of veterans administration education benefits during the 10-year limit following their military discharges. ..
there is a big difference between people with incurable medical problems and people who choose not to fight their thirst for alcohol. ..
but legally defining alcoholism as a disease would set a dangerous precedent that conceivably could lead to the decriminalization of drunken driving (or make it a prosecutable offense for social drinkers only). this trend could even spawn the birth of the alcoholic defense, by which those who can blame their addiction for their transgressions could escape punishment. ..
there comes a point at which the legal system must assume that adults are responsible for their behavior, and that line must be drawn at excessive drinking
march 4
the sheboygan (wis.) press on how hard congress works:
what's this? one of our local congressmen claiming that congress doesn't work hard enough?
what kind of way is that to treat one of your own? why, the very thought is almost un-american. it's also a good way for rep. thomas petri, r-fond du lac, to light a fire under his colleagues and then watch them do a slow burn
petri criticized house speaker jim wright, d-texas, for scheduling a ``measly'' 14 legislative working days and calling for only 10 votes in the first 50 days of 1988. he described it as ``a stunning absence of congressional activity.''
that accusation, of course, was enough to send his colleagues into a tizzy. before long, several of them were grumbling about how petri doesn't know what he's talking about
of course they all work hard, the insulted congressmen said. and how dare petri even think of such a thing?
if congress is so busy, why do they waste so much time on foolish proclamations to satisfy their constituents back home and dream up ways to tack their own pet projects onto bills that have absolutely nothing to do with each other?
the only thing petri is guilty of is calling 'em as he sees 'em. conferences, inserting new 3rd graf and subbing 10- grafs for grafs 5-11 pvs, many of ... state.</note>
vice president george bush stood within reach of the republican presidential nomination today after a sweep of super tuesday primaries. democrats michael dukakis and jesse jackson split a rich harvest of delegates with albert gore jr., who declared today ``it's a three-man race'' after thrashing richard gephardt in the south
it exceeded my fondest expectations,'' exulted bush as he surveyed his 16-0 primary shutout tuesday and looked ahead to an illinois showdown next tuesday, where another victory over kansas sen. bob dole would give his nomination an aura of inevitability
white house chief of staff howard baker, himself once a candidate, said of bush, ``i think it would take a major event to deny him the nomination.'' but there was no sign president reagan was ready to endorse him or another candidate, he said
super tuesday spelled disaster for dole, fellow republican pat robertson, and gephardt, all three teetering on the verge of elimination after rejection in state after state. robertson did win the party's caucuses in washington state on tuesday
almost certain to pack it in was republican jack kemp, who was meeting with advisers to see if there was any point in continuing. kemp, who got no better than 7 percent of the vote in any of tuesday's primaries, scheduled no announcement today about his plans, but a spokeswoman said he would have a news conference thursday
in nashville, tenn., today, gore dismissed the chances of gephardt. ``it's a three-man race, no question about it,'' gore said on nbc-tv. the tennessee senator, who won his own state and four other southern primaries, said ``all three of us are going all the way to california and probably to the convention.''
massachusetts gov. dukakis, who won the two biggest southern states, florida and texas, made television appearances from chicago, where he was already campaigning
i've always felt that ... this will go right down to the last primaries in california and new jersey,'' he said on cbs-tv
jackson, who won in five southern states, said at a houston news conference today his results show he is a serious contender
in these elections we are removing those doubts. ... our coalition represents the future of the democratic party,'' he said
robertson, at a news conference in atlanta today, said, ``none of us could have dreamed that he (bush) could be so strong. the mantle of ronald reagan has passed to george bush.''
but, he said, ``it isn't over yet. ... still half of the delegates are to be selected.''
robertson had hoped to do well in the south but won only the washington caucuses, which represent an early stage in that state's delegate selection. still, he said he believed he was ``making a profound change in american politics'' and he planned to continue his cause beyond this year's election
dole acknowledged he took a whipping. campaigning today in chicago, he said, ``it will be up to illinois now to turn it around.''
the delegate total dramatically spelled out how bush dominated the day
with 712 republican convention delegates at stake, bush won 578, giving him 705 when combined with the delegates he won in earlier contests. dole had 98, for a total of 163. robertson gained 9 delegates for a total of 17. kemp picked up four for a total of 39. the remainder will be apportioned as the final few votes are counted
it takes 1,139 to gain the republican nomination at the party convention in new orleans in august
on the democratic side, with 1,307 national convention delegates at stake in 21 contests, the race looked like this:
dukakis won 386 for a total of 455.5; jackson picked up 366, giving him a total of 393.55; and gore took 326 for a total of 347.8. gephardt picked up 93 delegates for a total of 143, while gary hart failed to pick up a delegate
it takes 2,082 to gain the democratic nomination at the party convention in atlanta this summer
super tuesday was designed by southern democrats hoping for a more conservative candidate that they believed could avoid the disasters which have befallen the democrats in four of the last five presidential elections
but the massive schedule _ 20 democratic and 17 republican contests _ appeared to offer an advantage to the best financed candidates or, in the case of jackson, the one who had the most solid base in the region
while jackson was far outspent by his rivals, he received more than 90 percent of the black vote in the south, according to exit polls, which said he won as much as 10 percent of the white vote _ more than twice as much as his 1984 showing among whites
with 96 percent of precincts reporting, the popular vote from the democratic primaries was jackson 2,493,700, dukakis 2,439,856, gore 2,431,306, gephardt 1,204,585, hart 276,594, and illinois sen. paul simon 179,580
with 93 percent of the republican precincts reporting, the totals were bush 2,584,238, dole 1,095,419, robertson 582,730, and kemp 218,136
while bush towered over his republican rivals after the biggest day in primary election history, the democrats still were a party in search of a clear leader
super tuesday gave them three and left gephardt on shaky ground. democrats will hold caucuses on saturday in south carolina, where gephardt, jackson and gore are the principal contenders, and then move on to illinois for next tuesday's primary
gephardt, already hurting for money, said he will concentrate scarce resources on michigan rather than illinois, where favorite son simon is making a last stand. michigan's democratic caucuses will take place march 26
i never told you it was going to be easy,'' gephardt told supporters in st. louis. he said the 20-state super tuesday landscape was just too broad for his financially pressed campaign
robertson's political base among fundamentalist christians was simply too narrow, and he failed once again to win a primary. even in his home state of virginia, he finished third
dukakis proved he could attract southern votes with victories in texas and florida to add to majorities in rhode island, maryland and his home state of massachusetts. he also was an easy winner in idaho's democratic caucuses, and topped the field in hawaii's caucuses also
jackson carried alabama, georgia, lousiana, mississippi and virginia
gore, the tennessee senator who gambled all on a southern strategy, came out a winner though he still needs to prove his appeal north of the mason-dixon line. gore carried arkansas, kentucky, north carolina, oklahoma and tennessee and was leading in nevada
the st. paul pioneer press &amp; dispatch's drama critic said today that he has resigned because he plagiarized portions of a review from a review published six years ago in the new york times
in his final column, david hawley said that in preparing to write his feb. 14 review of ``good,'' a play by c.p. taylor, he studied articles and reviews written when the play was performed elsewhere
my own piece contained material from a review by frank rich printed oct. 14, 1982, in the new york times,'' wrote hawley, who brought the problem to the attention of his editors himself and said he will remain at the paper in another capacity
although i did not have the original notice before me at the time i was writing, my reference notes _ by then `commingled' with notes taken during the performance _ were so detailed that i duplicated both the general structure of the original piece and many key phrases
it constituted blatant plagiarism, though i managed to ignore that fact while i was writing my review and after i had written it,'' hawley wrote in the column published today. ``i convinced myself that my reasoning was original enough to be my own and that my words, too, were my own.''
hawley, the st. paul paper's drama critic for 9{ years, said the plagiarism was discovered by a reader, who sent him a personal letter
my reaction was first surprise, then shock, then humiliation. clearly, i have forfeited any right to work as a drama critic,'' hawley said
hawley said his resignation as a drama critic was accepted on friday
plagiarism is one of the most serious of all journalistic sins and cannot be tolerated,'' editor deborah howell said in a notice to readers printed with hawley's column
yet, it is to his credit that he brought the case to his editors' attention and offered his resignation at the same time,'' howell said
i would like to assure readers that while we have compassion for a fellow human being's mistake, it does not lessen our commitment to high standards of critical journalism.''
in his column, hawley wrote, ``by not firing me outright, they have generously given me the opportunity to redeem myself in some other capacity.''
tobe reed, former radio and television performer and newspaper columnist, has died at the age of 76
reed died march 3 at eisenhower memorial hospital in this desert resort town
reed hosted tv's ``top dollar'' game show in the 1950s and performed with george burns and gracie allen on their radio show. he also was heard on the radio programs ``fitch's bandwagon'' and ``duffy's tavern.''
reed also worked as a columnist for the san francisco chronicle. he was born in seattle on christmas day 1911
reed is survived by his wife, mary elizabeth; a son, tobe jr.; a daughter, melinda, and two grandsons
rancho mirage is about 10 miles southeast of palm springs, about 120 miles southeast of downtown los angeles
march 3
st. paul (minn.) pioneer press dispatch on the noriega regime:
it is time for the united states to turn the economic screws as tight as possible on gen. manuel antonio noriega and his henchmen. that may be the only way to get them to relinquish their grip on panama
the state department is preparing to notify u.s. banks that hold panamanian deposits not to engage in any transactions with the noriega regime. (deposed president eric arturo) delvalle's lawyers also have started lawsuits to block any transfer of funds
the united states should refuse to hand over the $8 million payment of canal revenues due panama next month. that is part of the $80 million in revenues for this year
the united states also should consider a trade embargo and a ban against flights into the united states of air panama _ which also might cut down the drug traffic _ and termination of any humanitarian aid to panama
applying all available drastic economic pressure now may be the only way to topple the noriega regime without widespread bloodshed
march 6
providence (r.i.) journal on aid to the contras:
on thursday (march 3), the house of representatives defeated yet another proposal to aid the contra rebels in nicaragua. the vote leaves the resistance stranded with no american aid whatsoever
the issue of peace and freedom in central america is too important to lay to rest. president reagan can be counted on to press congress for a new vote on aid. ... but he must act swiftly. ..
when the tally was complete, it was applauded by reagan, but regretted by speaker (james) wright _ even though the president supports the contras and the speaker opposes them. this ... may possibly be explained by the cynical purpose of the measure itself
the real intent was not to aid the contras but protect their opponents on capitol hill
reagan wants to give congress one more chance. ... if speaker wright blocks this effort ... his democratic colleagues will need more than a fig leaf to hide behind in november
march 2
huntington (w.va.) herald-dispatch on irs accuracy:
if you've been putting off doing your 1987 taxes, here's a chilling thought: money magazine reports it asked 50 tax preparers nationwide to figure out one family's taxes _ and got 50 different answers
meanwhile, the general accounting office has told congress that the internal revenue service is giving incorrect answers to 39 percent of the questions posed by people who call for help with their tax returns
no matter how complex the law, those who turn to the irs for help are entitled to a straight answer, and congress should make it clear to irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs and his staff that it expects nothing less
two bombs exploded early wednesday outside the police headquarters in this northwestern city, damaging two police buses and a car but causing no injuries, a police spokesman said
the spokesman said the blasts occurred just before 4 a.m. on a street that runs past one side of the national police station
no group immediately claimed responsibility, but police suspected the small, radical nationalist group, the guerrilla army of the free galician people, which seeks independence from spain for the four-province northwestern region of galicia
in the past two years, the group has claimed responsibility for setting off several small, homemade bombs against utilities, public offices and banks in the region
the government charged 13 opposition leaders wednesday in connection with street violence that followed last month's presidential elections, according to an official report
the senegalese press agency did not give the specific charges. a conviction for inciting violence calls for a prison term of from one to five years
among those charged was abdoulaye wade, leader of the opposition senegalese democratic party, who was president abdou diouf's strongest opponent in the feb. 28 elections
diouf won re-election with 73 percent of the vote, while wade received 25 percent. the announcement of preliminary results declaring diouf the victor sparked several days of street riots
a state of emergency was declared, a curfew put into effect, and riot and police and army troops were called out to restore order. several opposition leaders were blamed for inciting the demonstrations and arrested
rep. wayne dowdy called for party unity wednesday to help him keep john stennis' senate seat in democratic hands, while a supporter of sen. albert gore jr. said he was ``the big winner'' despite his second-place finish behind jesse jackson
dowdy defeated secretary of state dick moplus by a 54 percent to 42 percent margin tuesday to grab the democratic nomination for the seat of the retiring stennis. rep. trent lott, who became the state's first gop congressmen since reconstruction when he first won election in 1972, was unopposed
we're not running against anybody,'' said lott, who said he'd based his campaign on issues. ``our strategy until november is to run a continous campaign and to work hard and aggressively all over the state.''
it will take a united democratic party to beat him,'' dowdy said. ``it can be won, and things are ripe for the democrats to win in november. mississippi should have at least one democrat in the u.s. senate.''
gop sen. thad cochran holds the state's other seat
in the democratic presidential primary, with 99 percent of precincts reporting, jackson had 157,523 or 44 percent, gore had 120,049 or 34 percent and trailing far behind were massachusetts gov. michael dukakis with 29,789 or 8 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt with 19,646 votes or 6 percent; and former colorado sen. gary hart with 13,439 votes or 4 percent
we're pleased. we were the big winner'' said gore state coordinator brad chism. ``we came away with a lot more than people thought we would.''
jackson was leading for 24 delegates, gore for 15 and dukakis for one
in the republican race, with 2,298 of 2,340 precincts or 98 percent reporting, vice president george bush had 103,498 votes or 66 percent to kansas sen. bob dole's 26,212 or 17 percent. former tv evangelist pat robertson had 21,291 or 14 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 5,699 or 4 percent
bush picked up 27 gop delegates, with two each going to dole and robertson
population growth puts pressure on the environment and resources, whether it occurs in the third world or the united states, a population group says in a new booklet
usa by numbers: a statistical portrait of the united states,'' was issued wednesday by zero population growth to show how increasing numbers of people affect the nation's environment, economy and society as a whole
although americans are increasingly aware of population pressures in other parts of the world, many of us do not recognize the symptoms of overpopulation when we find them in our own backyards,'' said susan weber, executive director of the non-profit population group
the group has compiled statistics from a variety of sources, many of which also appear in the massive statistical abstract of the united states issued annually by the commerce department
the new 164-page volume, however, concentrates on the relationship between population and the quality of life in the nation
chapters in the volume look at population growth over time, city and rural relationships, young and old, fertility and health, sexuality and abortion, unemployment, poverty, water use, pollution, land use and habitat
the paperback volume costs $8.95 plus $1.50 for shipping and handling and can be purchased from zero population growth, 1601 connecticut ave., n.w., washington, d.c., 20009
