a 15-year-old youth charged with murdering a classmate with a baseball bat for the thrill of it was a confused youth whose cries for help were ignored, the defense argued in closing arguments today
defense attorney john philip white, who urged the jury to deliver a verdict of innocent by reason of insanity, characterized rod matthews as having a ``diseased intellect'' that made him unable to act rationally
white also said that the canton youth's attempts to seek help from teachers prior to the nov. 20, 1986 slaying were ignored
norfolk county assistant district attorney peter casey said the defense's contention that ritalin adversely affected matthews was a ``smoke screen.'' he argued that mathews, who is being tried as an adult, was a calculating murderer
casey noted testimony from several medical experts that ritalin does not permanently alter behavior or trigger violence or hallucinations in normal doses
matthews, whose eyes were downcast during two hours of closing arguments on the seventh day of the trial, admitted to bludgeoning 14-year-old shaun ouillette of canton with a baseball bat in a wooded section of the community south of boston
white depicted matthews as a highly unstable youth whose use of the drug ritalin to control hyperactivity may have contributed to his violent behavior
he was working in his own world,'' said white
the judge gave final instructions to the jury and said deliberations would begin in the afternoon
a local cable access station has run the trial unedited, including dramatic testimony by classmates that matthews plotted the murder for a month and calmly showed them the body as it lay for weeks in snow-covered woods
nothing has impacted the community more than this case,'' canton cable general manager tanya willow said. ``it's what everyone talks about. it's such a tragedy.''
defense experts maintained and prosecution witnesses contested that matthews, who pleaded innocent by reason of insanity, had emotional problems worsened by his use of the prescription drug ritalin
coincidentally, ouillette's mother, jeanne quinn, testified that her son took ritalin from age 7 through 11 to successfully control frantic behavior that plagued his childhood
dr. michael annunziata, a court-appointed psychiatrist, testified tuesday that matthews suffered from a ``conduct disorder'' but had not experienced classic symptoms of psychosis, such as hallucinations
dr. marcel kinsbourne, a neurologist at the eunice shriver center in waltham, testified that standard doses of ritalin should not trigger violent behavior
under cross-examination by the defense, kinsbourne said the drug could not totally eliminate matthews' volatile behavior
dr. bernard yudowitz of belmont's mclean hospital testified monday that ritalin may have made it harder for matthews to control his behavior
matthews said he had plotted the slaying for a month to experience what killing someone was like, according to testimony from two classmates. ouillette's body was discovered in december 1986 after one of the classmates sent an anonymous letter to police
matthews has been held at a danvers children's facility since last year
the case has been compared to the trial of anthony broussard, 18, sentenced to 25 years to life dec. 3, 1982, in san jose, calif., for killing his girlfriend in 1981. broussard, who was tried as an adult, took at least 13 schoolmates to see the victim's body
here, at a glance, are results from the super tuesday primaries and caucuses:
jesse jackson had expected to win comfortably on the strength of a sizable black vote, but instead narrowly defeated tennessee sen. albert gore jr., who was endorsed by sen. howell heflin. vice president george bush swamped kansas sen. bob dole just as expected
democrats in the south pacific territory, smallest of super tuesday's players, chose one national convention delegate for massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, one for missouri rep. richard gephardt, and one uncommitted. only 36 people voted at party caucuses
gore won with 37 percent, dukakis had 19 percent and jackson had 17 percent. gov. bill clinton said gore benefited from undecided voters, and the big surprise was the fourth place, 12 percent showing of gephardt. bush won with nearly half the vote
rep. bill alexander won an 11th term, defeating political consultant darrell glascock by 2-1 in the democratic primary. alexander is unopposed in the general election
dukakis found a warm reception from transplanted northerners and pulled in 41 percent of the vote to jackson's 20 percent. bush took advantage of president reagan's popularity, gov. bob martinez' endorsement and family ties (his son jeb is secretary of commerce) to trounce dole nearly 3-1
jackson won by piling up margins of better than 8-1 over gore and dukakis in the 5th congressional district, composed largely of the city of atlanta. the heavy black vote outweighed gore's endorsements by sen. sam nunn and gov. joe frank harris. bush beat dole better than 2-1
endorsements by the state's top democrats were credited with helping dukakis defeat jackson at hawaii's democratic party caucuses by nearly a 3-2 margin. gov. john waihee, who backed dukakis, said he wasn't surprised by jackson's strong showing and called it ``healthy for the democratic party.''
dukakis captured 8 of 18 uncommitted delegates, with jackson winning 4 and 6 going to the state convention uncommitted. gov. cecil andrus, who says he will go to the convention uncommitted, said the turning point in the dukakis campaign was a last-minute visit to boise last weekend. jackson's strong showing was a surprise because the state has a minority population of less than 5 percent
gore won his neighboring state with help from gov. wallace wilkinson, gaining 46 percent of the vote to dukakis' 19 percent. bush's 59 percent vote was termed ``astounding'' by his state campaign chairman, rep. harold ``hal'' rogers, who had predicted a 48 percent victory
jackson outpolled gore 35 percent to 28 percent despite gore's endorsement by democratic gov.-elect buddy roemer. bush breezed to victory with 58 percent, leaving dole and roberston each with 18 percent
in the 4th congressional district race to replace roemer, his former congressional aide jim mccrery, a republican, and democratic state sen. foster campbell claimed spots in an april 16 runoff
jackson finished second to dukakis, 29 percent to 46 percent, with a strong showing in the two predominantly black congressional districts. bush carried all eight districts even though he didn't campaign personally in maryland, while dole did spend some time in the state. bush led 53 percent to 32 percent
democratic sen. paul sarbanes easily won nomination for a third term and will be opposed by millionaire businessman thomas blair, a newcomer to politics
dukakis' home state gave him 59 percent of the vote. jackson was second with 19 percent. the win at home and victories in florida and texas gave dukakis the three biggest super tuesday prizes. bush, who was born in massachusetts, got 59 percent of the vote to dole's 26 percent. gordon nelson, state co-chairman for new york rep. jack kemp's campaign, said bush convinced voters he was reagan's logical successor: ``george bush won because he is reagan ii.''
bush and jackson rang up big victories, with jackson helped by turnout in the heavily black delta that enabled him to defeat gore
in a democratic primary for the seat of retiring sen. john stennis, voters chose rep. wayne dowdy to oppose gop rep. trent lott in november
bush won a narrow victory in dole's backyard, getting 42 percent of the vote to dole's 41 percent. bush pulled ahead with returns from st. louis county. gephardt easily won his home state with 58 percent of the vote, but it was his only victory tuesday. jackson was second with 20 percent
gore won in a tally at nevada's democratic caucuses, with dukakis second and jackson a surprisingly strong third. in balloting for county convention delegates, gore, who got support from sen. harry reid and other top state democrats, had 33 percent to dukakis' 26 and jackson's 22. party chairman beecher avants said jackson's strong showing ``was a real surprise.''
dole lost his wife's home state as bush emphasized his ties to president reagan. bush had 45 percent to dole's 40 percent of the gop vote. endorsements from such key democrats as sen. terry sanford and former gov. jim hunt helped gore squeeze past jackson 35 percent to 33 percent
gore got 41 percent of the vote, almost double his nearest competitor, gephardt. gore's victory margin was a surprise because a recent poll showed him in a tie with gephardt and dukakis. but he visited the state several times and spent more on advertising than any other democrat. as expected, the gop contest was close, with bush capturing 37 percent of the vote and dole 35 percent
bush and dukakis continued their new england sweeps, with the vice president winning 65 percent of the gop vote and the governor from neighboring massachusetts getting nearly 70 percent of the democratic vote. bush had built up good will through previous campaign journeys on behalf of gov. edward d. diprete and rep. claudine schneider
gore's home state gave him about 72 percent of the vote, leaving jackson, with 21 percent, a distant second. bush trounced dole nearly 3-1
dukakis won the top delegate state with 33 percent of the vote. bush, who built an oil business in texas, crushed all his rivals, receiving 64 percent of the vote. robertson got 15 percent and dole 14 percent
democratic u.s. sen. lloyd bentsen easily won renomination for a fourth term. rep. beau boulter and wes gilbreath, a houston investor, advance to gop runoff for u.s. senate. the winner faces bentsen in november
jackson received 45 percent of the vote, with gore far behind at 23 percent and dukakis with 22 percent. jackson got strong support in hampton roads and the richmond area, overcoming gore's numbers in southwestern virginia and dukakis' power base in suburbs near washington, d.c. boyd marcus, bush's state coordinator, said he would have been pleased with a mid-40 percent showing. the 2-to-1 win over dole (53 percent to 25 percent) ``has been the most surprising thing,'' he said. virginia native robertson had 12 percent
robertson's 39 percent of the vote gave him his only victory of super tuesday. dole had 26 percent, and bush was third, his only loss of the night, with 24 percent. to claim their share of the state's 41 gop delegates, the candidates will have to fare as well in this spring's county or legislative district caucuses, which precede the july 15 state convention where delegates will be allocated. dukakis, endorsed by gov. booth gardner, led democrats with 45 percent, followed by jackson with 32 percent. the democrats' tally won't be completed for a week. english</head>
britain's army of civil servants got new marching orders wednesday: use plain english
citing such authorities as confucius and winnie the pooh, a cabinet office pamphlet appealed to the bureaucrats to be clear and concise in talking to the public and to each other
britain's 500,000-member civil service has never been known for using a word when three would do, as the pamphlet notes in citing this 18th-century note from the commissioners of excise to the supervisor of pontefract:
i am ordered to acquaint you that if you hereafter continue that affected and schoolboy way of writing, and to murder the language in such a manner, you will be discharged for a fool.''
the duke of wellington railed against official jargon as ``the futile driveling of mere quill-driving.''
some of the examples given as good writing would make those quill-drivers blanch. it quoted this note from a minister in ancient egypt to a senior civil servant:
apollonius to zeno, greeting. you did right to send the chickpeas to memphis. farewell.''
the pamphlet was written by john wright, head of information at the cabinet office. the introduction is by prime minister margaret thatcher, who likes to be thought of as the enemy of verbose bureaucrats
she's a very great friend of the plain english campaign and extremely keen on the civil service using plain english,'' said wright. ``she is a plain-speaking woman.''
mrs. thatcher writes: ``too often clarity and simplicity are overwhelmed by pompous words, long sentences and endless paragraphs.''
or as the book of ecclesiastes admonishes: ``let thy speech be short, comprehending much in few words.''
among the tips in the pamphlet:
_ ``use shorter words. write `try' for `attempt,' `about' for `concerning,' `more' for `additional.' long words are often a sign of a stodgy style that sends readers to sleep.''
_ ``use short sentences. aim at an average of 15-20 words _ even shorter if you can manage it. you can still be polite and, if need be, formal or forceful.''
_ ``use jargon and abbreviations only when you're sure the reader knows what they mean. otherwise explain them.''
it suggests sentences with active verbs, such as ``the department decided that employees should work from 9 to 5'' instead of ``the decision of the department was that employees should work between 9 and 5.''
or as confucius would say: ``if language is not correct, then what is said is not what is meant; if what is said is not what is meant, then what ought to be done remains undone.''
remember,'' says the pamphlet, ``readers are in a hurry to get to the point. they don't want to be stuck in a verbal traffic jam.''
wright told the associated press the problem has been clearing up in recent years. ``there's increasing use of crisp and direct language. there's a great deal of plain english around.''
that would please winnie the pooh, that bear of little brain who signs off the pamphlet: ``long words bother me.''
several people hospitalized after a speeding bus rolled off a mountain road have died, raising the death toll in the accident to 42, it was reported wednesday
the reports on china's evening news broadcasts said 33 of the 71 passengers were killed in the crash and nine others died from their injuries during hospital treatment
the bus reportedly was traveling too fast as it headed down a curved mountain road in henan province. the driver hit the brakes and the vehicle swerved off the road, plunging 371 feet into a ravine
the bus accident was the third biggest transportation disaster of the year. a plane crash in southwest china killed 108 and a train derailment in southern china claimed 88 lives, both in january. will continue to aid afghan govt. if agreement signed. no pickup.</note>
the afghan government today rejected washington's demand that a simultaneous cessation of u.s. and soviet military aid be part of an afghan peace settlement
afghan foreign minister abdul wakil said soviet assistance cannot be compared to u.s. aid for ``terrorist groups,'' a reference to guerrillas fighting the kabul government
afganistan has always received soviet assistance and will continue to receive it even after the withdrawal of the soviet troops,'' he said. he did not specify what kind of aid he was talking about
wakil charged that the united states was trying to introduce a new issue just as the nearly 6-year-old afghanistan peace talks appeared to be close to conclusion
the same approach, he said, was used by pakistan when it insisted that formation of an interim government to replace the current kabul government be linked to an agreement to withdraw soviet troops
asked whether these two points could produce a deadlock, he responded, ``don't you think so?''
wakil told reporters the latest round of u.n.-mediated talks had produced ``nothing important,'' since agreement was reached last week on the timetable for withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 soviet troops in afghanistan
the soviets intervened in afghanistan in december 1979 to back kabul in a war that has waged for nine years
wakil accused pakistan, which represents the guerrillas in the talks, of resorting to ``maneuvers to push the geneva negotiations toward stalemate.''
but he said the afghan side was determined to push for a speedy conclusion
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has said moscow will bring home its troops starting may 15 if a peace package is signed by next tuesday
asked whether afghanistan was prepared to continue negotiations if that target date was not met, wakil said, ``regardless of whatever new obstacles the pakistanis are going to create, we are determined to move seriously toward the finalization of the agreements.''
wakil's comments contrasted with the cautious confidence displayed earlier this week by u.n. mediator diego cordovez and the chief pakistani representative, acting foreign minister zain noorani
cordovez spoke tuesday of ``substantive'' progress in readying the documents which make up the settlement
sources close to the pakistani delegation said noorani was hopeful that some deal could be struck on the issue of the interim government, perhaps by a compromise on the timing of its formation
for the fourth straight day, the separate meetings cordovez had with the pakistani and afghan delegations were confined to the morning. cordovez earlier told journalists that no spectacular developments were expectable to emerge from the talks before next week
assistant secretary of state richard murphy headed for moscow today to brief kremlin leaders on u.s. efforts to bring about mideast peace talks, the state department said
murphy will brief soviet foreign minister edouard shevardnadze on the latest u.s. efforts in advance of shevardnadze's visit to washington later this month, said spokesman charles redman
secretary of state george shultz promised to keep the soviets updated about his mideast plans when he conducted a shuttle mission in the region last week. shultz personally briefed the soviets on the initial phase of his mission when he stopped in moscow last month
shultz is seeking to bring israel and the arabs to the negotiating table for talks on palestinian autonomy starting may 1. under the plan shultz presented to israeli, jordanian and egyptian leaders, the talks would be launched in an international forum that would include the participation of the united states, the soviet union, china, england and france
shultz, who initially rejected soviet involvement in the process, now views the kremlin's involvement as necessary to nudge along the reluctant arabs who are moscow's allies. shultz has asked both israel and jordan for responses to his proposals by next week
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir has balked at bringing the u.s. plan up for a cabinet debate, and intends instead to present a plan of his own when he comes here next week. that plan calls for joint u.s.-soviet participation in autonomy talks for the 1.5 million palestinians under israeli occupation
murphy will also stop in bonn, rome, paris and brussels to bring officials there up to date on the u.s. mideast initiative, redman said
western european leaders have praised the u.s. involvement, which is aimed at resolving the three months of israeli-palestinian bloodshed in which at least 80 arabs have been killed. ``anderson said it...''</note>
a former top aide to impeached gov. evan mecham testified today that she called a newspaper after she was told a state official had threatened her life in hopes that she would be safe if the matter were public
donna carlson, former special assistant to the first-term republican governor, also said that shortly after mecham took office in january 1987 he asked her to keep notes on conversations with legislators ``so that it might be used against them in the elections if he chose to use it.''
she said she did not do so because she thought it would be improper, and said her job at times was ``like a three-ring circus.''
director of public safety ralph milstead has accused mecham of ordering him not to cooperate with an investigation of the alleged nov. 12 threat against ms. carlson by lee watkins, former head of state prison construction
at the time, ms. carlson had resigned from the governor's staff and was about to testify before a state grand jury that was investigating mecham's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan
mecham is accused of trying to thwart an investigation of the alleged death threat
watkins refused to testify last week, citing his fifth amendment right against self-incrimination, but has previously denied threatening ms. carlson's life
ms. carlson spoke softly today as she described how milstead told her on nov. 14 that watkins had threatened her
ms. carlson testified that milstead telephoned and ``told me that there had been a threat made against me by lee watkins ... and it was something to the effect that if i didn't stop talking i would end up in the bottom of a river.''
i didn't say anything; i was taken aback,'' she said. ``it's kind of a shock.''
ms. carlson testified that she was upset and called a newspaper reporter and told him about the alleged threat after a friend advised her that the best thing for her safety might be to make the matter public
ms. carlson said she had previously expressed doubts about watkins to both mecham and then-chief of staff jim colter when she learned that watkins had a criminal record
she said colter told her, ``we have to take care of lee. he raised a lot of money for the campaign.''
on tuesday watkins' attorney, dale anderson, testified that a top mecham aide helped craft a lie-detector test so watkins could pass it
also tuesday, arizona supreme court chief justice frank x. gordon jr., presiding over the senate trial, decided to bar further testimony challenging milstead's credibility
mecham appointed max hawkins, then director of the state department of administration and watkins' boss, to investigate the alleged death threat
anderson testified that after his client failed four polygraphs, hawkins suggested having the polygraph operator ``figure out what kind of questions could be asked so my client could answer these questions and get his job back.''
anderson said it was not unusual to choreograph a lie detector test
you shop for polygraphers and you shop for questions,'' he said
the trial was scheduled to continue today with testimony from donna carlson, target of the alleged threat. at the time, ms. carlson was preparing to testify before the state grand jury about mecham's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan
prosecutor paul eckstein said the polygrapher, manuel valenzuela, also may be called to testify before the prosecution closes its case on the first of three charges against the first-term republican governor
in addition to the alleged death threat and loan matters, mecham is accused of misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
watkins was placed on administrative leave last november after he was accused of telling another state official that if ms. carlson didn't keep her mouth shut about the $350,000 loan she ``could take a long boat ride.''
a transcript of a tape-recorded nov. 12 conversation between anderson and hawkins was released tuesday and quotes hawkins as saying he wanted polygraph test results that would allow him to reinstate watkins
i love lee and i want to save his ass,'' the transcript quotes hawkins as saying. ``i believe he is getting railroaded.''
the transcript quotes hawkins as suggesting the polygraph operator ask, ``what did lee say he said? and then he just writes that down. ... then the polygraph (operator) says he (watkins) made this statement. is it true?''
on nov. 20, hawkins announced watkins would be reinstated but refused to release the polygraph results. at the time, hawkins said he knew little beyond the fact that anderson told him that watkins had passed the test
watkins resigned his state job, and hawkins was fired last week by acting gov. rose mofford, a democrat who took over when the house impeached mecham on feb. 5
much of tuesday's questioning by defense lawyer fred craft centered on use of state vehicles by milstead, arizona's highest-ranking lawman, and his relationship with a woman who claimed she had an affair with him
after milstead's testimony, gordon said he would allow no more testimony about these matters
you have made your point,'' gordon told craft. ``you have established that director milstead had a motive for testifying against the governor,'' including the knowledge that mecham wanted to fire him
under questioning by craft, milstead denied paying for the woman's meals or staying overnight at her home after driving there in a state vehicle. prosecutor william french contended the questioning was ``cross-examination by innuendo'' and was improper
mecham is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona. a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to remove him, and lawmakers also could vote to bar him from future public office
mecham also faces a march 22 criminal trial on charges of concealing the $350,000 loan and a may 17 recall election
a convicted rapist who was placed on the u.s. marshal service's 15 most wanted list after twice escaping from county jails was recaptured after seven months on the run, authorities said
garnett r. leacock, 38, offered no resistance when marshals acting on a tip arrested him tuesday at a brooklyn apartment, said frank peo, marshal for the northern district of new york
leacock escaped aug. 9 from the montgomery county jail in fonda, where he was awaiting sentencing in the rape of a 16-year-old girl at his home at griffiss air force base in rome, authorities said. he was sentenced in abstentia to 27 years
in july, leacock escaped from the madison county jail by digging a hole in the wall of his cell and slipping through after lathering his body with shampoo. he was recaptured two days later after his wife, who aided in both escapes, turned him in after having second thoughts, authorities said
air force sgt. deborah leacock is serving a five-year sentence for her role in the second escape. strength</head>
republicans claimed victory in georgia wednesday after almost twice as many people voted in the party's presidential primary as ever before, boosting vice president george bush's campaign
democrats, meanwhile, picked jesse jackson, with sen. albert gore jr. a surprisingly strong second
secretary of state max cleland said the 39 percent turnout _ a presidential primary record _ helped bush and gore, who were preceived as the moderate candidates
with 99 percent of the ballots counted, bush led with 214,892 votes, or 54 percent, giving him all 48 delegates to the august gop nominating convention in new orleans
sen. bob dole of kansas trailed with 94,121 for 24 percent. former television evangelist pat robertson had 64,995, 16 percent, and rep. jack kemp of new york had 23,459, or 6 percent
in the democratic race, jackson had 247,317 votes, or 40 percent. his plurality victories in two congressional districts, plus his statewide lead, put him ahead for 37 delegates to the atlanta convention in july
gore parlayed endorsements by several top state democrats, including sen. sam nunn, into 200,758 votes, or 32 percent, good for 30 delegates. massachusetts gov. michael dukakis was a distant third with 96,881, 16 percent, and received 10 delegates
with almost 400,000 ballots cast in the gop primary, the party doubled the turnout of 1980, when president reagan blasted bush on the way to nomination
longtime gop activist bob bell, currently chairman emeritus of the state party, was buoyed by the turnout, claiming it represented a solidifying of the party in the state
although he agreed that newly active robertson supporters were responsible for some of the increase, he said most of the new voters were oldtime democrats who ``couldn't find anything in the democratic party to attract their attention, ... so they opted for bush.''
cleland, a democrat, agreed with bell, saying, ``i think it (the gop turnout) shows that georgia is a bonafide two-party state.''
the air force has improperly allowed foreign servicemen to play slot machines at its overseas bases in six countries, violating the host-nation agreements that sanction the presence of u.s. troops, service auditors have found
the air force audit agency said in a 13-page report such a permissive attitude violates local laws prohibiting or controlling gambling in britain, west germany, turkey, the philippines, japan and south korea
the air force is allowed to operate slot machines at the overseas bases for american personnel only, the auditors noted
violation of host nation laws or supplement agreements is potentially embarrassing to the air force and could result in overall prohibition of slot machines in overseas open messes,'' the auditors added
the audit was conducted in the spring of 1987 and the results forwarded to air force officials at that time. the report was released publicly earlier this week
the air force said wednesday it had yet to resolve the issue because it originally had tried to develop a single policy directive to govern such situations
the foreign laws of the various countries vary to such an extent, however, that air force attorneys are now trying to write a directive that will allow service officials in each country to tailor their gambling regulations to local law, said capt. lou figueroa, an air force spokesman
it is true that we would appear to be in violation in these six countries,'' figueroa added
but i would also point out the air force is not aware of any complaints by any of the host countries. and we do not know the extent to which foreign nationals are really playing the slots.''
the air force currently operates 2,358 slot machines at 55 base facilities outside the united states. the machines generated $20.4 million in gross revenue in fiscal 1987. proceeds from the slots are designated exclusively for the support of morale, welfare and recreation programs at the bases
the air force had allowed gambling at its overseas bases for years until 1972, when all slot machines were removed amid disclosures of widespread corruption. the secretary of the air force, after promulgating new, more stringent controls, authorized their return in march 1982
we found accounting controls and existing regulatory guidance generally satisfactory,'' the auditors wrote in their report
overall management policies for slot machine maintenance and personnel administration were effective. cash and other asset controls were generally adequate. our review, however, disclosed problems associated with legality of slot machine play by citizens of host countries,'' the report said
the auditors said they were recommending more attention be paid to gambling policies at overseas bases not only because foreign laws were being ignored, but also because the air force was ignoring what other u.s. military services were doing
for example, south korean military personnel are prohibited from slot machine play in u.s. army open messes, whereas the air force was in violation of local laws prohibiting gambling,'' the auditors wrote
gallaudet university, currently embroiled in a dispute over the selection of its new president, is the only liberal arts institution in the world for the deaf
the 99-acre campus in northeast washington provides education for 2,200 university students, 400 high school students and 200 elementary school students. nearly all the undergraduates are deaf
the federally supported institution receives 75 percent of its $76 million budget from congress, with the rest coming from tuition, which is about $6,000 per student
the school began in 1856, when amos kendall, a wealthy journalist and former postmaster general opened the kendall school for deaf and blind children on his 99-acre farm
the following year, kendall persuaded congress to incorporate the school as the columbia institution for the instruction of the deaf and dumb and the blind, with president james buchanan as its patron
in 1864, president abraham lincoln signed legislation empowering the institution to award college degrees through a new national deaf mute college. edward miner gallaudet, son of thomas hopkins gallaudet, a pioneer in educating the deaf, became its president
five years later, president ulysses s. grant signed the diplomas of the college's first three graduates, starting a tradition that president reagan follows today
in 1894, the college was renamed in honor of the elder gallaudet, and in 1986, gallaudet college became gallaudet university by an act of congress
the institution today has 274 full-time professors, of whom 30 percent are deaf. in addition, 22 percent of the school's 1,300-member support staff are deaf
professors cannot receive tenure unless they demonstrate their proficiency in sign language to a panel of students and faculty, and all professors are required to simultaneously speak and sign their own lectures in english
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and vice president george bush cashed in on their new england connections to win rhode island's presidential primary
dukakis was a familiar face to rhode islanders long before he began running for president. he campaigned here several times and quickly gained support from most of rhode island's democratic hierarchy
a year ago, no one was going to say that mike dukakis would be the next president,'' lt. gov. richard a. licht said tuesday night
dukakis had 34,159 votes or 70 percent; jesse jackson had 7,369 votes or 15.2 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 2,013 votes or 4.1 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 1,932 votes or 4 percent, and illinois sen. paul simon had 1,392 votes or 2.9 percent
among republicans, bush won 10,403 votes or 65 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 3,637 votes or 22.6 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 921 votes or 5.8 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 783 votes or 4.9 percent
based on those results, dukakis likely would capture 19 democratic delegates and jackson 3, while bush would gain 15 gop delegates and dole 6
jackson supporters broke out champagne to celebrate their candidate's strong showing in a state that is only 2 percent black
given $2 million in tv advertising by dukakis and $100,000 by jackson nationally, it shows good management,'' said jackson's state campaign chairman, walter r. stone. tactics'</head> hemophilia and to show that study referred to transmission of aids virus, not hemophilia, which is herditary.</note>
surgeon general c. everett koop on wednesday attacked conclusions about aids by sex researchers dr. william masters and virginia johnson, saying their new book uses ``scare tactics'' and is irresponsible and unscientfic
koop said the sex experts have no scientific evidence to back up claims that aids among heterosexuals is ``rampant,'' that the disease can be spread by casual non-sexual contact or that the nation's blood supply is unsafe
the surgeon general was reacting to findings from a masters and johnson book co-authored by dr. robert kolodny, ``crisis: heterosexual behavior in the age of aids.'' excerpts from th book appeared in this week's newsweek magazine
koop, interviewed from london on abc-tv's ``good morning america,'' noted that masters and johnson did not submit their findings to scientific review or have them published in a recognized medical journal
i think it (the book) is irresponsible. it is scare tactics,'' koop said
he said the risk of aids-contaminated blood in medical blood supplies ranges from one in 40,000 to one in 250,000. masters and johnson claim it is one in 5,000, but koop said there is no evidence to support such a statistic
koop said he feared the book would cause ``hysteria'' but added that he hopes americans would ``stick to their usual habit of listening to the facts, sorting them out and doing what's right.''
masters and johnson were pioneers in sex therapy and sex research and run a sex therapy institute in st. louis
their new book calls for widespread mandatory testing for acquired immune deficiency syndrome infections, and estimates there are 3 million or more aids carriers in the united states. the government estimates that between 1 million and 1.5 million people are infected
koop acknowledged that there is an explosion of aids among heterosexuals in africa but said ``the united states is not like africa. ... that's not going to happen here.''
heterosexuals make up only 4 percent of aids cases, and this is expected to increase to 5 percent by 1991, he said
scientists say the disease is spread most often through homosexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from infected pregnant women to their offspring
if there were any truth to the possibility of aids being spread through other means, koop said, the government would be warning against it. ``we have never gotten ahead of our scientific base, and that's something the american people can rely on,'' he said
he said that among more than 50,000 aids cases so far in the united states, ``not one single one was proven to be transmitted by casual non-sexual contact.''
he said americans can take comfort from a survey of families of people with the heriditory disease hemophilia, who were also aids victims, mostly from blood transfusions. he said of 2,400 people studied, there was not one case of the aids virus being passed to another member of the family except between spouses due to sexual contact. he said 7 percent of those in the study even shared a toothbrush with the victim
aids is very hard to catch,'' koop said
a state appeals panel has unanimously upheld the conviction of a defendant in the botched 1981 brink's robbery that resulted in the deaths of two policemen and a guard
the state appellate division in brooklyn rejected the appeal by sam brown, 46, who is serving a 75-year to life sentence for his murder and robbery conviction
the charges stemmed from the $1.6 million holdup of a brink's truck in nanuet, north of new york city
kathy boudin, a former weather underground activist, pleaded guilty to the charges and is serving a prison term of 20 years to life. three other defendants were convicted
among the many arguments raised by brown's lawyer and rejected by the appeals panel was that the indictment should have been dismissed because his rights were violated when he was beaten by prison officials after his arrest and that government officials interfered with his right to counsel
the michelin guide, france's supreme arbiter of culinary excellence, promoted one restaurant to the three-star pinnacle wednesday but elsewhere went on a star-shearing rampage
the coveted third star, which in michelin parlance means ``exceptional cuisine, worth a special journey,'' went to bernard pacaud, the 40-year-old chef of paris' l'ambroisie restaurant
the auberge du pere bise in the alpine town of talloires was demoted to two stars, signifying ``excellent cooking, worth a detour.'' another three-star restaurant was lost when louis outhier retired and closed la napoule near cannes
the 1988 red guide, which went on sale wednesday at $17, reduced the number of stars it awarded from 656 last year to 635. the number of three-star restaurants fell from 19 to 18, two-star establishments declined from 92 to 88 and one-star eateries, meaning ``very good cooking in its class,'' fell from 545 to 529
the addition of a star, actually a squiggle with six round bumps, means fame for a chef and his restaurant and money in his pocket. loss of the symbol can mean anguish and despair, particularly in a country that considers cooking an art form
pacaud, of breton origin, established his restaurant in 1986 after a long apprenticeship in top kitchens, including la mere brazier in lyon and under marc meneau at vezelay and claude peyrot in paris
the red book, first published in france in 1900 by andre michelin, the tire manufacturer, is a complete tourist guide and basically is aimed at helping the motorist
though many tend to think of the guide in terms of gastronomy, it also contains a wealth of maps, information on hotels, repair services, sights, distances between towns, telephone numbers, prices and thousands of other useful tidbits for the traveler
keeping up with the times, this year's guide notes hotels and restaurants that have special rooms or a dining room specially reserved for non-smokers
the auberge du pere bise lost its third star once before, between 1983 and 1985, when the owner became ill. it was promoted again when his daughter took over, but appears to have run into trouble again. the michelin folk are typically vague
it's part of the life of an establishment,'' said bernard naugellen, director of the guide. ``people sometimes reproach us for not taking away enough stars. when a house goes down, we take measures.''
naugellen had nothing but praise for pacaud, whose specialities include creme de homard and florentine raviolis, turbot braised in spices and braised ox-tail
he is a young chef who is doing a classic cuisine, a traditional cuisine, but very intelligent, full of finesse and character,'' he said
the chef himself refused comment
chunks missing from a titan 4 motor after a recent ground test could mean a delay in the first scheduled launch of the rocket in october, the san jose mercury news reported wednesday
the test was conducted feb. 14 at the san jose research facilities of united technologies corp., whose engineers, along with air force specialists, are trying to find out if a flaw might require retesting or redesign, the newspaper said
u.s. space officials have been counting on the titan 4 to carry into orbit dozens of satellites
there are some chunks missing, not terribly large,'' spokesman rick huling of the el segundo air force unit said. ``i think in one particular case the burn was down fairly close to the metal on the outside of the (nozzle) casing. if the flames had burned through the remaining insulation and ruptured the metal nozzle case, then you've had it.''
a smaller titan 34d rocket exploded april 18, 1986, during launch at vandenberg air force base when some insulation broke loose inside the motor. the heat burned through the rocket's outer wall
the titan 4 launch, scheduled for october from the kennedy space center at cape canaveral, fla., would take up a classified military payload that analysts have said is a satellite equipped with a heat-sensitive infrared telescope to spot nuclear missile attacks
we have a backlog of space shuttle-size loads,'' said huling. ``the titan 4 is, in fact, going to be the substitute for anything that doesn't need a man up there in space. i would say we need to get up there as quickly as possible.''
the manned shuttle program was put on hold after the challenger explosion, with the target date for the next launch set for aug. 4. today; picks up 6th graf pvs, `the ntsb report...'; subs grafs 15, ``one survivor xxx, and 19th graf, ``two flight 1713 ^^^^, to correct, only one passenger saw ice</note>
the effort to save victims of a continental airlines crash went extremely well even though radio batteries failed, pens wouldn't write and rescuers weren't dressed for the cold, the rescue coordinator testified today
continental flight 1713 crashed while taking off from stapleton international airport last nov. 15 in a snowstorm and left 28 people dead and 54 injured
we feel fortunate we had that many survivors,'' said dr. michael brunko of denver general hospital, who was in charge of the rescue operation at the crash. he was testifying on the second day of a national transportation safety board hearing
obviously, there were people trapped in the wreckage who we could not do anything for. and to this day, i do not know what else could have been done,'' he said. the overall operation ``went very, very well,'' he said
among the problems, brunko said, were the fact that there were too many rescue workers and vehicles on the scene and that continental employees were questioning survivors at the site, even though the employees role had been part of an earlier crash rehearsal at the airport
we survived by adrenaline,'' he said of the cold and snow
brunko said there were so many emergency vehicles that he had to run 10 to 15 feet away to escape background noise so he could communicate with the airport command post
the four-day ntsb hearing is expected to lead to a report detailing factors that may have contributed to the crash
brunko's testimony this morning jibed with investigation reports released tuesday by the ntsb that quoted one firefighter as saying rescue personnel at the crash site were ``10 deep and waiting to get in to help.''
we had more personnel than we needed,'' brunko said
rescue workers also said that ``the continental people got in the way of medical treatment of the passengers,'' according to the report
brunko said that at one point at least 15 continental employees arrived at the crash site, many of them heading for the nose of the aircraft, which had flipped upside down on the runway and broken into three pieces
he said he had identified about 20 patients needing treatment before the continental employees arrived, and their presence made him suddenly uncertain who were patients and who were airline employees
the ntsb report outlined several problems found by a review team, including the lack of a staging area for rescue vehicles that caused ambulances to arrive an estimated 45 minutes after the crash
i was shocked at the number of people running around who were not firemen,'' ron fano, director of airport operations, testified tuesday
fano, who headed the rescue command post, said some operations were delayed because of two seriously injured passengers inside the post
he said buses to transport the injured did not show up until about an hour after the accident and ambulances did not show up for 45 minutes
the report also said firefighters were trained to extinguish fires on older models of aircraft, and had difficulty rescuing survivors
the ntsb team did not directly criticize the rescue effort. denver fire chief richard gonzales said he believed the work ``went rather smothly.''
the report said continental employees may have interfered with medical treatment of passengers by trying to interview them at a nearby fire station
however, continental spokesman bruce hicks said airline employees routinely are involved in rescue efforts, and he noted that continental workers participated in a crash drill at stapleton two months before the crash
de-icing and the pilots' experience flying dc-9s were the other chief issues raised during testimony tuesday, although government officials have said their inquiry is not focusing on a single possible cause
one survivor told investigators he saw ice and snow on one of the wings, but another survivor who also was concerned about ice said the wings only were wet. a pilot on another plane said the continental jet looked clear
wes zimmerman, a continental pilot whose 727-300 aircraft was on the runway at the same time as the continental jetliner, testified he saw no ice or snow buildup on flight 1713
i felt good about how my de-icing was holding up,'' he said, explaining that he looked at nearby aircraft to gauge the condition of his own plane. but he acknowledged that his plane did not sit as long between de-icing and takeoff as flight 1713 did
robert benzon, charge of the ntsb inquiry, said during his opening statement that officials want to know why 24 minutes elapsed between de-icing and takeoff when other planes on the runway took off within 15 minutes
two flight 1713 passengers, dr. fred helpenstell, 56, of nampa, idaho, and gregory wadsworth, 22, an airman stationed in idaho, testified they were concerned there might have been ice on the wings before takeoff
i wondered at one point, `is that ice?''' helpenstell recalled, ``but i decided it was just wet.''
wadsworth, who is stationed at mountain home air force base, said he had a clear view of the left wing
it had started to snow a lot harder, and it made me real nervous. it was like the snow was starting to pike up (on the wings),'' he said. ``i was very concerned, but i said it under my breath.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who called delegate-rich florida a bellwether state because of its diversity, swept aside his democratic opponents in the presidential primary
his well-financed campaign used heavy television advertising to spread from a liberal base in southeast florida to win 15 of the state 19 congressional districts. jesse jackson won three and tennessee sen. al gore jr. won only the conservative panhandle
this is a diverse group of voters in florida,'' dukakis campaign field director paul pezzella said. ``if we can win here, we can win anywhere.''
with all 4,459 precincts reporting, dukakis had 509,248 votes or 41 percent; jackson 250,579 votes or 20 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt 179,400 votes or 14 percent, and gore had 158,833 votes or 13 percent
vice president george bush crushed his republican rivals, winning 545,668 votes or 62 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 185,179 votes or 21 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 93,752 votes or 11 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 40,545 votes or 5 percent
based on those results, bush was expected to win all 82 of florida's gop delegates; dukakis would win 90 of the 136 democratic delegates at stake; jackson would get 33 delegates; gephardt 7 and gore 6
florida offered the second-largest batch of delegates on super tuesday, behind only texas, which bush and dukakis also carried
bush capitalized on president reagan's popularity and his own familiarity to floridians. he has visited often on official business such as heading the south florida task force on drugs, and for personal visits to his mother in palm beach and to his son, jeb, now florida's commerce secretary
the bush campaign had five full-time paid staffers compared to 16 for dukakis, and both were bankrolled for a strong television push to reach the diverse florida electorate on the final weekend preceding tuesday's vote
gephardt's poor showing was the biggest surprise in the democratic race. endorsed by rep. claude pepper and using a last-minute media campaign, gephardt had concerned the dukakis campaign most. he failed to carry a single district
kurt georg kiesinger, who served as west germany's third federal chancellor from 1966 to 1969 despite controversy over his nazi past, died wednesday of heart failure. he was 83
kiesinger spent 18 months in a u.s. postwar internment camp with other nazi party members, but he staunchly denied any wrongdoing during adolf hitler's third reich and never was charged with any crimes
in a widely publicized incident, kiesinger was slapped in the face by nazi hunter beate klarsfeld at a conference in west berlin on nov. 7, 1968
mrs. klarsfeld was convicted of causing bodily injury and insulting kiesinger, and after receiving and appealing a one-year prison sentence, was given four months' probation. she continued her bitter public criticism of kiesinger
during his three years at the helm of the nation's grand coalition of conservatives and leftist-leaning social democrats, kiesinger improved contacts with the east
the christian democratic chancellor also overcame a troubling recession with a series of economic measures during his term
known as ``king silver tongue'' because of his powerful speaking style, kiesinger retained his heavy swabian accent. he was a roman catholic, born april 6, 1904, in ebingen in baden-wuerttemburg
as a 29-year-old lawyer, kiesinger joined the nazi party in 1933, the year hitler came to power. he said he became disillusioned with the party a year later because of the bloody purge of storm trooper leader ernst roehm and his associates
during world war ii, kiesinger worked in the radio propaganda section of the nazi foreign ministry and served as department head for part of the war
after the war, u.s. forces rounded up thousands of germans pending investigations of their membership in the nazi party. he spent 18 months in an internment camp in ludwigsburg
a german court fined him 50 marks, then $12.50, for being a party member. the fine was returned when the court ruled later that he had risked his life to get a student out of a nazi prison
kiesinger's nazi past brought him much unfavorable publicity when he became a candidate for chancellor, and the sharp, public debate continued during his term
he always denied any wrongdoing and declared: ``i have clean hands. i know what i did and what i did not do.''
kiesinger was a party member for the full 12 years of the nazi regime from 1933 to 1945
in 1966, kiesinger succeeded fellow christian democrat chancellor ludwig erhard, forming the only grand coalition of conservatives and social democrats
kiesinger sought more contact with the communist states of eastern europe, breaking with past policy. he established diplomatic relations with romania and yugoslavia, but his overtures suffered a setback when the soviets invaded czechoslovakia in 1968
kiesinger's government remained a resolute ally of the united states, but he feuded with president lyndon johnson in 1967 and complained that he had not been adequately consulted on a u.s.-soviet nuclear weapons treaty
he was a symbol of reconciliation, grouping the conservative christian democrats and their bavarian counterparts with the social democrats
six years ago, a small-town minnesota girl left home for hollywood. but her dreams of stardom turned into an x-rated nightmare of porn movies and cocaine addiction, and two years later, she committed suicide
her mother, karen applegate, is still searching for answers in the march 21, 1984, death of her 20-year-old daughter, colleen. she and her family cooperated with hollywood in a television movie based on colleen's life in hopes that it might prevent similar tragedies
shattered innocence,'' wednesday night on cbs, depicts the final years of miss applegate, who left her farmington home in march 1982, posed nude for magazine photos and soon became porn movie star shauna grant
her name and hometown were changed in the film, but her mother said: ``the whole mess is true. the basic story is true. and why? i don't know.''
while the mother said she was generally satisfied with the film, she felt the horror of the worlds of pornography and cocaine addiction were soft-pedaled
at the peak of her career, shauna grant made 30 x-rated movies in one year and had film sex with about 40 men. the movie, however, gave the impression that grant made only a few films
the producers originally had a dramatization closer to the gritty details, but it had to be softened because of prime-time television,'' production representative karen ocamb said in a telephone interview from los angeles
you get the idea of what the world of pornography is all about, what it does to the individual is that it kills her.''
shattered innocence'' tells of a high school cheerleader who is bored and restless with her life in banning, kan., and after graduation heads for the bright lights and glitter of hollywood
dazzled by the quick money to be made in nude modeling, up to $2,000 a session for national magazines, she soon went for even bigger purses offered by porn films. she then started using cocaine to lose weight
throughout the film, she maintains contact with her family. her mother loves her but doesn't excuse or condone her behavior
it is very difficult for the family. they try to intervene but she wants the family to love her on her terms, not theirs,'' ocamb said
after briefly giving up her pornographic movie career, but being unable to kick the cocaine addiction, the young woman portrayed by actress jonna lee is about to re-enter the world of pornography when she kills herself
the mother asks, `why did this happen?' that's basically what the film asks,'' said ocamb. ``there are no answers. everyone in every family needs to ask this question. how did a cheerleader become a porno star and commit suicide?''
the movie was made because colleen applegate's story is representative of so many young people, ocamb said
there are a lot of kids who come from farmington, minnesota, or banning, kansas. they're just immature and irresponsible and they think they can come to hollywood and become a star overnight or they'll just `find something
as we know, they wind up on the streets,'' ocamb said
the applegates _ colleen had three younger sisters and one younger brother _ cooperated with the producers in hopes the movie might help someone else, said the mother, who is portrayed by actress melinda dillon
for people out there who think that it's exploiting her and exploiting ourselves, then they should be very grateful because then they can't relate to it,'' she said
there are many out there who can relate to it, and those are the ones i hope it helps.''
a court on wednesday sentenced an activist to two months in prison because of a ``street happening'' that poked fun at the government, an opposition spokesman said
waldemar frydrych, 34, head of the opposition cultural group orange alternative, was arrested by police with five other people on tuesday, said jacek kuron, a warsaw opposition activist
he said about 50 orange alternative supporters, some of whom carried a banner reading ``missiles _ no, sanitary pads _ yes,'' handed out cotton pads to women in downtown wroclaw. police moved in quickly and halted the demonstration
feminie hygiene products are in short supply in poland. tuesday was international women's day
the sentence marked one of the few times since a september 1986 amnesty for political prisoners that a misdemeanor court has sentenced someone to prison for a politically motivated offense. in almost all cases, people were held up to 48 hours and released after being fined
kuron said frydrych was sentenced on a charge of causing public unrest
two other orange alternative supporters, pawel kasprzak and krzysztof albin, were each fined the equivalent of $79 by the misdemeanor court, kuron said
he said the orange alternative members joked with the court by arguing that karl marx, the founder of communism, was actually a bearded lady
frydrych has been detained at least half a dozen times since september for organizing various orange alternative ``happenings'' in wroclaw in which demonstrators have dressed up as santa claus, lenten penitents and even secret policemen to satirize government policies
a convicted marijuana smuggler testified in the cocaine-smuggling trial of carlos lehder rivas that the colombian had helped finance terry knight, identified as a former auto racing partner of actor paul newman
the brief mention of newman came tuesday as defense attorney ed shohat questioned witness charles gregory von eberstein
knight lived on the bahamian island of norman's cay. von eberstein testified that he had seen a picture of knight's car with the insignia of the norman's cay yacht club on it
when shohat asked if newman, the actor, was in the picture, von eberstein answered, ``i knew terry was his racing partner. i knew (lehder) had put some money in it.''
the witness said he didn't believe knight was aware of the smuggling going on at the island
lehder, 38, is accused of conspiring with others to smuggle some 3.3 tons of cocaine into the united states from colombia from 1978 to 1980 via norman's cay in the bahamas
newman has long taken part in auto races as a sideline to his acting career. his last partner, jim fitzgerald, died last november when he crashed his car during the st. petersburg grand prix. there was no elaboration on knight's career in tuesday's testimony
von eberstein testified tuesday that he had decided not to return to the united states after knight played an audio tape which indicated von eberstein and his associate ed ward had been indicted. the source of the tape and how knight got it were not disclosed in testimony
von eberstein, a friend and neighbor of ward, a convicted smuggler, testified that he and ward made several cocaine flights for lehder in 1979 and 1980. he said one was into colombia and several were from norman's cay, lehder's private bahamian island, to prison airport near reidsville, ga
von eberstein, who was sentenced to 18 years in prison in 1981 after pleading guilty to three marijuana charges and one count of income-tax evasion, eventually had his sentence reduced to 15 years and was released after four years in prison
lehder, reputed to be one of the leaders in the violent colombian medellin cartel, is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise
a woman who works in the records department of the sports car club of america in englewood, colo., said the club keeps listings for racers registered in the last three years and had no listing for a terry knight
the woman, who declined to give her name, said there was no way to be certain who newman's partner was
michael dukakis went from the triumph of his seven super tuesday victories to the scrap-strewn wasteland of chicago's southeast corner on wednesday, seeking votes in the democrats' next major campaign test
the massachusetts governor talked to steel workers _ some laid off, some on the job _ in his first full day of campaigning for next tuesday's illinois primary, when 173 delegates will be at stake
gone were the condominiums and strawberry festivals of the florida primary campaign. now dukakis was campaigning for votes among steel mills, scrap heaps, refineries and belching smokestacks
dukakis did only slightly better on tuesday than rivals albert gore jr. and jesse jackson. but he quickly tried to stake out a claim as the only national candidate in the race capable of winning in the south and the industrial midwest
he said of gore, the tennessee senator, ``i'm not so sure he's a major contender. a guy from massachusetts beat him in texas, beat him in florida. he wasn't willing to go into the early primaries. but i still take everyone seriously.''
with two illinois residents in the race _ jackson and sen. paul simon _ ``obviously it's going to be an uphill battle,'' dukakis said. ``i hope when the people of illinois cast their votes they'll do so for someone who can clearly win the presidency.''
in a dig at another rival, he said the failure of missouri rep. richard gephardt to win any but his home state on super tuesday proved the futility of negative campaigning. dukakis, who had countered with an anti-gephardt ad of his own, said, ``i think that what happened to congressman gephardt yesterday demonstrates pretty clearly that when you engage in that kind of campaigning, you're going to get hurt.''
dukakis opened the day at a breakfast meeting at the lion's den restaurant on chicago's east side where he met with laid-off steel workers. ``i don't know a great deal about the steel industry as such,'' dukakis told the group. but he said he did have experience in massachusetts getting labor, management and government working together
later the governor and his wife kitty donned hard hats as they toured the metron steel factory in chicago's hard-hit calumet industrial section
aware of walter mondale's disastrous showing in 1984, dukakis has avoided appearing to be too strong a union democrat. rather, he said he wanted to be ``a full-employment democrat.''
jack corrigan, dukakis' campaign operations director, said there would be no change in the candidate's message now that he is in the nation's industrial section
we haven't gotten the afl-cio endorsement. we've gotten some union support and we're proud of it. i don't see it as a problem.''
despite the cash drain of super tuesday with its emphasis on television advertising, the dukakis campaign remains in good financial condition, aides said. campaign finance chief robert farmer said dukakis is raising half a million dollars a week. coming out of super tuesday, he said, dukakis has $2 million in the bank and $1 million on the way in federal matching funds. ``we're going to be in very good shape,'' farmer said
dukakis made it clear in a speech to about 1,000 cheering supporters tuesday night in chicago that his greek immigrant heritage will provide a key ingredient of his campaign in illinois. the chicago area is among the most ethnically diverse in the nation with its heavy population of first- and second-generation eastern europeans
many of your families, like my parents, came to this land in search of opportunity,'' dukakis told the cheering supporters. ``they didn't have much money in their pockets; they couldn't speak the language, but they believed in the american dream... it was their broad shoulders and strong arms and keen minds that built the mightiest industrial machine in the world.''
it was their hard work that built the steel mills and the auto plants and the foundries and the factories that carried our nation through two world wars,'' dukakis said. the phrases were new to an otherwise standard campaign stump speech
former gov. charles robb was recovering wednesday from what he described as ``a very physical encounter with a glass door.''
robb was knocked unconscious tuesday night when he walked into the closed door in his washington, d.c., office. robb said he ``blacked out for a few moments'' but did not require medical attention
i haven't had a sensation like that since the last time i played in a football game,'' robb said
robb, one of the architects of the super tuesday presidential primaries, said he was talking to a television cameraman as he was leaving his office. ``i had a pretty good head of steam because i had a lot of news interviews scheduled,'' robb said
the door normally is open, he said. the glass did not break
minutes later, robb cut short an appearance on the cable news network. ``i couldn't remember why i was there for a few minutes,'' he said. ``finally, i said on the air that i wouldn't be doing the viewers a service by continuing.''
robb said he was interviewed by other news organizations throughout the night, but he asked that the interviews be kept brief
people kept trying to get me to go to the hospital, but i was hard-headed,'' he said
the people's consultative assembly gathers thursday to elect president suharto, the only candidate, to his fifth five-year term
the 1,000-member assembly, which meets every five years, began a session last week to choose the president and vice president and issue new guidelines for state policy
suharto has led the nation of 170 million people since 1967
for vice president, the moslem united development party has nominated its chairman, jailani naro, to run against state secretary sudharmono, chairman of the governing golkar party and suharto's most trusted aide. the vice president is to be elected on friday
naro said that despite advice from several senior assembly members to drop his candidacy, it was his democratic right to run for election and ``we will fight 'til the end.''
sudharmono was nominated by golkar and supported by the military, provincial and indonesian democratic party factions in the assembly
all five factions, including the moslem united development party, nominated suharto for president
the five factions also approved suharto's 35-page report on the state of the nation under his administration in the last five years
in his report last week, suharto said his administration had been able to overcome unpredictable challenges and difficulties, including a recession and a sharp drop in the price of oil, a major foreign exchange earner for indonesia
he said indonesia's economy was expected to grow by an annual average of 3.6 percent during the five-year economic period ending in march 1989. the original target had been 5 percent
in elections last april, golkar won 299 seats in parliament, which also has 100 government-nominated members from the military. the moslem united development party has 63 seats and the indonesian democratic party 38 seats
the 500-member parliament and 500 provincial and district officials make up the people's consultative assembly, the highest policy-making body in the country
seats in provincial and district legislatures were decided by proportional representation based on the total votes each party received
in the assembly, golkar has 548 seats as well as 151 government-nominated members from the military and 147 from the provinces. the moslem united development party has 93 and the indonesian democratic party 61
hawaii's democratic caucuses came down to a test of strength between party leaders' support for michael dukakis and grassroots organizing by followers of jesse jackson. the massachusetts governor won, but jackson performed impressively
dukakis received 2,026 votes in the presidential preference poll, compared with jackson's 1,470 votes, according to incomplete returns wednesday
this is the first time we've really had a race,'' said gov. john waihee, a dukakis supporter. ``i don't ever remember this much excitement.''
dukakis was expected to get 12 of the 20 pledged delegates that were up for grabs, with jackson getting the rest
it's incredible,'' said jackson's state coordinator richard port. ``jackson showed his appeal to hawaii's multi-cultural voters. that's the real story here.''
much of jackson's support was thought to have come from the 2,000 new party members his organization signed in recent months
missouri rep. richard gephardt received 83 votes, illinois sen. paul simon 46, tennessee sen. albert gore jr. 41, and former colorado sen. gary hart 83. there were 183 votes for ``uncommitted.''
a sick and hungry panda cub that a farmer found tangled in tree branches has bounced back to health, boosting efforts to save the increasingly scarce animal, it was reported wednesday
cun cun _ or ``spring spring'' _ was found in the mountains of tianquan county in sichuan province and rushed to a zoo in the sichuan capital of chengdu, the china news service said
when this panda arrived at the zoo, he was in very bad shape. he had contracted an intestinal virus, was severely dehydrated and very weak,'' a zoo official was quoted as saying
the giant panda, native only to china, has become an endangered species. the number in china has dropped below 1,000 and scientists have had limited success breeding them in captivity
about 200 pandas are in chinese zoos, but some experts have called for a halt their capture, arguing that they live longer and reproduce better in the wild
truckloads of police and cars with wailing sirens patrolled the tibetan capital of lhasa through the night in an apparent show of force after an anti-chinese uprising by thousands of tibetans, a western source said wednesday
the westerner, a tourist who reached chengdu from lhasa, said the trucks drove past the lhasa hotel where he was staying after midnight
a tibetan source in lhasa reported similar police movement both day and night since the saturday uprising, in which buddhist monks and thousands of tibetans stoned police and built bonfires across the city
asked if she was frightened, the source said, ``no, i'm not frightened because _ ,'' but the telephone line was broken in midsentence
the panchen lama, tibetan buddhism's second-highest leader, denounced those who participated in the all-day violence
i represent the tibetan comrades here and myself in expressing my indignation ... at the violence committed by the small numbers of separatists during the riot,'' the panchen lama, a loyal supporter of the beijing government, said at a special meeting of tibetan leaders in beijing on wednesday
the panchen lama called for severe punishment for the rioters, saying, ``as a tibetan and a devout buddhist, i cannot condone this kind of crime.''
the evening news devoted nearly five minutes to the panchen lama's remarks and briefly showed footage of saturday's rioting
doje cering, chairman of tibet's regional government, said official policy toward tibet would not change because of the rioting, the official xinhua news agency reported
lhasa tv said one tibetan and a chinese policeman were killed, but western sources in lhasa said as many as five tibetans and three police may have died
western tourists arriving in katmandu, nepal, on wednesday reported seeing five people dead, including a 10-year-old tibetan monk, two tibetans and two chinese
the western tourist in chengdu, in southwestern china, reported being allowed to visit sera monastery on the southern edge of the city, one of lhasa's leading monasteries
speaking on condition of anonymity, he said a truck carrying about 20 armed police was parked along the road to the monastery and two police officers watched the entrance
by contrast, sera and other leading monasteries were cut off by police blockades after the last tibetan protest against chinese rule on oct. 1. at least 14 people died then
china sent troops into tibet in 1950, but it has claimed sovereignty over the himalayan region since the 13th century
many tibetans maintain they were effectively independent for centuries under the dalai lama, their temporal and religious leader. the current dalai lama fled to india in 1959 after an abortive anti-chinese uprising
thursday is the 29th anniversary of the uprising
there were unconfirmed reports from lhasa of widespread arrests in the city. officials released no figures, however
the western source said police set up two checkpoints along the road from the lhasa airport to the city and were stopping vehicles and asking passengers to get out for a check of their identity
saturday's violence was followed by a small confrontation sunday in which tibetans built barricades and threw stones at police in lhasa's central market square
saturday was the final day of the ``moinlam qenmo'' prayer festival, a more than 500-year-old annual event that is one of the most important in the tibetan buddhist calender
chinese authorities had feared pro-independence tibetans would take advantage of the gathering of hundreds of monks and pilgrims to stage a protest
one source said chinese police in tibet were put on orders during the festival to exercise restraint. the source said tibet's communist party secretary wu jinghua ordered police to retreat from any confrontation. reports from several western sources indicated police initially did so, then fired tear gas to control the crowd
xinhua reported earlier that no police officers carried arms while on duty saturday
one western source reported gunshots being fired after nightfall saturday after more than 12 hours of violence. none of the western witnesses reported seeing police open fire
in the next few weeks, al gore needs to prove what mike dukakis demonstrated on super tuesday _ that he can win outside his home region, that he's not just another favorite son
and now dukakis has something new to prove _ that he can win primary after primary across the country, become the front-runner and build the momentum to clinch the democratic nomination before the convention opens in august
no one is conceding an inch to the massachusetts governor, who now sports a lead in delegates and wins in the mega-states of florida and texas on tuesday
the calendar should now give dukakis a little edge, shifting from the southern accents of super tuesday to some of the nation's toughest political battlegrounds _ the big industrial states of illinois, michigan, wisconsin, new york and pennsylvania
as the governor of a major northeastern industrial state with a strong ethnic background, dukakis should have less trouble speaking the voters' language in the upcoming states than he did in the south
gore has exactly the opposite problem _ he just had the contests in his best region and is now moving to less familiar ground
what state is al gore going to win in the north?'' is how dukakis aide leslie dach posed the problem
the tennessee senator and jesse jackson each won a goodly share of the states and the delegates available tuesday, splintering the standings among the democratic hopefuls with dukakis
that proved both are winners, essential to continuing in the race, even though the victories were on home turf
but dukakis proved more _ he won at home but also in the south, a region critical to the democrats' hopes of regaining the white house. he showed he could win in a variety of regions of the country _ from texas to washington
one big advantage dukakis now has is his bank account
we've got $2 million in the bank and $1 million more coming in federal matching money,'' dach said wednesday
that, plus a well-regarded campaign organization, is a major advantage in big states where television advertising is expensive
organization will be an asset in the major behind-the-scenes battle over the next two months that could be the key to the nomination. dukakis is working hard to convince the 645 super-delegates _ governors, members of congress, senators and democratic national committee members _ that he will be the nominee and that they should join his effort
in contrast, gore had to borrow a $1 million to finish his southern media advertising. but gore said he has $500,000 to $1 million on hand to fight on
gore's campaign has had its share of organizational problems over the past few months, as it struggled, for example, with the question of how much effort to put into the new hampshire primary
the next battleground is illinois with two favorite sons on the ballot _ jackson and sen. paul simon
simon, saying no candidate will have enough delegates to win going into the democratic convention in august, hopes to restart his stalled campaign with a homestate victory next tuesday. but even he concedes that is not enough
nobody's going to have that first-ballot nomination,'' simon said wednesday. ``but i also have to win in wisconsin or ohio or pennsylvania or new york.''
dukakis was already in chicago on tuesday night, working for a good showing
gore said wednesday, ``we're going to be competing vigorously there.''
the big loser among the democrats on tuesday will not even be in illinois. rep. richard gephardt could could only manage a super tuesday win in his home state of missouri. he is heading to michigan for the march 26 caucuses there
illinois could turn out to be a crucial state for the democrats _ just as it may be for the republicans
if neither simon nor jackson wins at home, the candidate who does win would get an enormous boost. and simon's hopes would dwindle away
in contrast, a favorite-son victory would not be an equally important boost for the victor, since such wins tend to be expected
editors' note: evans witt is a washington-based political writer who has written about each presidential election since 1976
the growing number of private businesses spawned by mikhail s. gorbachev's economic reforms may soon face an enemy long familiar to their capitalist counterparts: higher taxes
the draft of a new law on private enterprises, published in the government newspaper izvestia, outlines plans to tax the profits of the new ventures as well as the incomes of their workers
while the law remains in draft form, it is likely to earn approval from the nation's nominal parliament, the supreme soviet, at its next session expected in late spring
gorbachev last week cited the taxation plan in an apparent effort to assure workers in state-run businesses that they should not feel their private counterparts are getting off easy
it's understood that we need industrious and honest initiative, but not of the kind of some cooperatives which exploit a deficit and engage in outright money-grabbing,'' the soviet leader told workers at a moscow factory
many cooperatives charge higher prices than state-run industries and services, and complaints about this have appeared in the soviet press. many soviets say, for instance, that while food quality and selection are better in cooperative restaurants, the prices are out of their reach
the government, while proposing broader opportunities for cooperatives, also apparently felt the need to tap the businesses' wealth, calling this approach ``social fairness.''
the law does not specify at what rate cooperatives will be taxed, saying this will depend on the kind of business. it said the tax rate will be fixed for five-year periods. cooperatives can deduct from their taxes contributions to charities, and the government may give some businesses tax breaks for producing certain high-demand items, according to the law
personal income taxes will be progressive, the law said. currently, a social security tax is deducted from the pay of workers in state-run enterprises
the law on private business that took effect may 1 already provided for a heavy individual tax structure that gave the government claim to 70 percent of incomes in excess of 600 rubles, or $1,000, per month
president reagan said today he sees ``a will to succeed evident in our land'' reminiscent of the spirit of legendary football coach knute rockne, who led notre dame to five undefeated seasons
reagan, unveiling a commemorative stamp to mark the 100th anniversary of rockne's birth, reminisced both about rockne's storied career and his own role in hollywood's portrayal of it
and the president used the occasion to predict a rosy future for u.s. business
american industry is lean and mean and ready to meet the competition head-on,'' he said. ``i predict that, as this year progresses, we will see american manufacturing re-emerge as the leading force in the world marketplace. exports will, in fact, race ahead and lead our domestic economy.''
reagan said the rockne legend ``stood for fair play and honor, but you know, it was thorougly american in another way. it was practical; it placed a value on devastating quickness and agility and on confounding the opposition with good old american cleverness. but most of all, the rockne legend meant this ... that on or off the field, it is faith that makes the difference, it is faith that makes great things happen.''
reagan said rockne recognized ``the fundamental element of the american character that no tyranny and few of our competitors can ever hope to match. knute rockne knew and appreciated it: the creative genius and omnipresent optimism of our people.''
reagan also reminisced about his own heyday in hollywood, when he convinced a producer to allow him to play the part of george gipp in the movie ``knute rockne: all american.'' gipp was the notre dame football player whose deathbed request to rockne _ ``win just one for the gipper'' _ inspired the team to a 12-6 victory over army in 1928
reagan called the part ``a young actor's dream'' and he said the movie still has a message for americans:
there's a will to succeed evident in our land. i happen to have always believed in the american people. don't ever sell them short. given the proper tools and a level playing ground, our workers can out-produce and out-compete anyone, anywhere.''
he added that ``there are those who see a dark side to our technological progress'' with the development of more deadly weapons
however, the president said, ``technology is pointing a way out of this dilemma'' and cited his ``star wars'' space-based missile defense system
the crowd in joyce athletic center was treated to several minutes of the rockne film on a giant screen showing the young reagan as he portrayed gipp throwing the ball and hustling with his teammates
at the end of reagan's speech, he was handed a football which he hurled toward a group of players seated in the crowd. heisman trophy winner tim brown caught the pigskin as the crowd roared its approval
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said ``the gipper goes back'' as he announced the trip. during his presidency, reagan's supporters have seized upon his movie-inspired nickname to help build support for his political programs
the president himself recalled the emotional movie during his first visit to notre dame's south bend campus, when he delivered the commencement address on may 17, 1981
rockne, a graduate of the men's college, was its head football coach from 1918 to 1931 and compiled a record of 108 wins, 12 defeats and five ties. during his tenure, the ``fighting irish'' were undefeated in five seasons and won six national championships
an innovator of the forward pass and the ``box formation,'' rockne taught his players to excel in the classroom as well as the playing field
rockne was killed in a plane crash on march 31, 1931, an accident that stunned the nation. his funeral mass was broadcast across the nation on radio
he won a place in the college football hall of fame's first group of inductees in 1951
the 22-cent stamp produced in his honor bears a portrait of the smiling, balding coach holding a football. rockne's name is emblazoned in blue and gold, the colors of the ``fighting irish.''
it is the sixth in the american sports series, which has honored babe didrikson zaharias, bobby jones, babe ruth, jim thorpe and roberto clemente
the stamp was a joint effort of designer peter cocci and engraver tom hipschen, both of the bureau of engraving and printing, the white house said
the new stamp goes on sale nationally tomorrow
queen mother elizabeth has expressed dismay at the closure of a welsh geriatric ward she officially opened less than a year ago, her office said wednesday
it said the 87-year-old mother of queen elizabeth ii, the reigning monarch, was expected to write to the government querying the cost-cutting closure at st. tydfil's hospital in merthyr tydfil
the merthyr and cynon valley health council said the comptroller at clarence house, the queen mother's official residence, had written to say she heard of the closure ``with much distress.''
she visited merthyr tydfil last april to reopen the refurbished hospital, including a six-bed dependency ward that was closed eight months later as part of a budget-cutting program
health council secretary bryn williams said his staff was ``delighted that the queen mother should feel so strongly about the closure. it shows there is a genuine concern among royalty.''
larry king, whose interest in politics produced the long-running ``best little whorehouse in texas,'' has turned to louisiana and ``the kingfish.''
the show loosely based on huey p. long's term as governor, opens thursday in thibodaux, a cajun town of 17,500 people
king, who wrote ``whorehouse'' with peter masterson, collaborated with former texas legislator ben grant on ``the kingfish.'' it incorporates many of long's speeches and a slideshow which lets the audience see how much comedian john mcconnell resembles the man whose part he plays
the play is to remain at the thibodaux civic center through sunday, then move to in winnfield, long's home town, as the start of a statewide tour
three cuddly koalas upstaged joan rivers, showing that star power is no match for outback charm
miss rivers shared a flight from san diego with the koalas when they arrived tuesday en route to metrozoo. she graciously accepted second billing
they were terrific,'' said the comedian, who was on her way to san juan, puerto rico. ``they didn't eat, they didn't smoke and they didn't smell.''
miss rivers walked all but unnoticed through a crowd of metrozoo volunteers, onlookers, reporters and photographers intent on getting a glimpse of the furry creatures
all most got was a view of three animal carrying cases. the koalas were described as ``stressed out'' after their early morning flight
eddie ``the eagle'' edwards, the myopic, bespectacled ski jump star of the winter olympics, has recovered the lucky pair of skis that launched him to fame
the unlikely hero of the british team, who won international recognition when he finished last in the 90-meter and 70-meter jumps in calgary, disclosed wednesday he mislaid his favorite pair of skis after his final jump at the games, and has only just found them
edwards said a ski company had picked up the skis and taken them back to west germany. he said he hoped they would be forwarded to finland in time for a weekend meet there
i am taking up a spare pair just in case,'' edwards said
he also said he wanted to to get down to serious business after all the ballyhoo in calgary
it will be nice to get back to my sport. i have enjoyed the promotion work but i haven't had much sleep over the past couple of days.''
edwards said his new-found fame could pose problems
his family, he said, is ``enjoying it at the moment but i think there will come a time when they find it tiring. and it's worse for my girlfriend, but we are just going to have to see how things go.''
the socialist workers party announced wednesday that its candidate for president will be james macwarren, 36, a black rights activist from jersey city, n.j
the party's vice presidential candidate will be kathy mickells, 37, a coal miner from westover, w.va
the candidates were chosen by the 70-member socialist workers national committee, said nancy rosenstock, speaking for the party
the party has fielded a presidential ticket for 40 years and in recent elections has been on the ballot in about 20 states. it pulled about 25,000 votes nationally in 1984
a party statement said the candidates will oppose use of american military power in central america and the persian gulf and seek to unify working people to meet a coming economic and social crisis signaled by the october stock market plunge
louisiana's super tuesday primaries won by george bush and jesse jackson drew mixed reviews wednesday from state republican and democratic leaders
we think super tuesday was wonderful,'' said carolyn blue-mikell, a spokeswoman for state democrats. ``there was much, much more attention paid to the voters, particularly here in louisiana.''
in 1984, the democratic candidates virtually ignored the state, while in the months leading up to tuesday's voting, the top hopefuls came to louisiana more than 100 times, she said
but state gop chairman donald bollinger questioned whether the big event would be repeated
the democrats thought they'd come out of the south with a conservative democrat that would make the republicans look silly. where's their conservative?'' he said. ``i think in four years, they won't want another super tuesday.''
with reports in from 99 percent of the precincts, bush had 83,585 votes, or 58 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 26,227, or 18 percent; kansas sen. bob dole tallied 25,602, or 18 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp had 7,818, or 5 percent
jackson had 219,960 votes, or 35 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 174,458, or 28 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 95,310, or 15 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt tallied 66,894, or 11 percent
the results translated into 32 delegates for jackson, 23 for gore, six for dukakis and two for gephardt. on the republican side, bush nabbed 34 delegates with 7 uncommitted
jackson, who aimed at expanding his ``rainbow coalition'' of support across racial and ethnic lines, captured his second straight victory in the louisiana democratic primary
we think he's been able to take his message to the people of louisiana,'' said new orleans mayor sidney barthelemy, a key jackson supporter. ``his base of support has grown.''
but bud courson, gore's state coordinator, said that jackson should be worried about the tennessee lawmaker's performance
we feel that a turnaround has come, and again looking further down the road we feel that sen. gore can pull the democratic party back together,'' said courson
in the 4th congressional district race to replace gov.-elect buddy roemer in the u.s. house, former roemer aide jim mccrery, a republican, and democratic state sen. foster campbell claimed spots in an april 16 runoff
roemer gave his backing to stan tiner, former editor of the shreveport journal, who finished third
a bid to forge a united opposition to the government of president roh tae-woo collapsed wednesday, with one faction accusing the other of sacrificing unity for power
kim dae-jung, head of the party for peace and democracy, told a news conference a merger with the rival reunification democratic party wasn't possible in time for the general assembly elections, expected to be held in april
kim said he would not follow the lead of his counterpart, former reunification democratic party chief kim young-sam, and step down from his party's leadership
the (reunification democratic party) made unreasonable demands, including my resignation,'' he said
opposition supporters split ranks last year when both kims ran for president, dividing the anti-government vote and allowing roh to win the presidency without a plurality
since then, public pressure has been on both to step down. kim young-sam resigned from his party's leadership in february. the resignation of both were seen as the key to merging the parties
kim dae-jung vowed to continue wednesday as supporters shouted ``no resignation!'' but he offered a compromise, saying that the parties should jointly support national assembly candidates as an interim measure
the reunification democratic party rejected the proposal, saying a merger is possible only if kim dae-jung resigns
this is a real betrayal of the people and democratic forces. at this point, the only and largest obstacle to reunification is kim dae-jung,'' the reunification democratic party said in a statement following kim dae-jung's news conference
kim dae-jung formed his party just prior to the presidential elections when he and his supporters bolted from the larger reunification democratic party
at stake in the elections are 299 seats. under a law adopted tuesday, 224 lawmakers must be picked in as many districts by popular vote and 75 others under a proportional representation system based on the total votes each party gets
roh was elected on dec. 16 in the first direct presidential elections in korea in 16 years
more than 250,000 people chanting ``rajiv must go!'' crowded outside parliament house on wednesday and demanded the resignation of prime minister rajiv gandhi and midterm parliamentary elections
the rally and a day-long strike in the indian capital were sponsored by the right-wing bharatiya janata party and the lok dal, a rural-based party
most shops in new delhi were closed, but government offices, banks and schools remained open. traffic was normal
the capital's 35,000-strong police force and another 5,000 paramilitary troops were deployed to maintain peace. police spokesman ravi pawar said no violence was reported
police said at least 250,000 people gathered for the rally. organizers claimed there were more than 500,000 participants
this mammoth gathering ... declares the congress (party) government at the center to be anti-laborers, anti-farmers and anti-rural,'' said a resolution adopted at the rally. both parties called upon opposition groups to unite and form a government in the next general elections
gandhi's congress party also faces a rally and strike sponsored by two communist parties and leftist opposition groups on march 15
the next general elections are not due until december 1989, although gandhi could call them earlier. gandhi's party holds 410 of the 544 seats in the governing lower house of parliament
the opposition has blamed gandhi's adminstration for failing to control inflation and impose law and order in northern punjab state, where at least 400 people have died this year in violent attacks by sikh separatists
gandhi's government also has been accused of corruption in its arms purchases from foreign companies
