workers at the disneyland hotel are now subject to a 31-year-old dress code established for employees at the amusement park across the street
facial hair is a no-no, so even the late walt disney would have had to shave his mustache to work at the hotel recently acquired by disney co
six of the seven dwarfs, uncle remus, captain hook and pinocchio toymaker gepetto would all be renegades working in the real-life world of disney
and men aren't the only ones bound to conform with the company's desire for a uniform ``wholesome'' look among employees
women will have to abandon slacks, heavy makeup, gaudy jewelry and wild hairdos. men will have to get haircuts, shave, and cover any tattoos

when disney co. assumed control of the hotel, its 1,600 employees fell under the dress code established for the magic kingdom in 1957. workers who rebel will be terminated
the reason that we are doing this is because the disneyland hotel is becoming part of disneyland attractions, and we have an appearance standard. ... it is associated with disney and is expected by our guests,'' said disneyland spokesman bob roth
disney officials are explaining the dress code to employees this week, with compliance expected virtually immediately
but some hotel employees said they'll rebel, including engineer mike searles, 40, who wears a handlebar mustache. ``i don't think it's right, and i'm not going to compromise,'' he said
high school students cooked up what they hope was the world's largest burrito to feed some of the city's needy and maybe earn a spot in the guinness book of world records
creating the 1,492-foot mexican specialty consumed 1,200 tortillas, 461 pounds of meat, 3,400 olives, 32 pounds of tomatoes, 14 pounds of onions, and 71 pounds each of salsa, sour cream and lettuce, said betty swan, cafeteria manager at lincoln high school
it took 400 students all of tuesday morning to put together the big burrito, she said
two members of the portland school board measured the burrito as it wound around the school's gym. ``i consider this a very solemn responsibility,'' said steve griffth, one of the board members
after the burrito was measured, it was divided among representatives of various social service agencies to be given to their clients
afghanistan on wednesday rejected a u.s. demand that the soviet union halt military aid to the afghan government as soon as the united states stops aiding the moslem insurgency
the dispute could become a major snag in u.n.-sponsored talks aimed at ending nine years of fighting in afghanistan and securing the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 soviet troops
foreign minister abdul wakil of afghanistan flatly opposed the u.s. position, explained at a state department briefing friday, that there must be a ``symmetrical cessation'' of u.s. and soviet military aid
wakil said at a news conference that soviet assistance could not be compared to western aid to ``terrorist groups.''
he said afghanistan had received soviet assistance for ``68 years'' and would continue to do so ``even after the withdrawal of soviet troops.'' but he did not specify what kind of soviet aid afghanistan expected to receive
soviet troops entered afghanistan in december 1979 and are helping the marxist government battle the moslem resistance
the united states is the main supplier of arms to the guerrillas. aid reportedly totaled about $700 million in 1987, including the shoulder-fired ground-to-air stinger missiles said to have downed at least 200 soviet and afghan aircraft
wakil said the u.s. demand was bringing a new issue into the talks. he said another was pakistan's attempt to link a geneva settlement to the formation of a broad-based transitional government replacing the present soviet-backed one in kabul, the afghan capital
he said there had been no important developments in the talks since ``concessions'' by moscow and kabul led to an agreement friday on the timetable and logistics of a soviet withdrawal. u.n. mediator diego cordovez said this completed the main elements of a settlement
wakil accused pakistan of ``trying to kill time'' and maneuvering to ``push the geneva negotiations toward a stalemate'' by holding out for an interim government. he said the chief pakistani representative, acting foreign minister zain noorani, had returned ``empty-handed'' from weekend consultations in islamabad with the country's opposition leaders
noorani said early last week that pakistan would decide after those consultations whether it was prepared to sign a settlement with the afghan government under president najib, which it does not recognize
wakil, speaking as the latest round of the nearly 6-year-old talks entered its second week, said the afghan government would continue to push for a speedy settlement. he also stressed that his country was not setting a deadline after which it would leave geneva
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev said last month moscow would bring home its troops starting may 15 if the settlement was signed by march 15. wakil said the start of the withdrawal depended on the date of the signing and suggested the 60-day time span would be retained
the navy on wednesday defended the pentagon's planned seawolf submarine, promising congress that the latest generation of attack subs would maintain u.s. undersea superiority far into the 21st century
vice adm. bruce demars, assistant chief of naval operations for undersea warfare, said the ssn-21 seawolf will have double the fire power and be faster, quieter and more survivable than the ssn-688 los angeles class sub, which the seawolf is expected to replace as the nation's chief attack submarine
the ssn-21 seawolf, which has been in the research and design stage for six years, has been criticized by some lawmakers who fear the sub is not advanced enough for the soviet's planned successor to their akula attack sub
but demars dismissed that notion, telling the house armed services sea power subcommittee that the seawolf is ``the foundation for far-term submarine superiority.''
repeated, objective analyses have concluded that seawolf and her sister ships will have three times the mission effectiveness of the improved ssn-688 and will restore the commanding technological and tactical margin which historically we have enjoyed over the soviets,'' demars said
last year, a house subcommittee tried to delay funds for the project, but congress restored the money. navy officials have warned that such a delay could severely damage the seawolf program and cause massive cost overruns
demars said the project now is on schedule and on budget
general dynamics corp.'s electric boat division and the newport news (va.) shipbuilding and drydock co., rival sub makers who traditionally have split scan-688 contracts, have been researching and designing the seawolf for the navy
peter yeo, an aide to rep. sam gejdenson, d-conn., whose district includes the electric boat shipyard at groton, conn., said seawolf proponents do not expect intense opposition again this year
opponents ``made their case last year and it didn't fly,'' yeo said
the first ssn-21 contract is expected to be awarded later this year, demars said. delivery is planned for late 1994
the first seawolf will cost $1.6 billion, and following subs will be about $1 billion, the navy estimates
demars said the seawolf costs about 25 percent more than the ssn-688, but predicted it would only be about 10 percent more over its 30-year life span because it has much lower operating and support costs
demars dismissed suggestions that the ssn-688 could be improved significantly. he said since the program began in 1976, the navy has ordered 4,600 improvements, and there is simply no more room left on the sub for new systems
he said a lack of room on the new ssn-688s has forced the navy to put bunks in the torpedo room and line some floors with canned goods
suggestions that the sub could be modified further are made by ``people who have obviously never been on these subs,'' demars said
meanwhile, demars dismissed a scenario posed rep. charles e. bennett, d-fla., chairman of the subcommittee, under which funds for a trident submarine would be delayed for a year and the savings would go towards building more ships
to delay the trident, which is our most survivable sub and best deterrent, would be the wrong signal to send to both the country and the soviets,'' demars said
the tridents, which carry long-range nuclear missiles, are made by electric boat. the government orders one a year
writers and editors of a dissident publication met the ambassador to afghanistan on wednesday to protest the jailing of a french journalist in afghanistan on spying charges, one of the dissidents said
alexander podrabinek, chief editor of the weekly express-chronicle said in an interview with the associated press that ambassador mohammadulah subhani safi met with six writers and editors for about 30 minutes
the dissidents were protesting the conviction of french journalist alain guillo, who on jan. 4 was sentenced in kabul to 10 years in prison
reading from a copy of the statement handed to the ambassador, podrabinek said, ``incarceration for fulfilling his (guillo's) journalistic duty is possible only in a barbaric country that does not value citizens' or human rights.''
the group demanded the release of guillo, 45, and said afghan authorities should allow him to leave the country
the ambassador accepted the group's statement but told its members their reliance on western media reports was giving them an inaccurate picture of the situation in afghanistan, podrabinek said
guillo, a filmmaker, was captured sept. 12, 1987, after he entered afghanistan with guerrillas of the afghan national front
state-run kabul radio said in announcing the sentence that guillo had entered afghanistan nine times since 1980 ``to prepare video films and cassettes, to carry out spying activities and to stengthen relations with armed opposition groups.'' trade</head>
rep. richard gephardt on wednesday acknowledged his dismal super tuesday showing but insisted ``the race is still on'' as he attacked two of his democratic presidential rivals on the trade issue central to his campaign
standing outside a textile mill threatened with closure, gephardt said of massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and sen. albert gore jr. of tennesse, ``the bottom line is are they really for new policies.''
the fact is that gov. dukakis and sen. gore talk tough about trade,'' gephardt said, but they don't support policies that would reduce the nation's trade deficit
aides said gephardt's comments were a signal that he's sticking with trade as the central theme of his campaign
in the super tuesday polling, gephardt won only his home state of missouri. dukakis, gore and jesse jackson shared the spoils in the other super tuesday contests
still, gephardt vowed to stay in the race until the democratic national convention in july, and said he had enough money to do just that
the race is on,'' gephardt said. ``i'm not where i'd like to be but i think i have ample opportunity to make up lost ground and get back in the middle of this race and to win.''
mike nelson, a gephardt aide, said campaign is less than $100,000 in debt. ``our fund-raising has not let up at any of the dry points in the campaign,'' he said
we did not borrow, as others did, to run on super tuesday,'' gephardt said. ``maybe in retrospect we should have.''
gephardt made his comments at the first of a series of stops in south carolina, where he was campaigning for that state's caucuses on saturday. deputy campaign manager joe trippi said gephardt hopes for a second place showing behind jackson, who was born in south carolina
gephardt planned a farm rally later in the day before flying to michigan and illinois on thursday
illinois holds its primary tuesday, and the michigan democratic caucuses are march 26
but gephardt's aides said the results in illinois will be muddled because of two favorite sons, sen. paul simon and jackson. as a result, gephardt has characterized the michigan contest as the next major democratic showdown
he challenged gore to a contest outside his rival's native south
sen. gore has to show he can win outside of his region,'' gephardt said. ``he's going to have to go and show he can do well in illinois and michigan and the other states in the north and northeast
obviously it is clear i need to do well in michigan,'' gephardt said. ``when i get my message out to the voter i win.''
the missouri congressmen blamed his fourth place super tuesday showing on a lack of money. gephardt said he was only able to spend $1 million on television, less than one-third of what was spent by his rivals
voters, he said, ``didn't hear what i had to say. that was the problem.''
the cutting question is can i get my message to the voters.''
the textile plant where gephardt spoke employs about 500 people, and officials there said as many as 420 of those jobs could be lost by next month
plant manager harold simmons cited foreign competition and the depressed local economy as reasons for the potential closure
pat robertson won round 1, but republican leaders cautioned wednesday that the results of precinct caucuses could change at county-level meetings and the state convention
grassroots organizing in washington helped the former television evangelist prevent vice president george bush from repeating here the victories he recorded in the 16 states holding gop primaries on super tuesday
a sample of precincts taken by the democrats showed massachusetts gov. michael dukakis with a slight lead over jesse jackson, 40 percent to 38 percent
with 71 percent of the state's gop precinct caucuses reporting, robertson led the republicans with 39 percent, kansas sen. bob dole had 26 percent and bush was third with 24 percent
but ``no candidate won a clear majority of delegates statewide,'' noted john meyers, executive director of the state republican party. ``this is a three-tiered system, and super tuesday was just the first step
now some coalitions will form. people have to start coming together to get votes for the next two steps. nobody has 50 percent of the votes by themselves,'' he said
state democratic chair karen marchioro was blunter, saying she would be ``very surprised if robertson came out of this state with any delegates.''
but if the proportions held during the later steps of delegate selection, robertson would get 16 delegates, dole 11, bush 10, kemp 3 and one delegate would attend the national convention uncommitted
of jackson's surprisingly strong showing behind dukakis, marchioro said, ``obviously, it's an organizational effort ... i think also that people like his message _ and that's everywhere in the state.''
official returns for the democrats won't be known until next week, after precinct leaders mail in their results. debt</head>
vice chairman manuel h. johnson of the federal reserve board told congressmen wednesday he opposes their plan for an international body to lift some of the debt burden from third world countries
he praised mexico's effort to exchange old debt for new bonds, saying it was based on the market and gave creditor banks a chance to adjust their holdings. critics have called the results disappointing
the mexican plan has resulted in a reduction of mexico's debt by $1.1 billion, said rodney wagner, vice chairman of the credit poliy committee at morgan guaranty bank. his bank sponsored the plan
mexico's debt is estimated at over $100 billion. total third world debt is expected to reach $1.45 trillion by the end of this year
johnson was sharply challenged by both democrats and republicans on the house banking committee. two of its subcommittees sponsored wednesday's hearing
rep. bruce a. morrison, d-conn., told johnson to ``stop setting up straw men and start working with us.'' rep. jim bunning, r-ky., asked how johnson could say that the debt situation has improved when the price of third world debt has been dropping on the world market
bunning cited quotations that indicated mexico's debt was selling at 57 to 60 cents on the dollar last may and 48 to 52 cents in november
johnson replied that the market is thin, easily influenced by relatively small deals. he said he expects it to turn upwards as a result of willingness by brazil and argentina to come to agreements with the international monetary fund. with mexico, they are the biggest third world debtors
bunning told morrison he does not believe that putting public money into a new international institution would solve the debt problem, and that public money is already going into the third world through the fund and the world bank. they are owned by 151 governments
morrison was influential in getting a plan for a new world body into the trade bill passed by the house. the proposed institution would buy up third world debt and package it for resale, giving debtor countries at least some of the benefit of the discount
police on wednesday identified a murder victim whose dismembered body was found in a freezer as a woman with a record of prostitution arrests
the body of kimberly hanlon, 30, a native of east liverpool, ohio, was discovered sunday by two teen-agers, police said. it was not known when she died, said detective maj. tom depolis
identification was made tuesday afternoon based on fingerprints from the woman's arrest record, which included several prostitution-related charges, depolis said. the last arrest was in august 1983, he said
ms. hanlon was last seen alive in early 1984 by a sister who lives in north tampa, depolis said. the sister told police she reported ms. hanlon missing in april 1984, depolis said, but police have been unable to find such a report
depolis said ms. hanlon was dead when her body was dismembered and placed in the freezer at the home of james warren bailey, who has been charged by police with first-degree murder. assistant state attorney michael benito said the state will seek a murder indictment when the grand jury meets next week
bailey was being held in the hillsborough county jail without bond
homicide capt. buzz sawyer said police don't know exactly when the woman was killed, but it apparently was between early 1984 and mid-1985, when james jr., 18, son of the suspect, said he first saw the body in the freezer but told no one about it
two teen-agers, the daughter of the suspect and a son of the suspect's girlfriend, ignored admonishments to stay away from the locked freezer on their back porch and pried it open sunday. they notified police
depolis said the cause of ms. hanlon's death was being withheld because of the investigation
while bailey remains the prime suspect, depolis said, ``we're not positive who caused her death.''
a man has been charged with criminally negligent homicide after he allegedly suffered a seizure while driving and struck and killed a pedestrian
bevis b. barker, 30, of albany, pleaded innocent tuesday to charges of criminally negligent homicide and offering a false instrument for filing. he was being held in lieu $25,000 bail
barker allegedly suffered an epileptic seizure and lost control of his car dec. 7. the car struck and killed 85-year-old christine towle
the seizure resulted from barker's failure to take medication, said chief assistant district attorney daniel dwyer. barker was on the way to a pharmacy to refill his prescription when the accident happened, according to his lawyer, joseph zumbo
dwyer noted that the state's highest court, the court of appeals, has ruled that if someone knows they have a disabling disease and fails to take required medication to control it, ``they are responsible for their actions under the theory of criminal negligence.''
the false instrument charge alleges that barker did not disclose that he has epilepsy when he applied for a driver's license in 1986
president reagan has nominated two air force generals for promotions and new assignments, the pentagon said wednesday
maj. gen. jimmie v. adams has been nominated for a third star and the rank of lieutenant general and elevation to the post of vice commander of the tactical air command, the pentagon said
adams, 51, is a native of prichard, ala., who is currently serving as the commander of tac's 1st air force. he will replace lt. gen. james r. brown, whom the pentagon said wednesday would retire on aug. 1 after more than 34 years of active service
brown, 57, is a native of bozeman, mont., who has served as tac's vice commander since september 1986
the president also nominated maj. gen. monte b. miller to receive his third star and to become the surgeon general of the air force. miller, 57, is a native of independence, mo., who is currently serving as the command surgeon for the u.s. european command
miller will replace lt. gen. murphy a. chesney as the air force's top medical officer
the 60-year-old chesney is retiring on aug. 1 after more than 33 years of active service, the pentagon said. chesney is a native of knoxville, tenn., who has served as surgeon general since august 1985
early models of the baby buddy clip-on pacifier holder are being recalled because of a potential choking hazard, the consumer product safety commission announced wednesday
about 9,000 of the holders were distributed nationwide in 1986 and 1987, officials said. they sold for about $3.95 each
while no injuries have been reported involving the holders, parents were urged to return them to the store where purchased for a free replacement. when tested, the small bear figure separated from the holder and thus could pose a choking hazard, officials said
new model holders can be distinguished by the two round holes in the back of the clip. there are no holes in the clip of the holders being recalled
recalled pacifier holders include those with a pink ribbon and white bear, blue ribbon and bear, yellow ribbon and brown bear, red ribbon and white bear and red ribbon and brown bear
persons needing more information can contact baby buddies inc., 615 jasmine avenue north, suite i, tarpon springs, fla., at 1-813-934-3359 or the safety commission at 1-800-638-2772
the state department expressed grave concern wednesday that northern ethiopia could face widespread starvation because of fighting between government and insurgent forces
spokesman charles redman said insecure conditions along roadways in tigray province caused an 8,000-ton shortfall last month in deliveries of emergency food supplies to the people in that area. the goal was 20,000 tons
we are gravely concerned that expanded fighting will prolong road insecurity, further complicating transportation difficulties and leading to depletion of food stocks and widespread starvation,'' redman said
he attributed the insecure conditions to insurgent activity and the inability by the ethiopian government to control it
we deplore the militarization of roads in northern ethiopia and the politicization of the famine precisely at a time when the people of the area are most vulnerable,'' he said
he said truck convoys are prepared to move when circumstances permit. food airlift operations sponsored by the united nations will continue, he said
tigray province is one of a number of regions in ethiopia facing severe food shortages which were partly caused by a drought last summer
according to u.s. estimates, the lives of between 6.7 million and 7.2 million people are at risk. the u.s. contribution to an international food relief effort is about 267,000 tons of food valued at approximately $108 million
vice president george bush never campaigned in the state, but ``the bush steamroller leveled maryland'' anyway on its way to a 16-state sweep of kansas sen. bob dole in the republican presidential race
in super tuesday's democratic primary, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis exploited a superb organization and the backing of sens. barbara mikulski and paul sarbanes to leave jesse jackson a distant second
sarbanes easily won nomination for a third term with 86 percent of the democratic vote. he will face millionaire republican businessman thomas blair, a newcomer to politics who drew 46 percent of the gop vote
bush's tally of 53 percent or 103,899 votes was stronger than the 48 percent ronald reagan polled in the 1980 gop primary here, when bush had 41 percent, according to republican officials
with all 1,574 precincts reporting, dole finished with 32 percent or 62,721 votes, former tv evangelist pat robertson was third with 12,891 votes or 7 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp tallied 11,581 votes or 7 percent
the bush steamroller leveled maryland like the rest of the south,'' maryland gop executive director nelson warfield said. ``i think bush did a little better than expected. the dole camp had great hopes.''
dukakis took 46 percent of the democratic ballots with 237,389 votes, while jackson had 150,129 votes or 29 percent
the voting was likely to give dukakis 47 delegates and jackson 20 delegates. bush was expected to receive all 41 republican convention delegates
dukakis was the best organized. it was a maryland-oriented campaign that used maryland people to organize maryland,'' said john willis, vice chairman of the maryland democratic party
willis said jackson maintained his base from 1984, improving his showing from 129,387 votes in 1984 to 150,129 votes in 1988
tennessee sen. albert gore, with 45,138 votes or 9 percent, finished third among democrats, followed by missouri rep. richard gephardt, 41,268 votes or 8 percent
aids may be causing an upsurge in tuberculosis in many countries, a world health organization researcher said wednesday
dr. gary slutkin said cases of tuberculosis have increased in regions worst hit by aids, including the united states, where the number of people with tuberculosis rose in 1986 for the first time in modern history
about 1,000 health specialists from 20 countries are attending the three-day first international conference on the global impact of aids. the meeting opened tuesday
slutkin, an epidemiologist with who's global program on aids, said acquired immune deficiency syndrome might trigger symptoms of tuberculosis in people already infected with the lung disease
the aids virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers. it is most often transmitted through sexual contact. other means of transmission include the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles
in normal circumstances, 95 percent of ``people who are infected with the tuberculosis organism will go through life and never come down with tuberculosis,'' the researcher told reporters later
we know that immunosuppression can bring tuberculosis out into overt disease,'' he added
i think we should certainly expect to see increases in the number of cases of tuberculosis in the next five years,'' slutkin said. ``in fact, it's almost certainly already occurring in many countries.''
tuberculosis, or tb, is a contagious airborne infection that mainly attacks the lungs, causing coughs that can produce blood
once a worldwide scourge, tb is now relatively rare in industrialized countries and easily treatable with antibiotics. but the disease, known for centuries, is still rampant in developing regions such as southeast asia and central africa, which are poorly equipped to deal it
slutkin said an estimated 8 million to 10 million new cases of tb occur worldwide each year and about 3 million people die of it
he did not identify all the countries where there has been a rise in aids-related tb. but he said there were many, including the united states and central african nations
but he said there has been no rise in tb in southeast asia, where aids is not yet prevalent
as of feb. 29, the centers for disease control in atlanta had received reports of 54,723 americans with aids, 30,715 of whom had died
slutkin said the number of reported tb cases in the united states rose from 22,201 in 1985 to 22,768 in 1986 for the first increase in u.s. records
he said the largest increases in tb in the united states occurred in new york city, where the rate jumped by 50 percent to about 2,200 between 1981 and 1986. he said there also have been increases in tb rates in 25 states and in washington
he said that in africa, where aids is prevalent, 20 percent to 50 percent of tb patients tested positively for the aids virus. that rate is three to 20 times higher than the rest of the population
asked if tb programs in africa are adequate to cope with a surge in cases due to aids, slutkin said, ``no way.''
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. poured money into a television blitz and won nearly double the number of votes cast for his closest democratic opponent in oklahoma's presidential primary
with all 2,439 precincts reporting, gore had 162,511 votes or 41 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 82,565 votes or 21 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 66,226 votes or 17 percent, and jesse jackson had 52,431 votes or 13 percent
vice president george bush had 78,273 votes or 38 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 72,991 votes or 35 percent; robertson had 44,146 votes or 21 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 11,414 votes or 5 percent
based on those results, gore would win 23 of 46 delegates, gephardt would get 13, dukakis 7, and jackson 3. bush would get 33 of the state's 36 gop delegates, and dole would get the remaining 3
gephardt won the endorsement of three of oklahoma's four democratic congressmen, and was locked in a virtual tie with gore in pre-election polls
but the missouri congressman was outspent 3-1 by gore in oklahoma, with much of the money going for television advertising, said lt. gov. robert s. kerr, gephardt's campaign co-chairman
gore's biggest victory was in the 3rd congressional district, where he campaigned in a stop at muskogee in the final week of the campaign. the nearby town of gore is named for thomas p. gore, a former oklahoma senator who was a distant cousin of the candidate
super tuesday has proven that al gore is the candidate for mainstream democrats,'' said state sen. stratton taylor, co-chairman of the gore drive in oklahoma
bush emphasized his texas oil business background and visited the state a day before the primary. dole made five stops in oklahoma in the final week of the campaign, vising oklahoma city and tulsa twice
the army chief of staff was considering ordering israeli officers to carry weapons at all times following a bus hijacking by terrorists who first overpowered four unarmed officers, it was reported wednesday
in budapest, hungary, a plo official said the bus attack was not aimed at taking hostages but at entering the dimona nuclear facility in israel's negev desert
three israeli civilians were killed in the monday hijacking, which was later claimed by the palestine liberation organization
the three guerrillas were killed when israeli police stormed the bus, which was filled with workers headed to the dimona plant
the military command confirmed that lt. gen. dan shomron, the army chief of staff, was investigating the hijacking, but it refused to provide any details
before commandeering the bus, the guerrillas managed to seize a car containing four unarmed army officers, drive past police setting up a roadblock, keep ahead of a police van during an eight-mile chase, shoot at passing cars and hijack the bus while police looked on helplessly
shomron said monday that if the officers had been armed, they might have prevented the attack. their commander, col. zeev zachrin, sentenced each of the officers to 35 days in jail for ignoring orders to carry their weapons outside the base
the daily davar reported that shomron was considering ordering all officers to carry their weapons at all times anywhere in israel
police minister chaim bar lev defended police conduct in the hijacking. the israeli news agency itim quoted him as saying officers chasing the guerrillas could not fire at will because there were passenger cars on the highway
the daily haaretz said the police, who carried israeli-made uzi submachine guns, were outgunned by the guerrillas who used karl gustav and soviet-designed kalashnikov rifles which have a longer range
the police managed to shoot a hole in the tire of the seized car, haaretz reported. the police parked their van 20 yards away from the abandoned car and rushed for cover while the guerrillas kept firing in all directions
nearby, the driver of a bus carrying workers to the nuclear plant heard the shooting and opened his doors to let the passengers get away. police stopped shooting as the passengers rushed out, haaretz reported
the guerrillas took over the bus, where 11 passengers remained trapped. survivors later testified the guerrillas killed at least two of the hostages. the army is still investigating whether police or guerrillas shot the third victim
hekmat zaid, chief of the plo mission in budapest, told reporters wednesday, ``the aim of the palestinian commando action ... was not to take hostages, the plan of the plo's armed men was to enter the strictly guarded complex by overpowering the bus that carried the workers of the dimona nuclear center.''
zaid said the attack was ``only aimed against workers in a military establishment, an action against the israeli enemy,'' adding ``the fact is israel refuses international supervision over its negev nuclear station.''
we will increase our military action against israel,'' he said. corps; picks up 3rd graf pvs, for years</note>
china has agreed in principle to accept peace corps volunteers, foreign minister wu xueqian said today
in a speech at the national press club, wu said details of the program are still to be worked out, but that ``china has adopted a positive attitude on this matter.''
he called it ``an agreement in principle.''
there was no immediate public comment from the peace corps, the 27-year-old volunteer agency operating grass-roots aid programs in 64 of countries
an agency official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the corps had ``been interested for some time in seeing this. china could benefit from our programs.''
wu's announcement came during a question-answer session after a speech at the national press club. he also welcomed a reagan administration decision to lift sanctions on sales of new high technology to china because it is satisfied that country is not selling silkworm anti-ship missiles to iran
secretary of state george p. shultz informed wu during a meeting tuesday afternoon that the restrictions would no longer apply
for years, the united states has continuously increased the types of high technology products china could purchase from american companies. to protest the missile sales, however, the administration froze that process last autumn
we are encouraged by chinese statements and actions regarding iran's acquisition of chinese anti-ship missiles, silkworms,'' state department spokesman charles e. redman said
we have therefore decided to resume the export control liberalization process for china,'' he said
during a 40-minute meeting with president reagan on tuesday, wu also said his country would not stand in the way of a united nations resolution calling for an arms embargo against iran, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said
the united states has been trying for months to line up support on the u.n. security council for an arms embargo against iran designed to stop the 7-year-old iran-iraq war. the ban on weapons sales would be the second installment of a u.n. resolution last july calling for a truce in the war
u.s. officials who estimated in recent weeks that china sold $1 billion in weapons to iran in 1987 said they did not expect china _ a permanent member of the u.n. body _ to veto the arms ban. fitzwater's report on wu's meeting with reagan appeared to solidify that view
the spokesman quoted wu as saying ``if the overwhelming majority of the security council believed it should be adopted, including the arms embargo, that they are in favor, that there was no difficulty on their part in terms of that second resolution.''
the final step in the resolution would be soviet support. u.s. officials have said moscow appears willing to lift its objections to an arms embargo if it is accompanied by a short period of further diplomacy _ one last effort to get iran to agree to a cease-fire
fitzwater said of wu's assurances, ``it was our reaction, the president's reaction, that this was a very positive sign, a very strong expression of support and one, frankly, one we hope the soviet union would emulate.''
of all the weapons china has sold to iran, silkworm anti-ship missiles used in attacks on tankers in the persian gulf have caused the most consternation to neutral countries
the united states repeatedly protested to china about the sales last year, but since last autumn, u.s. officials have said they believe the chinese are o longer sending the missiles to iran
to the best of our information, they have not delivered any missiles since then,'' fitzwater said. ``they have indicated they are not sending missiles to the gulf, and we don't have any information to the contrary.''
while noting that china still remains a major supplier of conventional arms, he said, ``we think the fact that we have not detected any new missile shipments and their general attitude toward the iran-iraq war and the u.n. resolution _ that those are very hopeful signs.''
when iowa voters spoke they gave their blessing and momentum to presidential candidacies of bob dole and richard gephardt, but the day after super tuesday it looked like the rest of country wasn't listening
the big iowa winners were big super tuesday losers, while two of the biggest iowa losers _ vice president george bush and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee _ were riding high
gore had denounced the iowa caucuses as ``sort of like a roulette game _ it's not democracy in action.''
iowa caucus-goers responded in kind, giving the tennessee senator less than 1 percent of their votes. they gave more support to gov. mario cuomo of new york, who was insisting he was not a candidate
iowans weren't much kinder to bush. he finished third in the republican caucuses, not only far behind dole, but trailing an embarrassing distance behind former television evangelist pat robertson
exactly a month later, super tuesday weighed in and bush beat dole and robertson in 16 out of 16 republican primaries. on the democratic side, gephardt carried only his home state of missouri, while gore carried six states. paul simon, the other democrat treated well by iowans, was waiting for one last shot at survival in his home state of illinois
so, the question arises, is this it for iowa?
al gore may have demolished the theory that you've got to run in iowa and new hampshire,'' said white house chief of staff howard h. baker jr. ``he is a very credible candidate and he did not make a major effort in iowa and new hampshire.''
it looks like the allure of the land of corn wears off by the time you get to the hominy grits,'' said john buckley, press secretary to rep. jack kemp, who failed to excite iowa voters _ or those anywhere else
but iowa still has its defenders
phil roeder, spokesman for the iowa democratic party, said the super tuesday results simply ``addressed one of the biggest criticisms a lot of people had of iowa, that it had too much influence.''
we learned last night that iowa certainly is not the beginning and the end of the campaign, it's just the beginning and a lot can change once things get rolling,'' said roeder
nelson polesby, a professor of political science at the university of california at berkeley and an expert on the nominating process, was another dissenter from the theory that iowa's importance was diminished by the super tuesday vote
it seems to me they (iowa and new hampshire) framed the alternatives for super tuesday quite successfully,'' said polesby. ``i think what it demonstrates is that front-loading is terribly important, having money ahead of time is terribly important.''
polesby said one might as well write off super tuesday since that southern-generated event did not produce the desired result of a conservative front-runner
as well as gore did on his home ground, the strong dose of southern events proved just as beneficial to two liberals _ massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and jesse jackson
david keene, who was a dole political adviser until he had a falling out with campaign chairman william brock, said having a small state or two at the start of the process is a good thing
guys without as much money who are not as well known can test and break through against a front-runner,'' he said. ``it gives you a ticket to the game. it doesn't necessarily and shouldn't necessarily mean you're going to win the game.''
soldiers shot three arabs dead and wounded 13 in the occupied lands wednesday, which the plo named ``martyrs day'' for the scores of palestinians killed by israeli bullets or beatings, army and arab reports said
arabs paralyzed commerce in the west bank and gaza strip with a general strike. protesters pelted soldiers with rocks, bottles and firebombs. the outlawed palestinian flag flew in dozens of locations
israel's divided coalition government refused to vote on whether to endorse a u.s. peace plan designed to end the violence that began dec. 8 in the territories israel captured from jordan and egypt in the 1967
many missed opportunities may be forgiven but a missed peace is unforgiveable,'' foreign minister shimon peres said in parliament after prime minister yitzhak shamir, his conservative rival, headed off a vote in the 10-member inner cabinet
wednesday's deaths brought to 87 the number of arabs confirmed killed by israeli gunfire or beatings in three months of violence. u.n. figures put the toll at 91, including five who died of tear gas inhalation
martyrs day'' was called in a palestine liberation orgnization leaflet distributed last week. the strike closed shops, halted public transport and kept most of the 110,000 arabs who work in israel away from their jobs, the army reported
in clashes near qalqilya, a west bank village 35 miles northwest of jerusalem, armored personnel carriers fired pebbles at protesters with a newly developed riot-control device, israel radio reported. it said the gravel-firing gun was used this week for the first time
associated press photographer anat givon saw five soldiers grab an arab teen-ager by the neck and drag him down the street after a clash in al amari refugee camp near ramallah on the west bank. troopers slammed a woman who tried to intervene into a wall
at silwad, 10 miles northeast of ramallah, troops opened fire on about 200 protesters who built street barricades, surrounded soldiers and stoned a passing israeli car, an army spokesman said
he said mohammed othman farris, 18, died of a bullet wound in the back and another palestinian was wounded in the leg
villagers told an ap reporter that a car taking farris to a hospital was held up at an army checkpoint for half an hour and soldiers took the wounded man away. they said he was bleeding from the mouth and they later were told farris had died
jamil hijazi, 19, was killed by gunshots to the chest in nearby turmas ayya villlage, the army and ramallah hospital officials said
bassem al badarin, 25, was shot in the heart in samu village near hebron, the palestine press service and arabic daily al quds said
ramallah hospital officials said they treated two other arabs from samu and nearby yatta for serious chest wounds and a palestinian from bir zeit, near ramallah, was admitted with a leg wound, the officials said
in the fara refugee camp near nablus, soldiers fired on hundreds of arabs who were throwing stones, bottles and metal pipes, wounding seven, the army reported. most were wounded in the legs, hands and rib area, said officials at al ittihad hospital said
they said a palestinian from masha, a village 15 miles west of nablus, was treated for a gunshot wound in the left leg. officials at rafidiyeh hospital in nablus said a palestinian from jenin, 20 miles north, was shot in the shoulder
peres and his center-left labor party had tried to force a vote in the decision-making inner cabinet on the u.s. peace plan
why did we reject the outstretched hand of peace because of imaginary fears?'' he asked in parliament after the attempt was defeated by shamir and his right-wing likud bloc
shamir said on army radio: ``i think we are forbidden to give in to pressure and accept this initiative. we are also forbidden to give up by not fighting, by withdrawing from this battlefield without presenting our position.''
secretary of state george p. shultz, presented the plan to arab and israeli leaders on a trip last week, and asked shamir to bring israel's response to washington for talks with president reagan on march 14. labor had hoped to commit shamir to accept it before he left
shamir's spokesman, yossi ahimeir, said the prime minister ``opposed most of the ideas'' in the u.s. plan and would try to get it changed
in ``lavalava'' sarongs, beneath the thatched roofs of a south seas hotel, and hours behind the rest of the electorate, samoans gathered for their moment in the super tuesday sun
no negative ads filled the airwaves. no tv anchorman or presidential candidate descended. and no exit pollster tapped the wisdom of the voters, all 36 of them. but an upset was in the making
the local democratic chairman had urged those attending the party caucus, choosing a three-member delegation to the democrats' convention, to vote ``uncommitted.''
we would rather wait to see where the trend is going ... who doesn't make the cut,'' said chairman utu r.m. sinagege
but american samoa gov. a.p. lutali hailed masschusetts gov. michael dukakis for his virtues as a fiscal manager, and american samoa's congressional delegate, fofo i.f. sunia, endorsed another presidential hopeful, rep. richard gephardt of missouri. by the time the party faithful left the rainmaker hotel, at the foot of lushly green rainmaker mountain, dukakis had one delegate, gephardt another, and ``uncommitted'' the third
the local party chiefs had scheduled the caucus for super tuesday to gain national attention for their pacific island territory, which in republican eyes does not even rate convention delegates
polls were already closed in most of the 20 super tuesday states when the three dozen democrats, many clad in traditional, brightly hued ``lavalavas,'' assembled here in pago pago, six time zones behind the u.s. east coast and 2,300 miles southwest of hawaii
it was a light turnout _ only one-tenth of those eligible. national committeeman glenn jones blamed it on the fact that the territory of 37,500 people has no electoral votes in november's presidential election
but samoans are deeply interested, nonetheless, in what goes on in washington
most of their local budget comes from the u.s. treasury, and government welfare payments, made to samoans on the u.s. mainland, often find their way here to the home islands, where few jobs are available beyond the government and two tuna canneries
the samoans' interest apparently is not reciprocated. party officials said tennessee sen. albert gore had pledged to call, but didn't. jesse jackson sent a box of campaign buttons, but sinagege said his son sold them to classmates for about 50 cents _ total
the lapel strategy may have had an impact, however. fourteen of the 36 votes went to dukakis, eight to gephardt, 12 were uncommitted, and the final two went to the man on the buttons. killed</head>
south african troops are moving farther north into angola to support rebel forces pounded in a three-day battle this week, government officials said this week
the officials said troops loyal to the marxist government killed 180 unita rebels and captured large quantities of south african-supplied equipment in the battle near cuemba in central bie province
this was a major battle and we expect more fighting in the area,'' said one of the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. he said the battle ``shows the south african incursion into angola is still moving north in conjunction with rebel forces.''
angolan government radio said government troops destroyed two south african-built armored personnel carriers and captured another along with south african arms and ammunition
unita, the national union for the total independence of angola, also is backed by the united states
the action was the farthest north unita has engaged government troops since it began driving them out of their southeastern strongholds when south african troops entered the area in october to help the rebels repulse a government offensive
cuemba is 375 miles north of angola's border with south african-ruled south-west africa, also known as namibia
in a statement in lisbon on wednesday, unita said rebels were enagaged in heavy fighting around cuemba. it said guerrillas killed 11 angolan soldiers and four cubans on monday in an attack on the nearby town of catabola
three weeks earlier, unita overran munhango, 40 miles east of cuemba
both cuemba and munhango are along the east-west benguela railroad, southern angola's vital transport link to landlocked zaire and zambia. unita has targeted the railroad during its 12-year bush war to press president jose eduardo dos santos' government for a power-sharing accord
our troops are holding cuemba,'' the official said
angolan defense minster gen. pedro maria tonha said monday in lubango, capital of the southern province of huila, that to take the strategic city of cuito cuanavale, south african forces fighting with unita ``have resorted to bombardment of our positions with long-range artillery because of the failure of their air attacks on the city.''
angolan authorities announced last month their forces fought off the third major south african-unita offensive against the garrison city of cuito cuanavale in three months
dos santos said an estimated 7,000 south african troops were in position around the city, with another 2,000 south african soldiers scattered around south-central cunene province
south africa acknowledged in november it was sending troops into angola to aid unita and has reported casualties among its forces in angola in the past two weeks
in december and january, the u.n. security council called for a total withdrawal of south african forces from angolan territory
the angolan officials confirmed cuban support troops are in place in the southern war zone but remain behind angolan front line positions. ``they are there if needed,'' one official said
cuba has said its has 40,000 troops in angola and has agreed with the government to withdraw the cubans from angola when south africa pulls out of the country, stops aiding unita and begins implementing a u.n. plan for namibian independence
south africa has demanded a cuban withdrawal first
the navy said wednesday it would launch a new guided-missile cruiser later this month in bath, maine
the uss normandy, a so-called aegis cruiser, will be launched during ceremonies on march 19 at the bath iron works, the service said in a statement
retired army brig. gen. john s.d. eisenhower will deliver the principal speech
the normandy, named after the massive allied landings in france that led to the defeat of germany in world war ii, is 567 feet long, 55 feet wide and displaces 9,500 tons
the aegis cruisers are considered the most advanced air-defense ships in the world, carrying a variety of missiles and gun systems for use against enemy aircraft and a wraparound radar system that allows them to ``see'' in all directions at once
