there are a lot of people who are turned off by the so-called establishment in any way,'' said andrus, who remains an uncommitted delegate and urged others to remain uncommitted
in this case, that is to his (jackson's) benefit,'' andrus said
in a state with only a tiny minority population, jackson waged a limited campaign but captured four of the state's 18 uncommitted delegates to the national convention. the massachusetts governor won eight delegates, and six will go to the convention uncommitted
party officials were pleased with the turnout, which in most cases was sharply higher than four years ago when the county caucus process was used for the first time
in ada county, two caucuses that drew less than 800 people between them four years ago attracted about 1,700 tuesday night
former governor john evans, who was state chairman for dukakis, said he felt dukakis was gaining recognition for his accomplishments, including the economic revitalization of his state
that's the message: it can be done,'' said evans
glenda jackson and christopher plummer have avoided broken legs and other major disasters traditionally associated with the staging of ``macbeth.''
but their broadway-bound production of shakespeare's blood-soaked tragedy hasn't been without problems
five weeks before the play arrives at the mark hellinger theater in new york for a 12-week run, the original director, kenneth frankel, has been dismissed and new sets and costumes at a cost of $250,000
we decided we had to make some moves,'' said co-producer garth drabinsky of toronto, owner of the cineplex odeon movie theater chain
the new director, robin phillips of canada's stratford festival, agreed to rescue the production but doesn't want his name on the program
there also are rumors of strife between the two stars _ although they appeared amiable enough upon arrival march 8 in toronto for 16 performances at the o'keefe center, where $1 million in advance sales set a box office record
when we found robin was free, it was a miracle,'' said plummer, a toronto native and hollywood veteran who earned critical acclaim for his iago in a 1982 broadway production of ``othello.''
it saved our necks,'' he added
we have been working almo  critics said frankel, an off-broadway obie award winner, lacked a cohesive vision of what ``macbeth'' was all about
miss jackson is tackling lady macbeth for the first time and finds passionate, erotic bonds between the murdering king and his ambitious wife
undoubtedly part of the attraction each has for the other is they both have largish sexual appetites. i've never thought that lady macbeth breathed life into a man of straw _ what would be attractive to her in a man like that?
it was a time when people were infinitely more passionate than they are now ... they see no alternative to what they are doing,'' she added
the challenge always is to make it clear to an audience that shakespeare is about real people. he's probably the most contemporary dramatist there is. i'm sure there's a mr. and mrs. macbeth walking around now.''
working with plummer for the first time, miss jackson repeated her old saw that it's not necessary to like fellow actors in order to put on a play
asked if he had done anything to make his co-star dislike him, plummer smiled and said: ``i constantly do.''
she chimed in: ``this is true.''
the production will be seen at boston's colonial theater from march 22 to april 3 and the shubert theater in new haven april 5-10 before one week of previews in new york. opening night is april 21
michael dukakis was a big winner on super tuesday and a hit in his ancestral country on wednesday, picking up the sort of television and newspaper coverage reserved for a native son
dukakis triumphs, all consider him a certain president,'' screamed a second edition banner headline in messimvrini, a conservative daily newspaper
dukakis, the massachusetts governor, won democratic primary victories in his home state, florida, texas, rhode island and maryland and caucuses in idaho and hawaii
the name dukakis has a great deal of recognition and the fact that he is a greek-american draws intense interest here,'' said messimvrini's chief editor, giorgos bertsos
dukakis' showing also was one of the top items on the state-run tv news
the conservative afternoon daily 24 hours, a national tabloid, ran a large color picture of a smiling dukakis on its front page. the left-wing eleftherotipia said he was ``the main winner among the democrats.''
the dukakis campaign has been closely followed by the greek press and many newspapers have run long interviews with the candidate
on tuesday, messimvrini ran four pages on the super tuesday contest under the headline ``the test of victory,'' with color pictures of dukakis taking up two pages in the middle of the newspaper
wednesday's left-wing newspapers also had in-depth reporting of the democratic and republican campaigns
dukakis and bush advancing steadily,'' headlined the left-wing afternoon daily proti above a half-page story
many newspapers played down the fact that dukakis had split the vote with sen. albert gore jr. and jesse jackson in the south. instead, they highlighted the governor's big wins in texas and florida
a bill revising the clean air act most likely would cost the economy $32 billion and 300,000 to 600,000 manufacturing jobs, a business group told congress on wednesday
in the worst case the cost could reach $73 billion and a million jobs, about 5 percent of the nation's manufacturing payrolls, the group said. the minimum cost was put at $14 billion, without a jobs estimate
we can't afford to be exposing ourselves to 30 to 70 billion (dollars) a year and expect to be part of the solution to the trade problem'' characterized by a $170 billion annual trade deficit, said david m. roderick, chairman of usx corp., in presenting a study of the air pollution bill approved by the senate environment and public works committee
the bill would require tighter pollution controls in several areas, including new controls on the precursors of acid rain from old power plants, and stricter requirements for motor vehicles. passage is by no means certain
roderick, who is chairman of the environment committee of the business roundtable, an organization of chief executives of large companies, told a news conference, ``a very high proportion of the money wouldn't do anything
... it would be the least cost-effective of all our nation's environmental laws'' as well as the most costly
he said congress should design measures targeted to areas of the country that don't meet clean-air standards
roderick used an example from his company's steel-making subsidiary, u.s. steel corp., saying the bill would ``go after your coke ovens in a horrendous way, it would go after your blast furnaces in a horrendous way ... you could not justify retrofitting some of those plants.''
though the company would have to spend $1.5 billion to $2 billion on compliance, some ovens and furnaces would be closed and ``we would import more semi-finished product.'' one of the company's most efficient plants found it would have to raise prices $25 to $40 a ton or roughly 6 percent to 8 percent
the company only recently resumed exports, which earn profits of 5 percent to 8 percent on sales. ``this would just wipe that out,'' roderick said
as for weaker steel companies, some of them operating under protection of the bankruptcy laws, ``they're dead; they're history,'' roderick said
manufacturing industry spending of $6 billion a year on air pollution control would rise to $26 billion, the study said
the study by r.m. dowd &amp; co., a washington consulting firm, pulled together findings from trade association and government agency studies. no estimates were possible for 22 of 43 provisions in the bill, roderick said
those omitted costs included costs to auto makers and their customers, already paying by some estimates $1,600 a car for pollution control equipment. ``the technology doesn't exist'' to go further. ``how are you going to estimate the costs?'' roderick said
richard ayres, chairman of the clean air coalition of environmental and other groups, said roderick's study was ``an elaborate, thick stack of back-of-the-envelope calculations ... probably two to four times too high.''
there is no estimate given here of the benefits'' of the bill, ayres said, adding that in his opinion a cleaner environment and less respiratory disease would be worth $32 billion a year
among estimates from the study of spending requirements:
_by industry as a whole except utilities, $10.4 billion on new controls of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides, raw materials for transformation into acid rain, and on compounds that help form ozone
_by utilities, $9 billion on additional control of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides
_by industry, another $3.7 billion limiting emissions of highly toxic chemicals
_by petroleum refiners, $4.3 billion in changing fuel characteristics
_by local governments, $1.3 billion in auto pollution inspections
some expenditures like inspections would be necessary even if congress does nothing. the environmental protection agency has estimated its plans for ozone control could cost $8 billion a year
the study's $32 billion estimate was not out of line with earlier studies, which made different assumptions and omitted some provisions included by dowd
epa estimated the bill would cost $16 billion to $24 billion in addition to the $8 billion the agency's plan would require. the congressional research service estimated $14 billion to $28 billion. the senate committee report estimated costs at $16.87 billion
the 50th anniversary of austria's annexation to nazi germany finds austria's youth beginning to question the country's past, the validity of democratic institutions today and prospects for the future
political leaders, analysts and historians have called on members of the world war ii generation to teach austria's youth about the events that led up to the anschluss on march 11, 1938, and austria's involvement in the war and the holocaust
over the two years since the first disclosures that president kurt waldheim had covered up his service with the nazi army, a nationwide debate has raised political awareness among austria's youth and often pitted young against old
in a strongly hierarchical society that has traditionally ducked conflict, youth began in the late 1970s to question the maxims they inherited from their parents
these included the silent consensus of postwar generations to keep quiet about the war and not to provoke open conflict
for some young people, the waldheim debate has sharpened their growing political awareness and unwillingness to accept things just as they are
many young austrians who voted for waldheim in 1986 now say they made a mistake in voting for him and in failing to inform themselves about the candidates
a panel of historians appointed by the austrian government issued a report last month that said waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to nazi atrocities when he was a lieutenant in the balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them. it left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime
whole generations were not taught about the 1930s and 1940s in school. even many austrians under 30 say that by the time they finished school their history teachers had reached only the end of world war i
by contrast, many teen-agers today receive comprehensive and objective lessons on the events that led to world war ii and the holocaust from teachers young enough to be distant from those events
socialist chancellor franz vranitzky told foreign journalists recently that his teen-age children ``do not find it embarrassing or painful'' to discuss the war years because they are not preoccupied with their own involvement
austria's youth ``has read more, traveled more, is more open, more liberal and more tolerant'' than earlier generations, said josef figl, head of an 11,000-member catholic student group
sociologist silvio lehmann said the level of education rose tremendously in the 1970s and 1980s, increasing interest in politics. he cited protests against the zwentendorf nuclear facility, which led to a 1978 referendum in which austrians voted against nuclear power
in december 1984, demonstrators clashed with police in hainburg on the danube to protest a planned hydroelectric plant environmentalists say would destroy a unique natural landscape
the clash shocked and outraged many austrians in a country where confrontations with authorities have been rare since the street battles between socialists and conservatives in the 1930s
memories of that violence prompted all political parties to bury their differences after world war ii in public consensus and reconciliation
psychologist erwin ringel, author of ``the austrian soul,'' said that after the war austrians ``threw themselves into rebuilding the country to avoid rebuilding the soul.'' he said waldheim symbolizes that suppression of the past
robert koschin, 27, of innsbruck, said the younger generations' growing interest in the past has reversed the parent-child role
the children are giving their parents their experiences and knowledge,'' making older generations more willing to discuss the ``blocking'' of the past, he said
many austrians perceive their country as adolf hitler's first victim, but many leading nazis were austrians
as in west germany, austria's parents have struggled to shelter their children from the deprivation they knew immediately after the war, showering them with the benefits of a rebuilt consumer society
now the economy and an extensive social welfare system are beginning to falter, with 6.7 percent of youth unemployed and much of the state-owned industry running heavy deficits
it is depressing for a generation that was born into having everything to have to fight for things that were taken for granted,'' koschin said. ``it is the first time people are confronted with having to do something themselves.''
the alleged chief of a smuggling ring that imported cocaine through cuba was ordered held without bond wednesday after prosecutors played a tape of the defendant saying ``the money went in fidel's drawer.''
reinaldo ruiz, 50, a cuban-born u.s. citizen, was indicted along with 16 others last month on charges of flying drugs from colombia through cuba and other caribbean islands
it was the third miami drug indictment involving alleged cuban connections since october
on a secretly recorded videotape played for u.s. magistrate william turnoff during a pre-trial detention hearing, ruiz is heard telling an informant, ``i am the only one that has connections'' in cuba
then, apparently referring to payoffs, ruiz states, ``the money went in fidel's drawer.''
ruiz never identified cuban president fidel castro as the ``fidel'' he was referring to, and prosecutors refused to comment on the statement
castro has strenuously denied any involvement in drug smuggling
but last month's indictment of panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega here alleges the cuban leader mediated a drug payoff dispute between the general and the medellin cartel, a colombian ring responsible for up to 80 percent of u.s. cocaine imports
and an indictment in october charged that another drug ring routinely used cuba as a waystation for cocaine shipments
no cuban officials were indicted in the most recent case. but prosecutors say the conspirators used a cuban military base to ship drugs, and promised an informant an escort of cuban coast guard vessels for a cocaine shipment
the indictment accuses ruiz of heading the smuggling ring which allegedly imported cocaine from colombia through cuba, haiti and the bahamas to mexico and the united states
assistant u.s. attorney thomas mulvihill asked that ruiz be held until trial, contending he is a danger to the community and may flee. ruiz faces trafficking charges and a continuing criminal enterprise count that carries a maximum life sentence
turnoff agreed to hold ruiz, over objections of defense attorny alvin entin
the government appears to have a very strong case,'' said turnoff
besides ruiz, the tapes showed a woman named rosa and ruiz's son rubin, who is also a defendant in the case. a cooperating informant was out of camera during the part of the tape shown in court
the elder ruiz has not entered a plea in the case
italian designers are coming on strong at the fall-winter collections, scoring with new ideas that include waist-skimming jackets, pants and skirts
the mood is buoyant as store buyers jostle to place their orders
before the shows started, there was fear that the low buying power of the dollar would adversely affect orders. and there were also considerable jitters regarding all the publicity given recently to the fantasy fashions of paris-based designer christian lacroix
the italians were worried that the success of their more sober type of elegance would be compromised. but their fear of this two-headed bogeyman appears to have been unjustified. and what's more, the sun has shone from a cloudless blue sky throughout, putting everybody in a good mood
laura biagiotti, the designer who lives and works out of a medieval castle nestling in the countryside outside rome, showed styles that were perfect for an elegant castle dweller
there were soft cashmere ``horse blankets,'' ideal for keeping out the chill along the ramparts. they wrapped up comfy sweater-dresses, over-size twinsets or slim-fitting pants, all in flat knit
daytime colors were rustic: oatmeal, moss-green and maize. and there was moderation in the details with a more natural shoulderline, flat-heeled footwear and skirt-lengths just a fraction above the knee
biagiotti took paisley-patterned fringed head scarves in fine wool and fashioned them into wraparound skirts and did an attractive series of that fashion indispensable, the ever-popular little black dress in velvet or silk crepe
on a completely different wavelength was the baby doll look of the collection designed by muriel grateau for complice. models, with elfin hairdos, wore short, high-waisted styles with tight-fitting bodices and jauntily gathered skirts
a brand-new girlish look for coats in double wool crepe featured a shoulder-framing cape collar and a broad martingale belt that tied tightly in a bow at the waist in back
party dresses came in the same style with waist gathers transferred to just under the bust while mini-skirts were decorated with frills and ribbon cockades
almost all the clothes at complice came in a rich titian red, lace-up shoes and stockings included
there is a certain style that the italian designers have always done beautifully: understated but elegant tailored blazers, well-cut pants and loose top coats in men's-type smooth woolens
it is a look that is timeless and unbeatable, and the women of milan love it. basile did it for them again, tucking pants into the newly fashionable winter boots and putting velvet on collars for an even more well-bred air
six men were arrested wednesday on the new york state thruway after a downtown shooting that left one man dead and two others seriously injured, police said
the three men were shot shortly after 8 a.m. in a second-floor apartment, said police sgt. bob wolfgang. one victim, who was critically injured, managed to flee the apartment and call police, wolfgang said
the wounded men, both in their 20s, underwent surgery at albany medical center hospital, said hospital spokesman greg mcgarry. their identities were not released
the man who was in critical condition suffered multiple wounds to the head and neck, mcgarry said
wolfgang would not say if the shootings were drug-related, but said a drug raid had taken place earlier in the morning at a nearby residence. automatic weapons and a shotgun were apparently used in the shootings, he said
about two hours after the shooting, state police stopped a sedan about 70 miles south of albany, said state police sgt. william nolan. the car was carrying six men who were taken into custody, said maj. wayne bennett. they were taken to the loudonville state police barracks and were being questioned, but no names were immediately released
a woman who apparently was at the apartment at the time of the shooting was also taken to the hospital for observation, authorities said. she had not been shot
a british transport plane headed to the falkland islands for military exercises had engine trouble and made an emergency landing in uruguay after reportedly being denied permission to land in brazil
in neighboring argentina, the government news agency telam reported the emergency landing and said the aircraft contained ``a shipment of bombs and explosives.'' it did not elaborate
both telam and radio montecarlo in uruguay reported that the plane landed at montevideo's carrasco international airport on tuesday night after brazil refused to let it land there
british officials said only that the aircraft encountered engine troubles while heading to the islands and requested emergency authorization to land
the hercules c-130 aircraft, carrying a crew of seven, was en route to the falkland islands for military exercises that have been denounced by argentina, which has claimed the islands since 1833
argentina calls the islands the malvinas and fought a 74-day war with britain over them in 1982 before surrendering
telam said without elaboration that argentine foreign minister dante caputo was ``in telephone communications with his uruguayan counterpart, luis barrios tassano.''
the aircraft was in protective custody of uruguayan soldiers at carrasco airport, said an air control tower spokesman who would not give his name
the british exercises, which simulate an argentine attack on the islands, are scheduled to last until march 31
pat robertson was humiliated by a third-place finish in his southern backyard, while a strong black showing boosted jesse jackson to victory as many white voters shunned virginia's primaries
robertson lagged far behind super tuesday's super winner, vice president george bush, who captured the republican primary with 103,743 votes or 53 percent to kansas sen. bob dole's 50,191 votes or 25 percent, with 93 percent of the 1,986 precincts reporting
jackson's easy win in the democratic primary with 162,355 votes or 45 percent was based on a large turnout by black voters, who cast 40 percent of the ballots in the democratic primary, said larry sabato, a political scientist at the university of virginia
whites virtually boycotted the democratic primary,'' he said wednesday
tennessee sen. albert gore was next with 80,650 votes or 22 percent, followed closely by massachusetts gov. michael dukakis with 78,141 votes or 22 percent. missouri rep. richard gephardt was fourth with 16,082 votes or 4 percent
jackson captured 38 delegates, gore had 22 and dukakis won 15
sabato said the ``abysmal'' voter turnout _ about 21.5 percent of the 2.6 million virginians eligible _ should have helped robertson. the former virginia beach television evangelist was believed to have the most committed followers of all the gop candidates, but their impact was not felt at the polls
no one thought robertson would do so poorly,'' he said. ``this is a real humiliation for him.''
robertson captured only 29,556 votes or 15 percent. new york rep. jack kemp was next with 8,696 or 4 percent. no delegates were selected in the non-binding republican primary. another missile into tehran and u.s. convoy; adds 2 grafs at end with more on convoy.</note>
missiles exploded in baghdad and tehran on wednesday and artillerymen shelled border cities in the 10th day of random attacks on civilian targets that have killed or maimed hundreds of people
iran said 35 were killed in tehran and iraq reported deaths in baghdad, but did not give figures. the missile duel that began feb. 29 is the latest round in the ``war of the cities,'' which has cost thousands of lives since the iran-iraq conflict began in september 1980
a kremlin official acknowledged wednesday that the soviet union furnished short-range missiles to iraq, but said modifying them so they could reach tehran was not part of the deal. iran had accused the soviets of providing the weapons, and a mob tried to storm the soviet embassy in tehran on sunday
in the persian gulf, shipping officials confirmed a raid by iraqi warplanes tuesday on the 101,977-ton felicity, a cypriot-flag tanker under charter to iran. they said the ship sustained minor damage
the raid ended a three-week lull in attacks on commercial shipping by both sides that have damaged more than 400 vessels
american warships escorted the u.s.-flagged kuwaiti tanker sea isle city down the gulf wednesday. it was the tanker's first trip since being hit by a silkworm missile iran fired into the kuwaiti anchorage in october
iraq said it fired three surface-to-surface missiles into tehran on wednesday. iran said 35 people were killed and 120 wounded by those rockets and another that fell on the city the night before
it said iranian gunners fired two missiles at baghdad. dispatches from the official iraqi news agency said only one hit baghdad but it demolished houses and stores, ``killing or wounding numbers of civilians.''
iran claims to have fired 25 missiles into baghdad and several at other iraqi cities. iraq has reported 47 missiles launched, all but five at tehran
casualties in tehran totaled 157 dead and more than 420 wounded through wednesday, according to official iranian reports. iraq has reported ``many'' civilians killed or wounded, but has not given figures
reports from iraq said iranian artillery pounded the southern port of basra during the night, killing ``many civilians,'' and later poured shells into qurnah and zubair, to the north and south of basra respectively
it said the shells hit densely populated residential areas of basra and the dead included four children buried in the rubble of their home
the iraqis said their warplanes raided military and economic installations in several towns or cities of western iran
gennady i. gerasimov, spokesman for the soviet foreign ministry, said in moscow: ``the soviet union previously delivered a limited shipment of short-range missiles'' to iraq. ``we never gave our permission to modify those missiles to increase their range, and modernization was not foreseen by that agreement.''
western military analysts had said the missiles were soviet-built scud-b weapons provided by other countries, possibly north korea, to which the iraqis attached boosters enabling them to reach tehran
both sides have scud-bs, which have a range of 190 miles. western experts say iran's missiles are supplied by its arab allies syria and libya
baghdad is within easy range 80 miles from the border but tehran and the iranian holy city of qom, which also has been rocketed, are nearly 300 miles from the frontier
a u.s. navy official, who could not be identified under navy rules, said the 81,283-ton sea isle city and 79,999-ton chesapeake city were part of the 16th convoy of reflagged kuwaiti tankers this year. he said the missile frigate uss simpson was accompanying them
eleven kuwaiti tankers have been given u.s. flags and registration so the navy can protect them. convoys began in july
incineration of obsolete chemical weapons will resume this week at this remote desert installation, where disposal operations were shut down after a nerve gas leak 13 months ago
work began tuesday to prepare equipment for renewed destruction of m-55 nerve gas rockets at the chemical agent munitions disposal system, said depot spokesman w. allen kenitzer. disposal operations were to begin by week's end, he said
the army is using the facility to test equipment and procedures it eventually will use to destroy the nation's aging chemical agent stockpile. the size of the chemical arsenal is classified but has been estimated at 30,000 tons
on jan. 28, 1987, a small quantity of deadly liquid nerve agent leaked from an incinerator. no injuries were reported, but the army closed the plant pending an inspection and review of management problems that allowed the leak to occur
corrective actions included increased quality control, tougher requirements on plant filter units and stricter emphasis on monitoring and maintenance, kenitzer said
the tooele facility has disposed of 38,000 missiles, shells or bombs filled with nerve or mustard agent since operations began in 1979
the depot is one of nine chemical storage sites officials plan to use for incineration of old chemical arsenals using the tooele model
the splintered results of the south's regional primary gave both its architects and its detractors room to claim they were right about super tuesday
super tuesday succeeded,'' said one who was present at its creation, former gov. charles robb of virginia. he saw his state go to jesse jackson but his own candidate, albert gore, establish his candidacy in much of the rest of dixie
super tuesday is not what i hoped it would be,'' said florida's state democratic chairman, charles whitehead. his state and texas, the two big delegate prizes of the south, went to northerner michael dukakis
the sharp, three-way division of democratic winners means no one will likely clinch the nomination before the convention in atlanta, former president jimmy carter said
i was surprised at how well gore did,'' carter said. ``i thought (richard) gephardt would do better in the south.''
twenty states held democratic primaries on super tuesday, including the 14 southern and border states and six others, including dukakis' own massachusetts
in total popular vote, the result was a near-equal division among the three winners. jackson, the black candidate, won the most votes with 2.54 million, or 27 percent. dukakis got 2.51 million, or 26 percent, and gore got 2.46 million, also 26 percent
super tuesday pretty much guarantees a protracted struggle for the democrats,'' said merle black, political science professor at the university of north carolina. none of the candidates, he said, displayed the strength needed to defeat the republicans in november
super tuesday was largely a democratic creation, led by southern democratic legislators. but it was the republicans who got the decisive winner, george bush
the great republican fear was that pat robertson would emerge as a strong, divisive force,'' black said. ``that possibility has pretty well dissipated.''
texas state sen. chet edwards, one of the sponsors of the bill that created texas' entry into regional primary, declared the day ``a real success story.''
i think the biggest myth that non-southerners have about super tuesday was that it was set up to assure the nomination of a conservative anglo southerner,'' said edwards
instead, he argued, super tuesday had wide support among hispanic and black minorities in texas. the goal, he said, was not to nominate a conservative or a southern candidate but to give the south a voice early in the nominating process, before the choices had been too narrowed
it speaks well for the south and for michael dukakis that the governor of massachusetts can come to the south and address the issues and win,'' said edwards
but even some of its boosters acknowledged super tuesday may have been a bit of overkill, with 20 states voting. if the idea survives, some say there may at least be a reduction in the number of states holding primaries on the same day
the wide battleground, coming just three weeks after new hampshire's primary, put a premium on television advertising and the money it takes to buy it
candidates fell back on the one proven method of moving large numbers of voters in a short time span: negative advertising. dukakis and gore blistered richard gephardt with tough negative ads that took their toll
each of the other three beat expectations,'' said former party chairman robert strauss. ``it came out of dick gephardt's hide.''
and super tuesday also said something about the hoopla surrounding iowa's caucuses, the first event of the season and the one that seemed to get the most attention. its winner was gephardt, the big loser of super tuesday
south africa may have aided canoe-borne raiders who staged an abortive coup attempt in the west african island nation of sao tome and principe, it was reported wednesday
officials said security forces captured 43 armed men who landed in fishing canoes before dawn tuesday on beaches near sao tome, the capital of the marxist nation 100 miles west of gabon
president manuel pinto da costa said in a national radio broadcast that soldiers, police and militiamen were searching for two remaining members of the assault force. he appealed for calm and vigilance against renewed attacks
the portuguese news agency lusa said celestino da costa, prime minister of the two-island nation, identified one of the captured assailants as afonso santos. it said he was leader of an opposition group that sought asylum two years ago in south african-ruled south-west africa, also known as namibia
lusa said 76 sao tome exiles arrived by boat in south africa-ruled namibia in may 1986 and sought south african aid to overthrow the government of pinto da costa
the agency said a south african foreign ministry spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, acknowledged the south african government had granted asylum to the refugees. but he denied reports that it trained about 100 refugees from sao tome and principe to overthrow the government, lusa said
da costa, whose sao tome and principe liberation movement has governed since independence from portugal in 1975, blamed the opposition national resistance front. the front is based in libreville, the capital of pro-western gabon
the lisbon-based secretary-general of the front, quintiliano amado, denied it was behind the attack. but he said it may have been carried out by dissidents within his movement
earlier wednesday, informed sources in sao tome and principe told the associated press that government opponents, possibly based in gabon or south africa, were suspected in the raid, which left two attackers dead and one assailant and a policeman wounded
the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said investigators would seek information about sao tome exiles expelled from gabon to south africa two years ago
they said the attackers were armed only with light weapons and that angolan troops stationed on the islands were not called to assist in capturing the raiders. they said the army was no longer securing key facilities and life had returned to normal
the two volcanic islands of 110,000 people are known chiefly for their white sand beaches, coffee and cocoa plantations, and brightly colored tropical birds
but attention was focused on their strategic position in the gulf of guinea in 1978 when rumors of an imminent invasion swept the country. cuba, angola and guinea-bissau sent troops to help defend the islands
the invasion never happened, but the country since has strengthened its ties with angola, cuba and the soviet union. news reports in 1984 said about 2,000 soviet and cuban troops were operating two radio stations and a submarine port in the area
an estimated 1,000 angolan troops also are stationed in sao tome and principe to support the regular army. counties</head>
long-distance telephone service for more than a quarter-million customers in santa barbara and part of san luis obispo counties was cut off wednesday after a cave-in at an excavation project damaged a major phone line, officials said
gte california co. said it has 196,000 residential and 68,000 business customers in the affected area
the excavation accident in los angeles kinked the only major long-distance line into the affected region, said american telephone &amp; telegraph co. spokeswoman kelly williams. at&amp;t owns the line, but rival long-distance carriers mci and sprint lease space on it, she said
telephone customers in the affected area could not call out to or receive calls from other areas of california or out of state, officials said. calls within the affected area weren't affected
ms. williams said the line was expected to be repaired by mid-afternoon. the accident occurred about 9:30 a.m
the nation's industrial heartland will prosper in the next few years, but lagging population growth threatens the region's political clout and share of federal programs, a public policy group said wednesday
the hemorrhage of jobs from the region was another point of weakness in the 18 northern states stretching from minnesota to new england, the northeast-midwest institute said in its study, ``the state of the region.''
the short-term economic outlook for the entire region is positive,'' the report said. the region shared in the national return to prosperity from 1983 to late 1986, with new england benefiting the most and the midwest the least
however, the study warned that the region's well-being is endangered by the failure of its population growth to keep pace with the rest of the nation's
the trend is expected to continue through the turn of the century,'' the study said. ``government researchers expect population in the northeast and midwest to grow at only 3.8 percent throughout the 1990s, about half the national average.''
the sunbelt states in the south and west will show population increases of 10 percent in the 1990s, the study said
the lagging population gains in the northeast and midwest result both from lower birth rates and migration to southern and western states, the study said
slower population growth translates into less clout in congress, with the region expected to lose 14 house seats after the 1990 census. the region lost 15 seats after the 1980 census, for a total projected loss in representation of 13 percent in the 1970s and 1980s, the study said
political influence, from the selection of the president in the electoral college to appropriation fights in the house of representatives, will shift further to the south and west,'' the study said. ``moreover, because billions of dollars are allocated by formulas based on population, the northeast-midwest region can expect reductions in its share of federal funding.''
although unemployment dropped below the national average in parts of the region, it was unlikely to regain many of the 1.3 million manufacturing jobs lost between 1980 and 1986, the study said
the south and west for the first time topped the northeast and midwest in manufacturing employment in 1986. the sunbelt had 9,542,500 employees on manufacturing payrolls, compared with 9,394,000 in the northeast and midwest
other points made by the study were:
_per capita personal income increased faster in the northeast and midwest than in the south and west
_the northeast and midwest invested more in public school education than did other regions
_the trend toward an older population was more evident in the northeast and midwest than in the rest of the country
the study covered these states: connecticut, delaware, illinois, indiana, iowa, maine, maryland, massachusetts, michigan, minnesota, new hampshire, new jersey, new york, ohio, pennsylvania, rhode island, vermont and wisconsin
the privately funded northeast-midwest institute was formed in 1977 at the request of members of the house and senate from the region. the study was also sponsored by two legislative groups: the northeast-midwest congressional coalition and the northeast-midwest senate coalition
sen. albert gore jr. swamped his fellow democrats in his home state and on wednesday predicted that his victory in five presidential primaries proved his campaign can survive a national contest
two or three days ago, the conventional wisdom ... through the country was that super tuesday was going to see the end of al gore's campaign. the conventional wisdom was wrong,'' gore said. ``sooner or later, it's going to stop being a surprise.''
with all 2,391 precincts reporting, gore had 414,569 votes or 72 percent; jesse jackson received 118,615 votes or 21 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 19,268 votes or 3 percent and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 8,657 votes or 2 percent
in the republican race, vice president george bush had 151,130 votes or 60 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 54,493 votes or 22 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 31,402 votes or 12 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 10,871 votes or 4 percent
based on those results, gore would take 56 democratic delegates and jackson would get 14. bush would capture 29 of tennessee's 45 gop delegates, dole 10 and 6 would go to the national convention uncommitted
gore predicted his super tuesday showing would propel him to the democratic nomination to face bush in november and ``bring the party back to the grass roots and make a fresh start for america.''
gore, who will be 40 on march 31, likened himself to the late john f. kennedy
in 1960, we replaced the oldest president then to serve with the youngest to be elected,'' he said. ``we have a chance to do it again.''
about 150 jackson supporters cheered as they watched election returns tuesday night in nashville
i think it's a victory,'' said jackson's tennessee chairman, state rep. lois deberry. jackson would have carried tennessee if gore hadn't been in the race, she said. routs dole</head>
white voters who joined ranks with jesse jackson in a state once known as a bastion of segregation helped put him over the top in alabama's democratic primary
in the republican contest, vice president george bush swept to victory atop a record turnout on super tuesday. bush picked up an estimated 35 of the state's 38 gop delegates, with kansas sen. robert dole apparently getting the other three
among democrats, jackson gained an estimated 30 delegates, but tennessee sen. albert gore jr. ran stronger than expected in his neighbor state and appeared to be pulling the remaining 26 delegates
for the jackson forces, the victory was particularly sweet in the cradle of the confederacy, where blacks were routinely denied the right to vote before the 1965 voting rights act
jesse jackson's message has touched the hearts of many in the south,'' said his state coordinator, youlanda curtis. the victory ``shows that alabama is progressing. alabamians should be proud, both black and white.''
al lapierre, executive director of the alabama democratic party, estimated that jackson received as much as 5 percent of the white vote in addition to overwhelming black support, helping to give the former minister the margin of victory
with 3,788 of 4,304 precincts or 88 percent reporting wednesday, jackson had 165,570 votes or 44 percent to gore's 139,892 votes or 37 percent. massachusetts gov. michael dukakis was next with 28,949 votes or 8 percent and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 27,997 or 7 percent
the gop turnout appeared headed toward 230,000, defeating the 1980 record of 211,000 for a republican presidential primary in the state
with 3,713 of 4,304 precincts or 86 percent reporting, bush had 127,937 votes or 64 percent, dole followed with 32,274 or 16 percent, pat robertson was third with 28,174 or 14 percent and new york rep. jack kemp had 9,739 or 5 percent
democrat bob kerrey burst onto the political scene in 1982 by winning the governorship in a state dominated by republicans, then made the gossip columns with his romance with actress debra winger
the free-wheeling style that carried him to the governor's mansion in his first political campaign won't change much as he seeks election to the u.s. senate, kerry said
unopposed for the democratic nomination in the may primary, kerrey has been campaigning for several months but planned to formally announce his candidacy thursday
two republicans, incumbent sen. david karnes and rep. hal daub, are battling for the gop nod. karnes was appointed by gov. kay orr to fill the seat after the death last year of incumbent democrat edward zorinsky
despite his frequent assertions when he left the governor's mansion in 1986 that he didn't know if he would again seek public office, kerrey was regarded by political observers as a possible senate candidate. when zorinsky died of a heart attack, kerrey was seen as his party's best hope
i had to decide if i would enjoy this, if i wanted to serve and whether i wanted a public or private life,'' kerrey said
a war hero who earned the medal of honor and lost part of a leg as a navy commando in vietnam, kerrey became a successful entrepreneur who owns several restaurants and then a successful politician
he became an intregral part of the democratic scene when he worked for gary hart in 1984, and was instrumental in hart's victory in the nebraska primary
part of his personal notoriety came from his relationship with winger, who married actor timothy hutton a few years ago
kerrey, 44, is ready and willing to discuss his campaign, but he usually deflects questions about winger
we are friends,'' he said recently. ``i don't know that there is anything else to be said.''
he is divorced and the father of two children. ben, 13 and lindsey, 11, live in texas with their mother
an interview with kerrey is often peppered with off-the-record asides, some self-deprecating and some reflecting that he doesn't appear to take himself too seriously
kerrey chose not to seek a second term as governor, saying it was time to seek other challenges
the former governor admits he doesn't have a list of proposals and solutions
i learned as governor you don't solve problems from the top, down. what you do is engage the citizens in an effort to find out what we are willing to do about a problem
my sense is that we are afraid sometimes to try something different, to get in there and say, `hey, we're going to try to make a difference here.'''
part of the political process, he says, is to ``select that part of the status quo we want to hold on to, and that part which we want to change and that's where the fun of it is.''
the cost of campaigning keeps many out of the political arena, according to kerrey. the nebraska senate race could cost each candidate as much as $6 million, he said
if you don't conclude after this race that campaign spending restraints are needed, you've got a pretty warped sense about how democracy should operate.''
in kerrey's first political outing, he defeated incumbent republican gov. charles thone
during that campaign, he often spoke of the ``hopes and dreams'' of nebraskans and his vision of the future, and to some, he seemed a living symbol of determination. despite the loss of his right leg below the knee, he runs five miles every day
a troubled farm economy led to four years of tight budgets, and kerrey's readiness to trim state spending didn't endear him to some democrats or to state employees
no one tells you that everything will go your way just because you have good plans and good intentions,'' kerrey said. ``that's because things don't always go your way. so you do the best you can by facing the realities of the problems.''
the european parliament on wednesday rejected a european economic community financial aid package for israel in a protest of the nation's treatment of palestinians in the occupied territories
by a 205-143 vote, the parliament rejected the eec's agreement to provide israel with low-interest development loans of up to $76.9 million in the next four years
in separate votes, the parliament turned down two minor accords updating the eec's treaties on the sale of israeli farm produce in europe
this is the first time the parliament has rejected eec agreements since it was given the power last year to ratify foreign treaties
all three documents will have to go back to the 12 common market capitals for renegotiation, which could delay implementation for several months
the vote represents a sharp rebuke to israel for its policy in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
many deputies also criticized israel for breaching an unrelated pledge to allow palestinians to export their farm produce directly to europe. instead, all palestinian exports must be channeled through israeli authorities
sen. albert gore jr., looking for a new win to follow up his super tuesday successes, faced potential problems wednesday in both of the next two states on the democratic schedule
gore traveled to chicago with a recognition that illinois poses large obstacles to his candidacy, with two favorite sons _ jesse jackson and paul simon _ running hard for next tuesday's primary
south carolina democrats select delegates in caucuses on saturday, and gore had planned to fly to that state for campaigning on wednesday and thursday. but with jackson favored to win a lion's share of delegates in the state he was born in, gore postponed his visit until at least friday, campaign spokesman paul risley said
faced with the task of proving he has a truly national campaign, gore said he would compete head to head with simon, jackson and michael dukakis in illinois
it's true that there are two favorite sons in illinois,'' gore said as he flew to chicago from nashville, tenn. ``both of them have substantial support. we're going to be competing vigorously there.''
dukakis, also campaigning in illinois, taunted gore with his victories in the big southern states of texas and florida and questioned whether gore had in fact vaulted to the top tier of democratic contenders
i'm not so sure he's a major contender,'' dukakis said. ``a guy from massachusetts beat him in texas, beat him in florida. he wasn't willing to go into the early primaries. but i still take everyone seriously.''
gore also sought to parlay his strong showing on super tuesday into fund-raising strength. gore won six states: north carolina, kentucky, tennessee, arkansas, oklahoma and nevada
they've got a full press going,'' risley said of gore's campaign finance office, where at least ten fund-raisers were working the telephones all day wednesday
gore, too, was making phone calls to potential contributors and trying to strengthen his illinois campaign. the campaign expected to reach 10,000 people by telephone over 48 hours to ask them for contributions
in the past five days, we have raised $500,000. this victory caused tremendous response,'' gore said
the gore campaign took out a $1 million line of credit to air more television commercials in the final days of the southern campaign. officials said there was $500,000 and $1 million on hand
gore said the outcome of super tuesday, with wins for himself, jackson and dukakis, narrowed the field, and he suggested richard gephardt would be knocked from the race
it's a three-person race between gore and dukakis and jackson,'' he said
illinois' primary next tuesday offered only a week for gore to establish his credentials in a northern state. while he was campaigning there, his campaign considered how much money to invest in that state, regarding a large investment there as a high-risk strategy
beyond illinois on the democratic presidential calender are a series of big, northern states, including michigan on march 26
two or three days ago, the conventional wisdom ... was that super tuesday was going to spell the end of al gore's campaign. the conventional wisdom was wrong,'' gore said. ``sooner or later, it's going to stop being a surprise.''
the gore campaign suggested dukakis was not an electable candidate, with gore depicting both dukakis and jackson as representative of the democrats' debacles of 1984 and 1972. gore contended he was attracting the independent voters that democrats will need in november
they both offer a defense and foreign policy that has been rejected by the american people many times,'' gore said. ``i think the people are asking for more.'' israeli financial regulations.</note>
arab tax collectors resigned this week, giving impetus to a campaign by leaders of the palestinian uprising to cripple israel's occupation government in the west bank and gaza strip
israeli officials have fought to keep the resignations from taking place, warning those who quit they won't get severence pay and telling community leaders they may lose basic services
the resignations threaten to add to the financial burden of occupation and deprive israel of a potent symbol of cooperation and coexistence
you can't go against 600,000 people in gaza,'' said eid akram sharif, former head of the income tax department who led all 40 employes in a mass resignation
sharif, a plump, well-dressed man who nervously twirled his car keys as he spoke, drew nods of agreement from a half-dozen other ex-taxmen
they sat on chairs in a semi-circle on a dirt street in the relatively well-to-do ramali quarter. children on the corner erected a barricade. graffiti on a wall nearby declared the taxmen to be ``honorable brothers.''
before we were collaborators. now, we are nationalists,'' said sharif
but the taxmen were less than enthusiastic about their new roles as heroes of the three-month uprising. they felt trapped between the threats of arab militants and the pressure from israeli authorities who refused to accept the resignations
one of the resigned taxmen said israeli authorities warned him not to speak with the press or palestinian activists, saying they could get up to six months in jail for inciting violence
hafez al borno, a gray-haired man in his mid-40s, later drove a reporter downtown to point out a wall where graffiti demanded the tax department's resignation on palestinian flag day
arab employes of the income tax and value-added tax department must resign otherwise we will _'' said the graffiti, which ominously left unsaid what the punishment would be
as part of their three-month strike, palestinians in gaza and the west bank have refused to pay taxes. israeli authorities decline to give figures on the non-payment
israel imposed new rules last month on the occupied territories as a way to pressure the palestinians to end the activism. they require palestinians to prove they paid their taxes before they can travel abroad or import or export goods. they must also register when they bring $1,000 or more into the country. the previous limit was $5,000
the striking groups will have no mercy on anyone paying taxes. this money funds the occupation and is a tool of oppression,'' said a leaflet circulating in the west bank last week
new graffiti targeted police officers as the next to be called on to abandon their posts. ``yes to the resignation of police,'' one said
in a chilling warning this week in the west bank city of jericho, an arab policeman suspected of collaborating was stabbed to death. his body was wrapped in a palestinian flag and left on his mother's doorstep
in response to the plo campaign, a group of west bank police officers issued a statement stressing they were not involved in suppressing the riots
lt. mustafa adawi, spokesman for the group, was quoted by the daily al quds newspaper as saying before the killing that police limited their jobs to fighting ordinary crime and directing traffic
it is not their business to arrest protesters, prevent demonstration or inform on those who participate,'' he said. ``policemen are an integral part of the palestinian people and share their political aspirations for the future.''
palestinians claim that more than 20 of the estimated 300 police in gaza already have resigned
shmuel goren, government coordinator for the occupied territories, said the civil administration had 18,000 employes, about 11,000 of them teachers who were exempted from the strike call
we are today witnessing brutal plo threats against public officials and notables in the territories,'' goren was quoted a saying by the daily al hamishmar
a goren aide warned that life would only become more difficult for the 1.5 million palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip if israel had to assume the whole burden of administering the areas
public services will be damaged if they are to resign, and the only ones to suffer from these resignations, if they occur, will be the palestinians themselves,'' he said
the government provides electricity, water, road maintenance, garbage collection, health care and education
countering palestinian claims that israel profited financially from the occupation, a former military administrator said $160 million was in taxes was collected from the west bank last year and all of it was poured back into services for the 850,000 arab residents. figures for gaza were not available
the ex-official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said another $24 million in income and sales taxes was collected from the 110,000 palestinians working in israel and went to israel's treasury
leaflets last week called for collaborators to go to mosques and declare their repentence and for employees of israeli-appointed municipal councils to resign
in an apparent effort to win good will, the municipal authorities in the west bank towns of jenin and al bireh took out advertisements in newspapers to announce a 25 percent reduction for 1988-89 in property taxes and al bireh said it was eliminating city fees
gov. michael dukakis beat jesse jackson by a nearly 3-1 margin to win on home turf in massachusetts' democratic presidential primary, but fell short of the victory margin predicted in pre-election polls
it just goes to show you the only polls that count are the ones on election day,'' said steve akey, a dukakis spokesman. ``we are very pleased with the landslide victory here in massachusetts.''
with 2,114 of the 2,140 precincts or 99 percent reporting, dukakis had 413,806 votes or 59 percent; jackson had 130,643 votes or 19 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 72,053 votes or 10 percent, and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 31,575 votes or 4 percent
vice president george bush had 137,639 votes or 59 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 61,266 votes or 26 percent; new york rep. jack kemp had 16,331 votes or 7 percent, and former television evangeleist pat robertson had 10,779 votes or 5 percent
based on those results, bush would get 30 of massachusetts' 52 gop delegates to the national convention; dole would get 13; kemp 3; robertson 2, and 4 would be uncommitted. dukakis would get 79 of the state's 98 democratic delegates, and jackson would get 19
u.s. rep. chester atkins, the state democratic party chairman, said he had hoped dukakis would win at least 60 percent of the vote, but added, ``59 is close enough.''
dukakis may have been hurt by some of the ``tough positions (he has taken) over the years on things that were important for the state,'' atkins said
i also think that it's really a factor that in massachusetts, politics is a favorite contact sport and we're probably tougher on elected officials in massachusetts than any other state in the country,'' he said. ``we are the most critical electorate i think there is in america, which i think is positive.''
there were a lot of reasons why some voters didn't bother to make super tuesday a super turnout day. some of the best came from massachusetts and american samoa
the biggest primary-caucus day in history had been billed as a battle ``south of the mason-dixon line and the drive to dixie,'' according rep. chester atkins of massachusetts, the state democratic chairman
people in massachusetts,'' he observed, ``just don't think of themselves as part of the drive to dixie.''
in american samoa, where 300 democrats were eligible to take part in the caucuses, only 36 bothered to do so. national committeeman glenn jones provided a reason: residents of the u.s. territory can't vote in presidential elections
in many states, officials were jubilant over the numbers who cast ballots in primary elections, which traditionally get a far lower voter turnout than do the general elections in november. this year the turnout was higher because there was spice in the contested elections of both parties
the voting in florida fell short of the 50 to 55 percent predictions made last week, but still came to a respectable 42 percent of eligible democrats and 43 percent eligible republicans
i would presume a lot of the (george) bush supporters felt it was not necessary to go to the polls because he was leading by such a majority anyway,'' said dot joyce, state supervisor of the division of elections
it was that certainty for the outcome that also held down the turnout in massachusetts, said susan pye, a spokeswoman for the secretary of state
the biggest reason why people don't turn out and vote is because they feel that their vote doesn't matter,'' she said. only about a third of massachusetts' 2.9 million registered voters cast ballots, and ms. pye said it was confidence among democrats that gov. michael dukakis was a shoo-in in his home state. republicans assumed bush would win
taking a nose count in some of the 20 super tuesday states:
maryland: higher than predicted, but less than the 48 percent in the 1976 jimmy carter-jerry brown contest. of 1.3 million democrats, more than 500,000 or 38 percent cast ballots. of 520,000 registered republicans, 195,000 or 37.5 percent voted
hawaii: ``this is the first time we've really had a race; i don't remember this much excitement,'' said gov. john waihee, delighted that jesse jackson put up a strong challenge to dukakis, whom waihee supported. around 4,000 party members _ double the usual turnout _ attended democratic caucuses
texas: ``it's very clear super tuesday has been super for texas,'' said secretary of state jack rains. ``when i stop and think about the potential for this fall, i can get very excited.'' the turnout in texas was 35 percent of the 7.9 million registered voters _ more than 1 million republicans and 1.75 million democrats
wouldn't it be wonderful if we could bump our registration totals up to 8.5 million and get 50 percent of those or better to the polls, which would mean 4.25 million plus in november,'' rains said. ``i believe that's an achievable goal.''
arkansas: state auditor julia hughes jones had predicted a turnout of 514,000. it was 50,000 higher
georgia: the jimmy carter primary in 1976 had set a state record, but the mark was broken tuesday when 1 million of the state's 2.5 million registered voters cast ballots ``i love it when a plan comes together,'' said georgia secretary of state max cleland, one of the architects of super tuesday. ``this shows that a regional primary can focus time, attention, money and organizational talent on one particular goal.''
rhode island: ``some people might have thought it was a fait accompli _ that the vice president was going to win and that governor dukakis was going to win,'' said gop chairman j. michael levesque. the turnout was was 12.6 percent, best since the 14 percent in 1976
oklahoma: lee slater, secretary of the election board, had said anything over 500,000 would be a good turnout. by unofficial count, more than 600,00 voted. ``it's a wonderful turnout, it's a super turnout,'' slater says now
an alleged rapist whose genes match those of a rape victim's fetus may as well have left ``a full set of fingerprints, social security number and a signature'' at the scene of a crime, a medical expert testified
circuit judge marvin mounts is presiding in a hearing to determine whether genetic tests should be admitted in the trial of george forrest, charged with raping eight women between december 1986 and october 1987
four genetic tests on dna molecules from forrest's blood, a rape victim's blood and tissue from the fetus she aborted indicate that the fetus shared common genes
the tests showed a 99.99 percent probability that forrest fathered the child, said michael baird, laboratory manager of lifecodes corp., the elmsford, n.y., company that performed the tests
mounts has not ruled if the tests described tuesday will be used during forrest's trial
that's a narrow possibility, albeit a possibility,'' he said of the test results
forrest, 34, of boynton beach, is being held in the palm beach county jail. he was arrested as police sought a man they dubbed ``the congress avenue rapist,'' after the area in which the attacks occurred
he was charged with eight counts of sexual battery with a deadly weapon, six counts of sexual battery with force likely to cause serious personal injury, 4 counts of kidnapping, two counts of attempted sexual battery and one count of burglary while committing assault or battery
dr. karl muench, a professor of medicine at the university of miami, testified that dna tests are revolutionizing legal proceedings across the country. he said the results were as convincing as ``a full set of fingerprints, social security number and a signature'' left at a crime scene
the tests use blood, semen or human tissue and semen in a 200-step process that determines whether the genes of an alleged father match those of a child
dna, deoxyribonucleic acid, is the protein that carries an organism's genetic information. each dna molecule consists of four amino acids arranged in a code that is unique to each person
forrest's genetic code was determined through a blood sample and compared with that of a fetus aborted by a white woman he is accused of raping
the genetic code of the fetal material is so similar to that of forrest, who is black, that 533,790 other blacks would have to be chosen at random before one would be found with almost identical coding, baird said
asked by forrest's attorney, james cassidy, whether two brothers could produce the same test results because of similar genetic blueprints, baird said the possibility was remote unless they were identical twins
test results have been used in new york, california and virginia courts to link defendants to crimes, and lifecodes is working with the fbi to develop dna testing at its laboratories, baird said
in other cases, when dna tests have indicated that a defendant is not linked to a crime, the charges have been dropped, he said
federal tax refunds are averaging 6.2 percent more than last year, the internal revenue service said wednesday
through march 4, said spokesman wilson fadely, 12.66 million refunds had been certified, up slightly from the 12.6 million at this time a year ago. refunds averaged $802, up from $755 for the same period of 1987
the irs has processed 22.1 million of the 36.7 million returns received so far. the number of returns filed was 2.4 percent below last year's pace, although the gap was considerably less than four weeks ago
the irs has processed about 1 percent fewer returns than at this time last year. the backlog of unprocessed returns totals 14.6 million, down from 15.3 million last year
the filing deadline is april 15
a man apparently bent on revenge against a deputy city attorney who had successfully prosecuted him a day earlier opened fire wednesday in a courtroom, wounding a bailiff before he was killed, officials said
jeremy sigmond, 35, of woodland hills was killed in the shootout at los angeles municipal court in suburban van nuys at 10:15 a.m., said ted goldstein, a spokesman for the city attorney's office
the bailiff, county deputy marshal cliff wooford, 30, of palmdale, was shot in the abdomen and was undergoing surgery at st. joseph's medical center in burbank, said hospital spokeswoman linda roberts
the prosecutor, jessica silvers, 48, was ``shaken'' but unharmed, goldstein said
sigmond ``came looking for her today,'' goldstein said
i heard one shot, and then all the doors flew open and people started streaming outside,'' said becker mubani, who was outside the courtroom
sigmond was convicted in the same courtroom 24 hours earlier of four misdemeanor counts stemming from an oct. 22 chase by california highway patrol officers, goldstein said. he was eventually arrested in front of his woodland hills home, goldstein said
goldstein said he did not know what on charges sigmond was convicted or the sentences he received, but he said ms. silvers had not been threatened
he walked into the courtroom and (later) opened fire,'' said marshal's cmdr. clyde gatlin
mubani said that after the shooting he saw the bailiff running from the courtroom, ``his left hand covering the wound.''
the officer staggered down some steps to the sidewalk as other officers ran to assist him. mubani screamed, ``watch, watch, he's wounded.''
then the wounded officer began shouting, `where is the ambulance, where is the ambulance?''' mubani said
a 19-year-old soldier practicing a parachute jump became entangled in the doorway of an airplane and fell to his death, fort bragg officials and a newspaper said wednesday
the incident happened tuesday afternoon as the soldier was taking part in a training exercise over the base, said base spokeswoman carol jones
officials refused to give details of the accident, but the fayetteville observer quoted unidentified sources wednesday as saying a strap from the soldier's parachute gear begame entangled in the doorway as he exited the aircraft, and he fell out without opening the parachute at the proper time
he was pronounced dead where he landed, said master sgt. michael hartt. the soldier, a member of an airborne infantry regiment of the 82nd airborne division, was not identified pending notification of family
the death is the second fatal parachute accident in six years at the military base, ms. jones said
pat robertson finished poorly in super tuesday primaries because george bush won the votes of the conservative christian community considered most likely to support the former television evangelist, analysts said wednesday
exit polls said robertson failed to win majorities or even many pluralities of the fundamentalist, evangelical or born-again christian vote in the southern states
that's his group, and he didn't get them,'' said cbs news pollster kathleen a. frankovic. ``the core support that robertson expects to get clearly wasn't there.''
robertson finished second in iowa last month by drawing christian supporters to the caucuses. they made up 36 percent of the gop vote there, and he won half of the caucuses. in new hampshire, they made up just 9 percent, but again robertson won half
it was different in the south. in mississippi, where 24 percent of the gop voters said they were fundamentalist or evangelical christians, bush won with 49 percent of the group, to 31 percent for robertson, frankovic said
bush also won the fundamentalist vote in alabama; robertson won it in georgia and the two men split it in north carolina, the cbs-times polls said
other network polls used other gauges but found similar results. abc news said 34 percent of the gop voters in the south said they were born-again christians and 40 percent of them backed bush, to 35 percent for robertson
nbc said the born-again christian vote ranged from 28 percent in alabama to 63 percent in tennessee. bush won it in alabama, louisiana, tennessee and texas and split it with robertson in arkansas, nbc polls said
it's pretty tough to put together a winning coalition if that's his secret army. he's not getting more than a third of them anyplace,'' said sheldon gawiser, an nbc poll analyst
frankovic said overwhelming approval in the south for vice president bush and the reagan administration cut into robertson's support, and he may have been damaged by negative publicity. robertson last week dropped his libel suit over charges that he shirked combat duty in korea, still maintaining that the allegation was untrue
there was something pulling people to support bush and there wasn't something pulling fundamentalists to support robertson,'' frankovic said
but claibourne h. darden jr., a pollster in atlanta, had another view: he said robertson never had support from more than a hard core within the ranks of fundamentalists, who make up a much larger group in the south than elsewhere
so many people consider themselves fundamentalists in the south that it gets out of the core group and becomes the norm,'' darden said. ``he's got the hard core. he doesn't have any more than that and he never did.''
in iowa, where voter turnout is low, and in new hampshire, darden said, the fundamentalist vote was made up largely of the small central core of robertson supporters. ``anywhere you get a large turnout'' _ as in the south _ ``that core shrinks in percentage,'' he said
the robertson campaign took a similar line. ``part of the problem has been the perception that this group is a monolithic group,'' said campaign spokeswoman teresa george. ``we've been telling people they aren't.''
as the race moves north, said george, ``i don't think there's any doubt that pat robertson is going to try to reach those people,'' even he tries to build new support in other groups
the margin of sampling error for the polls was about 5 points
responsibility for the car bomb discovered near the hotel where secretary of state george p. shultz was staying remained a matter of conflict wednesday within the palestine liberation organization
hours after the bomb was found and removed by israeli police on march 5, a spokesman in beirut for yasser arafat's fatah faction of the plo claimed responsibility for the bombing attempt and said shultz was the target
the spokesman is well-known to beirut news organizations and often is in telephone contact with correspondents. the claim was widely reported and the various plo factions did not challenge it immediately or in subsequent days
but when an associated press correspondent contacted another plo spokesman in tunis on march 7, he denied the plo had planted the bomb. ahmed abderrahman, a member of fatah's central committee, blamed mossad, israel's secret service
abderrahman claimed israel was trying to harden anti-palestinian sentiment in washington and prevent the possible acceptance of the plo in any peace talks
the ap then asked bassam abu sharif, a close arafat aide, and he also denied fatah involvement in the bombing attempt
it is nothing to do with palestinians whatsoever,'' he said by telephone from tunis. ``the car bomb was a clear israeli trick to make it look like the palestinians wanted to blow up shultz and to make the israeli security services look good by discovering this so-called bomb.''
it is not unusual to receive several claims by competing palestinian groups. and some palestinian sources say that is done on purpose to confuse israeli and western intelligence services about which group is behind attacks
but on other occasions, plo and fatah officials have denied their fighters were involved when they considered claiming responsibility would harm their cause
on monday, when an israeli bus was hijacked by three palestinian guerrillas there was agreement that fatah had carried out the action that ended with the deaths of the three guerrillas and three passengers on the bus
again, the beirut source issued the initial claim that fatah was responsible. this time, abu sharif confirmed the claim, saying: ``fatah carried out the attack on the bus.''
so did azam al-ahmad, the plo representative in baghdad, where arafat has his military headquarters. al-ahmad, who also is a senior fatah official, said the guerrillas hijacked the bus carrying workers from israel's top-secret dimona nuclear power plant in the negev with the aim of holding them hostage
on wednesday, however, hekmat zaid, chief of the plo mission in budapest, told reporters: ``the aim of the palestinian commando action ... was not to take hostages, the plan of the plo's armed men was to enter the strictly guarded complex by overpowering the bus that carried the workers of the dimona nuclear center.''
the president of the national association of evangelicals said wednesday colleges have undergone such a radical transformation from their religious beginnings that many are now systematically undermining christian values
many institutions of higher learning have surrendered the ethical and moral sanctions upon which they were built,'' ray h. hughes told delegates attending the group's convention here
they have been cut off from their ``deep roots in the christian faith'' and offer up a wide range of ideologies, ``cafeteria-style,'' he said
however, he said, the evangelical schools that were founded as a defense to materialism and secular teachings are themselves moving away from their basic religious foundations and are in danger of becoming ``pale carbon copies'' of those secular colleges
evangelical colleges have to return to the principles of spiritual commitment, hughes said, because the nation faces ``a generation of students for whom much in life has lost its meaning, for whom morality has lost its moorings.''
the organization, which represents more than 50,000 churches from 72 protestant denominations, is holding a series of workshops and seminars on the theme ``go teach.''
among the speakers is the rev. jerry falwell, whose thursday speech will address television evangelism and its problems
u.s. education secretary william j. bennett told the group earlier that he was angry about the well-publicized scandals involving television preachers
it doesn't help my cause to teach moral values when those who speak the loudest cannot live up to their own beliefs,'' bennett said tuesday
another speaker, m. wayne benson, senior pastor of the first assembly of god church in grand rapids, mich., warned his audience to be careful during these ``perilous days.''
it's a deception of satan to think that any ministry is above human frailty,'' benson said
benson, bennett, hughes and others named no names and avoided any discussion of the latest scandal in evangelism broadcasting. famed tv evangelist jimmy swaggart stepped down from his pulpit last month after tearfully telling his congregation he had sinned; published reports said he paid a prostitute to pose naked for him
falwell, who is not a member of the national association of evangelicals, will speak to the organization for the first time. he accepted an invitation from the national religious broadcasters, a member group of the nae which last month adopted a stringent code of ethics for its 1,350 member organizations
several hundred voting delegates of the nae approved a number of resolutions of faith, including one on illegal drugs that supports efforts of the president and mrs. reagan in calling for ``an all-out war to end this travesty.''
the national assembly has approved unanimously a new constitution that will do away with the concept of ``president for life.''
the new constitution, approved tuesday night on its first reading, will take effect after its approval by two-thirds of the national assembly. the vote is expected later this year
former president-for-life habib bourguiba, who ruled tunisia without interruption for 32 years following the end of french colonial rule in 1956, was ousted nov. 7 by his prime minister, zine el abidine ben ali
ben ali justified the bloodless coup on grounds that the 84-year-old bourguiba had become senile and unable to exercise his duties and that tunisia needed to revert to genuine democratic rule
bourguiba, who formerly controlled 100 percent of the national assembly, had himself named president-for-life by assembly members in march 1975
the former leader has remained confined in his chateau near tunis since the coup. all mention of his name has been banished from the media in this north african arab nation
but the former leader, whose photograph for years was featured prominently in every television broadcast and on the front page of every newspaper, remains an unspoken factor in tunisian politics
tunisian sources said he has steadfastly resisted pressure from the government to issue a public endorsement of ben ali as tunisia's president
yet no voice was raised in tribute to him when the national assembly, exclusively composed of members of the ruling constitutional democratic rally, debated the new constitution
the constitutional democratic rally is the new name of bourguiba's ruling destourian socialist party. the name change was approved feb. 28
under the new constitution, the president will be elected for five-year terms. the president can be reelected but must face voters every five years
a man authorities said used his own paycheck stub to write a holdup note at a bank was indicted wednesday on federal robbery charges
kevin d. thompson, 26, was accused in the robbery of $8,000 from a bloomfield branch of midlantic national bank on june 22. he was being held in lieu of $75,000 bail at the metropolitan correctional center
according to a criminal complaint, the money was handed over after a teller received a note saying, ``this is a stickup, keep clam i have a gun give me some $100, 50, &amp; 20 keep clam and no won will get harm. thank you.''
the note was written on a stub from systems maintenance corp. of fairfield, where thompson had worked and was absent on june 22, the complaint said. the stub had no names on it, but listed specific pay figures
the government's complaint said an anonymous caller last month described the getaway car, identified thompson, gave thompson's address and gave other details
but the defendant's attorney, lawrence lustberg, said his client was innocent
he has no idea how his stub came to be used and was ``educated enough to know to spell not like the note is spelled,'' lustberg said
a new daily newspaper debuts monday when the south west news-sun, a weekly newspaper for 96 years, begins publishing six days a week
the news-sun will report community news and sports in libertyville, mundelein and vernon hills, as well as state and national news, said publisher glenn pfeil
the south west news-sun is affiliated with copley press, whose illinois holdings also include the aurora beacon-news, elgin courier news, joliet herald-news, lincoln courier, springfield journal-register, wheaton daily journal and its sister newspaper, the news-sun of waukegan
to accommodate the changes, the newspaper has added five new editorial positions, three advertising representatives, and additional office and circulation department personnel, said jan gehrig, managing editor
a soviet opera singer who defected to sweden was reunited with his wife wednesday after almost seven years, auguring improved swedish-soviet relations
during all these years, the hope never left me,'' vera morozov told swedish radio after arriving by ship at a stockholm harbor
alex morozov, who was living in leningrad, defected in june 1981 during a concert stop in goteborg
in january, he protested to press for his wife's visa during an official visit of soviet premier nikolai ryzhkov to goteborg
soviet approval of her visa resolved the last of 21 human rights cases raised by prime minister ingvar carlsson on a visit to moscow in 1986
we have ... noted a pronounced thaw in the ice, a change, from before'' in the soviet attitude, said a spokeswoman for the swedish foreign ministry
the two countries have resolved three other asylum issues since carlsson's 1986 visit. the foreign ministry spokeswoman was unsure if other cases were pending
two cousins who hadn't seen each other in 60 years had an unexpected reunion in a hospital waiting room, where one had gone to have a shoulder injury examined and the other was seeking treatment of lung congestion
elmer gnau, 73, on vacation from la grange, ky., wound up sitting just one seat away from kenneth gnau, 63, of margate, at hca university hospital on tuesday
when the nurse came out and called `gnau,' both men stood up
i looked at him and asked him his name,'' said elmer gnau, a retired tool and dye maker. ``i knew if he said kenneth, he would be my cousin. not many people are named gnau.''
the chance meeting was emotional for the first cousins, who last saw each other when they were children in louisville, ky
i never thought i would have recognized him,'' said kenneth gnau. ``but i looked up, and my stomach came right up to my throat. he has the face of my father. i almost cried.''
elmer gnau was in florida to visit his son, jerry gnau, in north lauderdale. still suffering from congested lungs after a bout with pneumonia a month ago, he went to the doctor for a prescription to clear up the infection
kenneth gnau, who retired to margate with his wife, was waiting to have an x-ray taken of a shoulder injury
jerry gnau's daughter, teresa, said her family had tried to find kenneth gnau three years ago when they saw a picture of his motorboat in a newspaper. the boat had exploded in a canal in margate, but kenneth gnau's phone number wasn't listed
the cousins planned to visit each other later this week after kenneth gnau undergoes an operation for his injured shoulder
the only effective way to prevent the spread of aids is to halt sex outside marriage and to end intravenous drug abuse, the vatican newspaper said wednesday in a major statement on the disease
the prevention of aids has moral implications of a reach greater than what it seemed at first,'' said the unsigned editorial on the front page of l'osservatore romano, the vatican's daily newspaper
the responsibility for the battle against the evil does not fall only on the shoulders of some doctors and researchers, but, on the contrary, must be shared by everybody,'' it said
the vatican newspaper said the defeat of aids ``requires an effort extended to modify and to overcome ethically aberrant behaviors.''
the only really effective measure is prevention ... avoiding the causes of contagion, which means, in 95 percent of the cases, abstaining from sexual practice outside marriage and from consuming drugs,'' the editorial said
it said medical and ethical prescriptions have coincided before, such as the campaign against smoking and calls for moderation in diet
the newspaper said trying to prevent aids ``by promoting the use of condoms ... is not only scarcely trustworthy from the technical point of view, but also and above all inacceptable from the moral point of view.''
in december, a report by the administrative board of the united states catholic conference said instruction about condoms in aids education programs could be permitted in the context of church teaching advocating ``abstinence outside of marriage and fidelity within marriage.''
cardinal john j. o'connor of new york called the report a ``very grave mistake'' and said he will not allow such instruction
