george bush paused briefly wednesday to savor the fruits of his stunning super tuesday success while his aides toted up the vice president's advantages in next week's illinois primary
campaign manager lee atwater cautioned against overconfidence following bush's 16-state primary sweep. but the vice president enters his illinois campaign with the support of gov. james thompson and most other state party officials, as well as the lead in public and private polls
the vice president's aides also have mapped their largest single-state television advertising effort of the campaign in the days before illinois votes
bush's super tuesday showing left him with roughly 700 of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the nomination, and illinois offers the possibility of another 92
aides agreed that his close identification with president reagan helped bush on super tuesday. but a key strategist said it would be ``clearly an oversimplification'' to credit bush's lopsided victory to reagan's popularity
bush himself rested wednesday before plunging into his campaign in illinois on thursday. his aides tried to avoid sounding overconfident the day after his string of victories
i'd rather be more like ronald reagan and be cautiously optimistic,'' said deputy campaign manager rich bond. ``it's a marathon and we've got to play this thing through until we're mathematically certain that we're going to win the nomination.''
atwater had said late tuesday, ``the second in this business you start resting on laurels ... is the second you start getting in trouble.''
the vice president's aides said they could not quarrel with exit polls showing bush benefited handsomely from his association with reagan. but lanny griffith, who was bush's southern regional political director, said he thought the coattail effect was exaggerated

his strength was the work that was done in the 14 months leading up to super tuesday,'' griffith said in an interview. ``the real heroes were the people that put this thing together.''
griffith said that bush's ties to reagan helped, ``but that's clearly an oversimplification. the vice president has shown that he is as strong on the issues as any candidate.''
a cbs-new york times exit poll said that in some states, as many as four out of five republican voters approved of reagan and that three out of five of them backed bush
he stayed away from political rhetoric as usual. he stayed away from name-calling,'' atwater said. and he said bush's association with ``a very successful administration'' played a big role in his victories
rep. lynn martin, r-ill., co-chairman of bush's illinois campaign, attributed at least part of bush's super tuesday success to mistakes by sen. bob dole of kansas
i think he's terrific. i think he's funny. i think a lot of him,'' she said of dole. ``but bob dole did himself in'' by seeming too ingracious after losing the new hampshire primary to bush, she said
in a telehone interview, she said bush is being perceived as sending a more positive message
i don't think it's because george bush suddenly became so charismatic that you couldn't take your eyes off him,'' she said
bush carried all but the state of washington tuesday, winning around 600 delegates, the largest one-day collection in the history of presidential nomination politics
by refusing to meet dole in one-on-one debates in illinois, and by hewing closely to a campaign regimen that has bush mixing frequently with people and posing for pictures, the vice president's strategists signaled they plan no change in campaign style
the vice president is going to go and do in illinois what he did in new hampshire and in south carolina, and that is, go through all corners of the state, campaign directly and forthrightly and get his message out,'' atwater said
bush is scheduled to campaign nonstop in illinois from thursday through monday, including a one-day flying tour of the state
