opponents of vice president george bush credited his huge kentucky win to president reagan's popularity, while tennessee sen. albert gore jr. got help in the democratic primary from the state's governor
bush's 16-state primary sweep over kansas sen. bob dole in the south and elsewhere on super tuesday ``will practically cinch the bush nomination,'' said u.s. rep. harold ``hal'' rogers, who led bush's state campaign
george bush is not just whistling dixie, he's got the full orchestra behind him,'' rogers said wednesday
gore emerged from kentucky's primary with less than half the popular vote, but with the backing of gov. wallace wilkinson he could control more than two-thirds of the state's 62 delegates
with all of the 3,243 democratic precincts reporting, gore had 145,201 votes or 46 percent, followed by massachusetts gov. michael dukakis with 59,424 votes or 19 percent and jesse jackson with 49,659 votes or 16 percent
gore won 37 of the 55 pledged delegates, dukakis had 12 and jackson, six. wilkinson, however, will be able to control at least four of the party's unpledged official delegates, giving gore a solid two-thirds of the total delegation
al gore is right for kentucky; he's right for america. we're just now starting the momentum in this campaign,'' wilkinson said tuesday
in the republican race, with 100 percent of the vote counted, bush had 71,954 votes or 59 percent, to 27,845 votes or 23 percent for dole
state sen. john rogers, of the dole campaign in kentucky, said there had been hopes of getting up to 40 percent of the vote for the senator, but ``a security vote'' brought the republicans out for bush
he was just more closely associated with reagan and the majority of people _ republicans anyway _ liked what reagan's done for the last eight years,'' rogers said
bush won 27 of the state's 38 delegates and dole captured the other 11
