a continental jetliner that had two tires blow out while landing at newark international airport was flying without a special braking device that prevents such incidents, authorities said
the federal aviation administration is investigating the trouble with the landing monday of dc9 flight 612 from rochester, n.y., said faa spokeswoman kathleen bergen
legally the airline could fly the jet without the braking device for three days before fixing it, ms. bergen said
none of the 29 passengers or crew was hurt when both tires on the main landing gear under the left wing failed, ms. bergen said
passengers were taken to the terminal by bus, said rick scott, a continental spokesman
the device is called an ``anti-skid'' braking system, which is supposed to prevent pilots from applying the brakes too hard, officials said. if the brakes are applied too hard they can lock and cause blowouts, officials said
scott said the inoperable braking device had nothing to do with the tire blowouts. he said the pilot reported the tires blew ``immediately upon landing'' and before the brakes could be applied
