the united states is considering ways to help merchant ships which aren't flying the u.s. flag in the war-torn persian gulf, defense secretary frank c. carlucci said wednesday
we are examining a number of options in this regard, but serious policy, legal, economic and force level issues remain,'' carlucci told the house foreign affairs committee
since last july 22, the navy has been protecting 11 kuwaiti-owned tankers which were reflagged with the star and stripes. the large-scale convoy operation increased the number of navy ships in the area from six to about 30
the kuwaiti ships are being protected against attack by iran, which has been at war for seven and one-half year with iraq, an ally of kuwait
the reagan administration has been asked for aid by u.s. shipowners using so-called flags of convenience, such as panama and liberia. the navy has consistently refused, citing u.s. policies of helping only american-flagged ships
u.s. shipowners ``continue to ask us to provide protection to their non-u.s. flag vessels,'' carlucci said. ``despite our humanitarian desire to be helpful, our longstanding requirement for ships to be flying the u.s. flag remains very persuasive.''
absent a u.s. flag, we believe a substantial foreign force operational commitment would be mandatory,'' he noted
carlucci did not explain, nor was he asked, what other measures are being considered
however, some shipowners have pushed to have the u.s. navy freed to protect shipping under attack if the navy warships are in the vicinity. there have been a number of incidents where navy warships were nearby when non-u.s.-flagged vessels were under attack
the navy has actually decreased the number of ships in the gulf area, carlucci noted, after the battleship iowa and helicopter carrier okinawa were withdrawn earlier this year
the withdrawal ``does not represent any change in our policy or any weakening of our capability,'' carlucci noted. ``the numbers will continue to fluctuate somewhat, but our steadfast commitment along with our capabilities will remain a constant as long as our presence is required.''
american allies in europe are providing a wide range of help for the navy in the persian gulf, carlucci noted
most of that aid comes from allied minesweepers, which were sent into the region after the first of the reflagged kuwaiti tankers hit a mine last july 24 and other mines were found in the following months
japan is also providing financial help, carlucci noted, but is prohibited by its u.s.-written laws from sending ships to the region
carlucci said the pentagon is considering the sale of four aegis defense systems to japan for use in the japanese navy. each would cost about $1 billion
the aegis, with its sophisticated electronics, is considered the world's most advanced air defense system and plays a key role in navy plans to defend american ships in wartime
rep. olympia snowe, r-maine, noted that the sale could be ``a serious problem'' if any of aegis equipment were resold to american enenies. she noted that a japanese company, toshiba, reported helped sell sophisticated equipment to the soviet union which the soviets then used to make much quieter submarines
there has never been a compromise by the japanese government,'' said carlucci, noting that the previous incident involved a private company
but snowe noted that ``even though the japanese government was not involved in the toshiba case, there have been a series of problems with other nations.''
carlucci said, ``we have no reason to question the sincerity of the japanese government.''
adm. william crowe jr., chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, noted calls in congress for japan to do more in its own defense. selling the aegi systems to japan ``would buttress our position in the northwest pacific'' and improve the navy's ability to operate with the japanese navy, he noted
treasury secretary james a. baker iii said wednesday that the need for an independent federal reserve did not mean the central bank should be ``totally sheltered from outside advice or criticism.''
baker defended the administration against charges that it had sought to bring undue political pressure on the central bank to insure that the economy continues growing without a recession during this presidential election year
testifying before the joint economic committee of congress, baker was asked specifically about a letter that assistant treasury secretary michael darby sent to the central bank on jan. 28 in which darby warned that slow growth of the money supply was threatening a recession
darby's letter was sent to every member of the federal open market committee two weeks before a crucial meeting in which the group was to set monetary growth targets for this year. the central bank seeks to provide enough money to the banking system to promote healthy economic growth while guarding against supplying so much money that it threatens higher inflation
sen. william proxmire, d-wis., said that in 30 years in congress he had never seen such ``overt, direct interference with the independent federal reserve.'' proxmire, chairman of the senate banking committee, asked whether darby faced any disciplinary action for his letter
baker said the darby letter had been sent without his knowledge and when he learned about it, he told darby not to do it again. but baker denied that darby's letter, which he characterized as raising academic questions about monetary growth, was an example of administration pressure
on feb. 24, federal reserve chairman alan greenspan issued a rare public warning to the administration to stop pressing the fed to lower interest rates, contending that further pressure might force the central bank to demonstrate its independence by doing exactly the opposite
greenspan specifically cited the darby letter, saying he had objected to the letter strongly with an administration official, later identified as baker
administration critics charged that the darby letter was just one example of administration pressure on the federal reserve to keep the economy expanding as a way of boosting republican chances of holding onto the white house
baker denied these accusations and said he had never engaged in ``fed bashing'' since becoming treasury secretary in 1985. he said he had worked closely with both greenspan and former fed chairman paul volcker in an effort to coordinate policies on a whole range of economic issues including international debt, currency exchange rates, the government's tax and budget policies and monetary policy
the federal reserve ought to be independent, but that does not mean that they should be totally sheltered from outside advice or criticism,'' he said. ``it is my view that the administration has a right and a responsibility to advise the federal reserve on all elements of economy policy, just as we welcome their advice to us on all elements of economic policy.''
baker added, ``the federal reserve is independent and it ought to remain independent, but it is independent within this government and it is not independent of this government.''
on another matter, baker said he did not view the big rise in the value of the british pound in recent days as a breach of the currency stabilization agreement between the united states, britain and five other top industrial countries reached last december
baker said british prime minister margaret thatcher had not informed the united states beforehand of her government's decision not to intervene in currency markets to stop the rise of the pound against the u.s. dollar and other currencies
baker said he did not see the rise in the pound as jeopardizing the dec. 22 accord between the united states and other top industrialized countries to stabilize the value of the dollar around current exchange rates
we don't see this as in any way running counter to that agreement or being somehow a repudiation of it,'' he said, adding that the recent increase in the british pound had more to do with british interest rates and monetary policy decisions in that country. mississippi</head>
acknowledging that he won't match his opponent dollar-for-dollar, u.s. rep. beau boulter on wednesday challenged millionaire wes gilbreath to a series of joint appearances in the runoff for the republican senate nomination in texas
in mississippi, republican rep. trent lott promised an issue-based campaign against rep. wayne dowdy, who won the democratic nomination tuesday for the seat being vacated by sen. john stennis
we're not running against anybody,'' lott said
in other super tuesday primaries, democratic sen. paul sarbanes won renomination in maryland and will face political newcomer thomas blair in november. in louisiana, a republican led the pack but still faces a runoff for the 4th district seat in congress
it will take a united democratic party to beat him (lott),'' dowdy said. ``it can be won, and things are ripe for the democrats to win in november. mississippi should have at least one democrat in the u.s. senate.''
sen. thad cochran, a republican, holds the state's other seat
dowdy polled 189,203 votes or 54 percent to defeat secretary of state dick molpus, who had 148,051 or 42 percent. pipefitter gilbert fountain had 13,244 votes or 4 percent
both parties will have runoffs march 29 to choose nominees to succeed dowdy, who won his seat in 1981, and lott, who was elected in 1972
boulter, 44, who is giving up the house seat he has held for two terms to run for senate, finished second to gilbreath tuesday
with 89 percent of the vote counted, gilbreath had 252,213 or 36 percent and boulter had 202,326 or 29 percent. former state rep. milton fox of austin had 132,787 or 19 percent and businessman ned snead of georgetown had 103,979 or 15 percent
gilbreath, a millionaire from houston, spent $500,000 on the race while boulter's campaign cost an estimated $130,000
we want to force mr. gilbreath out from behind his own personal money, and billboards and television,'' boulter said
gilbreath, the only candidate to use television ads in the senate primary, acknowledged that he was not well-known when he entered the race and was delighted to finish first on tuesday
i think it's unheard of in texas politics to accomplish that,'' said gilbreath, 59
boulter estimated the campaign for the april 12 runoff would cost ``a few hundred thousand dollars,'' but added, ``i don't think we need to compete with him (gilbreath) dollar-for-dollar.''
democratic sen. lloyd bentsen easily won the democratic nomination for a fourth term and expressed no interest in who the republicans choose to oppose him
i don't look on anyone as unbeatable. i'm going to work very hard as i always do,'' said bentsen, 66
thomas blair, a millionaire businessman who captured 46 percent of the vote in a nine-man republican senate primary in maryland, celebrated his victory by accusing sarbanes of being an absentee senator
i predict this summer mr. sarbanes, who we have not seen for years, will come out,'' blair said, comparing the senator to a cicada, the insect which turns up every 17 years
picking up an issue from the republican primary, sarbanes said: ``the republican nominee hasn't even bothered to vote over the last six years, and was taken off the election rolls, which i think tells you something about his commitment to the political process.''
in louisiana, republican jim mccrery finished ahead of nine democrats in a non-partisan election for the the 4th district house seat, which will be vacated monday by mccrery's old boss, democratic governor-elect buddy roemer
mccrery will meet state sen. foster campbell in a runoff on april 16
