solidarity leader lech walesa criticized police on wednesday for using force to break up student demonstrations in warsaw and krakow
walesa made his remarks one day after club-wielding riot police clashed with youths demonstrating for more academic freedom on the 20th anniversary of student protests against censorship and political repression
on tuesday, police charged into hundreds of demonstrators in warsaw and krakow and made scores of arrests
the leader of the outlawed labor federation said he expected authorities eventually to admit error in using force against students this year
i don't have a detailed account of what happened, but i think that in a few years' time there shall be great efforts to disavow all that took place,'' walesa said before meeting with austrian foreign minister alois mock in warsaw
the authorities use ``such a method of disavowing things that should not have taken place at all,'' he said
a commentary by the official polish news agency pap said that in warsaw and krakow ``attempts were made to take advantage'' of anniversary observances to hold illegal demonstrations
the attempts were abortive owing to the lack of wider support and thanks to the determined attitude of the forces of law and order,'' pap said
the students were calling for restoration of academic freedoms won during the 1980-81 solidarity labor upheaval and for legalization of the independent students union, which was outlawed under martial law was imposed in 1982
zygmunt lenyk, a krakow opposition spokesman, said at least 64 people were detained in the southern polish city, but everyone was released later tuesday. an aide to government spokesman jerzy urban said a total of 83 people were detained in tuesday's demonstrations but less than 15 people remained in custody, awaiting appearances in misdemeanor courts
the student protests of 20 years ago were violently broken up by police and worker activists. but the communist polish united workers party recently disavowed repressive measures used against reform-oriented intellectuals 20 years ago. pvs., ``vice president ...''</note>
president reagan renewed his vow of neutrality in the republican presidential race wednesday, while white house chief of staff howard baker said ``it would take a major event'' to deny george bush the nomination
i will remain neutral,'' reagan told inquiring reporters as he returned to the white house from a trip to notre dame university in south bend, ind. he seemed bouyant, dribbling a basketball he got at notre dame and passing it back and forth with a woman well-wisher
baker, talking with reporters earlier, said, ``the president is still neutral and i expect will continue that way for the foreseeable future.''
vice president bush scored a sweep of the super tuesday primaries, moving within reach of the gop presidential nomination
he was the front-runner before and clearly is the front-runner now,'' said baker. ``i think it would take a major event to deny him the nomination. he's certainly got the momentum.''
baker, who dropped out of the presidential race a year ago to lead reagan's staff, said the last word he had from reagan was that as the titular head of the republican party, he intended to remain neutral
and whether he would re-address that in light of other circumstances, we'll have to wait and see but i have no indication of it,'' the former senator said
baker said reagan was ``awful pleased with the exit polls,'' which showed an 84 percent approval rating for the president among republican voters in the south
i told him this morning ... he was really the one who swept the south,'' baker said. ``i think that was a matter of pride for the president.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater, traveling with reagan aboard air force one to south bend, ind., also described the president as ``very impressed with the republican turnout.''
we have a strong movement toward the republican party in the south,'' fitzwater said. he called it a ``strong indication of the realignment that's taken place'' in the region
citing texas as an example, fitzwater said that 500,000 persons voted on the gop side during the primary season in 1980 and 900,000 voted in the gop ranks in 1988
baker said the overall republican voter turnout was about 44 percent of the total vote cast tuesday
so that's a far cry from the old democratic solid south and that may be the most significant single aspect of super tuesday,'' baker said
he said the gop turnout ``indicates that the reagan revolution and the republican growth in the south is not a transient phenomenon but is a permanent fixture in the american political system
commenting on the outcome on the democratic side, baker singled out the success of fellow tennessean albert gore jr., who won his own state and four other souther primaries
al gore may have demolished the theory that you've got to run in iowa and new hampshire. he is a very credible candidate and he did not make a major effort in iowa and new hampshire,'' baker said. groups</head>
fbi files declassified wednesday quoted three intelligence operatives as saying they had been directed by high-level fbi and cia officials to infiltrate the political organizations of lyndon larouche
excerpts from the files, surrendered to defense lawyers in the fraud and conspiracy trial of larouche, six aides and five of his political groups, showed that one of the three refused to discuss his larouche-related dealings with low-level fbi officials, saying he had been instructed by ranking officials at the agencies not to do so
that man, retired army sgt. maj. fred lewis, also was referred to in a memo from retired air force maj. gen. richard secord to marine lt. col. oliver north in which secord indicated lewis had collected evidence against larouche
both the declassified fbi material and the secord memo were dated in may 1986 and refer to giving lewis a polygraph to determine if his information was valid
lawyers for larouche, a political extremist who has accused such international figures as queen elizabeth ii of drug trafficking, have obtained growing evidence in recent weeks of infiltration of larouche groups by the fbi and cia. they contend the effort was directed by north, the former national security council aide fired for his role in the iran-contra scandal. secord worked with north to set up a private network to aid the contra rebels in nicaragua
the defense lawyers, who have requested thousands of other documents from the fbi, cia and nsc, contend the records will prove their claim that charges of credit card fraud and conspiracy against larouche and his followers were concocted as part of a government plot to ruin larouche because he refused to support aid to the contras
this was an activity that was headed up by oliver north and mr. secord in a political attempt to stop the larouche people,'' defense attorney michael reilly said wednesday
the defense lawyers also have said they believe they have grounds for dismissal of the case because of prosecutorial misconduct, contending the government has deliberately withheld evidence of fbi and cia penetration of larouche groups
the three men referred to in the declassified fbi material are lewis, gary s. howard and ron tucker
lewis, tucker and howard indicated they have a very high level source in the federal government who advises them regularly concerning cooperation or lack thereof between lewis and his associates and the federal government,'' the document said
when asked about their possible ties to larouche, they claimed to have been previously been requested by the fbi and cia to penetrate the larouche organization,'' said the document, which was excerpted from an unidentified fbi file
according to the material, lewis said he had been instructed by contacts in cia and fbi headquarters not to discuss his larouche ties without authorization from top officials at the agencies
defense attorney daniel alchorn, who represents larouche aide paul goldstein, said during wednesday's hearing that lewis was a principal in a dallas-based group known as peregrine international, which he said was tied to secord and helped carry out covert activities for the u.s. government
in the north-secord memo, there is a reference by secord to ``our man.'' the defense lawyers said they have been informed by the government that the reference is to oliver revell, an fbi assistant director invovled in counterintelligence
tucker, a former texas department of public safety narcotics agent, and howard, a former border patrol agent, claim in a suit against the customs service that they have been government informants since 1979
in the suit, filed in washington in august, tucker and howard say the government owes them $1.4 million for their expenses in a sting operation that led to the arrest of a man allegedly buying arms for iran. they claim the government lost interest in prosecuting the case because it would have revealed the reagan administration's arms shipments to iran and the diversion of profits from the sales to the contras
the fbi document also said that during interviews with fbi agents in texas, tucker and howard said they had approached family and friends of soviet dissidents andrei sakharov and his wife, yelena bonner, claiming they could free the couple from the soviet union for $2 million. ``no further information was available concerning this matter,'' the document said
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. narrowly defeated jesse jackson in a north carolina presidential primary that observers said showed the changing face of southern democratic politics
it shows there are many souths _ no solid south,'' said merle black, political science professor at the university of north carolina. ``it's too diverse.''
meanwhile, vice president george bush's lopsided victory in the republican primary showed his links with president reagan were stronger than kansas sen. bob dole's ties to north carolina. dole's wife, elizabeth, is a native of salisbury, n.c
what george bush has shown is that he is strong in the south,'' said jack hawke, state gop chairman. ``people are associating him with the president.''
bush held off a late surge by dole, who targeted north carolina in his effort to avoid a southern shutout. bush had said he was worried because polls had indicated the contest was neck-and-neck
with all 2,387 precincts reporting, gore had 235,345 votes or 35 percent; jackson had 223,207 votes or 33 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 137,755 votes or 20 percent, and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 37,483 votes or 6 percent
in the republican race, bush had 124,028 votes or 45 percent; dole had 109,999 votes or 40 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 26,747 votes or 10 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 11,364 votes or 4 percent
based on those results, bush was expected to win 29 gop delegates and dole 25. gore would capture 34 democratic delegates, jackson 31 and dukakis 17
gore carried north carolina becuse he ``has a lot of appeal to middle-of-the road, common sense democrats,'' said former gov. jim hunt, who with sen. terry sanford endorsed gore in january
black, however, said the closeness of the race indicated many conservative democrats had not voted
i don't think gore would have made any showing if jim hunt and terry sanford had not gotten active in his campaign like they did,'' said dan blue, a black state representative who was state chairman for jackson
republican pat robertson said wednesday that super tuesday showed the ``mantle of ronald reagan has passed to george bush'' but he refused to write off his own presidential try, saying his political agenda now extended beyond 1988
in the south, where i thought i would be strong, ronald reagan and his mantle was a lot stronger, but there are other parts of the country that maybe don't feel this way,'' said robertson, who took a drubbing at the hands of george bush
most of tuesday's contests were in the south, where robertson had expected to do well. but he won only nine of the 712 delegates at stake, losing all 16 primaries and winning only the caucuses in the state of washington. bush won all the primaries
none of us could have dreamed that (bush) could be so strong,'' robertson said. ``the mantle of ronald reagan has passed to george bush.''
exit polls showed bush picked up more votes from conservative christians than the former television evangelist, and robertson blamed himself
i talked too much up in south carolina,'' he said, referring to statements there which seemed to suggest bush's campaign was responsible for revelations about questionable sexual practices by television evangelist jimmy swaggart
some of the things i said, unfortunately, were misinterpreted by the press, at least spun in a different way than what i intended,'' he said
robertson also stood by a controversial statement he made during the new hampshire campaign. ``i still think there are (nuclear) missiles in cuba,'' he said, restating a claim denied by the reagan administration
robertson, who also finished behind bob dole, said he would continue the race until the new orleans nominating convention as ``a rallying point for conservatives.''
i will probably go into the convention with a number of delegates that are at least mine in heart,'' robertson said at a morning news conference in atlanta, where he watched election returns tuesday night
he said he would take a day off before continuing to illinois to campaign for next week's primary there
it isn't over yet. there're still half of the delegates left to be selected,'' he said. ``my goal this year is to win the presidency. i haven't given that goal up. i am in for principle.''
robertson said his candidacy has helped expand the republican party and that will leave him with a reservoir of support he could tap later, perhaps in 1992
i will have people favorable to me in key party positions ... in a lot of (state parties),'' he said, estimating as much as 40 percent of the gop structure in some states is loyal to him
that would be a significant base for something in the future,'' he said
if he doesn't win this year, robertson said, ``my role (in 1990) will be what george bush's role was in '86. he went to many, many congressional districts, helped raise ... about $17 million for party candidates during that cycle
i could help a number of good men and women be elected,'' he said. ``i want to build the republican party and make it the majority party.''
the children's defense fund urged its supporters on wednesday to press the presidental candidates to increase funding for children's welfare and education programs
it is now time to reverse course and invest in the future, to invest in our children, if we as a nation are going to save ourselves,'' the fund's president marian wright edelman said at a news conference at the organization's annual meeting
edelman called on supporters to ``urge those seeking and holding public office this year to commit themselves to making preventive investment in our children and families the cornerstone of national domestic policy in the coming political era.''
the fund will press for immediate enactment of legislation providing safe daycare and establishing minimum health care coverage for poverty-level mothers and children, she said. the group's long-term priorities include five-year incremental increases in the minimum wage and in funding for educational programs for poor and handicapped chldren
the fund, a non-profit lobbying group for children's issues, has produced briefing books and a list of questions for its members to quiz the candidates and eventually elicit support for its legislative agenda
edelman said she was optimistic about the success of the agenda because of the ``new and powerful allies'' it has found in corporate leaders, who want to ensure an educated work force
what we see now is a new coalition of those who worry about the health and social welfare of children and those in the business community who recognize the economic connection in investing in children who are at risk in this society,'' said donna shelala, the fund's board chairman
she referred to the committee for economic development's report for 1987 in which the business community spoke ``in terms of investing in children early on, in prenatal care, in early childhood programs, and head start programs, as ways of ensuring the economic future of the country.''
this is the eighth year the fund has produced a children's budget and provided analysis of the administration's fiscal proposal. as in the past, the organization criticized the reagan administration's emphasis on defense spending over funding for social programs
a mountain lion was shot dead wednesday after he was spotted stalking a residential area where children were waiting for school buses and adults were leaving their homes for work, officials said
the 120-pound male mountain lion was spotted in this northwest orange county community below the chino hills, said patrick moore, spokesman for the state fish and game department in long beach
police cornered the lion outside a house, and a fish and game warden shot it, moore said
these animals are extremely shy and normally don't come in residential areas,'' moore said. ``we like to remove the animal permanently from those situations.''
moore said the animal was killed rather than tranquilized because the drug takes 10 to 20 minutes to take affect and animals sometimes have a violent reaction to it
there was fear that he would run amok in the area and threaten children,'' he said
the cat's body was taken to the fish and game laboratory in victorville for a necropsy
mountain lions are common to the hillside areas of southern california but rarely attack humans. peace corps</head>
relations between the united states and china brightened wednesday with a u.s. decision to liberalize the sale of high technology to the chinese and beijing's agreement in principle to accept peace corps volunteers
the reagan administration announced that it lifted a five-month suspension on the transfer of new technologies after receiving assurances from chinese foreign minister wu xueqian that his country was not sending silkworm anti-ship missiles to iran
this removed a major irritant in the relationship
then, during a question-answer session at the national press club after three days of talks with u.s. officials, wu said of the peace corps that ``china has adopted a positive attitude on this matter,'' though many details still need to be resolved
the agency, established in 1961 by president kennedy to put a grassroots and people-to-people stamp on u.s. overseas aid, currently has programs in 64 countries
alexander sinclair, a peace corps spokesman, said representatives from the two countries will discuss china's development needs and how the agency can help
as for how large the program will be, when it will start and how many volunteers will go to china, ``it's too early to tell,'' sinclair said
we welcome the opportunity to enter in discussions with the people's republic of china about a future peace corps program there,'' sinclair said. ``we expect to have more information about such a program in the weeks ahead.''
the presence of peace corps volunteers in a country has for many years been a significant measure of the warmth of its ties to the united states. the most populated country that has ever accepted the peace corps was india, which invited volunteers from 1962 until 1976, when it shut down the program
after more than two decades of years of emnity, including several years of war in korea, the united states and china normalized relations in the late 1970s and have steadily increased trade and defense ties
there have been some rough spots in the relationship recently, however, and one of the major ones appears to have been smoothed during wu's three days of talks with u.s. officials, including a 40-minute session with president reagan on tuesday
last autumn, to protest what it said was continuing chinese sale of silkworm anti-ship missiles to iran, the administration froze a decade-old process of liberalizing the list of high technology items china is permitted by buy from u.s. companies
china denounced the decision and in his press club remarks, wu reiterated chinese denials of ``direct'' arms sales to iran. he also said that since july, beijing has made efforts to stop the flow of chinese weapons sent through other countries
he said that in his talks with secretary of stte george p. shultz and other administration figures, complaints about chinese arms sales to iran were voiced ``20 times.''
without commenting on the truth of wu's denials about arms sales, administration officials said after meeting the foreign minister they had no reason to believe chinese arms are now flowing from china to iran
we are encouraged by chinese statements and actions regarding iran's acquisition of chinese anti-ship missiles, silkworms,'' state department spokesman charles e. redman said
we have therefore decided to resume the export control liberalization process for china,'' he said
the administration also announced during wu's visit that he assured reagan his country would not stand in the way of a united nations resolution calling for an arms embargo against iran
the united states has been trying for months to line up support on the u.n. security council for an arms embargo against iran designed to stop the 7-year-old iran-iraq war. the ban on weapons sales would be the second installment of a u.n. resolution last july calling for a truce in the war
the nation's orange harvest for the 1987-88 crop season is estimated at 199.6 million boxes, 3 percent more than forecast in february and 10 percent more than last year, the agriculture department said wednesday
florida production, based on march 1 indications, was estimated at 140 million boxes, up 4 percent from february and 17 percent more than last season's crop
the california harvest was estimated at 55 million boxes, up 2 percent from february's forecast but 6 percent less than in 1986-87. the arizona crop was indicated at 3.05 million boxes, unchanged from february and down 3 percent from last season
texas production, at 1.55 million boxes, was unchanged from last month's forecast but was up 77 percent from 1986-87's harvest of 875,000 boxes
the u.s. labor department has rejected arguments from south carolina and north carolina officials who are trying to keep 17-year-old school bus drivers on the road through the end of the school year
south carolina gov. carroll campbell on wednesday repeated his state's plea to allow the drivers to remain behind the wheel
representatives of each state argued unsuccessfully for a stay of the department's revocation of waivers, effective april 1, that had allowed the use of the young drivers if they had clean driving records, labor department spokeswoman linda tavlin said tuesday
the two states won waivers last year of a federal law prohibiting school bus drivers under 18, but the department revoked the waivers in late february. in an investigation following the death of a west columbia child hit by a 17-year-old driver with a bad driving record, the department said it found many of the 17-year-olds had bad records
campbell, in a letter to labor secretary ann mclaughlin, said he understands the department's decision and does not intend to seek a waiver for next year. but he said firing drivers before the end of the school year would not serve the department's purpose
the state superintendent of education assures me that he has on file a letter from each of the 91 district superintendents certifying that all 17-year-olds currently driving school buses meet all ... conditions outlined in the letters of exemption,'' the governor wrote
replacing these drivers with slighly older, inexperienced drivers for two months could potentially lead to a less safe transportation system,'' he wrote
a spokesman for campbell said wednesday the governor's office will continue working with south carolina's senators, ernest hollings and strom thurmond, to get legislative relief from the labor department's action
the u.s. house already has approved a bill that would allow both states to use the drivers through the school year, and the senate is expected to take up the measure next week
carl garris, deputy state superintendent of schools, said the state has about 950 17-year-old drivers now, down from 2,250 at the beginning of the school year
a passenger bus overturned on a mountain road in the southwestern state of guerrero, killing 23 people and injuring 12 others, authorities said wednesday
emma camelo, a spokeswoman for the district attorney's office in guerrero state, said the accident occurred tuesday outside chilpancingo, the state capital 180 miles south of mexico city
the bus was carrying residents of nearby villages
the government news agency notimex said the bus was traveling between the villages of chilapa and colotlipa. the injured were brought to chilpancingo hospitals, it said
a nearly blind glaucoma victim whose doctors vainly sought legal permission for her to use marijuana to help her see now faces up to a year in prison for allegedly growing her own
elvy musikka, 43, was arrested friday and charged with felony possession of almost a pound of marijuana. she was freed on $1,000 bail
ms. musikka is sightless in her right eye and retains little vision in the other
i don't think i'm above the law,'' she said tuesday. ``i've always resented being a criminal to protect my sight. it's a scary situation.''
born with cataracts, she was diagnosed as suffering from glaucoma in 1976. by 1980 she had to retire from her job as a bank switchboard operator because of poor vision
glaucoma is characterized by increased pressure inside and hardening of the eyeball. it can gradually lead to blindness
dr. paul palmberg of the bascom palmer eye institute of the university of miami medical school said 80 percent of glaucoma patients responded to legal drugs
ms. musikka, however, did not, and pamberg said he neither recommended nor discouraged her use of marijuana to help her see
in ms. musikka's case, marijuana lowered the pressure of fluid in her eye while not lowering her blood pressure, allowing the optic nerve to be nourished with blood, palmberg said
dr. richard parrish, also of the eye institute, said he did not recommend marijuana, either, but had tried to obtain it legally for her when he realized it was helping
norman kent, counsel to the florida chapter of the national organization for the reformation of marijuana laws, said it was extremely difficult to legally obtain marijuana for medical reasons
to secure that right, you need a scientist, engineer, physician, lawyer and magician on your side,'' he said
police spokesman jim rabbitt said officers did ``what they had to do.''
we had a violation,'' he said. ``she's going to have her day in court.''
a man who rented a room at her home turned her in for growing four marijuana plants after the two argued, police reports said
missouri voters dealt bob dole a narrow but embarrassing loss blamed on a tidal wave of southern support for george bush, while rep. richard gephardt tolled his only super tuesday win in his home state
supporters of dole, a senator from neighboring kansas, said polls that showed the vice president with commanding leads in the southern states prior to tuesday prompted missouri's uncommitted voters to side with the vice president
everything in the past two weeks has been bush is sweeping the south, bush is going to win the nomination, bush is the next president,'' roberta capps, dole's missouri campaign chairman, said wednesday
with all precincts reporting, the vice president had 168,823 votes or 42 percent and dole had 164,452 votes or 41 percent
on the democratic side, gephardt garnered 305,159 votes or 58 percent. jesse jackson trailed with 106,287 votes or 20 percent. massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 61,557 votes or 12 percent
results showed gephardt with 68 delegates, jackson with 14 and dukakis with one
i don't think we have done as well as we'd hoped.'' gephardt said in st. louis after finishing poorly in the 19 other super tuesday states
bill macon of the missouri bush campaign said the victory, along with the vice president's triumph in oklahoma, was especially gratifying because it showed dole could be beaten in states neighboring his own
i'm certainly not trying to humiliate any good republican but i think this shows he ought to go back to being the senate minority leader and quit cluttering up the race,'' macon said
bush was expected to capture 22 delegates and dole 18. pat robertson and new york rep. jack kemp failed to attract enough missouri republican votes to receive any delegates
the first b-1b bomber to be strengthened against damage by birds was cleared for flight training wednesday, allowing the air force to fly a low-altitude training mission with the plane for the first time in more than five months
lt. col. fred harrop, a spokesman for the strategic air command, said a b-1b based at dyess air force base, texas, had flown low-level bombing runs on a practice range after the rockwell international corp. completed a series of modifications to reduce vulnerability to birdstrikes
we're back in business,'' harrop said
the modifications were ordered for all of the air force's b-1bs after one of the bombers crashed last sept. 28 in colorado during a low-level training flight, killing three of the six crewmen aboard. an air force inquiry determined the plane went down after slamming into a large pelican, whose body ripped through the underside of a wing and severed key hydraulic systems
the modifications involve strengthening an area between the wings and engines, which are attached to the underside of the wings; another area around the so-called pivot pin on which the wings swing back and forth, and an area around the base of the tail fin
in each case, the service is toughening or shielding the internal electrical and hydraulic lines that run through those sections of the plane. the modifications are not visible from the outside
harrop said the air force hoped to have all of the b-1b modified by late fall
before the crash, the air force was allowing b-1b crews to practice low-level attack runs at an altitude of 500 feet. ultimately, the service intends to allow training down to 200 feet
harrop said wednesday the b-1b with the completed modifications had flown its training mission at 500 feet
the b-1b, the nation's first new heavy strategic bomber in 25 years, is designed to fly just below the speed of sound at altitudes as low as 200 feet to evade detection. the air force has purchased 100 of the bombers, but will be left with 99 because of the sept. 28 crash
a group of catholic nuns resigned as managers of the hospital in this small minnesota town after nearly 1,500 people gathered to protest suspension of the hospital's obstetrics services and the resignation of a respected doctor
at a joint meeting of the jackson municipal hospital board and the city council on tuesday night, hospital board president steve handke read letters of resignation by the hospital's chief administrator, sister maureen mcdonald, and the assistant administrator and nursing director, sister patricia glowski
the nuns are members of the alma, mich.-based religious sisters of mercy, which has run the 22-bed jackson hospital since 1981. two members of a newly formed citizens committee were nominated tuesday to help the hospital board find replacements for the nuns
the resignations cited a desire to calm tensions that have risen in the southern minnesota community of 3,800 people since obstetrics services were suspended feb. 26 following a stillbirth at the hospital
it's a relief,'' said lance edlin, a pharmacist and leader of a citizens' group that had been trying to remove the nuns from hospital management. ``i'm not surprised. we had 1,000 signatures on a petition. we hope to get back to a harmonious relationship now.''
the nuns did not return a telephone call seeking comment
meanwhile, dr. gumersindo alvero, who was one of the hospital's two staff doctors, announced wednesday he was withdrawing his resignation because of support from the community. the resignation by the nuns means the hospital has been brought ``back to the people, where it belongs,'' he said
alvero, who has practiced here for 10 years, said the woman involved in the stillbirth was not a patient of his, and said the cause of the stillbirth remains confidential. but he maintained that was not the key issue in the dispute
the issue was how they (hospital administration) discriminated against me. they investigated without giving me a chance to talk with the doctor who investigated the case,'' he said
the board said monday that it had been informed that a ``serious medical incident concerning patient treatment had arisen'' on feb. 16
in such a case, normal hospital procedure requires a review, the board's statement said. after the board and alvero were advised, the statement said, complete medical records were forwarded to dr. robert a. diamond, an officer of the governing board of the minnesota obstetrical and gynecological society in minneapolis, who serves as consultant to the hospital
according to the report from diamond, the mother was ``poorly managed'' during her labor
diamond said the mother should have been transferred to a hospital in nearby worthington when, according to the medical records, she started exhibiting severe pregnancy-induced hypertension four days prior to delivery. he also said the use of fetal heart monitoring at jackson municipal hospital had to be improved
edlin and others said there is no quarrel in jackson with the quality of health care. in fact, the hospital board released a statement tuesday night saying the sisters' management of the hospital had been ``superior.''
residents at the tuesday night meeting voiced concerns about high staff turnover and an air of secrecy about the nuns
it's a mystique of secretiveness that's really got everyone in town wondering who the heck they are and what got them coming here,'' said john sathe, owner of a funeral home in jackson
a state department official said wednesday the administration would talk to the soviet union about reports of japanese vessels fishing illegally in waters off alaska, but a house committee chairman demanded more action
ed wolfe, the state department's ambassador for oceans and fisheries, told a congressional hearing that the reagan administration was still pressing the government of japan for an official explanation of an incident in which japanese trawlers were videotaped apparently fishing in american waters in the bering sea
i am personally disappointed that i am not able to provide the subcommittee with a full report of the japanese investigation,'' wolfe said
wolfe said an interagency task force was developing a ``u.s. government position to help avoid a recurrence of this problem in the future.''
he said the united states will be holding bilateral talks with the soviet union, which has its eastern-most tip on the bering sea, later this month to discuss fisheries problems in the area
it's a good exercise,'' said wolfe
it's a good exercise mr. ambassador,'' replied rep. don bonker, d-wash.. ``but good grief, we want more than an exercise
it's been three months since the alleged illegal activity took place and i'm wondering how long we will have to wait before something is forthcoming.''
bonker, chairman of the subcommittee on international economic policy and trade of the house foreign affairs committee, called on the state department to ``greatly accelerate it's actions
i can promise you, if you don't do something we will.''
american fishermen and the u.s. coast guard have suspected for more than a year that foreign trawlers were entering the 200-mile u.s. fishing zone under cover of darkness or in stormy weather to fish illegally
seven foreign trawlers, most of them thought to be japanese, were videotaped with their nets down 38 miles inside the u.s. zone off alaska. the tapes were taken from a private plane chartered by a fishing industry group in early january
bonker said he was considering legislation that would require that foreign fishing vessels inform u.s. authorities before they enter american waters
wolfe said the administration would probably finish formulating a policy within a month, but said the best deterrent to illegal foreign fishing might be increased surveillance and enforcement by the coast guard
president reagan signed an executive order wednesday allowing continued cooperation with european nations on peaceful nuclear energy matters
the document extends more than two decades of cooperation between the united states and the european atomic energy community (euratom). rockne</head> reagan mispronounced `gipper' and edits 12th graf pvs, after his, to conform; picks up 13th graf pvs, reagan then</note>
president reagan revisited the university of notre dame on wednesday and dedicated a new 22-cent stamp in honor of knute rockne, telling students that the legendary football coach's life exemplified ``the faith that makes things happen.''
it was reagan's second visit as president to the notre dame campus. on his earlier visit in 1981, he was reunited with pat o'brien, who played the title role in the 1940 movie, ``knute rockne, all-american,'' in which reagan enjoyed one of the first big successes of his hollywood career
but reagan first went to notre dame as a young sports announcer, to broadcast a football game. later, he returned with o'brien and other stars for the premiere of the rockne film
clips from the black and white picture, in which reagan played notre dame football star george gipp, were played for the audience in the joyce athletic and convocation center before reagan's arrival on wednesday
the clips showed o'brien, as rockne, giving a pep talk to his players at halftime of a 1928 game against army, with the score tied 0-0. gipp had died eight years earlier, but the coach tells his charges that on his deathbed the young athlete said, ``some time when the team is up against it and the breaks are beating the boys, tell them to go out there with all they got and win just one for the gipper.''
in fact, army went ahead in the third quarter, 6-0, but notre dame went on to win the game, 12-6. army was on the 1-yard line with the tying touchdown as time ran out
reagan told his audience that the role of gipp ``was a young actor's dream'' but that playing in a film about rockne ``was more than that'' to him
i know that, to many of you today, rockne is a revered name, a symbol of greatness and, yes, a face on a postage stamp,'' he said
but my generation, well, we actually knew the legend as it happened _ we saw it unfold. and we felt it was saying something important about us as a people and a nation.''
most of all, the rockne legend meant this ... that on or off the field, it is faith that makes the difference, it is faith that makes great things happen.''
rockne, a graduate of the men's college at notre dame, was its head football coach from 1918 to 1931 and compiled a record of 108 victories, 12 losses and five ties. during his tenure, the ``fighting irish'' were undefeated in five seasons and won six national championships
at the end of his speech, reagan repeated the line from gipp's deathbed scene in the movie, saying, ``win just one for the gipper.'' but he actully pronounced it ``gippet,'' although few in the crowd noticed the mistake because they already had begun their applause
afterward, reagan was handed a football, which he hurled toward a group of football players seated in the crowd. heisman trophy winner tim brown caught the pigskin as the crowd roared its approval
reagan then unveiled a replica of the new postage stamp, which shows rockne in a jersey holding a football. as a 22-cent stamp, it is unlikely to be widely used for long, since first-class letter postage is due to go up to 25 cents next month
the ceremony ended when reagan, a graduate of eureka college in illinois and the holder of an honorary degree from notre dame, was given a plaque bearing the words of the school song, ``notre dame, our mother.'' he sang along softly as the song echoed through the athletic center
in his speech, the president coupled his reminiscences about rockne with praise for the american economy, saying, ``there's a will to succeed evident in our land.''
it is a far different picture than the agonizing sight of a decade ago, when many were counting out american workers and american industry,'' he said
we were told americans would no longer go the extra mile, no longer had the drive to excel; that our country was in decline; and that we, as a people, should lower our expectations.''
today, we see an america ready to compete, anxious to compete,'' reagan said
i predict that as this year progresses, we will see american manufacturing re-emerge as the leading force in the world marketplace.''
reagan also used the occasion to renew his claim, disputed by some, that his administration, abetted by first lady nancy reagan's ``just say no'' campaign, is making significant inroads into drug use among young people
we still have a long way to go, and when nancy and i see stories saying just that in the story, we welcome them,'' he said
but let's also remember that the shock of recognition is not a sign of defeat, it's the beginning of victory.''
the president tempered his customary optimism with the observations that ``there are those who see a dark side to our technological progress. ... it is pointed out that, regretfully, as man has advanced into this new age, so has his capability to kill and destroy.''
but, he said, ``technology is pointing toward a way out of this dilemma'' with research on the space-based missile defense system. the system, informally called ``star wars,'' is a cornerstone of the reagan national security policy
as he boarded air force one in south bend for the trip back to washington, reagan was carrying an autographed basketball presented to him by notre dame basketball coach digger phelps
reporters shouted at reagan to toss the ball toward them, which he did. nbc-tv reporter chris wallace caught it, lobbed a pass to a member of the white house staff, who then presented it to reagan
reagan laughed as he reached the top platform of the stairs, bounced the basketball once, grinned then entered the plane
the president arrived at andrews air force base, on the outskirts of washington, shortly before 4 p.m. est and then returned to the white house
eleven democrats on the house judiciary committee asked attorney general edwin meese iii on wednesday to step down temporarily until independent counsel investigations into his conduct are completed
meese spokesman terry eastland said the attorney general would not comply because, ``no one should be urged to step down from a government position simply because that person is under investigation.''
the lawmakers made their request in a letter to meese, and five of them held a news conference to elaborate on their remarks
rep. barney frank of massachusetts, one of the signers, denied that the signers had a political motive, saying, ``ed meese is the best thing to happen to the democratic party.''
another signer, rep. bruce morrison of connecticut, said the standard meese is setting for ethical conduct is ``not in the slammer.''
meese has been under criminal investigation by independent counsel james mckay since last may 11. mckay has been examining meese's involvement with scandal-plagued wedtech corp., and with a $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline project
mckay also has been examining the attorney general's involvement with the regional bell telephone companies at a time when he owned $14,000 in phone stock
in addition independent counsel lawrence e. walsh, investigating the iran-contra arms and money affair, has called meese before a grand jury numerous times
we strongly believe that your increasing inability to spend time on the day-to-day demands of your job, the deteriorating morale at the department of justice and the continuing cloud over your office are undermining your ability to act effectively as the nation's chief law enforcement officer,'' the democrats said in the letter
the letter said the pending investigations ``detract from the time required to properly administer the department of justice
the pervasive perception that you have allowed personal considerations to encroach on your constitutional responsibilities threatens to breed contempt for your office, your administration and the rule of law itself,'' the lawmakers said
eastland responded, ``this is an old idea, a politically partisan idea and a thoroughly bad idea.''
he said meese ``has every intention of serving to the end of this term. he has spent some time with his lawyers on the investigation, but there has been no serious subtraction of his time or effort from leadership of the department of justice.''
rep. howard berman, d-calif., told the news conference that the pipeline project may have involved an attempt by a u.s. company _ with meese's knowledge _ to bribe foreign officials. such bribes would violate the foreign corrupt practices act
at this moment, some business groups are conducting a major drive to weaken the (act),'' berman said. ``in that effort, they have consistently been supported by this administration and by this justice department.''
the letter was signed by reps. dan glickman, kansas; edward feighan, ohio; berman; frank; morrison; lawrence smith, florida; harley staggers jr., west virginia; john conyers, michigan; george crockett jr., michigan; mike synar, oklahoma and patricia schroeder, colorado
police in three states interviewed witnesses wednesday as they tried to identify two men sought in a cold-blooded rampage that left four people dead, including a woman whose throat was slit while she struggled with her assailants
another victim, an 85-year-old man, was shot in the back of the head, and his son was shot in the face. the fourth victim was shot three times and then dumped by the side of an arkansas road after he gave two men a ride, authorities said
by all indications, it was overkill,'' said cooke county sheriff john aston, where the first of the victims, a 23-year-old woman, was found in her gainesville mobile home
vehicles stolen from the victims turned up in lakes in oklahoma and arkansas, authorities said, and items found with vehicles linked the four killings
we do not have a motive at all,'' aston said
we don't know where they are, not now,'' said sgt. anthony hancock of the collin county sheriff's office. ``i would not say a search is under way because we don't know where to look. we're trying to compile information, compile artists' sketches. we're trying to make an identification on these guys. we just don't know which way to go.''
deana andrews woodard was killed monday morning in her home in gainesville, just south of the texas-oklahoma line. aston described the slaying as cold-blooded
these people were there the whole time she was bleeding to death,'' he said. ``there are indications there had been a struggle. she was hit in the head.''
her infant son was in the home but was not harmed. the suspects stole her gun and apparently drove her car to the collin county community of farmersville, north of dallas. there, the bodies of cecil floyd morrison and his son, cecil leonard morrison, 62, were found monday night in their home, hancock said
they had been brutally beaten with a tire iron or other tool, and shot in the head or face, hancock said
the men are believed to have abandonded mrs. woodard's car near farmersville and to have stolen the morrisons' pickup truck. mrs. woodard's car has not been recovered
they then drove the pickup truck to the hope-saratoga, ark., area and drove it into a lake, hancock said
the men went to a home in the area to ask for assistance after dark monday, and the fourth victim offered them a ride, hancock said
the body of kenneth olden, 34, of arkansas, was found about 9 a.m. tuesday on a rural road outside saratoga, authorities said
they left him on a roadside and drove his vehicle back to marietta, oklahoma, where that vehcile was discovered somewhere before noon tuesday,'' hancock said. marietta is just north of the texas-oklahoma line
a checkbook taken from the men in farmersville, two gold necklaces and a prescription bottle with mrs. woodard's name on it were found with the vehicle in arkansas, hancock said
authorities said they were trying to determine whether the killings were linked to the robbery by three men of a seminole, okla., bank monday. the fbi recovered most of the stolen cash in muskogee, okla
the chairman of the house energy and commerce committee says congress will not enact a bill to define insider trading, although the securities industry is seeking such legislation
the definition that has developed in case law is clear,'' rep. john dingell, d-mich., said in a speech this week to the securities industry association
reporters were not invited to the lobby group's meeting in washington on monday, but dingell's office released a copy of his remarks on wednesday
the offense of insider trading has developed over the years through court and regulatory interpretations of fraud and securities laws
the securities industry has been pushing congress to write a definition into the law, arguing that traders need to know beforehand what constitutes insider trading in order to avoid violating the law
sens. donald w. riegle jr., d-mich., and alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., in june introduced a bill with a definition. they have been working with the securities and exchange commission, which favors legislation but has suggested changes in the senate bill to broaden the definition
however, in the house, dingell told the lobby group flatly, ``there will be no definition of insider trading.''
he said his committee is drafting a bill that would ``implement needed reforms'' and promised ``we will work toward passage this year.''
he did not elaborate what reforms would be in the bill, beyond advising the association that ``you will probably dislike some of them.''
dennis fitzgibbons, a spokesman for dingell, said the chairman favors additional penalties for insider trading. he also wants harsher treatment for violations of internal ``chinese wall'' barriers designed to prevent executives in a securities firm involved in mergers and aquisitions from communicating with traders in the same firm, fitzgibbons said
fitzgibbons said dingell is not philosophically opposed to legislating a definition, but recognizes the difficulty of getting congress to agree on one and is comfortable with the definition developed by the courts
donald j. crawford, a senior vice president for the securities association, said the group has endorsed a statutory definition but believes there is some validity to dingell's arguments
in a related matter, dingell critized a bill passed last week by the senate banking committee that would permit banks to underwrite most securities, except corporate stocks
dingell said the bill provided insufficient safeguards against conflicts between banks' role as lenders and what would become their new role as a securities underwriters
the bill ``has emerged ... with firewalls as thin as rice paper,'' he said. that izvestia is soviet newspaper. subs 20th graf ``but the . .. this way:'' to show that le monde is french newspaper.</head>
george bush grabbed the lion's share of the overseas headlines after his string of super tuesday victories, with much of the press portraying him as a low-key reagan loyalist with one foot in the white house door
why is bush so popular? the answer comes easily,'' said the independent tabloid expressen, sweden's largest-circulation paper. ``party people see him as ronald reagan's loyal aid _ loyal to the grave _ and therefore his natural successor.''
the vice president's republican primary victories in 16 states grabbed more media coverage than the more muddled outcomes on the democratic side, although massachusetts gov. michael dukakis got huge display in his ancestral country, greece, and jesse jackson drew strong coverage
jesse jackson, the one-time `leftist radical,' has become a ... kingmaker with a strong influence on the democratic program and on the ultimate choice of the presidential candidate,'' the independent amsterdam newspaper, het parool, noted in an editorial
poland's state-run radio, in a commentary read during the midday news, drew parallels between bush and sen. albert gore, d-tenn
gore, it said, ``originates from a well-to-do family, graduated from elite universities, and his life, including the political one, has been happy,'' it said
this moderate conservative from the south describes himself as the toughest among the democrats as far as military issues are concerned. his political profile therefore offers no contrast to bush's...''
prevailing foreign sentiment attributed bush's big day to president reagan. the british papers seemed ready to announce an inauguration
white house here i come,'' shouted the the banner headline in the standard of london, which ran a photo of an exhilarated bush waving to supporters
senate minority leader bob dole was shown rubbing his brow in a photograph captioned ``feeling the pain.''
by a stunning series of triumphs, grinding his rivals to dust beneath his chariot wheels in the super tuesday primaries, george bush emerged almost invincible as the next presidential candidate of the republican party,'' the standard rhapsodized
in west germany, the bonn-based newspaper die welt said: ``george bush's impressive victory is without doubt the most important event of the primary elections
this was not just a victory for george bush, it was a triumph for ronald reagan.''
in greece, where the dukakis campaign has been followed closely, the media trumpeted his victories in five democratic primaries. ``dukakis triumphs, all consider him a certain president,'' said a banner headline in the conservative daily messimvrini
a front-page article in the soviet-government newspaper izvestia in moscow said super tuesday appears to have decided the republican contest, but only raised more questions about who will emerge as the democratic contender in november
dukakis, jackson and gore ``practically split up among themselves the states where elections were held,'' the newspaper said
izvestia quoted ``a prominent democratic figure who didn't want his name used'' in speculating that his party might run a ticket pairing dukakis with jackson
in contrast with past coverage, reports issued this week by the official tass news agency were notable for their balance and clarity
both tass and izvestia noted the poor showings by republicans jack kemp and pat robertson, ``who had been conducting their campaigns from extreme right positions.''
but the leftist french daily le monde of paris, in an editorial, summed up the whole process this way:
it will take hundreds of millions of dollars, thousands of kilometers, countless hours of television, to realize (that) hopes have been disappointed, careers destroyed and contestants hopelessly plunged into debt before there is the slightest idea or the vaguest program'' put forward by the candidates
le monde said there was an ideological vacuum on the democratic side, with the exception of jackson and his ``out-of-date liberalism.''
rome's moderate il messsaggero, said in its headline: ``bush did it. beating dole, he has become the political heir of reagan.''
state-run rai-tv spent nearly five minutes explaining the process before giving the results wednesday morning
buoyed by a heavy vote in claiborne county, ed pittman was within reach of winning the democratic nomination in a mississippi supreme court race
problem was, elections officials had forgotten that claiborne county wasn't part of the district any longer
i would have loved to win the first time, but as a matter of fact when you have three worthy opponents you don't anticipate winning the first day,'' the former attorney general said wednesday
he will face attorney john swartzfager in the march 29 runoff
swartzfager said he was shocked by the snafu, and blamed it partly on pittman
pittman was the state attorney general when the redistricting plan was approved in december, swartzfager said, ``and he should have notified the secretary of state and the democratic party.''
final but unofficial returns without claiborne county showed pittman with 49 percent of the vote in the supreme court's southern district and swartzfager with 21 percent
including claiborne county, where pittman won by 1,554 to 107, his unofficial total was about 50 percent. a runoff is required if a candidate receives less than 50 percent
the bottom line is they may have voted in the southern district but they are not in that district,'' said john emfinger of the attorney general's office. ``the next step will be up to the party.''
emfinger said the legislature had moved the county as part of a redistricting plan last year
brian martin, executive director of the mississippi democratic party, said the mistake would have no impact on the central district, where claiborne county belongs and where two incumbent justices had no opposition tuesday
we received the sample ballot from the (state) party and our democratic executive committee had the ballot made up exactly as it was sent to us,'' said sammie good, the claiborne county circuit clerk. ``we are very disappointed our votes will not count and i'm sure ed pittman is disappointed.''
an absorbent material called super slurper is helping tiny worms to kill root weevils that threaten citrus trees, the agriculture department said wednesday
william j. schroeder, an entomolgist in the department's agricultural research service, said the super slurper keeps soil moist so that the microscopic worms, or nematodes, can survive and kill weevils which chew the tree roots
in tests, 60 percent of the weevils were killed, compared with only 25 percent without the help of the worms. schroeder said that weevils can kill up to 30 percent of the trees in a grove if not controlled
the nematodes haven't been used before as a natural weevil control because they die quickly if soil dries out, schoeder said
other agency scientists are looking into the use of super slurper and nematodes to see if they can control pests of corn and vegetables
agency scientists in peoria, ill., invented the cornstarch-based super slurper 14 years ago. it has been successfully used in dozens of commercial products, including body powder, medical dressings and many other items
schroeder, who works at the department's horticultural research laboratory in orlando, fla., said he thought of super slurper in 1985 when he observed nematodes dying in dry soil
companies could mass-produce nematodes and ``package billions of them alive'' for sale to growers, who then could mix the worms with super slurper for application on tree roots before planting, he said
for citrus groves already inhabited by the beneficial nematodes, schroeder said he is looking into the possibility of injecting super slurper into the soil with a nozzle
the tiny worms, which survive as long as the soil is kept moist, penetrate the weevils and release lethal bacteria, which don't harm plants or other organisms, schroeder said
