chicago (ap) _ jesse jackson returned to his home base on wednesday, fresh from his strong showing on super tuesday, and predicted a ``hotly contested race'' in next week's illinois primary
i will do well in illinois,'' he told reporters. but he also said he anticipated a tough fight with illinois sen. paul simon, who sat out the super tuesday primaries and caucuses across 20 states
jackson reaped more than 300 delegates, coming in second overall to massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
jackson placed first in the popular vote for the day, with 27 percent to 26 percent each for dukakis and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee
but that was a total for all the states. the delegates are alloted state-by-state depending on the votes each candidate wins in each state, not how many they win regionwide
jackson's campaign staff pointed to exit polls showing he had won the hispanic vote, the women's vote and the 18-to-21 age group
the exit polls indicated jackson won about 95 percent of the black vote and about 10 percent of the white vote across the super tuesday states
jackson came in third in texas, and to put the best face on that showing in a state where he campaigned vigorously, his aides said he had spent only $30,000 on tv there, a fraction of what was spent by his opponents
campaign official steve cobble said polling showed that jackson did well in the places that he appeared personally, as in the case of beaumont, texas, where he went to show solidarity with striking oil workers
jackson talked repeatedly wednesday about how he was outspent by the multi-million dollar tv campaigns of dukakis, gore and rep. richard gephardt of missouri
my opponents have money, and money is powerful, but we the people are more powerful,'' he told a rally of plant workers in the chicago suburb of cicero. ``we get stronger every day.''
his campaign manager, gerald austin, said the jackson campaign will be buying tv ads as new money comes in. jackson spent $100,000 on tv in the super tuesday contests
in south carolina, jackson's boyhood state where voting occurs saturday, austin said the tv budget is about $20,000. in illinois, austin anticipates a total budget of $200,000, with about $30,000 for television
jackson has been a political force in chicago for many years starting when he worked with the rev. martin luther king jr. for open housing and other civil rights causes. jackson makes his home here, and his operation push, people united to serve humanity, is based here
upon arriving home wednesday, jackson went to cicero to speak at an outdoor rally of about 150 general electric workers who are upset because of plans to close down a refrigerator plant where more than 1,000 people work
jesse, help us save our jobs,'' their placards read
jackson said he was challenging ge to meet with workers and him to discuss ways of converting the plant to other uses
earlier, at a news conference in houston, he said the primary elections are muting democratic party establishment doubts about the viability of his campaign
but he said many white democratic politicians who were elected with support from black voters he helped bring into the party had failed to endorse him
it would be fair to say that many of them had reasonable doubts about the success of our campaign,'' he said. ``in these elections we are removing those doubts. ... our coalition represents the future of the democratic party.''
he said white officials must assess not only who can win, but which candidate ``can help them.''
he decried the negative ads his opponents ran against one another, and said the democrats must not ``self-destruct'' their chances for winning the white house in november
although jackson so far has not been attacked by his rivals, austin said the jackson camp is prepared to face ``slings and arrows'' now that he is amassing delegates. prevails</head>
michael dukakis organized early and spent big to tell texas voters that the economic program dubbed the ``massachusetts miracle'' could mean jobs and tax breaks for them. he succeeded, convincingly
supporters of vice president george bush, meanwhile, said they hoped the former texas resident's sweep of all 111 state republican delegates on super tuesday dispelled the ``wimp'' issue
he's the best of what texas is,'' said margaret wolf, who served as bush's secretary in 1977-78. bush, a massachusetts native who keeps a voting address at a houston hotel, was ``gutsy'' for starting his own oil business in texas in 1953, she said
dukakis, who says he helped spur his state's economic revival as governor, ``ran a good campaign'' to defeat jesse jackson by 33 percent to 24 percent of the primary vote, said george christian, a former press secretary to lyndon johnson and an austin political consultant
he had the strategy of finding his constituency and organizing it. his constituency was the hispanics and liberals. that was a sufficient number to put him at the top,'' christian said
in contrast to a dukakis advertising blitz that cost hundreds of thousands of dollars, jackson spent about $20,000 on texas ads but used volunteers to build his no. 2 spot among democrats, said his campaign secretary, steve coble
with 6,534 of 6,933 precincts or 94 percent reporting, dukakis had 533,076 votes, jackson had 387,440, tennessee sen. albert gore received 334,365 or 14 percent and missouri rep. richard gephardt finished with 225,770 or 14 percent
dukakis earned an estimated 45 delegates and jesse jackson was expected to capture 44. gore had 26 delegates and gephardt tallied 9
in the republican primary, with 5,238 of 5,616 precincts or 93 percent reporting, bush amassed 588,081 votes or 64 percent.former tv evangelist pat robertson was a distant second with 141,444 votes and kansas sen. bob dole had 125,702 or 14 percent
in other races, democratic sen. lloyd bentsen easily won renomination in his bid for a fourth term. top republican challengers beau boulter, who gave up his congressional seat for the senate race, and wes gilbreath, a houston investor making his first race for a political office, will meet in a runoff on april 12
a slow-moving cold front set off showers wednesday through the ohio and tennessee valleys and along the gulf coast, where more than 3 inches of rain drenched central louisiana in 24 hours
heavy rain also fell in the pacific northwest, and up to 5 inches of snow were expected in washington's cascade and olympic mountains
temperatures climbed to record highs in north dakota, while much of texas had readings in the 60s and 70s
rainshowers were scattered from western new england into the upper ohio valley and from virginia through the eastern carolinas into northern florida
northeast michigan got a dusting of snow
in louisiana, more than an 3 inches of rain were measured in 24 hours at oakdale, bunkie, eunice and alexandria. lake charles got more than an inch
more than 3 inches were recorded in 24 hours in washington at spada lake and verlot
snow and blowing dust hindered travel across northwest nevada, reducing visibility to less than a mile. winds gusted to 36 mph at tonopah, nev
heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 0.70 inch at mccomb, miss., 0.65 inch at gainesville, fla., and charleston, s.c., 0.49 inch at crescent city, calif
temperatures at 2 p.m. est ranged from 26 degrees at limestone, maine, gunnison, colo., and elko, nev., to 83 degrees at avon park, fla. the morning low for the nation was 5 degrees below zero at gunnison, colo
record high temperatures included 58 in bismarck, n.d., 60 in dickinson, n.d., and 56 at williston, n.d
thursday's forecast called for rainshowers along the middle and southern atlantic coast, with showers and a few thunderstorms across the florida peninsula; rain across the northeast plains and the central intermountain region; snow across the northern rockies and high plains into the colorado rockies, and gusty wind from the desert southwest into the southern rockies and from the carolinas into northern florida
high temperatures were expected to reach the 50s or 60s across much of the nation, with readings in the 30s and 40s from the northern plateau and central intermountain region through the northern rockies, the northern plains, the great lakes and upper ohio valley into new england; in the 70s across the southern coast of california, the southern plateau, the southern plains and the lower mississippi valley as well as much of florida, and in the low to mid-80s across western and southern texas
the world's cities must be more than simply places to do business: they must strive to meet the higher human aspirations of their citizens, experts attending an international conference on cities agreed wednesday
it's more than a tax base. it's more than buildings. it's aiming to make the city enjoyable for those citizens who have the least,'' charleston mayor joseph p. riley jr. told the international conference on making cities liveable
about 300 experts from around the globe are attending the conference which runs through this weekend. social policy and values as they apply to cities were the topics of the opening session
if we can give homes rather than housing projects, if we can create types of beauty everyone can enjoy ... then we are on our way to making cities liveable,'' said riley, who showed slides of rehabilitation and restoration projects he said has given charleston an international reputation
eduardo salzano, a professor at the university of venice in italy, said modern cities are confronted with ``a cluttered mass of individual interests.''
he suggested planning should be in the hands of local boards that have adequate citizen input, and residents of cities must agree ownership of urban land does not automatically give the owner the right to build anything he wants
a sense of place is a human hunger'' which many modern cities don't satisfy, said don robert johnson, a new york scholar. he added that ``individuals without a sense of history are incapable of planning the present and the future in an informed manner.''
the mayor of erlangen, west germany, dietmar hahlweg, said cities need strong planning authority and the right to take land when needed for public purposes
cities also need enlightened leadership and ``people who have the necessary knowledge and have a feeling for the wishes, needs and problems of the people,'' he said
planners must also consider the needs of the elderly and children, said suzanne lennard, one of the organizers of the conference
she said liveable cities have some sort of unity. cities in the united states ``have grown cancerously'' with a wide separation of shopping areas and neighborhoods and ``a lack of order or reason in the sequence of streets and places,'' she said
a community cannot be said to exist in a series of pockets of persons wishing to know only those in their own group and shunning contact with others,'' she said
william whyte of the american conservation association in new york suggested many american cities fear ``undesirables'' and ``bustle with distrust'' of some of their citizens
he noted that in some cities, park benches are cut short to make it hard for people to sleep on them. in other metropolitan areas, it's virtually impossible to find a public rest room in the center of the city, he said
in some large downtown development projects featuring hotels or shopping arcades, benches are omitted to discourage ``undesirables,'' he said
many such projects are financed in part through tax money, he said
these things the public has an equity in and it should be mandatory they can be used by the public,'' he said. season</head>
the democratic presidential candidates on wednesday found themselves stuck in a logjam of delegates in which nobody was likely to lock up the party's nomination when the primaries end in june
mathematically and politically this process is in gridlock,'' said terry michael, spokesman for illinois sen. paul simon, who suffered a shutout in super tuesday's round of primaries and caucuses
simon, who held just 35.5 delegates both before and after tuesday's balloting, is banking on nobody being able to gain the 2,082 delegates needed to win the democratic presidential nomination when the primaries conclude on june 7, with california and new jersey, two of the largest states with a total of 423 delegates at stake
the person or persons with the greatest potential to negotiate his way to a first-ballot victory will be the candidate who is hottest at the end,'' michael said
the odds are growing longer that any candidate can come up with the magic number needed to win on the first ballot at the democratic convention in atlanta
the democrats have yet to allocate 2,524 of their national convention delegates, and another 258.65 delegates list themselves as uncommitted. thus the available pool of delegates to be won between now and early june would be 2,782.65
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who was leading the field of democratic candidates with 456.5 delegates, needs to win another 1625.5 delegates to wrap up the presidential nomionation. or, put another way, he has to win more than 58 percent of all the delegates that are still left to be won _ roughly twice as well as he's done so far
dukakis was followed in the delegate count by rev. jesse jackson with 395.55 and tennessee sen. albert gore with 346.8
the three-way tie in the democratic race prompted former president jimmy carter to observe that ``i think it's accurate to say the chances are less likely that one of the candidates will arrive in atlanta with a clear majority.''
new york gov. mario cuomo said wednesday he wanted to see his party hold a ``quiet convention,'' although he conceded it would be difficult for any of the current candidates to secure a first-ballot victory based on results of the primaries and caucuses
cuomo said he had talked to democratic national committee chairman paul kirk about the problem last week
i believe what you, paul kirk, should do is try, right after california and new jersey, the last primaries, to take whoever is ahead and make that person the concensus choice,'' cuomo said as he recalled the conversation
michael said if no candidate holds a majority by the time the primaries conclude, the rule of conscience that binds delegates to the candidates will begin to bend and break
however, jude barry, an aide to missouri rep. richard gephardt's presidential campaign, disagreed, saying, ``i think there's going to be loyalty and commitment. we're prepared to protect what we have, as i'm sure the other candidates will as well.''
gephardt, who had 143 delegates after super tuesday, is hoping to hang on with a strong showing in the michigan caucuses on march 26 and the congressional democratic caucuses on april 19 and 20. gephardt is planning on winning big when his house colleagues pick 210 of their own to be national convention delegates. another 43 delegates will be picked by senate democrats
our hand certainly will not be weak with that wild card,'' barry said
simon, meanwhile, is hoping to score a victory next tuesday in his home state of illinois. trial including mafia claim, other detail. corrects spelling of wounded bailiff's name to wofford sted wooford. corrects gunman's first name to jeremey sted jeremy and hometown to sepulveda sted woodland hills. no pickup</note>
a ``violently crazy'' man bent on revenge after being convicted of reckless driving and weapons violations returned to the courtroom wednesday and opened fire, wounding a bailiff before being slain, officials said
jeremey sigmond, 35, a decertified chiropractor who had claimed during his trial that he thought the mafia was following him, died in a shootout at municipal court in suburban van nuys, said ted goldstein, a spokesman for the city attorney's office
sigmond had held a gun to the head of the deputy city attorney who prosecuted the case, jessica perrin silvers, 48. she broke loose when he was momentarily distracted and was unharmed, goldstein said
i realized he now apparently regarded me as part of the same conspiracy that involves the mafia, the governor, the governor's cousin, the district attorney, the city attorney's office, and all the rest,'' ms. silvers said. ``i know that makes me start sounding like the crazy one when i say it.''
he's just, in layman's terms, violently crazy, and i knew it,'' she said
the wounded bailiff, county deputy marshal cliff wofford, 30, of palmdale, was in stable condition at st. joseph's medical center in burbank, said hospital spokeswoman linda roberts. he was shot in the abdomen
sigmond, of sepulveda, was convicted in the same courtroom tuesday of four misdemeanors _ reckless driving, evading police, carrying a loaded weapon and carrying a concealed weapon _ stemming from a chase, goldstein said. he was awaiting sentencing
when sigmond was arrested in october, he was wearing two bulletproof vests and a crash helmet and carrying a .38-caliber revolver loaded with five rounds of armor-piercing ammunition, officers said
he testified he thought he was being chased by the mafia instead of the california highway patrol. he claimed the mafia was harassing him in retaliation for a suit he filed against the board of chiropractors, alleging price-fixing and restraint of trade
sigmond was also appealing the revocation of his state license to practice as a chiropractor
sigmond accosted ms. silvers on wednesday minutes after she arrived at the courthouse. she said he commandeered her into the courtroom
a bailiff pulled a gun on sigmond, but he countered: ``drop or i'll kill both of you,'' said jim epstein, a lawyer and friend of the prosecutor
the bailiff threw her gun behind sigmond, and as he reached for the weapon, ms. silvers broke loose and locked herself in a restroom, epstein said
the man, waving both guns, then went toward municipal judge michael b. harwin, screaming ``something like `i want my new day in court,''' said george schell, a deputy city attorney in the courtroom
the judge started wrestling with the gunman, trying to disarm him. a second bailiff, wofford, then rushed into the room and both he and sigmond were wounded in the ensuing shootout, officials said
though fatally wounded, sigmond continued to struggle with the judge and a bailiff who were trying to handcuff him, schell said. ms. silvers said 13 casings were found around the judge's bench
at his sentencing, which was scheduled for may, sigmond could have been sent to jail for up to 18 months
one witness outside the courtroom, becker mubani, said that after the shooting he saw wofford running from the courtroom, ``his left hand covering the wound.''
the officer staggered down some steps to the sidewalk as other officers ran to assist him. mubani screamed, ``watch! watch! he's wounded!''
then the wounded officer began shouting, `where is the ambulance? where is the ambulance?''' mubani said. report of meeting in yerevan.</note>
mikhail s. gorbachev and other kremlin officials met wednesday with leaders of the republics of armenia and azerbaijan to discuss how to resolve ethnic unrest that has killed at least 32 people, tass said
the report said party leaders kyamran bagirov of azerbaijan and karen demirchyan of armenia met with the soviet leader, soviet president andrei a. gromyko, premier nikolai i. ryzhkov and two other influential politburo members, yegor k. ligachev and alexander n. yakovlev
the conference involving the party's top echelon illustrated the kremlin's concern over the ethnic strife that has cracked the facade of cohesion among the soviet union's more than 100 nationalities
in its report on the meeting at the party's central committee headquarters, tass said the situation in the republics ``is returning to normal, although it continues to have its difficulties.''
meanwhile, an armenian who described himself as a city official loyal to the soviet government called the associated press from the armenian capital of yerevan to report that city officials from throughout the republic had gathered wednesday to appeal to authorities in moscow for support
this is not a nationalist or an extremist action,'' said gamlet kocharyan, who said he was a member of the governing council of the city of kafan. he said the armenians' effort to annex a section of the neighboring republic of azerbaijan was legal and deserved the central government's attention
he said the appeal was adopted unanimously by 1,500 delegates at the meeting in yerevan and would be sent to moscow. it also asked the national party central committee to reprimand soviet media for inaccurate and incomplete reporting on the ethnic disturbances, he said
the tass report on the kremlin meeting, which was the top item on the national news program ``vremya,'' said public order was being observed and that schools and businesses were open in azerbaijan and armenia
tass said the officials discussed ``the situation taking shape in these republics in connection with the events in nagorno-karabakh.''
nagorno-karabakh is an armenian-dominated region of azerbaijan that armenians want to be annexed to their republic
tensions between armenians and azeris erupted in violence feb. 28 in the azerbaijani city of sumgait. foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov said 32 people were killed in the rioting
at a news briefing, gerasimov said ``the situation is normal, but passions are still running high since people still remember what happened.''
the soviet government has blamed the killings on ``hooligans'' provoked by rumors of ethnic turmoil elsewhere. but some armenian activists claim the death toll is much higher and that the violence was instigated by azeris out of ethnic hatred
gorbachev issued an appeal last month to both ethnic groups to cease fighting and work together to resolve the territorial dispute
tass said the armenian and azeri officials who met with gorbachev declared their peoples' support for an orderly approach to determining the fate of nagorno-karabakh
earlier, armenian nationalists called on the politburo to protect their countrymen from attacks by azeris and said they plan a general strike later this week
hovik vassilian, a nationalist in yerevan, said armenians fear their azeri neighbors will resort to violence during a march 18-23 holiday observed by shiite moslems
azeris are predominantly shiite moslem, while most armenians are christian
vassilian also said that hundreds of thousands of armenians staged a demonstration tuesday in yerevan to mourn countrymen killed in the ethnic turmoil
gerasimov confirmed that a demonstration took place at yerevan's memorial to armenian victims of the 1915 turkish invasion, but said he did not know how many people participated
inspectors at 11 u.s. international airports who guard against agricultural pests and diseases are being equipped with x-ray machines to detect illegal sausages, mangoes and other contraband, the agriculture department said wednesday
imported meats can carry exotic diseases that could devastate american livestock,'' said james w. glosser, head of the department's animal and plant health inpection service. ``fruits and vegetable coming into the country can carry pests that could seriously damage american crops.''
agency inspectors have used x-ray equipment in puerto rico and hawaii for departures for several years, with interceptions of prohibited agricultural items doubling, he said
the new systems for arrivals were recently installed at international airports in miami, honolulu, luis munoz international in puerto rico, houson and chicago
additional equipment soon will be installed at international airports in atlanta, new york, boston, los angeles, san francisco and washington d.c
the usda agency also is installing large signs at the 11 airports telling travelers that x-rays are being used to check their baggage
although most people willingly declare their agricultural products, we do come across some intentional violators,'' glosser said. ``that's only natural, considering that we encountered an estimated 43 million air travelers in 1987. some ignore the regulations and others are not even aware of them, despite all our information efforts.''
glosser said the agency uses several methods to find smuggled agricultural items, including trained beagles to sniff out illegal imports
finally, we rely on the deterrent effect of penalties,'' he said. ``we fine violators $25 to $50, payable on the spot. we currently collect about $30,000 per month, and we have collected nearly $1.8 million since 1984. fines are deposited in the u.s. treasury.''
bowing to a british demand, the panamanian ambassador agreed to waive his diplomatic immunity wednesday and be questioned by police over a raid he authorized on his country's consulate, the embassy said
we haven't done anything wrong,'' embassy spokesman geronimo de obaldia said of the monday night raid, in which british security guards hired by the embassy crashed a land rover through the glass doors of panama's london consulate and occupied it
no one was hurt, there was some glass broken and that's it,'' de obaldia told the associated press
an embassy statement said ambassador guillermo vega told the foreign office in a letter wednesday he ``and relevant members of his staff ... are ready to be interviewed by the authorities in respect of the events of march 7 at the consulate.''
the foreign office, however, considered vega's response ``unclear and inadequate,'' summoned him for the third time in two days and gave him 24 hours to provide a ``definite response,'' said a spokesman, who under british procedure declined to be identified
vega supports panamanian military leader gen. manuel antonio noriega, who arranged the ouster of president eric delvalle on feb. 26. consul eduardo arango, whose fleet street offices were seized, is loyal to delvalle
the foreign office had set a deadline for the panamanians to waive diplomatic immunity and hinted that vega might be expelled if he refused
de obaldia told the ap the embassy announcement meant the ambassador waived diplomatic immunity for himself and other diplomats
under international law, diplomats cannot be charged with criminal offenses or questioned by police unless they waive immunity
besides vega, the foreign office said police want to question embassy counselor jorge e. constantino, who allegedly accompanied the raiders or was nearby, and any other diplomats involved
seven britons employed by the security firm which vega hired for the raid were arrested and charged with public order offenses. they have no diplomatic protection
panama's ambassador to the european economic community, angel. e. riera, also a delvalle loyalist, meanwhile said noriega supporters broke into his office in strasbourg, france, on wednesday
riera said the raiders, led by a panamanian colonel, smashed the office door, searched for money and left when they found none
the tough british response to the london raid underlined conservative government insistence that london streets not be turned into battlegrounds for internal disputes in foreign countries
control of panamana's washington embassy is also in dispute following noriega's takeover
delvalle was ousted hours after demanding that noriega resign following his february indictment in florida on drug trafficking charges. reference to shultz.</note>
a top state department official headed for moscow wednesday to explain to soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze what the united states is doing to get peace talks started in the middle east
the state department said that assistant secretary of state richard murphy left washington tuesday night headed for moscow, with a brief stopover in brussels to brief the u.s. nato allies on the american mideast peace plan
murphy's talks in moscow are designed to prepare shevardnadze for his visit to washington on march 22, when he and secretary of state george p. shultz will discuss how best to advance the mideast initiative
the two men already discussed the mideast situation when shultz visited moscow last month prior to undertaking a shuttle between jordan, egypt and israel to present his plan
the plan reportedly calls for israel and its arab neighbors to launch talks by may 1 on a three-year autonomy period for the 1.5 million palestinians living under israeli occupation. the sides would begin talks on a long-term solution to the occupied west bank and gaza strip in december
the united states is seeking soviet support for the plan in an effort to enlist the backing of the arabs, especially those closely allied with the kremlin like syria
the shultz plan calls for the soviets to join england, france, china and the united states in overseeing the talks
murphy is also scheduled to stop in rome, paris and bonn as part of the u.s. effort to ensure a broad base of support for the initiative which was sparked by three months of israeli-palestinian clashes which have left more than 80 arabs dead
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir is due in washington next week, but he is not expected to bring an israeli response to his plan, despite such a demand from shultz
shamir, leader of the right-wing likud bloc, objects to an international conference out of concern that such a forum will pressure israel into giving up occupied lands
instead, shamir will propose an agreement with jordan on a step-by-step plan for implementing self-rule quickly in a limited area of the west bank or gaza. no indication of mechanical failure in crash. pick up 6th graf pvs, `schoel said ...'; inserts two grafs after 10th pvs, `we have ...' to add weather conditions, number of servicemen in each helicopter.</note>
army crews wednesday retrieved the last eight bodies of 17 soldiers killed when two helicopters on a night training mission collided, then plunged 250 feet to the ground and caught fire
the uh-60 blackhawk helicopters from fort campbell spewed wreckage for hundreds of yards and charred the partially wooded, gently rolling site six miles from the choppers' air field tuesday night
one aircraft is located in the trees. one aircraft is right on the edge of a clearing,'' said maj. randy schoel, fort campbell spokesman
it was the worst army aviation disaster since 248 soldiers based at fort campbell were killed in 1985 in the crash of a chartered plane in gander, newfoundland, schoel said
the blackhawk, one of the newer helicopters used by the army, air force and marine corps, has been grounded four times in three years. last summer officials said about 40 people had been killed in crashes of the helicopter since 1978
i would say now there is no indication of any mechanical factor'' in the crash, said chief warrant officer joe adams of the investigation team from the army safety center at fort rucker, ala. ``we are looking at human and environmental factors. the human factors might include some restriction of vision.''
four bodies were taken from the wreckage of each helicopter wednesday, schoel said
schoel said the crash occurred on the western kentucky-tennessee border during a ``routine night mission,'' and left no survivors
obviously, there's an element of risk in everything we do. we train up to a standard that reduces that risk to an absolute minimum,'' schoel said. ``yes it can be, but it's not necessarily, more dangerous to fly at night.''
the helicopters were flying at 92 mph air speed and about 250 feet from the ground when they collided, schoel said. one of three helicopters flying in formation was hit by a fourth, said william harralson, deputy public affairs officer at the fort
there were three aircraft in formation, if you want to say ducks in a row, headed east, and another who was flying solo, hit one of those,'' said harralson. ``there can be 10 or 12 battalion-sized groups working at fort campbell at one time.''
we have been told by the tower that the weather was good,'' he said
the solo helicopter carried four servicemen; the 13 others were in the other aircraft
adams said the weather was good, which in military terms means visibility of better than a mile and a cloud ceiling of at least 500 feet
one helicopter crashed on the tennessee side of the border, the other in kentucky. although the soldiers were carrying personal weapons, such as m-16 rifles, the helicopters were not armed, schoel said
one of the other blackhawk helicopters returned to the air field; the other landed at the crash site
they witnessed the accident. they were providing statements to the investigators, and the decision was made not to make them fly it back,'' schoel said
a team from the army safety center at fort rucker, ala., was called to investigate. a safety expert from sikorsky aircraft in stratford, conn., the helicopter's manufacturer, also sent a safety expert
the army identified three of the dead as staff sgt. charles l. shirley, 21, of arkansas; sgt. dennis sabot, 28, of iowa; and spec. 4 samuel a. hintz, 23, of ohio, all from the 2nd battalion, 502nd infantry. home towns were not provided. names of the other victims were withheld pending notification of relatives
the army's fleet of 820 uh-60s was grounded twice in may 1987, once for inspection and once because of a design flaw. the entire fleet also was grounded in april 1985 and march 1986 after fatal crashes. in 1985, the army identified a defect in the main rotor assembly and ordered it corrected
army undersecretary james r. ambrose said in november he had confidence in the blackhawk. noting news reports that radio and microwave towers on the ground can interfere with the aircraft's electronic control systems, he said no safety hazard had been found
the blackhawk has a safety record at least four times better than the aircraft it replaced,'' said bob stangarone, a spokesman for sikorsky, a division of united technologies
stangarone noted the army has shown its confidence in the blackhawk by awarding sikorsky multiyear contracts for the helicopter
the blackhawk is designed primarily as a utility and assault aircraft and is used in air assault, air cavalry and medical evacuation, said maj. phil soucy, a spokesman for the army in washington
soucy said there had been no move by safety investigators to ground the blackhawk fleet as a result of the accident
the helicopter normally is operated with a crew of three and can carry 11 combat-equipped soldiers
fort campbell was the home base of 248 soldiers killed dec. 12, 1985, when a chartered jet bringing them home for christmas from peacekeeping duties in the sinai peninsula crashed in gander, newfoundland. 10th graf pvs, bgng: dole contended</note>
republican presidential candidate bob dole, conceding he must win in illinois, renewed his call for a series of one-on-one debates in the state with vice president george bush. but bush rebuffed the request, saying it was time to look ahead to the general election
i respectfully decline your invitation to debate in illinois,'' bush said in a telegram to dole, reminding his rival that the two have already been in six gop debates together. ``i believe it is now time to look ahead to the issues which distinguish us from the democrats.''
good luck,'' added the vice president, who trounced dole in the big round of super tuesday contests. dole was all to mindful of that as he kicked off his illinois effort on wednesday
i've got to win illinois,'' he said. ``and if i can do that then ... i think people will pause to reflect.''
dole spoke outside a hospital where he had surgery 40 years ago for crippling wounds suffered in world war ii. he said he came to visit wesley hospital, now part of the northwestern memorial hospital complex, because ``i walked out of these doors and started back on the road to recovery.''
after taking a bath yesterday, i've got to start down that road again,'' dole said
bush won 16 of 17 republican contests on tuesday, while dole won none
the kansas senator said ``it would not be easy'' to overtake bush but he maintained that he could do it ``the hard way _ one state at a time.''
at northwestern law school, dole renewed his call for bush to participate in a round of lincoln-douglas style debates without moderators
i just appeal to george bush. here's a chance, george, to finish me off right here in illinois,'' dole said
dole contended that past debates featured too many candidates and prevented a clear comparison of his record with the vice president's
he also began airing a tv commercial in which he links bush to u.s. arms sales to iran
dole projected a confident, come-from-behind theme and repeatedly told audiences that he was a ``strong person'' who had overcome past personal difficulties
i'm here after a rather difficult day,'' dole told the law students. ``i feel like i've just taken the finals, and i didn't flunk but i didn't do too well either.''
dole aides contend that the senator can survive if he wins a large share of the 82 republican delegates at stake in the march 15 illinois primary. but even if he does well in illinois, he would face an uphill fight with bush all the way to the nominating convention in august
asked if illinois is a do-or-die contest for dole, thomas rath, a senior campaign strategist, said: ``if it's not, it'll do until the real thing comes along. we have to view this campaign in short bursts, and clearly the next burst for us is illinois.''
assessing the impact of tuesday's defeats, william brock, dole's campaign chairman, would only say: ``that causes a lot of problems for us.''
rath said the dole campaign will begin to step up its attacks on bush with television ads to start running on thursday in some areas, drawing a comparisons between bush and dole's records. similar ads were used in the super tuesday states
in addition, rath said the campaign is considering a new tv spot to raise the ``electability issue.'' dole frequently cites polls that he says show him the strongest gop nominee against any democrat in the general election
by focusing on issues, the dole campaign can ``cut the umbilical cord'' that links bush to president reagan and gives him a popularity boost among republicans who favor the administration, rath said
dole campaigned in the chicago area on wednesday beneath leaden skies and in a damp chill _ weather that seemed to match the gloomy aftermath of super tuesday for his campaign
but in contrast to his defeat in new hampshire, when dole angrily lashed out at bush, the kansas senator tried to project an upbeat image and repeatedly declared that he was ``on the road to recovery'' in illinois
at a suburban commuter train station, dole shook hands with a few people as they hurried off to work
one man, who identified himself as a dole supporter but declined to give his name, summed up the political landscape for a reporter: ``i guess it's all over for him unless he wins illinois. that's too bad.''
the world court on wednesday ordered hearings on a united nations attempt to block the united states from shutting down the plo's office in new york
anti-terrorism legislation passed by the u.s. congress on dec. 22 calls for the palestine liberation organization u.n. observer mission to be closed by march 21
the united states defied a 143-1 u.n. vote last month that called for the dispute to be submitted to an independent arbitration panel
u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar last week asked the court for a ruling on whether the united states has a right to refuse arbitration, which is called for in the 1947 headquarters treaty
on wednesday, the 15-member world court ordered hearings april 11 in the case
the court also ordered the united nations and the united states to submit written arguments by march 25. other u.n. members are also entitled to file arguments, a court statement said
the world court, formally known as the international court of justice, has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its rulings
the plo was granted non-voting observer status at the united nations in 1974 and has maintained an office in new york ever since
the u.s. state department and the united nations say the united states is obliged by the 1947 headquarters treaty to allow the observer mission to remain. but attorney general edwin meese iii reportedly said he plans to enforce the measure anyway. he is expected to announce his decision later this month. for the day; picks up 2nd graf pvs, `the prosecution...'</note>
a jury wednesday began deliberating whether a 15-year-old who admitted bludgeoning a classmate with a baseball bat was a cold-blooded thrill killer or a troubled teen-ager whose cries for help had been ignored
the panel deliberated for four hours wednesday before recessing until thursday morning
the prosecution in its closing argument portrayed rod matthews of canton as a calculating murderer who lured 14-year-old shaun ouillette into the woods in november 1986 just ``to find out what it was like to kill somebody.''
he did that because he doesn't care about anybody,'' said norfolk county district attorney peter casey, who repeatedly jabbed an accusatory finger at matthews. ``what did it feel like? it was deliberate. ... he really wound up and hit him about the head.''
defense attorney john philip white urged the jury to deliver a verdict of innocent by reason of insanity, characterizing matthews as a ``diseased intellect'' unable to act rationally. white also said attempts by matthews, 14 at the time of the slaying, to seek help from teachers prior to the nov. 20, 1986, slaying were ignored
matthews, whose eyes were downcast during the two hours of closing arguments wednesday, the seventh day of the trial, admitted to clubbing ouillette, also of canton. he had told friends he wanted to kill someone and had chosen ouillette. after the slaying, he showed them ouillette's body
had they said, `no, don't kill shaun ouillette,' in all likelihood shaun ouillette would not have been harmed,'' said white, as matthews' mother, janice, sobbed quietly and shook throughout his statement
matthews faces a mandatory sentence of life imprisonment without parole if convicted of first-degree murder. if found guilty of second-degree murder, the maximum would be life imprisonment with a chance of parole. a manslaughter conviction would bring a maximum prison term of 20 years
white said if matthews is found innocent by reason of insanity, he will be evaluated by the state department of mental health and is likely to be hospitalized for at least ``14 to 15 years.''
casey said the defense's contention that the drug ritalin had affected matthews adversely was a ``smoke screen.'' casey noted testimony from several medical experts that ritalin does not permanently alter behavior or trigger violence or hallucinations in normal doses
white depicted matthews as a highly unstable youth whose use of ritalin to control hyperactivity may have triggered his violent behavior
dr. bernard yudowitz of belmont's mclean hospital testified monday that ritalin may have made it harder for matthews to control his behavior. matthews first decided to kill someone after viewing the controversial videotape ``faces of death,'' which shows animal and human executions and tortures, said yudowitz
matthews said he had plotted the slaying for a month to experience what killing someone was like, according to testimony from two classmates who were shown the body by matthews prior to a pre-thanksgiving pep rally
ouillette's body was discovered in december 1986 after one of the youths sent police an anonymous letter. the youths testified that matthews, who is being tried as an adult, selected ouillette because he did not feel he would be missed
none of the teen-agers who knew of the slaying faces prosecution
the trial was attended each day by several dozen residents of canton, a middle-class community of 17,000 people about 15 miles south of boston
it's been long and hard but it's been worth it. anytime you have to fight for your child it's worth it,'' said jeanne quinn, ouillette's mother
the case has been compared to the trial of anthony broussard, 18, sentenced 25 years to life dec. 3, 1982, in san jose, calif., for killing his girlfriend the year before. broussard, who was tried as an adult, took at least 13 schoolmates to see the victim's body. the movie ``the river's edge'' was based on that case
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said he had sent telegrams wednesday congratulating all the democratic candidates who won delegates on super tuesday and asking them to eschew negative ads from now on in the campaign
candidates with viable ideas and strong ideals do not need to rely on negative campaigning which only tarnishes and muddles the processes of democracy,'' wright said
wright said the use of negative ads had become a ``vogue,'' intensified by the short time between the new hampshire primaries and tuesday's 20-state extravaganza
the rush left ``no time to make a sensible ... appeal,'' wright said, and led candidates to ``succumb to the wicked blandishments of those in the advertising fraternity'' who specialize in attack ads
super tuesday, wright said, ``put a great premium on having an enormous amount of money to spend in little quickie tv spots'' and denied candidates the chance to be evaluated by voters on the merits of their ideas
he said rep. richard gephardt, who was strongly supported by a long list of his house democratic colleagues ``basically ran out of money'' but had not been eliminated from the race
house majority leader thomas foley, d-wash., agreed that the idea of a large regional primary could use at least some fine-tuning
it might be better if super tuesday were a little smaller and not quite so soon after new hampshire,'' foley said
gallaudet university faculty on wednesday overwhelmingly sided with students calling for the resignations of the deaf school's board chairwoman and newly named president
the selection of elisabeth zinser, a hearing woman, as president of the nation's only school for the deaf kicked off a protest that has virtually paralyzed the campus since monday
this is the selma of the deaf,'' said kathy karcher, a 29-year-old graduate student, comparing the desire by deaf students to be led by a deaf president to the demands in 1963 by blacks in selma, ala. to participate in elections
in the 11 years i've been here, i've never seen such support for an issue,'' said frank zieziula, chairman of gallaudet's counseling department
more than half of the school's 274-member faculty supported replacing board chairwoman jane bassett spilman and zinser
they also joined the students' call for a deaf majority on the school's 20-member board of trustees. the board now has four deaf members
the faculty vote came after spilman introduced zinser at a press conference by saying the school's 12-member presidential search committee had been looking for ``the best qualified candidate, not necessarily a deaf candidate.''
i do not feel that i made a mistake, and the majority of the board of trustees do not feel that they made a mistake,'' spilman said
zinser, an administrator at the university of north carolina at greensboro, does not know sign language, and students have claimed that her selection is another indication that the trustees do not understand how important a deaf role model is
spilman said she once tried to learn sign language herself, but had difficulties practicing it off campus
i do not have a great deal of interaction with deaf people,'' the trustees' chairwoman said. ``therefore, i do not know how to sign.''
zinser's decision to stay on surprised students and faculty, since protests that started after her appointment sunday night have stopped most instruction on the the campus
the only way in which i would step aside is if the board of trustees asked me to,'' said zinser, who prevailed over two deaf finalists
zinser has more experience, but this is the point no one is mentioning: deaf people just haven't been given the chance,'' zieziula said. ``how can they be expected to compete, academically or otherwise, if they don't have the same opportunities?''
gallaudet, founded in 1864 by an act of congress, receives three-quarters of its $76 million budget in federal funds. spilman and zinser met late wednesday with reps. steve gunderson, r-wis., and david bonior, d-mich, who serve on the board of trustees
earlier in the day, the congressman met with gallaudet alumni, students, faculty and staff
neither they nor sen. daniel inouye, d-hawaii, the third member of congress on the board, participated in the selection of zinser as the new president
gunderson said traditionally the congressional role in the operation of the university has been inactive
but that is going to change,'' he said
tom thieding, gunderson's press secretary, said the congressmen's intent was to hear all sides and make a decision ``that is best for the university.''
students say they will keep up the protest, despite zinser's determination to take her post
peaceful but well-attended protests on monday forced officials to cancel classes for the day, and a boycott of classes on tuesday and wednesday left most classrooms virtually empty
a professor at west germany's max planck institute said wednesday a japanese colleague may have solved a mathematical puzzle that has beguiled scientists and researchers since the 17th century
professor don zagier, an american working as a researcher at the institute, said in a telephone interview that mathematician yoichi miyaoka may finally have proven fermat's last theorem
the theorem was developed by french mathematician and magistrate pierre de fermat, who lived from 1601 to 1665 and was a founder of modern number theory and probability
it states: x to the nth power, plus y to the nth power, equals z to the nth power, where x, y, and z are nonzero integers, has no solutions for n when n is an integer _ or whole number _ greater than the number two
zagier said wednesday, ``many important developments in number theory have resulted from unsuccessful attempts to prove fermat's last theorem.''
he said miyaoka, who also works at the max planck institute for mathematics in bonn, now may have succeeded
zagier, who is also a professor at the university of maryland, said, ``this whole thing is of course in the preliminary stages, but miyaoka, who gave a presentation on his solution 10 days ago, believes he has proven the theory and it is certainly serious and very exciting.''
zagier replied when asked if miyaoka was available to discuss his solution that miyaoka was ``too busy rechecking his work ... he wants to be sure the manuscript is accurate before it goes out.''
the american added, ``i've been more or less answering the telephone for him since word of this leaked out.''
zagier said he jotted down notes at miyaoka's presentation and sent them to gerd faltings at princeton, mathematicians barry mazur and christophe soule in paris, and other experts
of course the notes alone are not sufficient, and miyaoka has been preparing and checking his manuscript on the solution for the past week, and that will also be sent to the experts to check,'' said zagier
zagier said he hoped results from the experts would come in the next 10 days, but it could take months. resignation of envoy to mexico; picks up 6th graf pvs bgng: they said ..., editing to conform.</note>
a nephew of omar torrijos, national hero in panama for negotiating the panama canal treaties, disclosed wednesday he has broken with his country's military-dominated government, accusing it of plunging panama into a political crisis
meanwhile, the panamanian embassy made public the copy of a letter by panama's ambassador to mexico, emilia arosemena vallarino, in which she announced her resignation because she was ``in disagreement with political events'' in her country. she had served in mexico for 18 years and was dean of the diplomatic corps there
santiago torrijos, about 40 years old, left his post tuesday as chief of panama's consulate in los angeles and flew to an undisclosed location in washington to join forces loyal to ousted president eric arturo delvalle
telephone calls to the consulate wednesday afternoon were not answered
santiago torrijos is the son of a brother of omar torrijos, the former head of the panamanian national guard, now known as the panamanian defense forces
he said in a type-written statement distributed to news organizations wednesday night the defense forces have not lived up to a pledge made by omar torrijos to establish constitutional democracy in panama
the political, financial, moral and social crisis in panama must be rectified,'' he said
diplomatic sources, insisting on anonymity, said santiago torrijos is the first member of the torrijos family to break ranks with gen. manuel antonio noriega, the commander of the defense forces who orchestrated delvalle's ouster two weeks ago
they said the defection is considered significant because of the close identification of the torrijos family with the defense forces
word of the defection came as the reagan administration prepared for a high-level inter-agency meeting thursday at which a series of economic sanctions against panama will be considered
u.s. officials, who asked not to be identified, said that it is almost certain that the united states will withhold a $6.5 million payment due to panama on march 15 for canal-related operations
also being considered are measures that will have the effect of making some panamanian products less competitive in u.s. markets. state department figures show that panama's u.s. exports totaled $342 million last year, but commerce department statistics list that category at $388 million
meanwhile, white house chief of staff howard baker denied wednesday that the united states is planning an invasion of panama, saying american troops there are merely holding regularly scheduled training exercises
panama is the site of national guard training exercises and has been for years,'' baker said. ``and as i understand it, the rhode island national guard is now holding regularly scheduled exercises in panama
and certainly if the united states was going to invade panama, it wouldn't be with the rhode island national guard. so it simply is not so. it has no connection at all,'' baker said, talking with reporters at the white house after seeing president reagan off on a trip to indiana
jorge abadia, panama's foreign minister, on tuesday accused the united states of conducting ``the prelude of an armed invasion'' by staging military exercises along the panama canal
as part of his effort to survive mounting protests in panama against the new government, noriega from time to time has invoked omar torrijos' name
omar torrijos was killed in a plane crash in july 1981. a former deputy of noriega, col. roberto diaz herrera, caused a political stir in panama last june by alleging that noriega was responsible for torrijos' death by arranging to place a bomb aboard the aircraft
torrijos, the key figure in panamanian politics from 1968 until his death, is a revered figure in panama for persuading president jimmy carter to agree to a treaty that will revert the panama canal to panamanian control at the end of 1999
santiago torrijos is said to be an engineer who headed a government-owned cement plant in panama before becoming consul general in los angeles about four years ago
delvalle attempted to fire noriega on feb. 25 but was fired himself hours later by the national assembly, which is dominated by noriega loyalists
the reagan administration has refused to recognize the successor government, nominally headed by president manuel solis palma, and instead continues to recognize delvalle as the constitutional authority in panama. noriega has been indicted by two federal grand juries on drug smuggling charges
a federal appeals court wednesday upheld an order requiring nbc to surrender outtakes of an interview with a former consultant for lyndon larouche who said a top larouche aide discussed killing henry kissinger
the 1st u.s. circuit court of appeals, which also affirmed a contempt citation against the network, said videotape of the entire interview should be given to the judge at the trial of larouche, six aides and five political organizations
larouche, a candidate for the 1988 democratic presidential nomination, is charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury investigation into an alleged scheme to finance his 1984 campaign through loan and credit-card fraud
floyd abrams, an attorney for nbc, said no decision had been made on whether to appeal. he said the ruling ``does not sufficient recognize the first amendment rights of broadcasters.''
nbc had contended that surrendering outtakes, or portions of the interview not broadcast, violated a first amendment right against judicial intrusion into newsgathering and editorial decisions
u.s. district judge robert e. keeton ruled in december that the rights of the defendants to access to the interview with forrest lee fick outweighed nbc's rights
at stake in the defendants' side of the equation are their constitutional rights to a fair trial,'' the appeals court wrote in concurring with keeton, who planned to review the tape and determine which portions, if any, were relevant to the case
keeton had issued a similar order requiring cbs to surrender outtakes of an interview with another larouche aide. cbs complied
fick, of reading, pa., worked as a larouche security consultant and is expected to be called as a witness at the trial
nbc interviewed fick for 100 minutes and in april 1986 aired a one-minute portion in which fick said he and larouche aide paul goldstein discussed a plot to assassinate kissinger, the former secretary of state
goldstein is a defendant in the case now on trial
defense lawyers argued for access to the entire nbc interview. they contend fick was among scores of operatives planted in larouche organizations by the fbi and cia to gather information and cripple larouche's fund-raising network
the contempt citation against nbc carried with it a $500-a-day fine, which keeton had stayed pending the appeal
larouche has attended most of the trial since in began in december. he was allowed to travel last week to west germany, where his wife lives, to have surgery for glaucoma
he is accused of ordering fund-raisers to flee the country and destroy records to stymie the grand jury investigation
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. ran strongly throughout arkansas to rack up nearly double the number of votes cast for massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in the democratic presidential primary
with all 2,762 precincts reporting, gore had 184,729 votes or 37 percent; dukakis had 93,532 votes or 19 percent; jesse jackson had 85,047 votes or 17 percent, and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 59,471 votes or 12 percent
in the republican race, vice president george bush had 31,327 votes or 47 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 17,359 votes or 26 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 12,232 votes or 18 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 3,405 votes or 5 percent
based on those results, gore would capture 19 democratic delegates, dukakis 10 and jackson 9. bush would get 15 gop delegates, dole 7, robertson 5 and kemp 1
also on the ballot, u.s. rep. bill alexander crushed the bid of political consultant darrell glascock in the race for the democratic nomination for congress in the 1st district. alexander won by a 2-1 margin. there is no republican nominee
dukakis was the choice of much of the state's democratic establishment, but gore had strong support that ranged from farm districts to cities throughout the state. jackson wiped out his democratic opposition in areas where blacks were in the majority, but finished third or worse in most other places
arkansas had a large voter turnout for the primary election; more than 55,000 people cast ballots, roughly double the state's norm
premier howard pawley of manitoba, head of the only socialist government in north america, resigned as leader of his party and called a provincial election wednesday after losing a vote of confidence
pawley, 53, leader of the new democratic party, had ruled with a one-seat majority until the unexpected defeat in a budget vote tuesday night
when renegade new democrat jim walding sided with the opposition, the government fell by 28 votes to 27
pawley, elected to a second five-year term in 1986, waited overnight before meeting with his party and announcing his decision to call an april 26 election in manitoba, a large central province with just over 1 million people
an election was expected, in accordance with canadian parliamentary tradition following defeat on a budget vote
but pawley stunned colleagues by also announcing his plan to step down after nine years as leader. a leadership convention will select a successor who will be thrust immediately into the election campaign
this would not have been a time of my choosing,'' said the premier
there was speculation pawley might switch to federal politics by running for the new democrats in the next national election, due within 18 months
ed broadbent, national leader of the new democratic party, said in ottawa wednesday he would welcome pawley aboard
the upheaval in winnipeg has other national ramifications
latest polls indicate the conservative party in manitoba is twice as popular as the new democrats, with a good chance of winning the provincial election
that would please conservative prime minister brian mulroney's federal government because pawley was the most outspoken provincial opponent of the free-trade agreement mulroney negotiated last year with the united states
pawley also has reservations about the meech lake constitutional accord fashioned last year to recognize french-majority quebec as ``a distinct society'' and to share federal powers with the 10 provinces
national opinion surveys put the new democrats in a dead heat with the conservatives and opposition liberal party. pawley could help broadbent convert that popularity into seats
the new democratic party has its origins in the cooperative commonwealth federation, a socialist political group founded in the canadian prairies in the depression 1930s. it introduced unemployment benefit and socialized medicine to canada
walding, a former speaker of the manitoba legislature who felt overlooked by pawley, explained his defection by saying he was under too much strain keeping the government afloat with his one vote
it is time for the people of manitoba to decide whether this government still has a mandate,'' he said
a group that opposes a peace accord with minority tamils killed six people from the sinhalese ethnic majority, including a government official and two family members, military officers said wednesday
the officers blamed the outlawed people's liberation front, a sinhalese group, for the killings near beliatta, 85 miles southeast of colombo
they said the official, p.k. dissanayake, and two members of his family were abducted tuesday night by men wearing police uniforms and their bodies were found early early wednesday. three other sinhalese were shot dead wednesday, the officers said, speaking on condition of anonymity
authorities blame the sinhalese group for more than 150 killings since july 1987 in its campaign against a peace agreement designed to end a 4-year-old tamil separatist war that has taken more than 8,000 lives. the front claims the july 29 agreement grants tamils too many concessions
tamils, most of whom are hindus, make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the majority sinhalese, a predominantly buddhist ethnic group that controls government and military. testimony</head> first count, senate refusing to drop charge, mecham interview shown, editing to tighten. picks up 19th graf pvs, `however, she...'</note>
a former aide to gov. evan mecham testified wednesday at mecham's impeachment trial that an official accused of threatening her enjoyed special status because of his fund-raising for mecham
donna carlson, mecham's former special assistant for legislative affairs, said that when she once complained about lee watkins' position in the governor's inner circle, she was told by mecham's then chief of staff: ``we have to take care of lee. he raised a lot of money for the campaign.''
the former chief of staff, jim colter, did not immediately return a telephone message left by the associated press
mecham is accused of obstructing the state attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat by watkins on ms. carlson's life in november as she was about to testify before a grand jury investigating mecham's campaign finances
after ms. carlson's testimony wednesdsay and the showing of videotaped comments by mecham, the prosecution rested its case on the obstruction charge, and the senate voted down, 25-4, a defense motion to dismiss the count
the presiding officer directed the defense to begin presenting its case
the governor also is accused concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 in state money by loaning it to his car dealership
mecham has not attended the proceedings, but senators wednesday were shown a nov. 16 tv interview in which mecham denied knowledge of the alleged death threat
prosecution witnesses have testified that mecham had been told of the alleged threat and had directed an aide to investigate several days before the interview
mecham, a 63-year-old first-term republican, is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades
it would take a two-thirds vote of the senate to convict him. the senators could then take another vote to bar him from holding state office again
mecham also faces a criminal trial on charges of concealing the $350,000 loan and a recall election may 17. on wednesday the trial was rescheduled, from march 22 to april 21
ms. carlson, who said she took the reported threat on her life seriously because watkins has a criminal record, told the senate that neither mecham nor any of his close aides ever called to inquire about her safety in light of the threat
i felt very alone,'' she said
she said she believed her only protection then was to go to the news media with word of the threat and ``let the world know about it.'' she said she was the source of an arizona republic story that first reported the alleged threat on her life
watkins, who previously denied threatening ms. carlson, last week refused to testify, citing his fifth amendment rights against self-incrimination. the former chief of prison construction resigned in january after it was disclosed that he did not report a 1966 assault conviction to the state
on friday, corrections director sam lewis testified that watkins told him in june 1987 the mecham administration owed watkins a job because ``the more that you raise for the campaign, the higher level job you received in state government.''
lewis also testified watkins told him ``he had enough (information) that he could bring the entire administration down.''
ms. carlson worked for mecham's election and became one of his closest advisers before resigning in a dispute over official policies and appointments
she said her emnity with watkins dated back to the early days of mecham's administration when she warned the governor to ``be very careful'' of associating himself with watkins, who had been the subject of negative newspaper articles
however, she said she didn't learn until last september of watkins' criminal record. in 1959, he was convicted at age 19 of the robbery of a post office and served time in a federal youth offender correctional facility. he was convicted of assault in 1966
she said she was upset that the information had come to the governor's staff so late and complained to department of public safety director ralph milstead
he said the information had been sent to the governor in january or february,'' she testified
ms. carlson said it was milstead who informed her of the threat on her life three days after it allegedly was made in november
the justice department filed a notice wednesday that it would appeal a federal judge's decision to suppress the confession of a former lebanese shiite amal militiaman accused of leading an airline hijacking
the government's move to appeal the ruling by u.s. district judge barrington d. parker stays the march 22 trial of fawaz younis pending a ruling by the u.s. circuit court of appeals here
parker ruled last month that the fbi illegally obtained a confession from younis when he was arrested in the mediterranean after being lured into an fbi-chartered yacht
the judge ruled that prosecutors could not use the confession as evidence that younis led four other hijackers who seized a royal jordanian airliner on june 11, 1985 at beirut international airport
the plane was destroyed a day later after the passengers and crew were taken off the aircraft
parker criticized the fbi's four-day interrogation of younis aboard a navy munitions ship following his arrest last sept. 13 in international waters off cyprus
younis, whose wrists were broken when two fbi agents slammed him to the deck of the yacht, suffered throbbing pain and seasickness that left him in no condition to rationally waive his constitutional right to remain silent, the judge said
parker said the four-day cruise aboard the navy ship was conducted solely for the purpose of obtaining a confession
the notice of appeal was filed even though prosecutors have not received permission from solicitor general charles fried to take the case to the appellate court. it can be withdrawn if fried decides the government has no ground to appeal parker's decision
the notice was filed as a protective measure to preserve the prosecution's right to appeal, according to government sources who spoke on condition of anonymity
although they want to use the confession, federal prosecutors have other evidence, including a videotape of younis reading a statement to reporters before the plane was blown up in the background. in addition, two americans who were aboard the plane when it was seized by heavily armed hijackers have identified younis as being one of their captors
the son of two former south vietnamese diplomats, on trial for their murder, was calm and under control the morning he found his parents dead in their bedroom, the family's physician testified wednesday
he struck me as controlled throughout the entire period,'' dr. philip james told a district of columbia superior court jury hearing the prosecution's case against tran van khiem
prosecutors presented medical evidence during the trial's second day to show that tran van chuong, 88, and his wife, nam tran chuong, 82, were murdered in the bedroom of their washington home the morning of july 24, 1986
tran van chuong was ambassador to the united states and his wife was south vietnam's observer to the united nations during the vietnamese war. the family was part of their nation's ruling hierarchy in the early 1960s, when one of their daughters, madame nhu, was married to the brother of then-president ngo dinh diem
a rift within the family dates back to the war period, when madame nhu became known as the ``dragon lady'' because of her support for diem's brutal policies
assistant u.s. attorney g. paul howes contends khiem, 62, killed his parents in anger after they disinherited him in their wills
medical examiner dr. carol mcmahon testified wednesday that she determined shortly after examining the bodies that they had been smothered and ``this was a double homicide.''
the wife was sprawled across her husband's body in a way that showed they died in an ``unnatural'' way, mcmahon said
james, the chuongs' family doctor for several years, told jurors khiem called the physician at his nearby office shortly after khiem has said he and a family butler discovered his parents' bodies
he said, `my parents are very old, my parents are very ill. they're in a coma,''' james said. ``he seemed calm. there was no great urgency or hysteria in his voice.''
the doctor said he came to the house immediately, examined the wife's body briefly and told khiem, ``they're gone ... i said, `i think they've been gone a long time.'''
dr. james said he had seen mrs. chuong the day before her death and that she appeared healthy and did not have any of the scratches and bruises later found on her body
the doctor said he immediately called police and that khiem then called one of his sisters, lecchi oggeri
that sister has said in police statements that her mother called her several times the night before the deaths and told her they were having an argument over khiem's inheritance. however, a judge has not allowed prosecutors to present evidence on what mrs. oggeri said her mother told her
riot police closed a technical school in the mainly moslem north wednesday after students there destroyed a christian chapel, newspapers reported
ten pupils were hurt when more than 10,000 students fled the campus of kaduna polytechnic school because of the arrival of the armed police, the lagos newspapers reported
christian students demonstrated wednesday in the streets of kaduna, where riot police were out in force. there were several violent incidents and one injury, the reports said without elaborating
kaduna is about 375 miles northeast of the nigerian capital of lagos
on tuesday, a group of moslem students marched on a christian chapel under construction at the technical school. the students smashed the walls, causing the structure to collapse, the newspaper reports said
christian students had been asking authorities to build the chapel for more than 10 years. there are five moslem mosques at the school
southern nigeria, where the capital city of lagos is located, is primarily christian
rosa l. parks, whose refusal to give up her seat to a white man on a segregated alabama bus sparked the 1955 montgomery bus boycott, was in satisfactory condition wednesday after receiving a pacemaker
mrs. parks, 75, of detroit, entered johns hopkins hospital on sunday and the procedure was performed tuesday, said hospital spokeswoman ghita levine. mrs. parks is expected to be discharged within a couple days, ms. levine said
mrs. parks in baltimore for medical tests and to help plan a birthday tribute to her in june, said spokeswoman ghita levine
nearly 33 years ago, mrs. parks was arrested for refusing to give up her bus seat. the black community retaliated by boycotting the buses
buses in montgomery and other southern cities ultimately were desegregated. her action was heralded as a watershed in the mounting civil rights movement
bavarian radio on wednesday banned a song that links the roman catholic church's opposition to birth control to the plight of millions suffering starvation in the world
udo reiter, director of bavarian rundfunk's radio division, said in a statement the song by popular west german entertainer udo juergens would not be broadcast because its lyrics ``would offend religious feelings.''
a station official said station managers concluded that the lyrics ``simply go too far.''
he spoke on condition of anonymity
the song ``go forth and multiply,'' which plays on a well-known bible passage, attacks church prohibitions against using artificial birth control
referring to problems caused by overpopulation, juergens wrote: ``the creator will become the destroyer if he continues on this way.''
bild newspaper on wednesday quoted juergens as saying, ``i don't want to offend anyone's religious beliefs, but the 50 million starving people in the world deserve a forthright voice.''
bild quoted a spokesman for augsburg bishop josef stimpfle as saying the lyrics contained ``hateful filth.''
conservative bavaria state has a large roman catholic population
peru extended a state of emergency wednesday in parts of two states in the eastern jungles, where leftist guerrillas are reported to be collaborating with drug traffickers
the government says that for the past year, mao-inspired shining path rebels have offered traffickers protection from police in exchange for money
a decree published in the official gazette and signed by president alan garcia prolonged emergency measures for two months across most of san martin state and two adjoining counties in huanuco state
the region lies on the eastern slopes of the andes, where most of the coca leaf, the raw ingredient of cocaine, is harvested. the drug is partially processed and then smuggled into colombia for refining
a state of emergency suspends constitutional rights to travel and meet freely. it permits government forces to conduct searches without warrants and hold suspects for long periods without filing charges
since the acts of violence continue ... it is necessary to maintain measures aimed at re-establishing public order,'' said the decree wednesday
the tupac amaru revolutionary movement, a smaller leftist guerrilla band considered less violent than shining path, expanded its urban insurgency to northern san martin state late last year
the government responded by declaring a state of emergency
