republican resistance to george bush's bid for the white house began crumbling wednesday as the impact of his fabulous super tuesday showing sank in. democrats michael dukakis, albert gore and jesse jackson savored their own successes while aiming for next week's showdown in illinois
massachusetts gov. dukakis and sen. gore of tennessee agreed the nomination struggle would last until the convention next summer. but they quarreled long-distance over which one of them could attract the most voters to the democratic banner in a campaign against the republicans
bush spent the day in houston savoring his 16-state primary sweep and the roughly 600 delegates they brought. the outlook for illinois wasn't bad either, as gov. james thompson was backing the vice president and sen. bob dole's own campaign polls gave bush the lead
dole, meanwhile, said rep. jack kemp had telephoned him to say he would drop out of the race thursday, without endorsing either of his republican rivals. kemp, who has scheduled a morning news conference in washington, had been expected to bow out after weak finishes in all the contests so far
he (kemp) wanted me to know he was going to get out tomorrow...he's not going to endorse anybody...he's going to stay neutral,'' dole told reporters in chicago
the vice president, for his part, sounded like he was trying to nudge dole from the race. he declined his rival's challenge to debate him in illinois in a telegram that said the time had come to ``look ahead to the issues which distinguish us from the democrats.''
good luck,'' he wrote
dole awoke to a campaign in shambles after losing all 17 super tuesday states and conceded, ``i've got to win illinois'' to save his candidacy. the kansas senator visited the hospital in chicago where he was treated 40 years ago for his crippling world war ii wounds, while his senior aides met to discuss wholesale staff reductions
republican pat robertson signaled he knew the game was all but over, although he said he would stay in contention
none of us could have dreamed that he (bush) could be so strong,'' said robertson. he said the vice president had run a ``fabulous race,'' and added, ``the mantle of ronald reagan has passed to george bush.'' the former television evangelist said he would remain in the race, but talked in terms of expanding his support for a campaign rerun in 1992
on the democratic side, gary hart was apparently poised to quit. he put travel plans on hold and scheduled a news conference on friday in denver. a denver tv station, kusa, said he had told his staff he would abandon his bid for the nomination
the former colorado senator, who has garnered few votes in any contest since re-entering the race in december, failed to win a single delegate on tuesday, and home state gov. roy romer endorsed dukakis. hart had dropped out of the race in may amid reports of his relationship with a miami model
at the white house, chief of staff howard baker said reagan would remain neutral in the race for a while longer. but then he added that it would take a ``major event'' to deny bush the nomination. ``he's certainly got the momentum,'' said baker, who once harbored white house ambitions of his own
if anything, the democratic race looked like it was just beginning. delegate leader dukakis stood only about a quarter of the way toward the 2,082 convention votes needed to be nominated
jackson was the early favorite to win the south carolina caucuses on saturday, while he and sen. paul simon looked like favorite son front-runners for next tuesday's illinois primary
jackson said he was ``overcome with a sense of history and joy'' after winning primaries in alabama, georgia, louisiana, mississippi and virginia and second-place finishes in massachusetts, rhode island, maryland and elsewhere
gore said dukakis was the embodiment of ``the same old formula'' that has led democrats to 49-state defeats in two of the last five presidential elections, and said he was the man to gain the allegiance of independent voters. ``this is a battle for the future of the democratic party,'' said gore, who won his home state of tennessee as well as arkansas, kentucky, north carolina and oklahoma and nevada's caucuses
dukakis, the leader in national convention delegates with 455, said polls show him running ahead of bush in florida and texas. the massachusetts governor said he had won a ``national victory,'' and pointed to wins in every corner of the country as evidence
he won primaries tuesday in texas, florida, maryland, rhode island and at home in massachusetts, and was the winner in the idaho caucuses and the leader in hawaii's caucuses
al hasn't won a primary outside the south,'' he said of gore
dukakis said he was the man with the message for the voters in the industrial state voters yet ahead. ``i'm a chief executive. i've balanced budgets, i took a state that was in desperate shape 12 years ago and today it's one of the great success stories,'' he said
simon, who sat out super tuesday, waited for his rivals in his home state. he said he fully expects to win both the popular vote and the plurality of the state's 187 national convention delegates, even though he won't be advertising on television. if he fails to win, he said, he will be reassessing his campaign
rep. richard gephardt, who won only his home state of missouri on tuesday, insisted the ``race is on'' as he attacked dukakis and gore on trade issues during a campaign stop in south carolina
despite his vow, aides said geophardt would make a minimal effort in illinois and hoped to conserve his resources for a major battle in the michigan caucuses on march 26
a formerly homeless woman who successfully fought her forced hospitalization by the city said wednesday she went back to the streets to panhandle for money over the weekend because she was broke
i'm not insane for having panhandled,'' said joyce brown, who has been living at a halfway house for women since her release from a psychiatric ward jan. 19. ``it's not a sign of insanity _ it's a sign of trying to survive.''
the 40-year-old miss brown, who called herself billie boggs on the street, said she won't panhandle again because she had just received social security checks mailed to her sister's new jersey home
the checks, totaling $7,000, were turned over to miss brown on tuesday, said her lawyer, norman siegel of the new york civil liberties union. miss brown said she needed $10 over the weekend for cigarettes and food
miss brown also acknowledged shouting obscenities at passers-by outside her hotel sunday, but only at those who taunted her
because i am known as a figure, people were being smart and sarcastic: `billie, didn't i see you on tv?' so i did use profanity to make them leave me alone, and it worked,'' she said, calmly answering questions
miss brown, after her release, had worked as a temporary receptionist at the aclu's office, and had given several interviews and made talk show appearances and speaking engagements, including one at harvard law school
she lived for months over a hot-air grate on manhattan's east side and was the first homeless person picked up and forcibly hospitalized when the city began clearing mentally ill people from the streets oct. 28
she was released after a judge ruled she could not be forced to take medication
dr. robert gould, whom miss brown visits weekly for psychotherapy, said she eventually will return to work but needs time to adjust to her freedom
her celebrity status in the last couple of months is not an easy thing to handle,'' he said
