the chief of the government's human rights watchdog agency said thursday allegations of widespread abuse raised by amnesty international were exaggerated
mary concepcion bautista, chairman of the government's human rights commission, made the statement after two human rights groups criticized the government of president corazon aquino on wednesday for allegedly using torture and terror to stem a 19-year-old insurgency by communist rebels
meanwhile, a former defense minister said the guerrillas were making major gains while the military has become increasingly plagued by infighting and lack of equipment
the activist task force-detainees, a private group supported by the roman catholic church, said that its investigation showed that 7,444 filipino civilians were arrested illegally in 1987, eclipsing the 5,967 arrests in 1985, when ferdinand marcos was president
spokesman noel salazar said his group's investigations showed that 602 of those people arrested illegally were tortured
aquino rose to power when marcos' authoritarian regime collapsed in feburary 1986
the task force-detainees allegations followed a critical report released wednesday in london by amnesty international
the human rights organization called on aquino's government to end killings by military and paramilitary forces, saying they represented the country's most serious human rights problem since mid-1987
it is exaggerated,'' mrs. bautista said of the amnesty report. ``it's a very one-sided story.''
she said the government was investigating about 200 cases of human rights abuses and that civil suits were pending in the courts against offenders
we have ongoing investigations,'' she added. ``they're not all saints in the military ... but there is a serious effort to clean up.''
mrs. bautista said investigations of human rights abuses against the military were often not publicized to avoid demoralizing soldiers fighting the rebels
amnesty praised the aquino government for ``some very real progress'' in human rights, particularly in restoring legal safeguards and in greatly reducing the use of torture. but it called on the government to reaffirm publicly its commitment to protect human rights
in manila, sen. juan ponce enrile told the american chamber of commerce that divisions in the 160,000-strong armed forces and a lack of supplies were hindering the effort against the communist rebels
the situation has become much more delicate than it was before, not only because of the qualitative improvement of the capabilities of the insurgents but also because of the fragmentation in the military organization and the lack of logistics needed to deal with this problem,'' he said
enrile, a former defense minister, said the communist army has between 25,000 and 30,000 fighters and controls more territory than at any time during the rebellion
police captured reputed guerrilla leader nemesio demafiles at a private home in bacolod, about 300 miles south of manila, brig. gen. domingo rio said
rio said police seized three other rebels in the wednesday raid and found a .45-caliber pistol and a map of a nearby philippine constabulary headquarters. rio alleged that demafiles apparently was planning to attack the constabulary
demafiles was believed to be a member of the outlawed communist party of the philippines' central committee and commander of the party's military wing on negros island, said col. oscar florendo, chief military spokesman
the military had offered a $5,000 reward for his capture
rebel sources in manila said demafiles was removed last year as negros commander and expelled from the party over an ideological dispute. they said he had been trying to organize a separate marxist group
elsewhere, the military said troops killed the head of a rebel propaganda unit and captured four other guerrillas tuesday in luzon's nueva ecija province
striking film and tv scriptwriters were active on both coasts wednesday, picketing outside the mgm building in new york and preparing to resume negotiations here under the guidance of a federal mediator
script shortages because of the strike begun monday have forced cbs to shelve indefinitely two programs set to debut this month, ``the dictator'' starring christopher lloyd, and ``the smothers brothers comedy hour.''
the walkout by 9,000 members of the writers guild of america also has forced ``late night with david letterman'' and ``the tonight show'' into reruns
writers have refused to continue working on the script for the academy awards ceremony, scheduled for worldwide broadcast april 11 on abc. soap operas have stockpiled scripts for several weeks and have not been affected
negotiators for the guild and the alliance of motion picture and television producers were scheduled to meet thursday at the producers' headquarters in sherman oaks
it's a mediation session and that's all i can say,'' wga spokeswoman cheryl rhoden said. ``it's important that those topics on the table be kept there rather than be aired in the media.''
the strike began after the scriptwriters rejected a final offer from the producers. main points of contention were writers' demands for higher fees from reruns and greater creative control
about 100 scriptwriters wednesday marched outside the mgm building. three writers of letterman's show, wearing jackets with the program name on the back, walked the picket line with about 125 other strikers and supporters
william peter blatty, who wrote ``the exorcist,'' was on the line, as was screen actors guild member barbara feldon of ``get smart'' fame
carson's show will be in reruns the remainder of the week, but his production company applied for a waiver that would allow the talk show's writers to resume work next week, spokesman jim mahoney said wednesday
the guild was expected to consider the request this weekend. a similar waiver was granted in 1981
the wga strike is the fourth since 1973. the longest, in 1981, lasted three months
the parliament extended emergency rule wednesday in nine provinces where the government has been fighting kurdish guerrillas, including istanbul, the country's largest city
under emergency rule, civilian governors can impose curfews, issue search warrants, halt strikes and ban meetings and rallies
wednesday's vote extends the emergency rule for four months
interior minister mustafa kalemli told parliament that kurdish guerrillas in eight southeastern provinces killed 100 civilians and 30 soldiers over the past six months. he said 53 people believed to be terrorists were killed during the same period and 1,761 others were arrested
in the same period in istanbul, two terrorists were shot dead and 168 terrorist suspects were arrested, he said
the kurdish labor party seeks to set up an independent marxist state in parts of eastern and southeastern turkey. it has been fighting the government since august 1984
about one-fifth of turkey's 52 million population are ethnic kurds
also on wednesday, a parliamentary commission approved a draft bill that would allow individuals to apply for a court order to halt or prevent publication of a story deemed an invasion of privacy
columnist oktay eksi wrote in the liberal daily hurriyet that the bill, introduced by members of the governing motherland party, meant plain censorship
the government disclosed that it has drafted legislation which would penalize the press for reporting false news, permitting fines up to $100,000
queen mother elizabeth made a foray wednesday into the hottest issue in british domestic politics _ the ailing, tax-funded national health service
her office said that in a letter to health minister tony newton, the 87-year-old mother of queen elizabeth ii expressed ``much distress'' at the closure last december of a ward for the elderly in a south wales hospital
she had presided at the reopening of the hospital eight months earlier after its renovation
although i am sure you appreciate the queen mother has no jurisdiction whatsoever over the affairs of the national health service, i have at her majesty's command written,'' the letter said
george boulton, the general manager of the mid-glamorgan health authority, told reporters the royal intervention was unlikely to reopen the six-bed ward at st. tydfil's hospital in merthyr tydfil
no one takes interest from the royal family lightly,'' he said
but we are facing a deficit of about 4 million pounds ($7.3 million) this year because we haven't got enough money from the government and prices are going up all the time. we made cuts to save 1.2 million pounds ($2.2 million).''
boulton said closing the ward would save about $73,000. he said more wards at the hospital may be closed
national opinion polls report that the state of the health service is the biggest worry among britons
nurses are quitting in protest over their pay and conditions, wards are closing and the more than 700,000 patients wait months and sometimes years for operations
the service now costs $39.3 billion a year and critics say it urgently needs another $3.6 billion to $9.2 billion
the royal family traditionally stays out of politics, although prince charles, heir to the throne, has expressed anger at inner-city poverty
robin cook, social services spokesman for the opposition labor party, which has repeatedly condemned the government for not spending more on the national health service, said: ``this is a dramatic intervention by the queen mother which demonstrates the state of the national health service.''
tony wilkins, an official of the national union of public employees in merthyr tydfil, said: ``perhaps the queen mother should be allowed to open every hospital _ it might be a good way of protecting our health service.''
enough snow fell while continental flight 1713 awaited takeoff at denver's airport nov. 15 for ice buildup on the wings to have been a possible factor in the crash, an airplane engineer testified wednesday
ralph brumby, manager of aerodynamics and acoustics for mcdonnell douglas corp., which manufactured the dc-9, said 0.032 inches of precipitation, or about a third of an inch of snow, fell in the 24 minutes between de-icing and takeoff
if all that precipitation had frozen on the wing, it could have caused problems on takeoff, brumby said. ice can change the shape of the wing, affecting lift
continental responded that the plane was going too fast at the time of the crash for ice on the wings to have affected it
testimony about possible icing and its effects, and detail on the efforts to rescue the passengers trapped in the plane after it crashed, dominated the second day of a national transportation safety board hearing on the crash
twenty-eight people were killed and 54 hurt when the dc-9 flipped over and broke apart on the runway at stapleton international airport shortly after takeoff during a snowstorm
brumby, under questioning by continental officials, said that the amount of precipitation that fell between the time the plane was de-iced and takeoff was high enough that the plane could have stalled at about 150 knots, or a little more than 170 mph
but continental officials noted that an ntsb study concluded the craft had reached 168 knots, or about 193 mph, at some point before it crashed. airline spokesman bruce hicks said that based on those findings, ice on the wings could not have caused the crash
continental officials also quizzed brumby about the possibility the de-icing fluid failed to keep ice off the wings. he said that was a possibility but did not elaborate
he said there have been three dc-9 crashes in which ice was a factor during the past 23 years, but in all cases there was no de-icing before takeoff
ntsb investigator robert benzon had said tuesday that officials want to know why 24 minutes elapsed between de-icing and takeoff when other planes on the runway took off within 15 minutes
earlier wednesday, officials testified that rescuers had to cope with frigid weather, confusion and occasional equipment malfunctions, but the operation went as well as could be expected. some victims were trapped in the wreckage for hours
we feel fortunate we had that many survivors,'' dr. michael brunko, the rescue coordinator, testified. ``obviously, there were people trapped in the wreckage who we could not do anything for
brunko said that ``to this day, i do not know what else could have been done.''
there were problems with pens that would not write, radio batteries that failed, confusion created by the number of continental personnel at the scene, and the effects of the cold on rescuers who were not dressed for it, according to brunko
eldon w. buller, denver assistant fire chief, said the upside-down position of the plane delayed the rescue
every time we moved the aircraft on one side, we compromised people on the other side,'' buller said. ``people were starting to get crushed.''
he said firefighters wanted to drain fuel from one of the aircraft's wings, but they did not know how and no other airport officials could explain the procedure
i was afraid it would drown the people trapped underneath'' if the fuel began leaking, buller said
if uncle remus and six of the seven dwarfs applied for jobs at the disneyland hotel, they would be turned down because of a new dress code. not even walt disney's pencil-thin mustache would pass muster
disneyland acquired the hotel in january and expanded its 31-year-old dress code to cover its 1,600 employees
under the code, men will have to get haircuts, shave and cover tattoos. women will have to abandon slacks, heavy makeup, gaudy jewelry and wild hairdos
six of the seven dwarfs, uncle remus, captain hook and ``pinocchio'' toymaker geppetto all would be renegades working in the real-life world of disney
when disney co. assumed control of the hotel, previously managed by the wrather corp., its employees fell under the dress code established for the magic kingdom in 1957
some hotel employees said they won't shave, including engineer mike searles, 40, who wears a handlebar mustache
i don't think it's right, and i'm not going to compromise,'' he said
he and others said they will go to their union to fight the dress code. but workers who rebel may be terminated, said disneyland spokesman bob roth
the reason that we are doing this is because the disneyland hotel is becoming part of disneyland attractions, and we have an appearance standard,'' roth said. ``it is associated with disney and is expected by our guests.''
a white supremacist changed his mind wednesday about pleading guilty to conspiring to overthrow the government
bruce pierce, 34, had said tuesday that he wanted to plead guilty after u.s. district judge morris arnold ruled that a confession given to fbi agents after his 1985 arrest was made voluntarily and is admissible at trial
the judge recommended that pierce wait and discuss the matter with his attorney
in a statement wednesday, pierce said he considered entering the plea ``to avoid further embarrassment over having given a statement to the authorities. upon further review and consideration i have reconsidered.''
pierce is among 10 of the 14 men on trial charged with sedition. five are accused of conspiring to kill a federal judge and an fbi agent, and two are accused of interstate transportation of stolen money
pierce is serving 100 years for racketeering and 150 years for civil rights violations in the slaying in denver of alan berg, a jewish radio talk show
pierce had contended that the confession was not voluntary. he said that he was told that if he did not talk to the fbi, his wife would be arrested and his three children would be placed in foster homes. killings</head> picks up 5th graf pvs, if there ...</note>
police said a bombing attack injured seven officers as roman catholic youths rioted in belfast wednesday for a third straight night over the killing of three unarmed ira guerrillas in gibraltar
a press officer at belfast police headquarters said the officers suffered slight injuries when bombs exploded at the rear of springfield road police station in catholic west belfast
earlier, police said a grenade was thrown at an army patrol but exploded harmlessly and that shots were fired at the new barnsley police station, which was attacked with gasoline bombs on tuesday
youths threw gasoline bombs and set vehicles ablaze but no casualties were reported in those incidents
a police official said earlier wednesday that security forces will not tolerate irish republican army shows of strength at the funerals of three guerrillas, who were shot to death by british commandos last sunday
if there is such a show and ``we move in, we know there is going to be an unseemly fracas but we simply can't allow the law to be blatantly defied,'' said a royal ulster constabulary officer. he spoke anonymously, in accordance with custom
paddy mcgrory, lawyer for the three families, arrived in the british colony on spain's southern coast to arrange for the return of the bodies. the funeral date has not yet been set
british officials said the ira members, two men and a woman, had planned to set off a car bomb tuesday at a military ceremony in the center of gibraltar
spanish police found a car loaded with explosives tuesday in marbella, about 45 miles up the coast from gibraltar. british officials believe it was rented by the three slain ira members
the guerrillas killed were mairead farrell, 31; daniel mccann, 30, and sean savage, 24, all of west belfast. the ira said all were on ``active service'' at the time of their deaths
police in madrid said a woman identified as mary parkin was detected in the gibraltar area in february and was being sought as a possible fourth member of the ira team
felix pizzarello, the gibraltar coroner, said an inquest will not be held until may
the coroner, who also is a lower-court magistrate, said in a telephone interview his court ``is fully booked until may and i can't realisticaly think of having an inquest until then. i don't consider that the matter requires any urgent treatment.''
he said gibraltar police were investigating the shooting and his inquest would be partly based on documents they would provide ``within two to three weeks.''
