a federal grand jury wednesday indicted a top haitian army official who witnesses say allowed drug traffickers to use his private landing strip for u.s.-bound cocaine shipments
the indictment of col. jean-claude paul on narcotics counts was immediately ordered sealed by u.s. magistrate william c. turnoff, sources close to the case told the associated press on condition of anonymity. the charges were expected to be made public thursday
paul heads the feared 700-man dessalines battalion in port-au-prince, which ruthlessly suppressed anti-government demonstrations last year and was accused of protecting the gunmen who disrupted november presidential elections, killing 34 people
paul was considered close to the government council that ruled haiti until a military-supported civilian president took office last month
also indicted wednesday, sources said, were paul's brother, antonio paul, and the colonel's ex-wife, merielle delinois, who is already a fugitive on previous federal drug charges here
the investigation of jean-claude paul has been widely reported for weeks, and the haitian army has already denied the officer's involvement. the haitian government and paul had no comment wednesday
all interviews with army officials must be cleared through gen. carl nicolas, the army chief of staff. nicolas has refused a written request from the associated press to speak with paul
asked during a recent interview at his home about reports of drug smuggling by the army, president leslie manigat said: ``i can't base my judgment on rumors.''
haitian gen. carl nicolas last month denounced reports of ``the so-called involvement of (col. paul) in drug trafficking,'' and called it part of a ``campaign of denigration'' against the military by the foreign press
one witness in the investigation that led to the indictment was businessman osvaldo quintana, 35, of miami who told a news conference last month that paul helped him smuggle cocaine into the united states in december 1986
we flew (the shipment) out of his own personal ranch in haiti,'' about 90 miles outside of port-au-prince, quintana said
quintana has testified for the government at previous drug trials. in january, outside of a federal courtroom, he told reporters he had once seen 9,000 kilograms of cocaine stuffed into duffel bags in the haitian presidential palace during the administration of ousted leader jean-claude duvalier
quintana has said haitian military officials routinely aided drug flights from colombia, allowing them to land and be serviced before proceeding on to the bahamas to drop their loads
the witness said he was originally approached by ms. delinois to take part in the smuggling scheme
ms. delinois was arrested in miami on drug charges in march 1987, but later skipped bond and is believed to be hiding in haiti, according to the u.s. drug enforcement administration
dea affidavits filed in the delinois case say quintana met with paul and his brother antonio at the ranch, and watched a plane carrying 220 pounds of cocaine take off
paul had close ties to the military-dominated junta that replaced dictator jean-claude duvalier after he fled into exile in france in february 1986
paul seldom appeared in public during the junta's two-year rule, which ended when manigat was inaugurated feb. 7. when he did, it often was to serve as bodyguard for two junta members, lt. gen. henri namphy, the junta president and now military chief, and brig. gen. williams regala, now defense minister. with panama-chartered plane searched at miami. picks up 11th graf, the united ...</note>
the government said wednesday that banks can reopen but people still will not be allowed to cash checks or withdraw money. the banks closed last week because of a cash shortage and political turmoil
the national banking commission said banks could accept deposits from clients, conduct interbank operations and transfer money from one account to another
it did not say when withdrawals and check-cashing would be permitted. panama's national currency is the u.s. dollar and the cash supply has been drying up because of the dispute over who should control the government
no banks in the downtown financial district opened for business immediately
depositors began a run on domestic banks when president eric arturo delvalle was ousted feb. 26 after trying to dismiss gen. manuel antonio noriega, the real power in panama, as head of the 15,000-member panamanian defense forces
on wednesday, the nephew of the late omar torrijos, panama's previous strongman, disclosed he broke with the noriega government. he said he left his post as chief of panama's consulate in los angeles and was joining forces loyal to delvalle
diplomatic sources in washington, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the defection of santiago torrijos was considered significant because of the close identification of the his relatives with the defense forces. omar torrijos is still considered a national hero for negotiating the panama canal treaties with the united states
the 12 domestic banks closed march 2 in sympathy with a nationwide general strike called by noriega's opponents. late last week, the government ordered them to remain shut and also closed more than 100 international banks
commerce has been crippled. with no way to process non-cash transactions, most businesses refuse to accept checks or credit cards
panama keeps an estimated $50 million on deposit in american banks and usually receives remittances, but u.s. judges froze panamanian assets in banks in miami and new york after suits were filed to prevent noriega's government from withdrawing funds
u.s. customs service agents in miami detained a boeing 707 chartered by air panama for four hours wednesday to search for u.s. currency, but no money turned up, customs spokesman michael sheehan said
fifteen agents and inspectors searched cargo unloaded from the plane after a tip someone might be trying to illegally take u.s. currency out of the country
the united states recognizes delvalle as panama's legitimate president. it has demanded noriega's removal since he was indicted in florida last month on narcotics and money-laundering charges
delvalle went into hiding in panama after noriega had the national legislature dismiss him
because of the cash crunch, panamanian families have put off non-essentials
rufina escobar, a 55-year-old schoolteacher, said she had oil, noodles and a few eggs _ enough food to make it through the week _ ``but if banks don't open next week i'll have to ask friends for a few dollars just to eat.''
panama city was calm wednesday, unlike a day earlier, when hundreds of burning trash barricades blocked the streets. the demonstrations were the largest since delvalle was dismissed
an editorial in the government-run newspaper critica on tuesday said ``all buildings, all institutions in which americans have any interest'' should be blown up
its 3-inch-high banner headline said ``invasion of panama.'' on tuesday, foreign minister jorge abadia claimed that maneuvers being conducted by the u.s. southern command are ``the prelude to an armed invasion of panama.''
the command, which is based in panama and is responsible for u.s. military operations in latin america, said the maneuvers involved fewer than 700 soldiers and were ``routine training and evaluation exercises.''
the u.s. embassy issued a communique wednesday calling abadia's allegations ``completely false and tendentious.''
it also dismissed as ``absurd'' allegations that u.s. ambassador arthur davis was manipulating funds of the panama canal commission
the government of the united states has reiterated on various occasions its faithful compliance with the panama canal treaties,'' the communique said
baltazar renan alzpurua, columnist for critica, said of the u.s. maneuvers: ``it is time to ... dedicate ourselves to the organization of volunteers who are ready to fight in the cities, the mountains, the streets and fields, rifle and machete in hand.''
real estate salesman alexis alvarez said with a shrug: ``let the gringos invade. we can't be any worse off with them than we are now with this bunch of thieves.''
customs agents detained a plane chartered by air panama to search for any u.s. currency being taken illegally out of the country wednesday but found none and sent the aircraft on its way, a spokesman said
u.s. customs had some information that there might possibly be an outbound currency violation connected with the flight,'' spokesman michael sheehan said
the chartered boeing 707 was scheduled to carry military and police-type uniforms, small machinery and other merchandise to panama city, sheehan said. it was detained for four hours
panama's national currency is the u.s. dollar, and the cash supply has been drying up because of a dispute over control of the panamanian government
