organizers called off a strike aimed at protesting the high cost of living wednesday after a first day of protest shaped up as a failure
most businesses, banks and government offices kept their doors open on wednesday, the first day of the planned 2-day walkout, and activity in the city was normal
virtudes alvarez, a spokesman for strike organizers, said the decision was made wednesday night to give ``the government a short time'' to talk with the ``those involved in this movement.'' he did not elaborate
alvarez represents the national conference of popular organizations, a coalition claiming to have the support of about 200 urban neighborhood and small peasant groups
no incidents of violence were reported wednesday
six people died and about 20 were injured in other protests in the last two weeks in the caribbean nation
soldiers in armored personnel carriers and police with automatic weapons patrolled the streets of the capital of 1.5 million on wednesday
bus and taxi drivers stayed home in the early morning and thousands of people were late for work, but by midmorning most drivers were back on the job
public and private schools stayed closed as a precaution in the event of incidents, school authorities said
most labor and church groups and political parties opposed the strike. however, the nation's largest union, the general workers union with an estimated 40,000 members, had said it would support the action
the coalition has led strikes since february that shut down several low-income communities in the capital and resulted in sporadic clashes between residents and police and soldiers
strike organizers demand that the government control the spiraling cost of basic commodities, improve public services and carry out capital improvements in their communities
about 4,000 supporters of the governing reformist party marched to the national palace on tuesday shouting slogans backing president joaquin balaguer and denouncing the strike
tuesday night, the archbishop of santo domingo, nicolas de jesus lopez rodriguez, termed the strike ``senseless'' and called for dialogue among government, business and labor
private economists estimated the inflation rate in the dominican republic at 30 percent last year and said it may reach 50 to 60 percent this year
the u.s. dollar, to which much of the dominican economy is pegged, meanwhile has been rising steadily with respect to the peso. the peso now is valued at around 19 cents, compared to 26 cents late last year
balaguer this week announced price controls on items such as plantains, onions, potatoes, rice, but strike organizers say the measures are insufficient. other commodities expected to be regulated include chicken, sugar and tomato paste
the police chief, maj. gen. fernando aristides sanchez aybar, said tuesday that public disorder would not be tolerated, and the armed forces minister, lt. gen. antonio imbert barrera, said soldiers would help police keep order
some left-wing and labor groups complained their leaders were arrested without warrants and were being held without charges
seventy-year-old joe redington dashed out of this checkpoint wednesday in the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race, declaring, ``i feel like an old fox being chased by 50 young hounds.''
the second-oldest racer in the anchorage-to nome mushing marathon left this kuskokwim river town after staying about four hours to feed and rest his 14 dogs
known as the father of the iditarod, the wasilla resident helped create the race 16 years ago but has never won, even though he has competed nearly every year
redington arrived in mcgrath, 410 miles into the race, at 6:48 a.m. he was followed by herbie nayokpuk of shishmaref at 10:26 a.m. behind them, in order, were jan masek of anchorage and joe garnie of teller
two other mushers _ joe runyan of nenana and ralph ``babe'' anderson of mcgrath _ also arrived in the morning but were not among the leaders because they had not yet taken their mandatory 24-hour layovers
redington, nayokpuk and garnie took their layovers early in the race, which began saturday. that turned out to be a successful strategy, because a pack of about 20 leading mushers later bogged down in new snow. as those mushers took their 24-hour layover in rohn, they watched helplessly as redington, nayokpuk and garnie sailed past on the smooth trail they had packed
one of those was the defending champion, susan butcher of manley, who was in fifth place
some racers said that despite redington's lead, nayokpuk is now the musher to beat because his dogs are stronger
i think it's going to take us quite a while to gain that kind of time back, unless he runs into some kind of situation up ahead,'' four-time iditarod champion rick swenson said in rohn
meanwhile, at the back of the pack, norman vaughan announced wednesday that he was dropping out. vaughan, at 82 the oldest iditarod musher, was the only one left at the puntilla lake checkpoint, 290 miles behind the leaders. another musher also dropped out, leaving the number of competitors at 50
a $30,000 first prize awaits the winner in nome, with the rest of the $150,000 purse to be split among the next 19 finishers
a federal appeals court judge wednesday temporarily halted irs efforts to revoke ptl's tax-exempt status
judge william williams of the 4th u.s. circuit of appeals in richmond, va., said the tv ministry built by jim and tammy bakker would suffer irreparable harm if it were determined later that the irs overstepped its authority
the judge set a march 31 hearing in greenville, s.c., where ptl attorneys are expected to argue that loss of tax-exempt status would be a death blow to ptl, which is trying to reorganize under bankruptcy court protection
on monday, u.s. district judge karen henderson had ruled that the internal revenue service could revoke ptl's tax-exempt status. she overturned a december order by a bankruptcy court judge, saying that court had no authority to stop the irs
as a religious organization, ptl does not have to pay tax on the donations that finance its religious work
ptl is trying to raise about $4 million by may 2 and emerge from bankruptcy court. if it loses its tax-exempt status now, thousands of contributors will be frightened off, the ministry said
the irs wants to revoke its status retroactively to 1981 and seek at least $55.7 million in back taxes. in effect, the irs has suggested that bakker wasn't running a ministry but a profitable business for himself, relatives and friends
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir expressed astonishment wednesday at a letter from 30 senators who said israel should be willing to give up control of occupied land in return for middle east peace
your letter came as a surprise, at a crucial moment in the peace efforts,'' shamir wrote in a three-page response. ``we were astonished by the words of criticism you leveled at us on the formula of `territory for peace.'''
shamir's letter was sent to sens. carl levin, d-mich., and rudy boschwitz, r-minn., said levin administrative assistant gordon kerr. both senators, strong supporters of israel, were out of town and unavailable for comment wednesday night
twenty-three democratic and seven republican senators had sent a letter to shamir last week in which they noted that israel in the past had supported the idea of ``land for peace'' by returning the sinai peninsula to egypt
they noted that shamir had rejected ``this expression of territory for peace'' and expressed hope that the prime minister's statement ``did not indicate that israel is abandoning a policy that offers the best hope for long-term peace.''
shamir, in his response, said israel accepts the u.n. security council resolution that provides for an israeli withdrawal from land captured in the 1967 war but he did not agree to israel's eventual withdrawal from the west bank and gaza
shamir said the occupied territories were a different matter than the sinai peninsula because they ``were occupied militarily and illegally by jordan and egypt.''
shamir also warned against any waning in america's commitment to the camp david accords, saying: ``if we are going to lose faith in solemn american and egyptian commitments under these accords how can we be assured of future commitments that will require us to take even further risks to our security and future?''
shamir is due in washington next week for meetings with president reagan and secretary of state george p. shultz
a former black panther whose conviction in the murders of two prison guards during a 1971 escape attempt was overturned was ordered released on $350,000 bail wednesday after 21 years in prison
u.s. district judge thelton henderson, who previously granted johnny spain a new trial in the san quentin six case, rejected a state to delay the setting of bail
spain, 38, could be released from the california medical facility at vacaville as early as thursday, lawyers said
mr. spain would walk from here to vacaville on hot coals before he would betray'' the people posting bail, said his lawyer, dennis riordan
wednesday's ruling was the second court victory in as many days for spain. he has been behind bars for more than half his life, since his arrest in 1966 for a murder and robbery in los angeles
on tuesday, los angeles superior court judge kathleen parker ordered spain paroled immediately from the sentence he has been serving for the 1966 murder, paving the way for henderson to grant bail for the 1971 case
spain apparently joined the black panther party after entering prison
he became the only prisoner convicted of murder in a bloody escape attempt that took the lives of militant leader george jackson, two other prisoners and three san quentin guards
the other members of the san quentin six were either convicted of lesser charges or acquitted
henderson granted spain a new trial in 1986, saying he had been denied a fair trial by being required to wear heavy shackles for every court appearance during the five years of proceedings. the state is appealing that ruling
parker on tuesday found that spain was eligible for immediate parole in the 1966 case because the parole board had improperly lengthened his sentence six years by applying 1976 regulations to disciplinary violations committed in 1970 and 1971
riordan said spain has been recommended for parole by numerous prison staffers, including a close friend of one of the slain guards, and two congressmen
the lawyer said spain had spent twice as long in prison as the average sentence for a similar crime
vice president george bush stood within reach of the republican presidential nomination today after a clean sweep of super tuesday primaries. albert gore jr. added a southern dynamic to the democratic race, splitting a rich harvest of delegates with michael dukakis and jesse jackson
it exceeded my fondest expectations,'' exulted bush as he surveyed his 16-0 shutout tuesday and looked ahead to an illinois showdown next tuesday, where another victory over kansas sen. bob dole would give his nomination an aura of inevitability
super tuesday spelled disaster for dole, fellow republican pat robertson, and democrat richard gephardt, all three teetering on the verge of elimination after rejection in state after state
mary fishbyrne, a 101-year-old politicial activist who hasn't missed voting since women were given that right, fumed because she couldn't vote for the man of her choice
why can't i vote for bush?'' a snippish voice said from behind the voting machine curtain on super tuesday
because you're registered as a democrat, miss mary,'' precinct commissioner betty shelton said apologetically. ``crossover voting isn't allowed in presidential primaries.''
i'm just miserable,'' came back the curtained voice. ``i'll vote for bush in november.''
panama's military regime could find itself subject to ``a whole panoply'' of economic sanctions by the end of this week, including the withholding of $6.5 million this month for use of the panama canal, u.s. officials say
final decisions on the sanctions are expected at an inter-agency meeting scheduled thursday, said the officials, who insisted on anonymity. a formal announcement is likely either thursday or friday, they added
