_ ``the phantom of the opera,'' the lavish andrew lloyd webber musical about a deformed composer who haunts the paris opera house and the young soprano he loves. majestic, 239-6290, same number as telecharge. difficult
she goes by old values: an honest day's work for an honest day's pay ... live within your means ... save money for a rainy day ... support the police. to margaret thatcher, that's also the formula for the success of a nation. it is essentially the basis for the thatcher revolution, which has put a staggering britain steady on its feet again. but her critics say it is at a heavy price
far from losing steam after nearly nine years in office, margaret thatcher is marching through her third consecutive term as prime minister looking more confident and powerful than ever
the 62-year-old conservative party leader has become such a fixture on the political scene, here and abroad, that at times she seems to be parodying the bossy, schoolmarmish image bestowed on her by her critics
she'll let loose an outburst every so often _ ``i never did understand men,'' she complained after an argumentative european summit meeting. she'll chide the united states about balancing its budget and badger her citizens about littering the streets
she advocates a return to ``victorian values,'' supports the restoration of the death penalty, has legislated curbs on the promotion of homosexual lifestyles, and brandishes the official secrets act with a vigor that makes many critics fear for the freedom of the british media
now, eight months into a fresh five-year term, the blonde mother of twins has governed continuously for longer than any other british prime minister in the 20th century. in the process, she says, she has wrought a revolution. it's a claim that not even her severest critics now totally dismiss
she has taught us that you don't win ... unless you have a clear ideological position,'' says roy hattersley, deputy leader of the socialistic labor party, which went down to its third successive election defeat by mrs. thatcher last june. ``we've made authoritarianism look respectable _ or, rather, she has.''
as the thatcher revolution surges on with shake-ups in state education, housing and the once-sacrosanct national health service, authoritarianism is the most frequent charge against her
but polls indicate that mrs. thatcher retains her trump card: a feeling among the united kingdom's 56 million people that, whether or not they like her policies, no one is offering anything more credible. the disarray in the left-of-center opposition gives her an unassailable parliament majority on just 42 percent of the popular vote
the voting pattern illustrated the divisions and polarization evident in mrs. thatcher's britain. tories swept the elections in prosperous southern england but won not a single seat in the house of commons in the north's five major cities, where unemployment and cuts in government spending are felt most acutely
she, more powerfully than anyone else, has articulated the moral doubts and yearnings of her age,'' wrote peter jenkins, a leading liberal analyst, in his recent book, ``mrs. thatcher's revolution.''
for what people wanted, surely, was an end to decline, release from the corrosive sense of failure, a government which governed and a country to begin to be proud of once again.''
mrs. thatcher feels her populist, anti-elitist instincts are ``absolutely in tune with how people feel ... not just in their pockets, but in their bones, in their hearts and in their minds. deep in their instincts they find what i am saying and doing right.''
she attributes it all to what she learned from, her father, alfred roberts, a smalltown grocer
my policies are based not on some economic theory, but on things that i and millions like me were brought up with,'' she has said
an honest day's work for an honest day's pay, live within your means, put a nest egg by for a rainy day, pay your bills on time, support the police.''
such is the message of her revolution
her laws have curbed the labor unions and nurtured a new breed of entrepreneurs who, like mrs. thatcher, are outsiders to the establishment
among the 200 richest britons, self-made chain store billionaires, computer whizkids and property tycoons outnumber the landed aristocracy and other old money 2 to 1, according to money magazine, a british publication
britain, the strike-plagued ``sick man of europe'' in the 60s and 70s, is now ranked by ambassador toshio yamazaki of japan as an olympics gold-medalist of business with ``one of the great reforming governments of the century.''
i have noticed not only a genuine economic resurgence but also a new attitude,'' yamazaki told the 1988 convention of the british institute of directors. ``the british seem to be enjoying success.''
unemployment is down from a peak 12 percent two years ago to 9.2 percent, lower than west germany and france; inflation hovers around 4 percent, down from more than 20 percent in the early thatcher years. britain's economic growth topped the west european league last year, while reins on state spending have produced a series of trim, low-deficit budgets
mrs. thatcher has steadily chopped away at tax rates at the highest income levels, which had reached 86 percent when she took over from prime minister james callaghan's labor government in 1979. her government succeeded in getting the top rate down to 60 percent and proposes to cut them even more this year
currency exchange controls are gone, and the blossoming of the city, london's financial district, into a global trading giant is just one sign of the radically changed business climate
but not everybody is better off, and much remains unchanged in thatcher's britain
a stubbornly class-conscious society survives with waiting lists for expensive, private high schools swelled by the children of the newly prosperous
people's accents still matter and are discussed _ including mrs. thatcher's, because it sounds acquired
critics who accuse mrs. thatcher of under-funding the national health service in favor of private medicine point to the three small children who died this year after heart surgery was delayed for lack of nurses at birmingham children's hospital
nine years after a woman became prime minister, british women are not noticeably better off. they still do most of the boring low-paid jobs and earn an average of 145 pounds ($255) a week, compared with 219.40 pounds ($386) for the average male
according to a survey published in february by the state-funded equal opportunities commission, women comprise 60 percent of bank employees but only 2 percent of the administrative and managerial staff. mrs. thatcher has never had a woman in her cabinet
says nurse rebecca malby, 24: ``i find her whole attitude totally out of tune with what young women think ... her references to the importance of staying home and raising children . .. the poor pay of women-dominated professions.''
everything about the grocer's daughter, from her frilly blouses and tinted hair to her right-wing views, offends a large section of the intellectual and cultural establishment
her odious suburban gentility and sentimental saccharine patriotism caters to the worst elements of commuter idiocy,'' charges writer-director jonathan miller,
the novelist kingsley amis retorts that the intellectuals are simply snobs and says he detects resentment among the intelligentsia that they, like the labor unions, are no longer consulted by mrs. thatcher
instead, she listens to small, right-wing think tanks like the institute for economic affairs, whose director, graham mather, says: ``there's no doubt the free-market right has been taking the offensive in recent years and has come to dominate much of the policy discussion
the left, the collectivists, the socialists, the believers in a corporate state, have almost opted out of the policy debate.''
internationally, mrs. thatcher has turned post-empire britain into what commentator brian walden calls ``a medium-sized power _ with clout.''
she is washington's staunchest backer in the north atlantic treaty organization. in western europe, her partners in european economic community may dislike her hectoring style and preoccupation with budgets, but they no longer call britain the weakling in the group
she is the longest-serving leader in the nato alliance, and general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev of the soviet union gave her a red-carpet welcome in moscow last spring. he stopped off to see her in december on his way to meet president reagan in washington to sign the treaty limiting nuclear weapons in europe
if she sees herself as the de facto leader of the west, that would give me not the slightest pain,'' former u.s. secretary of state henry a. kissinger wrote recently in london's sunday telegraph
i would like that. i have great hopes that even if she is not the founder of a new western structure, she can at least do what the roman tribunes used to do _ prevent the worst from happening.''
here are milestones in the life of prime minister margaret thatcher:
oct. 13, 1925 _ born at grantham, central england, the second daughter of grocer alfred roberts
june 1947 _ graduates from oxford with a chemistry degree
dec. 13, 1951 _ marries denis thatcher, a wealthy oil executive
aug. 15, 1953 _ gives birth to twins, mark and carol
june 1, 1954 _ qualifies as a barrister (lawyer)
oct. 8, 1959 _ elected to parliament
june 20, 1970 _ appointed to the cabinet as education secretary
feb. 11, 1975 _ elected leader of the conservative party, then in opposition
may 3, 1979 _ wins in general election and becomes prime minister
may 15, 1980 _ britain's inflation hits a record 21.9 percent
jan. 26, 1982 _ unemployment hits post-depression record of 3 million
april 2, 1982 _ dispatches a task force that recovers the falkland islands from argentina after a 74-day war
june 3, 1983 _ wins second five-year term
oct. 12, 1984 _ escapes an irish republican army bombing that kills 5 people and wounds 32
nov. 15, 1985 _ signs the anglo-irish accord, granting the irish republic a say in northern ireland on behalf ot the roman catholic minority
april 15, 1986 _ allows u.s. planes to launch bombing of libya from britain
march 28, 1987 _ gets a red-carpet official visit to moscow
june 11, 1987 _ wins third five-year term
jan. 3, 1988 _ becomes britain's longest continuously serving prime minister this century
in six years, george davies has turned a dowdy, obscure clothing company into britain's biggest retail success story of margaret thatcher's revolution _ a $1.75-billion empire for budget-conscious yuppies
raised in a working-class family in liverpool, davies is chief executive and chairman of next, a chain of nearly 500 stores, and epitomizes the ``go-getter'' society prime minister thatcher seeks to create
at 46, davies is not just an entrepreneur but a man eagerly sought by business experts and the media attempting to assess the thatcher revolution. he typifies the new class of young, self-made entrepreneurs who have benefited from the lower taxes and improved business climate of the thatcher years
i think the british do produce entrepreneurs, but perhaps the climate eight years ago didn't let them come through,'' davies said in a recent british tv interview, referring to the time before mrs. thatcher's conservatives took over from the labor party
so if someone like myself who is basically a working-class lad can start as i did on stock control of ankle socks and come through and do things i've always dreamed of and have a team that is equally positive, one's got to say something's going right,'' he said
davies worked in the clothing trade for nearly 20 years before his big break
in 1981, as a new senior executive with hepworths, a relatively little known clothing company, he spotted a gap in the market between pricy designer clothes and the mass production of the established chains
the first next store opened in wales in 1982 and they now cover britain. a mail order service davies launched this year was swamped with $10.8 million worth of orders in the first three weeks
company headquarters remain in leicester, an industrial city in central england town near where davies lives with his second wife, liz, in a 200-year-old rectory
he works six days a week, including saturday evenings when on his home computer he flips through the weekly takings from stores around the country
in un-british tradition, next employees call him george
it's attitudes that are divisive, not money,'' he says
at 24, rebecca malby is professionally a big success, but she considers herself a loser in margaret thatcher's revolution
miss malby is a nurse in charge of a 27-bed ward, mainly cardiac patients, at whipps cross hospital in a predominantly working-class district of the east end of london
on a salary of 9,000-pounds ($15,750) a year after seven years on the job, including gaining a postgraduate diploma, she makes roughly the same as a rookie policeman and about one-third less than many london secretaries
her home is a rented room in the house of two young doctors in london's far-from-gentrified stoke newington district and her major luxury is a second-hand car
she sees no prospect of buying her own apartment unless she gives up the car, vacations and most entertainment
but she loves her job, enthuses about being young and in london, believes passionately in the state-funded national health service, plans to train as a nursing manager _ and thinks prime minister margaret thatcher simply doesn't care
we think twice about ordering a brain scan on stroke patients now because of what it will cost,'' says miss malby, one of 515,000 nurses employed by the financially ailing state health service, which is used by 90 percent of britons
mrs. thatcher usually answers such criticism by showing statistics she says prove spending on health has increased. she says her aim is not to weaken the service but to streamline it by shifting funds from the health bureaucracy to the patients
she (mrs. thatcher) has made us think much more about what we're doing and there's nothing wrong with that,'' says miss malby. ``but we're on the edge now ... and she doesn't actually listen to anybody. she is driven by ideology and just determined we're going to have a mainly private health service.''
miss malby says she's not tempted into another career and hasn't seriously considered joining the hundreds of british nurses who leave annually to double their pay in jobs in u.s. hospitals
when i think of them (the government) lowering taxes again for wealthy people, it just seems a crime,'' she says
in ``wetherby,'' a 1985 movie about alienated english intellectuals, a character ruminates tipsily on what margaret thatcher is doing to his country
revenge! that's what she's doing. ... taking some terrible revenge. ... and now the whole country is suffering. and yet we've done nothing to her.''
the outburst is almost a metaphor for the arts in britain today after nearly a decade of thatcherism: enraged, unfocused, sometimes venomous to a degree never experienced by a prime minister this century
so deep is mrs. thatcher's imprint on society that she often becomes a stage character in her own right, whether as a cigar-chomping fascist in the satirical tv revue ``spitting image,'' or as nanny, leader of the rapacious, authoritarian money party in pete davies's novel ``the last election.''
now she returns in the hit movie ``sammy and rosie get laid,'' which features a thatcher speech on slum-clearance over footage of an urban wasteland
anti-thatcherism is not confined to left-wing artists. conservative novelists also rail against mrs. thatcher's ``go-getter society,'' which they claim is drowning ye olde englande in a greedy money-and-fast-food culture
the spate of recent movies with anti-thatcher messages provoked an angry article in the sunday times by the right-wing historian norman stone of oxford university in which he claimed that ``the done thing is to run down mrs. thatcher, to assume that capitalism is parasitism, that the established order in this country is imperialist, racist, profiteering.''
hanif kureishi, who wrote the award-winning movie ``my beautiful laundrette'' and the ``sammy and rosie'' film, responded by accusing stone of ``creative impotence and snobbishness.'' kureishi insisted the britain shown in his films is authentic: ``an intolerant, racist, homophobic, narrow-minded, authoritarian rathole.''
the cultural battle, observed the economist magazine, signifies ``that mrs. thatcher is not just the first prime minister of the century to have an `-ism' attached to her name. she is also believed by her opponents ... to have so stamped her values on the country that it has almost become a personal fief.''
the creaky old farm credit system is being rejuvenated, but it'll take a while before the 72-year-old financial empire starts feeling its oats again
it's more than just a face lift, says an agriculture department economist. more like a transplant of key innards, along with $4 billion worth of new blood and muscle
the surgery was performed by congress in the agricultural credit act of 1987, which was signed into law by president reagan on jan. 6. losses to the system totaled about $4.8 billion over the last two years and the outlook was grim
although other components came along later, a cornerstone of the fcs since 1916 has been the federal land banks. other parts include intermediate credit banks and banks for cooperatives. altogether, some 37 banks and hundreds of local associations have made up the system's cooperative network
in all, the fcs has a $50 billion loan portfolio representing about a third of the u.s. farm debt
while federal assistance allows the fcs to operate in the shortrun, the help is not cheap,'' says merritt hughes of the department's economic research service. ``changes included a reorganization of the system, additional rights for its borrowers, and additional measures to ensure the institution's future.''
structurally, the fcs won't be the same. for example, within six months the federal land banks and the federal intermediate credit banks must merge. other mergers between fcs institutions and districts may follow, she said. the banks for cooperatives must also decided whether to consolidate
the farm credit administration (fca), the federal agency that oversees the cooperative system, will have expanded regulatory responsibilities and powers ``along the lines of those already existing for other types of financial institutions,'' ms. hughes said
newly created components will include an insurance corporation to insure debt obligations of the system. a separate farm credit assistance board has been formed to administer the federal bail-out of the system and ensure that units getting aid take necessary steps to reduce costs
a secondary market for agricultural real estate loans and certain rural housing loans will be handled by a new autonomous institution within fcs called the federal agricultural mortgage corp., which already has been dubbed ``farmer mac,'' she said
reorganizing the fcs will reduce overhead cost as the number of fcs entities declines,'' ms. hughes said. ``farmer mac is expected to bring in additional income.''
although there will be added costs associated with the new administrative parts of fcs, the changes overall ``should result in a more efficient implementation and delivery of loans'' to farmers, she said
insurance against operational failure will be targeted to a number of areas, ms. hughes said. an internal fund will be created to guarantee against default on system debt issuances
the new act requires fcs institutions to build up equity in order to decrease interest rate exposure and stabilize net income,'' she said. ``banks will be able to charge loan origination fees and issue non-voting, at-risk stock to raise the capital to meet fca-determined standards. borrowers will not be allowed to withdraw stock as their loans are repaid, and non-borrowers will be able to purchase non-voting stock.''
ms. hughes' analysis was reported in the march issue of agricultural outlook magazine published by the usda agency
the fcs's recent troubles resulted from two simultaneous developments: the near-collapse in the farm economy, and the system's issuance of long-term bonds with high interest rates, ms. hughes said
how would the system react in the future under repeat circumstances?
the fcs will likely be more capable of coping with a recurrence of the first or these problems as capital is rebuilt,'' she said. ``if proportionately more income is generated from loan origination fees and the sale of non-insured stock, the adverse consequences of borrower default will be less of an issue.''
in the case of unanticipated high interest rates, the impact on the fcs ``may not be substantially reduced'' by the new legislation, ms. hughes said. the new requirements call for a high level of capital that can be easily drawn on during downswings
 the level of capital is probably not as important as the stability of capital (immunity from investor flight), since prior to the mid-1980s the system had developed very large capital stock without legislative prompting,'' she said
one of the problems in the old fcs was an inability to shuttle financial help from one bank to another
the former capital corporation mandated by a 1985 law, for example, was able to assess about $300 million from the various banks but was able to collect only $175 million and actually dispensed only $10 million, ms. hughes said. formerly, the sharing of capital among fcs institutions was in conflict with reponsibilities to stockholders
the 1987 act permits a more flexible organizational structure while at the same time requiring continues, rather than sporadic, shared financial responsibility,'' she said
r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. has begun its $6.1 billion tender offer for federated department stores inc. and has gone to court in hopes of torpedoing the competing $6.18 billion offer by campeau corp
macy filed suit tuesday in federal court in manhattan seeking an injunction to bar campeau from proceeding with its tender offer on the grounds that campeau's amended bid was actually a new offer and as such must remain open beyond its scheduled expiration at midnight march 15
extending campeau's bid would reduce the pressure on federated shareholders to decide between the rival macy and campeau offers, effectively putting the macy offer _ which expires april 4 _ on better footing
higher stamp prices won't take effect until next month at the earliest, postal officials say
the board of governors of the u.s. postal service decided tuesday to postpone a final decision on the effective date of the new rates, and scheduled a special meeting for march 22 to discuss putting the new rates into effect, effectively delaying the increase until april 3 at the earliest
the new prices, recommended by the independent postal rate commission last friday, would boost the first-class rate to 25 cents from 22 cents
dart group corp. has abandoned its $1.03 billion takeover bid for stop &amp; shop cos. and says it will return all tendered shares to stop &amp; shop stockholders
stop &amp; shop announced on feb. 29 it had agreed to be acquired in a $1.23 billion leveraged buyout by the investment firm of kohlberg kravis roberts inc
dart's tender offer expires at midnight wednesday and will not be extended, dart said tuesday in a one-paragraph announcement
a federal appellate panel has upheld a lower court's finding that there was no evidence general motors corp. knowingly sold 1.1 million 1980 x-cars with alleged brake defects
the panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals on tuesday affirmed u.s. district judge thomas penfield jackson's 1987 rejection of government claims that the cars had an inherent defect that caused rear brakes to lock up prematurely and spin out of control under certain circumstances
ford motor co. has handed thousands of profit-sharing checks to u.s. workers as their share of the company's industry record profit of $4.6 billion for 1987
ford distributed $653 million in profit-sharing checks tuesday averaging more than $3,700 to 156,479 hourly and salaried workers
cheating on federal income taxes has declined by as much as 20 percent, mainly because of tax law changes and tougher federal policing, internal revenue service commissioner lawrence b. gibbs says
gibbs told a house appropriations subcommittee on tuesday that an irs study indicates the difference between taxes owed and taxes paid has dropped to between $80 billion and $90 billion in 1987. the agency's last report on the annual gap estimated it would rise to more than $100 billion in 1987
commuter airlines which carried nearly 30 million people last year are being targeted for stepped-up inspections by the federal aviation administration after seven fatal accidents and 56 deaths since november
the agency announced tuesday it would make the special inspections of the commuters, which normally fly aircraft of 30 or fewer seats. it said that about 20 percent of the 173 commuter carriers are expected to be singled out for particuarly close scrutiny
corning glass works says it has agreed to acquire international clinical laboratories for about $260 million in cash
chairman james houghton said tuesday he hoped the merger would broaden corning's laboratory services. the company said it planned to combine nashville-based international clinical with its laboratory subsidiary, mepath inc
digital equipment corp. has unveiled a line of powerful computers in another challenge to industry leader international business machines corp
analysts said tuesday's introduction of the vax 8800 series makes digital, the world's second-largest computer company, a competitor with ibm in the mainframe field
tandon corp. has sold off the disk-drive business on which the company was founded to western digital corp. for $49 million in cash and other considerations
western digital, of irvine, a leading maker of computer storage, communications, video controller and logic-processing units, also will assume about $28 million in tandon liabilities, the companies said tuesday
the average college administrator got a 3.3 percent pay increase this year, down from a 5.3 percent increase a year ago, the college and university personnel association says
the 3.3 percent increase for 1987-88 was less than the 3.7 percent increase in consumer prices during the same period, and the first time since 1982-83 that the college salaries trailed the rise in the consumer price index
the association said tuesday it derived the figures from its 11th annual survey of how much colleges pay their presidents, deans and administrators
stock prices surged tuesday as the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 24.70 points to 2,081.07
the dollar continued to slide against other major currencies
bond prices were little changed
prices for future delivery of cocoa rose, cattle futures advanced sharply while futures prices for pork, grains and soybeans were mixed
a key stock market indicator has risen to its highest level since the october market crash, even as the dollar slipped further against foreign currencies
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 24.70 points to close tuesday at 2,081.07, its highest level since the oct. 19 crash
other market indices also rose, as two stocks advanced for every one that fell on the new york stock exchange
wall street analysts said the rally partly reflected a desire by managers of institutional investment funds to put unused money to work as the first quarter draws to a close at the end of this month
others said the increased interest in stocks reflected true buying interest and waning anxiety by investors over the impact of the october collapse, along with optimism over indications that the economy is thriving
but many professional strategists were reluctant to declare that the underlying post-crash nervousness has evaporated
in the currency markets, the dollar continued to slide as the british pound soared and other major currencies took their cue from sterling. analysts said the british currency was buoyed by high interest rates and the strength of the country's economy
sterling rose to $1.8425 on tuesday in new york from $1.8180 late monday and has gained nearly 7 cents against the dollar in two days
in the credit markets, bond prices finished little changed with the benchmark 30-year treasury bond ending the day barely below where it ended monday's trading session
oil futures prices rose slightly in response to calls for meetings among oil-producing nations over production and price issues
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the u.s. benchmark crude oil, settled at $15.45 per 42-gallon barrel, up 8 cents from monday's close.   
oil prices have firmed slightly in response to calls for meetings among oil-producing nations
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the u.s. benchmark crude oil, settled at $15.45 per barrel tuesday, up 8 cents from monday's close
among refined products, wholesale heating oil gained 0.08 cent to 43.49 cents a gallon. near-term contracts for wholesale gasoline dipped 0.23 cent to 43.71 cents a gallon
analysts said longer-term contracts for both crude and the products were stronger, reflecting sentiment that key world oil producers may yet agree on ways to limit production and stabilize prices
in gasoline, for example, the september contract gained 0.41 cent to 43.70 cents a gallon on hopes for firmer prices and a strong summer driving season
helping support prices tuesday was egypt's announcement that non-opec oil producers would meet today in london. venezuela also reportedly called for more future meetings of the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries, analysts said
members of both groups appear anxious to address the problem of price discounting by some oil producers, said bob baker, an analyst for prudential-bache securities inc
but analysts said meetings alone would not dissolve the world's oil glut
there will have to be some kind of results or we'll continue to see these kinds of prices,'' said john hill of merrill lynch energy futures
digital equipment corp.'s newest line of computers should continue the company's process of chipping away at the domination of industry giant international business machines corp., analysts said
digital, the world's second largest computer company, introduced the vax 8800 series on tuesday, boosting its mainframe capability and issuing another salvo in the battle to be number one
it's not an earth-shattering announcement but it is a topper in terms of price and capabilities,'' said sonny monosson, an independent computer analyst in boston. ``it is very capable and will make inroads into the ibm market.''
maynard, mass.-based digital has mounted an aggressive campaign to erode ibm's dominance in mid-sized computers and large mainframes, or central processing units
last fall, digital introduced two new microvax computers and positioned them as competitors with ibm's 9370, a mid-sized computer that came out last summer
in january, digital and apple computer inc. announced a joint development pact _ specifically designed to challenge ibm _ that would make vax programs available on apple's macintosh computers
the newest line of vax computers is priced from $543,900 to more than $1.7 million
digital said the vax 8800 series delivers up to four times the processing power of the 8700 series with multiprocessing capabilities. the series is designed for large, multifaceted companies
this does intensify the competition,'' said howard anderson, managing director of yankee group, a boston-based market research firm. ``historically what happened is that dec has great software and underpowered computers. every time dec comes out with a high-powered machine, its users, who have been power starved, grab it up.''
despite the announcement, digital stock fell $4 a share to $120.37{ a share in consolidated new york stock exchange trading
analysts said digital had been expected to announce new software in conjunction with the new computers. when the company didn't, analysts lowered their earnings forecasts, which may have helped depress digital's stock price
the company said vax 8700s can be upgraded to the new line, which is available immediately, and analysts said they expect a 60-40 split between upgrading and new sales. analysts said they expect the vax 8800 series to offer strong competition for ibm's 4300 series and 4381 model
what we have seen is that the largest users are assuming there are only two companies acceptable for all applications _ ibm and dec,'' anderson said. ``two years ago it was only ibm.''
dart group corp.'s decision to drop its hostile $1.03 billion takeover offer for stop &amp; shop cos. marks the latest of dart's series of unsuccessful but profitable attempts to acquire a major retailing chain
dart said in a brief statement tuesday that it would let its $37 a share tender offer expire at midnight est tonight return all tendered shares to stop &amp; shop stockholders
stop &amp; shop, a supermarket and discount department store operator, said feb. 29 it had agreed to be acquired in a $44 a share, $1.23 billion leveraged buyout led by the investment firm kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co
a dart spokesman, who did not wish to be identified, said the landover, md.-based company felt it was ``uneconomic to bid further.''
dart, which owns about 2.7 percent of stop &amp; shop's 27.9 million common shares outstanding, nevertheless stands to profit from its abortive takeover try
dart reportedly acquired its 730,000 stop &amp; shop shares at prices below $20 a share, giving them a potential pre-tax gain of at least $17.5 million if it tendered its shares under the company's buyout
stop &amp; shop closed at $43.50 a share tuesday on the new york stock exchange, down 12{ cents from monday's close
dart, which had launched its takeover bid with a $31 a share offer on feb. 1, in recent years has developed a reputation as a corporate raider that launches hostile takeover bids and later pockets huge profits by selling its stock to another suitor or to the target company
dart since 1985 has been spurned in takeover bids by several major retailers, including safeway, beatrice cos., supermarkets general corp. and dayton hudson corp
the company, which owns the crown books and trak auto parts retail chains, has maintained it wanted to acquire a major retail chain as part of its long-term strategy
in addition to the kohlberg kravis buyout agreement, dart faced another obstacle in stop &amp; shop's federal lawsuit to block the hostile tender offer. stop &amp; shop accused dart of failing to disclose that its purpose in making the bid was to boost the stock price of the target company in order to make a speculative profit
boston-based stop &amp; shop owns 113 stop &amp; shop supermarkets and 169 bradlees discount department stores. in a leveraged buyout, investors borrow heavily to buy out a company and then pay off the debt with the target company's cash flow or the sale of its assets
a federal judge has set a hearing for next week to review the constitutionality of ohio's anti-takeover law, but has refused to immediately prevent firestone tire &amp; rubber co. from using the law to thwart a $1.86 billion buyout bid from italian tiremaker pirelli
judge alice batchelder rejected pirelli's request for a temporary restraining order against the law and set a hearing for next monday to review the statute's constitutionality
attorneys for pirelli societe generale sa went to u.s. district court in cleveland on monday in an effort to prevent firestone from using provisions of the ohio takeover act, which attempts to hinder hostile buyouts
firestone rejected an earlier merger proposal from pirelli in favor of a venture under which it will sell 75 percent of its core tire business to bridgestone corp. of japan. that rejection led the italian tiremaker to launch its unsolicited tender offer for firestone on monday
john j. nevin, chairman of firestone, stated late monday that the company's board was reviewing the offer and asking shareholders to await its recommendation before deciding whether to tender their stock to pirelli, which is based in milan
the board will complete its review by march 18, nevin said
mark peabody's share of ford motor co.'s profits will go into a house he is building for his family. mike heaslip is taking his to las vegas and josephine aftanas plans to use hers for her daughter's may wedding
many of the 4,500 livonia transmission plant employees already had plans for their portion of the $635 million in profit-sharing checks that ford distributed tuesday to 156,479 u.s. workers
ford earned an industry-record $4.6 billion in 1987 and distributions to workers jumped by 70 percent to an average of more than $3,700, up from $2,100 in 1986 when ford earned a company-record $3.29 billion
most ford workers received their checks tuesday morning. but peabody and his colleagues on the main transmission assembly line at the livonia plant agreed to wait until ford vice chairman harold poling arrived for a tuesday afternoon ceremony
it's not only the politicians who can call this super tuesday,'' poling told a crowd of cheering workers. he noted that the plant's 4,500 employees received $17.6 million, or an average of $4,450 each
you helped make 1987 one of the most remarkable years _ and certainly the most profitable _ in the history of ford motor co.,'' poling said before he and a retinue of reporters and executives walked to the assembly line
the livonia transmission workers' checks were larger than the company average because most workers have high seniority and few new, younger workers have been hired there, said ford vice president peter pestillo
workers on that line assemble transmissions for front-wheel-drive cars such as the popular taurus-sable and the new lincoln continental
most of them said they are lucky to be there at all. most were on layoff from other plants and had enough seniority to be called to work at livonia when ford added the line three years ago
ford withheld the checks of about 2,244 workers under a court order for payment of delinquent child support. all but 50 of those workers live in michigan. the others live in jefferson county, ky., ford spokesman mike moran said
more than 160,250 ford workers in the united states received profit-sharing checks in 1986. ford workers took home an average $2,100 in profit-sharing for 1985, $2,000 for 1984 and $400 for 1983, when the company distributed the first checks
general motors corp. workers received no share of gm's $3.56 billion in 1987 profits, though the corporation said it would distribute $184.6 million in stock bonuses to executives
gm, the nation's largest automaker, switched to the ford profit-sharing formula for 1988, but said that formula would have generated no profit-sharing distributions had it been used for 1987
procter &amp; gamble co. has entered a joint venture with syntex corp. of palo alto, calif., increasing the cincinnati-based consumer products company's involvement in the pharmaceutical industry
the companies will work to bring naprosyn, syntex's popular prescription arthritis treatment, to the over-the-counter market
p&amp;g officials have joined syntex's talks with the food and drug administration concerning wider distribution of naprosyn, kathleen gary, syntex vice president of public affairs, said tuesday
once the venture is under way, syntex will benefit from p&amp;g's expertise in marketing over-the-counter drugs, she said
syntex and p&amp;g have indicated their work on naprosyn would be the first of several joint projects. the companies said they are ``engaged in a series of other broad ranging discussions regarding further collaboration.''
neither p&amp;g representative pam sussman nor ms. gary could provide details on what kind of ventures the companies might be planning
naprosyn and a related product called anaprox are syntex's biggest sellers, accounting for more than half of its $1.3 billion in annual sales. naprosyn is sold in more than 80 countries
roper corp. says it will meet with general electric co. to discuss an unsolicited $423 million takeover offer despite a pending merger agreement with whirlpool corp
the augusta, ga.-based company maintained tuesday that its earlier agreement with whirlpool didn't preclude meetings with ge. roper said it would advise shareholders about its stance on the ge offer by march 18
whirlpool, meanwhile accused ge of ``deliberate and heavy-handed interference'' in its efforts to acquire roper, which manufactures some of the gas and electric ranges currently marketed by ge
ge on monday bid $45 a share, or $423 million, to acquire 9.4 million outstanding shares of roper stock. the offer came a week after announcement of a definitive agreement under which whirlpool would pay $37.50 a share, or $350 million, for outstanding roper stock
ge's tender offer for roper expires april 1; whirlpool's expires march 25
the prior agreement ``remains in the best interest of shareholders, customers and employees of both companies and ... whirlpool remains firmly committed to effecting the agreed-upon transaction,'' benton harbor-based whirlpool said in a statement released in detroit
the statement said whirlpool officials were ``considering a full range of options to complete the transaction.'' it did not specify how the ge bid would be countered but noted that roper directors unanimously approved the agreement with whirlpool
whirlpool was ``deeply disturbed by ge's deliberate and heavy-handed interference with its definitive merger agreement with roper,'' the statement said
whirlpool officials also were concerned ``that ge's offer was inspired by a fear of the increased competition a whirlpool-roper combination would bring, especially for ge's hotpoint brand,'' the statement said
calls to ge headquarters in fairfield, conn., were unanswered late tuesday. ge said it made the offer after learning from a securities and exchange commission filing that roper agreed to the whirlpool merger under the threat of a unilateral takeover
west german chancellor helmut kohl on wednesday called upon the u.s. congress to recognize europe's contribution to liberalizing world trade and refrain from protectionist legislation
in a speech to the european parliament, kohl said the european economic community's recent decisions to cut back farm production set an example for washington to follow
we are confident the congress will understand our measures and therefore should refrain from all protectionist legislation,'' he said
kohl referred to a decision by the leaders of the 12-nation eec last month to cut spending on agricultural subsidies as a means of curbing the production of food europe can neither consume nor sell
speaking as the current eec president, kohl hailed the feb. 13 decision of the brussels summit as a turning point in the eec's 31-year history
he also outlined to the parliament a long list of measures his government plans to push through before the end of its eec presidency on june 30. among them were plans for complete liberalization of capital movements, opening of the insurance and financial services to international competition and harmonization of technical standards
the internal market will develop only if we coordinate our economic, financial and monetary policies,'' kohl said
west german chancellor helmut kohl wednesday called the creation of a european central bank an ``absolute necessity.''
but he told the european parliament that fusing the monetary policies of the 12 european economic community nations must be ``gradual, step by step.''
kohl's backing of an eec central bank was more cautious than that of his foreign minister, hans-dietrich genshcer, who last month called for the creation of an experts group to see how such a central bank could be formed
genscher suggested the experts be named by the next eec summit in june with the mandate of drafting within a year the statutes of an eec central bank
eec business leaders also have called for the creation of a european central bank
a major japanese trading firm and an agricultural group that imports about 40 percent of the nation's feed grain will jointly purchase a u.s. grain company, a spokesman said wednesday
the national federation of agricultural cooperative associations, or zennoh, and c. itoh co., one of japan's three largest trading houses, are completing an agreement to buy consolidated grain and barge of st. louis, missouri, said a c. itoh official, speaking on condition of anonymity
the official said final details, including the purchase price and the share of investment by each party, would be worked out by the end of april
a zennoh official said his organization planned to link its new orleans-based export arm, the zennoh grain center, with consolidated grain, which handles 3.3 million tons of corn and 750,000 tons of soybeans a year
consolidated grain, which operates primarily in ohio, illinois, missouri and iowa, controls 30 grain silos and 650 barges used to transport grain
the zennoh official, who also insisted on anonymity, denied a report in the japanese newspaper yomiuri shimbun that zennoh would use the company to apply pressure on grain-growing regions where farmers are pushing for an end to japan's restrictions on beef and citrus fruit imports
zennoh, which handles almost 40 percent of the 1.5 million tons of feed grain imported annually into japan, has condemned u.s. demands for an end to the quotas
chrysler corp. will try to cut costs in a new contract with the united auto workers union, while the uaw will push for improved job security and profit-sharing, negotiators for both sides say
among the top items on the no. 3 automaker's negotiating agenda are more employee-management programs. the uaw also will demand a halt to layoffs unless there is a sales slump
the company has offered an early start to negotiations this year, when a three-year contract with the uaw expires. the union's 190-member chrysler council is to meet thursday and may decide whether to accept the company's offer
the chrysler-uaw contract, which covers 71,700 workers, expires sept. 14
uaw vice president marc stepp, who heads the union's chrysler department, said the union will demand that profit-sharing be based on annual earnings, as it is at ford motor co. on tuesday, ford distributed profit-sharing checks averaging $3,700 apiece to its unionized employees
stepp also said the union was seeking job-protection language similar to uaw contracts at ford and general motors corp. those three-year contracts, negotiated last year, forbid layoffs unless there is a sales slump, put stronger restrictions on work performed outside the company and a 3 percent general wage increase in the first year and lump sum payments in the following two years
we won't take anything less than gm and ford,'' stepp said
general motors corp. spent 25 percent more on its television advertising in 1987 than it did in the previous year, ranking it as the top advertiser among automakers, a survey shows
gm spent $500 million on television ads last year, the largest chunk of the $2 billion car makers spent on the medium, according to a survey reported tuesday by the television bureau of advertising
the 1987 total figure was 19 percent more than in 1986
gm spokesman harold jackson said the automaker's increase came because of ``aggressive promotion of new gm models in a highly competitive market.''
ford motor co. ranked second, spending $304 million, and chrysler corp. was third at $265 million. toyota motor sales led foreign car makers, spending $167 million last year
the largest increase in advertising came from suzuki motor co., which boosted its television costs by 126.3 percent, from $12 million in 1986 to $28 million last year. the largest decline was at volkswagen of america, which spent 9.4 percent less last year than the year before
the figures represent annual network and spot television spending for the automakers and dealer associations, according to william moll, president of the television advertising bureau. filing, stock price.</note>
r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. has taken its battle for federated department stores inc. to the marketplace and to the courts
macy, which last week agreed to a $6.1 billion buyout of federated, on tuesday began a tender offer for 80 percent of the cincinnati-based retailer's common stock
macy also asked a federal court for an injunction to block the rival $6.18 billion buyout offer from campeau corp., contending campeau's bid _ which was revised from an earlier offer _ actually constituted a new offer and as such must remain open beyond its scheduled expiration at midnight est march 15
extending campeau's bid would reduce the pressure on federated shareholders to decide between the rival macy and campeau offers, effectively putting the macy offer _ which expires april 4 _ on more equal footing
campeau, a toronto-based real estate developer and retailer, is offering $75 in cash per share for 80 percent of federated's stock and $44 in cash per share for the remaining 20 percent. the campeau bid, which has an aggregate value of $68 per share, totals $6.18 billion
until march 2, when campeau officially announced its two-tier bid, the company had offered $68 in cash outright for each of federated's 89.6 million outstanding shares
in order to increase the pressure on federate's stockholders, defendants have unlawfully treated their new two-tier offer as a `mere' amendment to their prior tender offer,'' macy contended in court papers
because of the two-stage price structure, campeau's latest proposal bears little resemblance to its original bid and should therefore be treated as a new offer, macy argued
under federal law, a new offer would have to remain open for at least 20 business days after publication or submission to stockholders. if campeau's bid is considered a new offer, it could not legally expire on march 15 as scheduled
macy asked the court to block the campeau offer from closing before stockholders had a sufficient amount of time to review materials and to evaluate the changes included in the new bid
macy's tender offer will pay $74.50 per share in cash for up to 70.43 million shares, or approximately 80 percent of federated common stock. macy plans to swap shares in a new company, macy's-federated inc., for the remaining 20 percent of federated's shares
the macy offer expires at midnight est april 4. analysts estimate it is worth $6.1 billion
macy revealed in a filing with the securities and exchange commission tuesday that under the macy-federated agreement, federated executives have the option of being paid in cash for all of their shares in the company, instead of the cash-and-stock offer being made to the public. the price to be paid for the executives' stock was $73.80 per share, slightly less than the cash price in the tender offer
federated stock was up 37{ cents to $66.37{ a share in early new york stock exchange trading today
in a separate sec filing monday detailing its latest bid, campeau revealed that federated had received six offers for its ralphs supermarkets division in california. the bids ranged from $800 million to $990 million, including a $955 million offer by ralphs management, campeau said
macy also said in its sec filing that it expected ralphs to be sold
whoever ends up acquiring federated is also likely to sell the company's other non-department store divisions, gold circle discount stores and main street and children's place specialty stores
campeau announced last week it had agreed to sell federated's foley's and filene's department store divisions to the may department stores co. if its tender offer succeeded
federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer, also owns department stores including bloomingdale's, lazarus, rich's, abraham &amp; straus, bullock's and burdine's
in its sec filing, macy said it expected some department store divisions would be sold, but it did not elaborate. analysts expect macy, which has nearly 100 department and specialty stores of its own, to sell federated rich's and abraham &amp; straus divisions
the government is trying to push legislation through the belgian parliament to control corporate raiders in the wake of the takeover battle for societe generale de belgique sa, officials said wednesday
the law would make it mandatory for an investor to disclose a shareholding in a publicly-listed belgian company once the stake reaches 10 percent of the total voting stock. further disclosures would be required for each increment of 5 percent
if approved, the law would be effective from march 1, 1988 through dec. 31, 1989 and would apply to belgian companies with a minimum equity of 200 million francs, the equivalent of $5.71 million
the bill will be examined by a committee on thursday and be put to a parliamentary vote next week, marc de backer, a finance ministry spokesman, said
the absence in belgium of legislation to control raiders allowed the italian investor carlo de benedetti to build up a direct and indirect stake of 18.6 percent in societe generale before announcing his bid on jan. 18 for effective control of the firm, which is belgium's largest holding company
in the ensuing battle, the other major societe generale shareholder, cie. financiere de suez of france, bought its stake of 20 percent in similar secrecy
the stock market edged upward today, struggling to extend tuesday's rally
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up 24.70 on tuesday, gained .66 to 2,081.73 by 11 a.m. today on wall street
gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 788 up, 528 down and 461 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 72.23 million shares at midmorning
confidence has continued to spread lately on wall street that the economy remains healthy nearly five months after black monday on oct. 19
in addition, stock prices have been less volatile lately than they were as recently as early january, suggesting that investors' mood is less subject to sudden change
analysts say investing institutions have grown more eager to put some of their cash reserves into stocks, in order to show in their first-quarter reports to clients that they participated in the recent market rally
still, many observers wonder how much stock might be for sale at higher prices by investors sitting with paper losses and waiting for an opportune time to get out of the market
japanese stocks were mostly higher following an up day in the tokyo market. matsushita electrical climbed 4} to 200{ and honda motor gained 2~ to 129~
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose .31 to 151.93. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up 1.65 at 297.69
c. robert powell ought to be taking orders from tokyo. last year, the 60-year-old chief executive became one of the first americans to see his company seized by the japanese in a hostile takeover
so why is powell still telling his japanese bosses how he intends to run things at reichhold chemicals inc.? simple, he says. he knows the american market and they don't
in japan they have `harmony': a closed industry; you don't cut prices. i told them `harmony' in the u.s. is six years in leavenworth.''
more than 3 million americans work for businesses that have at least 10 percent foreign ownership, and their numbers are rising rapidly as foreigners snap up u.s. properties with the dollars earned from their huge trading surpluses
the bosses include italians in indiana, swedes in georgia, canadians in vermont and west germans in california. the businesses range from cars to cement
but people like robert powell in white plains, n.y., prove that working for a foreign boss doesn't necessarily mean giving up the american way of life
after one tough discussion with a superior from dainippon ink and chemicals inc., powell says he was told by a lower-level japanese, ``mr. maeda doesn't like to argue with you.''
i said, `fine, tell him not to argue with me.'''
foreign companies such as dainippon are learning to adapt to american ways, a lesson in flexibility learned years ago by u.s. companies such as international business machines corp. when they went global
we're really babies at working with each other,'' said clifford clarke, president of iri international inc. in redwood city, calif., a consulting firm specializing in u.s.-japanese management issues
the first step in a corporate relationship is denial of differences. the second step is ``throwing names at each other.'' the third step is understanding, and the final step is taking advantage of the differences, clarke said
out of the diversity comes the best decisions,'' clarke said. ``that's as american as apple pie.''
fretting about foreign bosses seems to be more common among people who don't have them _ presidential candidates, for example _ than people who do have them, such as wayne hancock, who works for a bridgestone corp. tire plant in la vergne, tenn
it's been real enjoyable working with the japanese,'' hancock, an accounting manager, said recently. ``it's not like an american company. there's a lot more emphasis here on the quality of the product. ... they're more people-oriented.''
bridgestone's relations with the union are so good that the united rubber workers flag flies next to the bridgestone flag in la vergne
some problems do arise when the boss lives in another country. differences in language and culture can inhibit communication, and there are ceilings at some companies on how high americans can advance
in barre, vt., david cuttler was worried that his way up at quebec-based bombardier inc. was blocked by his trouble learning french. now his worries have eased
after you work together for a while, you tend not even to distinguish americans and canadians. you're all part of the same team,'' said cuttler, production manager for a factory that builds train cars. ``it's nice to speak french, but it's not necessary.''
the leading states for foreign employers are california, new york, texas, new jersey and pennsylvania, according to 1985 figures that are the most recent available
japanese employers get most of the publicity even though they ranked only fifth in u.s. employment in 1985, behind british, canadians, west germans and dutch
japanese ranked far ahead of british, west germans and arabs in a poll asking which were the best u.s. employers. the poll was released this past week by smick-medley &amp; associates inc., a washington-based consulting firm
one reason for japan's high profile _ think of the movie ``gung ho'' _ is that japanese are likely to mold companies in their own image. europeans often remain at arm's length from their u.s. holdings
italian executives of ferruzzi group have paid only two visits to the fort wayne, ind., headquarters of food processor central soya inc. since buying the company last year. and that suits david swanson just fine
it would be foolish of americans to try to implant certain of their systems on europeans _ and vice versa,'' said swanson, central soya's president and chief executive
europeans are not always so invisible: west germany's basf ag has had labor problems in west virginia, michigan, new york and new jersey, and chemical workers in geismar, la., are just now trickling back to work after a company lockout that began in 1984
basf says its labor policies in the united states are set locally, but the oil, chemical and atomic workers union charges that the decisions are made in ludwigshafen
in west germany, it's illegal to lock your employees out. what they've been able to do here they would not have been able to do in their own country,'' said ernest rousselle, a union representative
both europeans and japanese have elaborate employment guarantees at home _ the europeans by law, the japanese more by tradition. americans sometimes feel cheated when the companies are not as protective when they do business in the united states
more than 130 people in the san diego area sued japan's kyocera international inc. after they were laid off in 1980, claiming they had been promised lifetime employment. they lost but have appealed
more typical are complaints from ambitious american executives that their road to the top has been blocked, such as the pending lawsuit by thomas mcdannold and edward neubauer against nec america inc. in mountain view, calif
potential for cultural conflict is probably greatest on wall street, where buttoned-down japanese managers try to deal with freewheeling american recruits, and vice versa
you need a kind of cowboy mentality,'' said gregory v. coggiano, an executive with nomura securities international inc., ``but you've got to be a team player as well.''
a consensus is developing among management experts that foreign owners would be wise to adapt their homegrown methods to the ways of americans. at bridgestone, for example, japanese stopped doing early-morning exercises in the parking lot when only a few americans joined in
the result, as bridgestone's human resources adviser seiji ohtsu describes it, may be a ``third approach'' _ a blending of good ideas, foreign and domestic
as such things as quality circles and flexible job classifications become standard operating procedure here, having a foreign boss may no longer seem quite so unusual
in japan's case, said labor analyst harley shaiken of the university of california at san diego, ``the real, key issue isn't so much how japanese companies are different, it's the enormous influence they have had on u.s. firms.''
it is a place few americans ever see, a plush lounge where japanese executives spend $100 an evening to sip whiskey, flirt with pretty hostesses and maybe take a turn singing to the accompaniment of a baby grand piano
the piano bar _ ``pianoba'' in japanese _ is the one place where japanese executives lower their reserve, speak frankly and consolidate working relationships with their colleagues and customers
in the office, nothing moves. in the piano bar, everything moves,'' a japanese executive said late into a recent friday evening at one club in midtown manhattan
americans other than ethnic japanese are generally not welcome at a piano bar unless they are in the company of japanese. piano bars do not advertise. the only way to get in is to know where one is _ and then to be able to read the message in japanese on a small piece of paper telling customers to ring three times for admittance
americans are accustomed to being the outsiders when they go to japan to do business. but at a piano bar, americans are outsiders in the middle of new york city
if you're not invited, you're being cut out of something,'' said a young american who speaks japanese, works for a japanese trading company and occasionally goes to piano bars
more business is done after 5 o'clock in these bars than is done during business hours. because that's when people can have a couple of drinks and really say what's on their minds,'' the american said, speaking on condition that he not be identified
the piano bar does not start to fill up until after 9 p.m. or so, when executives drift over after work and dinner. the $100 does not pay for food, except for light snacks. it doesn't even cover drinks: regulars have bottles of expensive scotch kept for them in a closet
the $100 does cover the attentions of the hostesses, young women who sit on stools and light guests' cigarettes, freshen their drinks and engage in flirtatious small talk. most are from japan or elsewhere in the far east; others are americans or europeans
lest the guests become too bored or too bold, the hostesses are shuttled from table to table by the mama-san, who is dressed in a traditional kimono
when their names are called out, men stride up to the microphone and sing the song of their choice, usually in japanese. among songs in english, a favorite is ``my way,'' a la frank sinatra
the importance of the piano bar to japanese business should not be underestimated, said clifford clarke, president of iri international inc., a redwood city, calif-based consulting firm specializing in u.s.-japanese management issues
while americans prize achievement above all, japanese give the most weight to personal relationships, which are forged in piano bars and their less-expensive cousins, the karaoke bars, clarke said
we talk about after 5 in the bars as being social. they don't separate private life and work life,'' clarke said. ``it's not felt that after-hours time is play time
a lot of americans feel that japanese never give direct feedback. well, that's what the evenings are for,'' he said
weakened by corruption and low prices, mexico's giant pemex petroleum monopoly has been trying to cut costs and raise productivity as it struggles to stay afloat in a world glutted with cheap oil
but experts say the effort by president miguel de la madrid's administration has not made much headway, even though the well-being of pemex is vital to this debt-ridden country of 84 million people
two of the main obstacles to raising productivity have been corruption and a very powerful union that has been against trimming an overblown work force,'' said one expert on the mexican oil industry, who spoke on condition of anonymity
nevertheless, pemex ``is enormously important'' to mexico both as ``a major source of foreign exchange, and the country's largest tax payer,'' said oil expert george w. grayson in a telephone interview from richmond, va
the taxes and royalties pemex paid last year made up half the federal government's revenues as it struggled through the nation's sixth year of economic crisis. but the petroleum products it sold abroad accounted for 39.6 percent of the country's 1987 export earnings, down from 79 percent in 1982 when the oil industry was booming here
petroleos mexicanos s.a., as it is known by its formal name, monopolizes everything from exploring and drilling to heavy petrochemicals, transportation and wholesaling. only the gas stations, which carry its logo, are privately owned concessions
it was created by president lazaro cardenas, an army general, through an executive order issued march 18, 1938, a few days after he expropriated 17 foreign companies
international financial circles did not expect pemex to live long because it lacked money, skills and technology
half a century later, pemex is celebrating its 50th anniversary as one of the world's biggest integrated petroleum companies and a national institution a majority of mexicans take pride in
the big bonanza came when jose lopez portillo, the son of a pemex engineer, became president in late 1976, shortly after a new generation of pemex geologists and engineers trained in modern techniques, located fields in the southeast that turned out to be about twice the size of alaska's north slope in prudhoe bay
with half the world starved for petroleum because of high prices, arab embargoes, and later erratic deliveries caused by the outbreak of the iran-iraq war, the young technocrats at pemex scrambled to find and develop even more sources of new oil
pemex has sole rights over all hydrocarbons in mexico's 761,604 square miles of national territory (three times the size of texas) and over the 200-mile offshore belt on both coasts that mexico claims as an exclusive economic zone
as a result, the country's proven oil reserves of 48 billion barrels in 1987 _ almost twice as big as those of the united states _ remain the world's fifth largest after saudi arabia, kuwait, the soviet union and venezuela
but much of that oil lies inside tightly packed rock formations, making it too expensive to pump out at today's depressed prices. reserves are down by an estimated 2 percent from three years ago, because exploration has not kept pace with production
exploration was restricted after the government cut pemex's budget by 8 percent last year, along with almost everything except a few priority projects, because of the country's economic crunch
the bust came during the last months of lopez portillo's six-year term, when north sea, alaskan and other non-opec oilfields started to flood world markets and traditional producers began slashing prices to hold on to their clients
at the height of the oil boom from december 1980 to may 1981, pemex light-grade isthmus crude sold at $38.50 a barrel. as of this january, isthmus crude had dropped to an average of $15.03 a barrel. february prices have not yet been released
aside from the price slide, the company also continues to battle corruption, much of it centering around the oil workers union, which represents 95 percent of pemex's 183,000 workers and employees
de la madrid, who inherited these problems along with a giant foreign debt now estimated at $105 billion and few resources to meet payments on it, launched a ``moral renovation'' campaign at the beginning of his administration and appointed mario ramon beteta, a veteran economist, as head of pemex
beteta riled the union by trying to crack down on corruption, cutting costs and pork-barrel contracts to union companies. by law, 5 percent of the value of all pemex contracts used to go to the union, which owns a host of service companies, from drilling to pumping and construction. beteta cut that to 2 percent, also mandating that the contracts be awarded through open bidding
francisco rojas, who succeeded beteta last year, replaced four of pemex's seven deputy directors and laid off 900 non-union employees, but the fight against corruption continues. industry sources say the union still wields considerable power and maintains the inside track on most contract work
to hold down costs, pemex has concentrated on developing the ``gusher'' fields on- and off-shore in the southeastern part of the gulf of mexico, where the oil is cheapest to produce
export revenues are down from an annual high of $16.4 billion in 1982-84, to a low of $6.1 billion in 1986 and $8.5 billion last year. production has dropped from an average of 2.65 million barrels a day, then, to 2.40 million in 1986 and 2.60 million last year
about half of pemex's production is used domestically, supplying an estimated 90 percent of mexico's energy needs
roughly a quarter more is exported to the united states. the rest goes mostly to japan, spain, france, israel and central america
mexico has consistently tried to project a conservative and independent image as a world exporter. it refuses to join the organization petroleum exporting countries, even though it has reluctantly cooperated at times with the 13-nation cartel in reducing export volumes to buttress prices
as a matter of policy, it also refuses to sell more than 50 percent of its exports to any single country
grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed today on the chicago board of trade
soybean futures opened higher but quickly turned lower in response to reduced spot market prices for soybeans, soybean oil and soybean meal, analysts said
wheat futures opened lower on follow-through selling from tuesday but soon turned higher as the reduced prices brought in buyers
wheat futures prices have been trending lower recently due to uncertainty about future u.s. export sales, especially large shipments under the government's export enhancement program, analysts said
we've got some business but we're in need of some new eep business,'' said dale gustafson of drexel burnham lambert inc
corn futures weakened on increased farmer selling, gustafson said. but algeria and south korea both had purchase bids pending, and sales of u.s. corn to those countries could boost corn futures, he said
in early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1 cent higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3 a bushel; corn was 1\ cent lower to \ cent higher with march at $2.00\ a bushel; oats were \ cent to } cent lower with march at $1.91} a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 2{ cents lower with march at $6.14{ a bushel
cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly lower in early trading on the chicago mercantile exchange
live cattle were .25 cent lower to .15 cent higher with april at 72.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .08 cent higher with march at 81.05 cents a pound; hogs were .28 cent lower to .03 cent higher with april at 43.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to .77 cent lower with march at 53.32 cents a pound
cattle and hog futures closed higher tuesday while frozen pork belly futures retreated
the stock market pushed ahead today, extending tuesday's rally despite some early resistance from sellers
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up 24.70 on tuesday, gained 3.64 to 2,084.71 by noontime today on wall street
gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 2 to 1 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 926 up, 480 down and 444 unchanged
confidence has continued to spread lately on wall street that the economy remains healthy nearly five months after black monday on oct. 19
in addition, stock prices have been less volatile lately than they were as recently as early january, suggesting that investors' mood is less subject to sudden change
analysts say investing institutions have grown more eager to put some of their cash reserves into stocks, in order to show in their first-quarter reports to clients that they participated in the recent market rally
still, many observers wonder how much stock might be for sale at higher prices by investors sitting with paper losses and waiting for an opportune time to get out of the market
japanese stocks were mostly higher following an up day in the tokyo market. matsushita electrical climbed 5 to 200} and honda motor gained 2~ to 129~
johnson &amp; johnson added 2} to 86\. analysts said the buying was prompted by renewed enthusiasm over sales prospects for a j&amp;j skin treatment product that has received considerable publicity of late
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose .59 to 152.21. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up 2.83 at 298.87
volume on the big board came to 139.26 million shares at noontime, against 107.60 million at the same point tuesday
grumman corp. today announced that it will lay off about 700 employees and eliminate another 1,900 jobs due to declining business in aircraft engineering and manufacturing
in an open letter to employees, grumman president john o'brien said the reductions were prompted by the loss of a recent competition for a new aircraft program, production delays caused by defense budget reductions, and uncertainty about the funding of the a-6 aircraft
however, o'brien said, ``the airplane business is the backbone of our company, and we're in it to stay.'' he said the company was investing millions of dollars in research for future aircraft
six hundred employees will lose their jobs at the aircraft systems, aerostructures, data systems and electronics systems divisions on long island, n.y.; another 100 layoffs are planned for aircraft systems facilities in milledgeville, ga., and stuart, fla., and the systems division in melbourne, fla
an additional 1,900 jobs will eliminated nationally through attrition, coupled with a reduction in part-time and temporary workers, the company said
the largest part of the layoff will occur by the middle of april, with the remainder spread over the remaining months of the year, grumman said
grumman said hiring has already been sharply curtailed and is now essentially limited to people with specialized skills
walt disney co. has filed a copyright and trademark infringement suit accusing more than 15 outlets in new york city of unauthorized distribution and sale of toy telephones bearing a likeness of mickey mouse
the suit, filed wednesday in u.s. district court for the southern district of new york, is the latest of a rash of legal actions brought by the burbank-based entertainment concern for alleged unauthorized use of disney characters
in the past 24 months, the company has brought 14 suits involving more than 400 manufacturers, distributors and retailers in new york, south carolina, florida, texas, california and washington, d.c., the burbank, calif.-based company said
disney's latest action asks the court to award unspecified damages and to enjoin the distributors and stores from importing and selling the telephones with the unauthorized mickey mouse likenesses
housing construction plunged 14 percent in 1987 from the previous year as rising interest rates and high apartment vacancies took their toll on the industry, a survey released wednesday showed
the report by the f.w. dodge division of mcgraw-hill information systems co. said nationwide housing starts fell to 1.58 million units from 1.84 million units in 1986
it noted that only three of the nation's top 10 metropolitan areas _ washington, d.c., detroit and philadelphia _ showed any pickup in construction activity last year
high vacancy rates and high mortgage rates took a heavy toll of apartment and one-family building alike last year,'' said george a. christie, chief economist for f.w. dodge
christie said the apartment surplus, which he describes as ``a hangover from early '80's tax shelters,'' was likely to persist this year but that a drop in interest rates after the oct. 19 stock market crash has improved the outlook for construction of single-family homes
leading the nation in 1987 housing construction was washington, with 52,045 units, up 1 percent from 1986. the los angeles-long beach area ranked second with 50,052 units, although activity decreased 32 percent from the previous year
the rest of the nation's top 10 housing areas for 1987 were: atlanta, 46,333 units, down 12 percent; riverside-san bernadino, calif., 41,282, down 20 percent; chicago, 30,189, down 6 percent; phoenix, ariz., 27,216, down 37 percent; san diego, calif., 27,011, down 34 percent; minneapolis-st. paul, 26,219, down 5 percent; detroit, 26,009, up 1 percent; and philadelphia, 25,366, up 1 percent
