advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 on the new york stock exchange, with 871 up, 636 down and 459 unchanged
big board volume totaled 210.90 million shares, against 237.68 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index lost .14 to 151.48
stora ab, a forestry products company, offered wednesday to pay the equivalent of $990 million for swedish match ab, the world's leading manufacturer of lighters and wooden matches
the offer of 5.94 billion kronor was the biggest cash takeover bid ever in sweden, but was widely criticized as being far below the value of swedish match, which also has major interests in home interior and consumer products
both companies are dominated by investment companies controlled by the wealthy industrialist wallenberg family. one group controls 85 percent of swedish match, and the other holds a major voting holding in stora, which has peter wallenberg, the family patriarch, as its board chairman
a merger would create one of sweden's largest companies, with annual sales of 36 billion kronor, or about $6 billion, and more than 55,000 employees
analysts said stora wants to diversify its paper, pulp and power operations and improve its access to the european economic community
brian knox, a scandinavian specialist at kleinwort grievson, a london brokerage, said the bid was far below the range of what swedish match is worth
if match were a london company, it would be putting up a vigorous defense,'' he said. ``but because of the huge (wallenberg) position, there will be a tendency for people to just shut their eyes and enjoy it.''
peter wallenberg conceded after a news conference that the price was disputed at meetings of the two companies' boards, but he said it reflected a fair value for swedish match
both companies released 1987 financial results wednesday showing strong gains in profit. stora said its pre-tax profit climbed 39 percent to 2.57 billion kronor from 1.85 billion kronor the preceding year. swedish match had a 26 percent rise in profit to 628 million kronor from 500 million
swedish match was taken over by the wallenberg family, along with several other companies, after financier ivar kreuger's empire collapsed and he committed suicide in paris in 1932. swedish match had created a virtual monopoly in the market for wooden matches and now also dominates in lighters
it later expanded into consumer products and housing products. its tarkett group is the world's second largest producer of flooring material
analysts noted that sweden's two other major forestry product companies recently diversified their operations through acquisitions. svenska cellulosa ab bought the french diaper company peaudouce, and mo-och domsjoe ab acquired holmens bruk ab, a swedish newsprint producer
hans larsson, chief executive of swedish match, said adding the financial strength of stora would help in future acquisitions
we will now have a very rich parent company,'' he said. ``we'll be on the offensive now, as we have been.''
among swedish match's latest major recent acquisitions are the $230 million purchase of wilkinson sword, a major british producer of matches, shaving products and household goods, and the $190 million purchase of the west german flooring group pegulan
those acquisitions are part of what makes the company attractive, because of the access they offer to the european economic community, peter wallenberg said
stora, like other swedish, norwegian and finnish groups, is eager to expand into the member countries of the trade bloc to avoid being shut out in 1992 when a single internal market is scheduled to be created. none of the three belongs to the group
chrysler corp. and the united auto workers union could be meeting over a bargaining table as soon as next month if 140 local union leaders meeting here thursday agree to a request for early contract talks
local union leaders said wednesday they favor early talks and uaw vice president marc stepp has said ``the earlier the better,'' but one issue must be settled first: will chrysler also agree to an early strike deadline?
our preference would be to actually start the clock ... a real strike deadline as opposed to an artificial bargaining deadline,'' uaw spokesman peter laarman said
chrysler's three-year national contract, which governs wages and benefits for 71,700 workers, expires sept. 14. talks normally would begin in july, but chrysler asked for early talks last week
chrysler made the request after it succumbed to uaw pressure and decided against selling its 28,000-worker acustar inc. parts subsidiary. as an alternative, the company said it would close four acustar plants if it could not sell them in the next 18 months
angry workers had threatened a series of plant-by-plant strikes over local issues and had stopped cooperating in union-management programs essential to improving quality and production efficiency
the no. 3 automaker doesn't appear willing to let the union set a deadline before sept. 14, after which workers could legally strike the company if no settlement were reached, laarman said
chrysler's chief negotiator and vice president for human resources, anthony st. john, told the detroit news on tuesday that the company doesn't want an early strike deadline, but the company would not comment wednesday
st. john and stepp both were in milwaukee on wednesday for negotiations on a plant closing agreement for 5,500 workers at the former american motors corp. assembly and stamping plants in kenosha, wis
stepp has said he would recommend early talks when he meets thursday with the uaw's national chrysler bargaining council, which represents workers at 49 local unions. the council will make its decision thursday afternoon
local union leaders said they would support early talks because it would increase chances of protecting jobs and of ironing out mounting difficulties in plant-level labor relations
i'm positive our membership would be 100 percent in favor of that. as long as we're talking about jobs they would be more than willing,'' said fred o'brien, an official with local 1264 at chrysler's key sterling heights stamping plant
if talks begin early on the national contract, local unions would follow suit on plant-level contracts, which govern working conditions and other issues specific to them, laarman said
chrysler is expected to agree to the job-protecting pattern contract established last fall at ford motor co. and general motors corp
chrysler's contract lacks protections included in the gm and ford pacts and workers said they want to sign a similar contract as soon as possible
the gm and ford contracts forbid layoffs except when production is cut because of slow sales, make it harder for the companies to move production outside the company or country and forbid plant closings that were not announced before talks started
o'brien said going to the table early would limit the time chrysler has to announce further plant closings and make it easier for the union to battle the possible closings of the four acustar plants
in addition, chrysler already buys the largest percentage of outside parts of any big three maker _ 70 percent compared with 30 percent at gm and about 50 percent at ford
o'brien said workers are anxious to sign a contract that keeps chrysler from moving more parts work to outside non-union ``scab shops'' or ``we'll all be on welfare.''
chrysler also has no profit-sharing program. stepp said last week that he would particularly like to see the ford profit-sharing formula included in the chrysler contract
ford workers tuesday received profit-sharing checks averaging more than $3,700 from ford's industry-record 1987 profits of $4.6 billion
grumman corp., wounded by defense cutbacks and the failure to win a major aircraft contract, announced wednesday it would lay off 700 employees and eliminate 1,900 more jobs this year
the reductions amount to 7.7 percent of grumman's 33,700 employees. of the 700 employees who will be laid off, 600 work on long island. the others work at grumman facilities in milledgeville, ga., and stuart and melbourne, fla
the other job reductions will be made by attrition, coupled with a cut in the number of part-time and temporary workers. officials said 1,700 of those 1,900 jobs are located on long island
grumman president john o'brien, in a letter to employees published wednesday, said recent reverses forced the reductions
he cited production delays caused by cuts in the defense budget, and questions about the status of the a-6 plane. congress must reconcile the budget, which calls for production of 12 advanced a-6fs, and a budget authorization, which calls for production of 11 of the old a-6e planes
he also noted that grumman had lost a competition for a contract to build the navy's advanced tactical aircraft. the contract, valued at more than $4 billion, was won by mcdonnell douglas corp. of st. louis
o'brien noted that other grumman planes, like the f-14d, e-2c and ea-6b, will remain in production, and ``we are continuing to invest millions of dollars in the development of technologies for future aircraft.''
the airplane business is the backbone of our company, and we're in it to stay,'' o'brien insisted
most of the layoffs will occur by the middle of april, with the remainder spread over the remaining months of this year, the company said
the stock market's recent rally bogged down wednesday as blue chips gave up some of their gains from the day before
smaller issues, however, showed more of the strength they have been displaying since late last year
