women business students are more eager for leadership positions than they were in the 1970s and men are more likely to accept the change, a wharton school study concludes
the improvement in relations between the sexes is dramatic,'' ross a. webber, management professor at the elite pennsylvania business school, wrote for the latest issue of human resources management journal of the university of michigan business school
he acknowledged, however, that the improvement apparent from responses about the roles of women in mixed-gender study groups may be slightly suspect because of 1980s expectations about men's attitudes toward women
webber studied behavior of men and women business graduate students at the wharton and columbia schools in group projects from 1969-75 and at wharton from 1980-84
women are much more likely to exercise leadership whether in the majority or the minority; conflict levels have sharply declined on predominantly female teams; and males appear to be much less threatened when working with women,'' webber wrote
clearly significant social change has occurred during the 10 years separating the two investigations.''
the study examined four-person study groups formed from 420 students in the 1969-75 period and 268 in the later period. course instructors gave neither leader designations nor instructions on how to organize to perform assigned tasks
of the 688 students overall, 120 were in groups of four males, 392 in groups of three males and one female, 164 in groups of three females and one male and 12 in groups of four females
in the male-majority groups, 51 percent of the men claimed to be leaders, compared with 13 percent of the women, in the earlier sample. by the 1980s, the disparity disappeared, with 57 percent of the men and 61 percent of the women claiming to be group leaders
group members' ideas toward others also changed, with the percentage of men being called leaders falling from 48 to 36, and the percentage of women considered group leaders rising from 7 to 56
the results suggest that when working with women, men feel less compelled to play the macho, dominating role,'' webber said
among women in female-majority groups, claims of being the leader rose from 35 percent to 61 percent over the decade. in the 1970s, all 21 men in those female-dominated groups considered himself the group's leader, but in the 1980s, 70 percent claimed that status
leadership status in those groups was attributed to the sole male member 83 percent of the time in the 1970s, falling to 60 percent in the 1980s. as women's views of themselves as leaders rose to 61 percent in the 1980s, the perceptions by all group members of other women as leaders fell from 53 percent to 35 percent
women appear to be much more willing to compete for leadership, even as a lone female on a predominantly male team,'' webber wrote
webber cautioned that expected attitudes may have influenced some men's responses in his most recent sample
even among our younger male graduate students, with their appearance of greater comfort with mixed sex teams, one can ask whether actual behavior has changed as much as claims and attributions,'' webber said
for example, today it may not be as permissible for a male to be critical of female behavior as in the past, so the 1980s questionnaire responses could be a bit suspect.''
a group of non-opec oil producers met in london wednesday to debate moves to halt plunging prices, while members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries considered similar talks
results of the london session weren't disclosed, but oil prices edged upward in response to hopes that producing nations inside and outside of the cartel would move quickly to stem the recent erosion of the market
the meeting of non-opec officials was called by egypt and was held at the mexican embassy in london, even though britain, which rejects group pricing policies for its north sea oil, wasn't invited
another european producer, norway, declined to attend
apart from egypt, the other invited participants were the soviet union, china, angola, malaysia, brunei, oman, mexico and colombia
the meeting is at expert level with no ministers involved,'' said a mexican official, who declined to be identified. ``they just want to talk about the situation in the market, although obviously they are not in any position to take a decision.''
oil prices have declined by an average of about 20 percent over the past few weeks amid reports of production excesses and price discounting by opec members
on tuesday, egyptian oil minister abdel-hady kandil said the london meeting was not aimed against the 13-nation cartel, ``but is an attempt by non-opec producers to help save the world oil market from further deterioration.''
there also was continued speculation that opec would convene its own emergency meeting. venezuela initiated calls for such a conference, which were supported by saudia arabia and indonesia, among others. but sources said the saudis preferred to hold preliminary, informal talks to set an agenda for a meeting
nigeria, whose oil minister rilwanu lukman is president of opec, has yet to respond to the proposal. sources said it was unlikely a date would be set before nigeria replied
the pricing committee is empowered by opec to hold an emergency meeting of all 13 members of the cartel when prices drop dramatically below the official price of $18 per barrel
the price slide was interrupted when reports of official concern surfaced tuesday. on the new york mercantile exchange wednesday, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the u.s. benchmark crude oil, settled at $15.49 per 42-gallon barrel, up 4 cents from the tuesday close. the contract had gained 8 cents monday
northwest airlines said wednesday it would impose a contract on the carrier's 6,700 flight attendants april 1, despite a stalemate over wage demands that nearly triggered a strike last month
northwest said a provision of the railway labor act allowed it to implement contract changes unilaterally following a 30-day cooling-off period that ended feb. 26
flight attendants have voted to strike since then, but have continued to work while pursuing negotiations with the airline through their teamsters union local
union spokesman jeffrey musto said he had no immediate comment on the airline's latest move because teamsters lawyers were still studying it
terry erskine, the airline's vice president of law and labor relations, said the contract did not include a union proposal to limit the number of years needed to elevate attendants to higher salary levels
the main obstacle to reaching an agreement between the airline and the teamsters union local representing the attendants has been a demand by the union to raise lower-paid b-scale attendants to a-scale wages
northwest has proposed extending the b-scale from five years to eight years, meaning lower-wage flight attendants would have to wait an additional three years before earning top-scale wages
but b-scale flight attendants say the airline is trying to break a promise that they would earn a-scale wages after five years
the union also has objected to two-tier wage agreements, saying they pit junior workers against senior workers
the issue has intensified since northwest acquired republic airlines in 1986. roughly one-third of the 2,600 republic attendants work for b-scale wages and the other two-thirds have said they wouldn't get enough out of northwest's latest wage offer
erskine told a news conference wednesday that there are some changes in the contract that will be imposed april 1, but they are minor
under the contract proposal that will be implemented, the entry-level wage will go from more than $13,000 a year to $15,000 a year and the top base wage will go from the current $32,000 up to $35,000 a year, erskine said
erskine said the airline has not talked with the union about its plan to impose the contract
federal regulators declined wednesday to renew their previous pledge not to take regulatory action against the thrift unit of troubled financial corp. of america
the move came as the federal home loan bank board, which oversees the thrift industry, sought to reassure nervous wall street firms who have lent more than $12 billion to american savings &amp; loan association of stockton, calif., irvine-based fca's thrift unit
the bank board declined to issue a new letter pledging not to take regulatory action against fca. regulators have issued such ``comfort letters'' to fca since late 1984, when the company was swamped by heavy losses and fell below regulatory capital requirements
at the end of 1987, the company for the first time posted a negative net worth _ the difference between assets and liabilities
fca has tried unsuccessfully to work out the problems by itself but has been hindered by persistent problems with bad loans. fca added $551.2 million to its loan-loss provisions last year, bringing the total since september 1984 to $1.7 billion
the bank board has tried unsuccessfully for nearly a year to find another institution willing to take over all or part of fca on terms that wouldn't be excessively costly to the federal savings &amp; loan insurance corp., the bank board unit that insures customer deposits up to $100,000 each
because of its size, a failure by fca would cause serious problems for fslic
fca, with $33.9 billion in assets at year-end, is the nation's second-largest thrift holding company after los angeles-based h.f. ahmanson &amp; co
in its effort to reassure wall street, the bank board said in an eight-page resolution wednesday that it would use its ``best efforts'' to insure that the market for reverse repurchase agreements, or repos, isn't disrupted if american savings defaults on its obligations, or if regulators must take any action such as placing the institution under receivership
american savings has about $12.6 billion in repos outstanding
repos are financing instruments in which a lender buys a security and agrees to resell it to the original seller when it reaches maturity. repos usually mature in 30 days or less and the collateral generally is in the form of mortgage-backed securities held by the borrowing thrift
fca's current comfort letter expires march 31
asked if the bank board was considering renewing that letter or issuing a new one, spokesman karl hoyle said, ``no. we feel today's resolution deals with that question.''
some industry leaders have argued that past comfort letters had unduly restricted the bank board's options in dealing with fca's problems
while wednesday's resolution didn't say the bank board would take any action against american savings, it did say it issued the resolution because of ``the potential disruption to the markets in such repos that could arise as a result of a receivership, conservatorship or similar proceeding with respect to american.''
fca's fourth quarter loss of $224.6 million boosted its deficit for the year to $468 million for all of 1987, and gave it a negative net worth of $163.4 million at year-end
in a brief statement, fca spokeswoman layna browdy said, ``we commend the bank board and wall street for arranging this agreement (on repos). we've had a good and long-standing relationship with wall street which is being helped by this latest actoin taken by the bank board.''
fca declined to elaborate or to say comment on the board's decision not to issue a new comfort letter
mcdonnell douglas corp. executives, using a symbolic gold-plated rivet, wednesday began assembly of the first md-11, the company's entry into a fierce competition to provide a new generation of jetliners
the action soothed concerns that were expressed about whether the new airliner would ever get off the ground after the company earlier this year scaled back the number of orders it had received for the plane
during a ceremony at the company's douglas aircraft co. plant in long beach, douglas president james worsham announced that two more carriers had ordered a total of six md-11s. identity of the new carriers wasn't disclosed
the new orders brought the total to 16 customers and 99 of the jetliners, which sell for between $90 million and $100 million each. if all the planes are purchased, it would create $9.9 billion in revenue for douglas, a division of st. louis-based mcdonnell douglas
douglas spokesman don hanson said wednesday that 31 of the orders are firm, 45 are conditional or options and 23 are listed as ``reserves,'' which the company defines as falling into ``various categories of intent to acquire the airplane.''
the md-11 is a roomier, longer-range and more fuel-efficient version of its current jumbo jet, the dc-10
however, the md-11 faces a tough fight with seattle-based boeing co. and the airbus industrie, the european consortium, to provide the new generation of passenger jetliners in what is likely to be a shrinking market
analysts say there is room in that market for only two manufacturers and it is a toss-up as to which will survive
in what is generally seen as a weakness for the md-11, the maker has yet to land an order from a domestic commercial passenger airline. the only domestic order it has received is from federal express, the parcel-delivery service. characterized proposed standstill agreement, update with further american standard response, closing stock prices, edit to tighten. no pickup.</note>
black &amp; decker corp. on wednesday refused to enter talks proposed by its target american standard inc. over the toolmaker's $2.26 billion hostile buyout offer
black &amp; decker said american standard had asked it to enter into a standstill and confidentiality agreement under which it would provide black &amp; decker with non-public corporate information
such an agreement would prohibit black &amp; decker from taking additional action to pursue its hostile bid for the new york-based plumbing and air conditioning maker
nolan d. archibald, black &amp; decker chairman and chief executive, called the conditions of the proposal ``excessively restrictive and totally unacceptable.''
he said black &amp; decker would continue to ``pursue aggressively'' its $73-a-share bid
american standard rose 37{ cents to $73.37{ a share on the new york stock exchange. black &amp; decker rose 25 cents to $18 in heavy trading
american standard on tuesday announced it would continue developing a recapitalization plan aimed at thwarting black &amp; decker's hostile buyout offer, but said it expected to engage in discussions and negotiations with black &amp; decker and other potential acquirers
on wednesday, american standard denied asking for a standstill agreement, saying it only sought to uphold ``shareholder values.''
we have just requested that they not drop their tender offer and conduct a street sweep...thereby preempting higher bids for the company,'' said spokeswoman linda king. ``we were puzzled to see black &amp; decker's release. we are trying to pursue a reasonable course and are talking to black &amp; decker's legal counsel to resolve the situation.''
in a street sweep, a bidder tries to gain a controlling interest in a target company by buying huge blocks of the target company's stock rapidly in regular market transactions
in a prepared statement, black &amp; decker said it had a right to the same information on the same terms that american standard had made available to third parties supporting the recapitalization
those parties include banks who have agreed to let american standard borrow nearly $2 billion to finance its plan and emerson electric co., which has agreed to buy $160 million in american standard junk bonds
thomas t. taylor, president of towson-based chesapeake securities research corp., said american standard was trying to buy time to find a ``white knight'' friendly suitor in proposing a truce with black &amp; decker
on friday, black &amp; decker sweetened its offer for the fourth time _ to $2.33 billion _ just hours after american standard had increased its own competing offer to shareholders
american standard said monday it would pursue other ways to boost its recapitalization plan before it accepted black &amp; decker's takeover bid
analysts estimate the american standard plan, paying shareholders a combination of cash, debt, and stock in the recapitalized company, is worth slightly more than $2 billion
